{"paper_id":"a-simple-rule-based-part-of-speech-tagger-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"A","method":"B"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal body is empty (A/B placeholders); inferring from title and prior work. A rule-based POS tagger positioned against dominant stochastic/HMM approaches suggests a contradiction/tradeoff opportunity (achieving comparable accuracy without heavy statistical machinery, addressing resource/complexity concerns). The central deliverable is a concrete tagger artifact. Low confidence due to missing text."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"a-simple-rule-based-part-of-speech-tagger-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Statistical POS taggers of the late 1980s/early 1990s reached ~96% accuracy with first-order (bigram) HMMs over word equivalence/ambiguity classes trained on unlabeled text (Church 1988; Kupiec, \"A Practical Part-of-Speech Tagger\" 1992) or by statistical optimization / Viterbi decoding (DeRose 1988). First-order context, however, misses important selective dependencies — e.g., disambiguating adjective-or-noun after a determiner (\"The period of...\"), or subject/verb number agreement across an intervening prepositional phrase. Kupiec's augmented HMM (1989) captures these by adding \"state chains\" that model higher-order conditioning ONLY where needed, avoiding the parameter explosion of a uniform trigram model.\n\nThe scope mismatch: the structure of those state chains is hand-designed from manual error analysis and linguistic intuition on a single corpus and tagset. This assumption is narrow and poorly transferable. Uniform higher-order models, at the other extreme, spend parameters everywhere (n^3 transitions), overfitting sparse contexts and forcing ad hoc smoothing. Yet the same literature argues (Kupiec 1992, sec. 5.3) that a tagger must be \"fast and easy to target... to new genres and languages, and to experiment with different tagsets.\" There is currently no principled, automatic way to decide WHERE to spend limited model capacity, and no explicit link between how much higher-order structure to add and how much (often sparse) training data is available. Every new domain, tagset, or language requires an expert to redo the error analysis and hand-build the network — leaving both portability and accuracy on the table.","method":"Replace manual state-chain design with an automatic, budget-constrained topology SEARCH that grows a selectively higher-order equivalence-class HMM from data. This is an optimization/resource-allocation contribution: adaptively allocate a fixed parameter budget to the contexts where extra capacity most reduces error.\n\n(1) Base model. Start from the first-order, fully-connected equivalence-class HMM that requires only a lexicon plus unlabeled text and is trained with Baum-Welch (as in Kupiec 1989/1992). Equivalence classes keep it vocabulary-independent so new words need no retraining.\n\n(2) Candidate expansions. Define a single primitive operation — a \"context split\" — that refines the model exactly like a hand-built state chain: take a state (a category used in some context) and split it by conditioning on a specific preceding category or equivalence-class context, introducing the extra states that uniquely model that second/third-order context (e.g., determiner-noun-X vs determiner-adjective-X). The set of all such splits over the current topology defines a large search space. Parameters of tied/duplicated states are pooled (state tying) as in the original augmented model.\n\n(3) Benefit-per-parameter scoring. Score each candidate by estimated benefit divided by parameters added: benefit = gain in held-out data likelihood, or reduction in expected tagging error measured from forward–backward posteriors on a small held-out set (which may be self-labeled by the current model, or a modest amount of tagged text as used for rule acquisition in Hindle 1989). Crucially, scoring uses only a few localized EM re-estimation steps around the affected states rather than full retraining, making the search tractable.\n\n(4) Adaptive/greedy search with pruning. Iterate: score all candidate expansions against the current model; add the top-k with highest benefit/cost; re-estimate the whole model with Baum-Welch; then prune (merge back) any expansion whose realized gain falls below a threshold. Continue until the parameter budget is exhausted or marginal gain < epsilon. The budget itself is chosen by cross-validation and scaled to the amount of training data, so capacity is added only where data can reliably estimate it — directly coupling model order to data sparsity. Uniform trigram (spend everywhere) and fixed hand-crafted chains (spend once, by hand) are the two degenerate endpoints this search interpolates between.\n\n(5) Evaluation and transfer. (a) On the original corpus, match or beat the hand-crafted augmented HMM with fewer parameters. (b) Retarget the identical procedure — no manual analysis — across Brown genre subcorpora, to a coarser/finer tagset (via the lexicon-to-tagset mapping), and to a second language, showing it automatically rediscovers effective structure. (c) Ablate the budget to chart the accuracy/parameter/data-efficiency tradeoff. (d) Inspect discovered expansions to confirm they recover known linguistically meaningful contexts (determiner–noun–X; subject–verb agreement across a PP) plus novel ones, demonstrating the search substitutes for expert error analysis. This turns a narrow, non-transferable hand-engineering step into a portable, data-driven optimization that allocates model complexity where it pays off."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a scope mismatch: hand-designed state chains are narrow and non-transferable across corpora, tagsets, and languages, with a secondary resource-bottleneck framing around portability and limited parameter budget under data sparsity. The core research move is an automatic, budget-constrained topology search that adaptively allocates parameters to high-benefit contexts, which is squarely optimization_search. The proposal identifies a precise limiting factor (where to spend model capacity given data sparsity), giving high bottleneck specificity, and is not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"a-simple-rule-based-part-of-speech-tagger-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The statistical taggers here (Church 1988; Jelinek 1985; Derouault and Merialdo 1986; Kupiec 1989; Cutting et al. 1992) claim robustness on unrestricted text and near vocabulary-independence, but share one narrow boundary condition: the HMM emission side is anchored to a manually constructed lexicon that lists, for each word, its admissible tags (its ambiguity class). Kupiec's 129 equivalence classes still presuppose a 30,000-word dictionary mapping every word to a class; Church trains word-level probabilities from the tagged Brown corpus. The ambiguity-class trick makes the model independent of vocabulary size, not of the existence of a curated lexicon. This breaks exactly where these systems claim to serve: new domains and genres, other languages lacking such a lexicon, and open text full of out-of-vocabulary tokens. The state of the art punts here; Cutting et al. concede an unrecognized word gets a default ambiguity class containing all open-class categories, failing on the hard words where errors concentrate. Reported accuracies near 96 percent are measured in a favorable in-lexicon, in-domain regime and often ignoring unknown words (Kupiec 1989), overstating real performance. Rule-based alternatives (TAGGIT; Hindle 1989) depend on hand-crafted English morphotactics or a pre-tagged corpus plus an existing parser. The gap: no method builds the ambiguity-class structure the HMM depends on from evidence rather than a pre-existing dictionary, so none truly functions under an incomplete or missing lexicon.","method":"Relax the complete-lexicon assumption by inducing ambiguity classes and emission structure from raw untagged target-domain text, keeping only a small cross-domain-stable seed. First, seed with the closed-class inventory (determiners, prepositions, pronouns, auxiliaries, conjunctions, punctuation): a few hundred largely unambiguous entries, stable across domains and reusable across related languages, far weaker than a full content-word dictionary. These anchor the HMM state space (the tagset) and act as reliable context markers. Second, for every other word (frequent, rare, or unseen), compute a distributional context signature from unlabeled counts over neighboring seed and high-frequency anchor items, and cluster words by signature similarity to induce data-driven ambiguity classes that replace dictionary lookup; map each cluster to a soft distribution over tags by aligning its contexts to the seeded closed-class contexts. Third, for rare and OOV words combine the sparse signature with morphological features (suffix and prefix tries, per the 1963 CGC and Kupiec suffix cues) to yield a soft, evidence-weighted ambiguity class instead of the all-open-class default. Fourth, plug these soft classes into a first-order HMM and re-estimate transition and emission parameters with Baum-Welch on the target text itself, self-adapting per corpus with no hand lexicon or tagged data. Evaluate against the relaxed scope: incomplete-lexicon curves that progressively delete dictionary entries and compare to dictionary-dependent baselines while reporting accuracy including unknown words; cross-domain transfer adapting on a genre far from Brown versus a Brown-trained fixed-lexicon tagger; and a low-resource language setting using only a closed-class seed plus raw text. Success means matching in-lexicon accuracy in the favorable regime while sharply cutting OOV and domain-specific errors and degrading gracefully as the lexicon shrinks."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a narrow boundary condition: statistical taggers presuppose a curated complete lexicon and break on new domains, languages, and OOV tokens (scope_mismatch), with secondary emphasis on where errors concentrate/overstated accuracy (failure_risk_gap). The method's central move is relaxing the complete-lexicon assumption to function under weaker assumptions and broader regimes (relax_extend_scope), with clear identification of the precise bottleneck (dictionary-anchored ambiguity classes)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"a-simple-rule-based-part-of-speech-tagger-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The statistical POS-tagging paradigm in these works reports high accuracy only under narrow, homogeneous conditions. Cutting et al. (1992), building on Church (1988) and Kupiec (1989), reach 96% by training a Baum-Welch HMM on half of Brown and tagging the other half; Klein and Simmons (1963) report over 90% on scientific text; the Markov-source line (1985) and phoneme-to-text work (1986) assume a stationary source; Hindle (1989) acquires rules from tagged text tuned to one domain. Each assumes a single in-domain corpus, a lexicon whose ambiguity classes are complete and correct, unlabeled training text from the same distribution as the target, and a forced single-tag decision per token. This is a scope mismatch with the goal of tagging unrestricted text, which is heterogeneous across genres, domains, and noise, and contains vocabulary the lexicon never anticipated. When lexicon ambiguity classes are wrong or the target genre differs from training, aggregate accuracy hides failure concentrated on unknown words, rare ambiguity classes, and out-of-domain constructions. Robust here means only that the model assigns non-zero probability to any token sequence, not robustness to distribution shift or lexical error, and not any calibrated signal of which tags are unreliable. The systems emit their worst errors silently, exactly where a downstream parser most needs a warning.","method":"Build a confidence-aware, self-adaptive HMM tagger that reduces brittleness to lexical incompleteness and genre shift and quantifies its own uncertainty, using the same resources these papers assume (a lexicon, unlabeled text, a small tagged sample for evaluation). Four robustification components. (1) Redundant evidence fusion: instead of trusting the lexicon ambiguity class alone, combine individually weak sources (the lexicon class, morphological suffix signatures extending Klein and Simmons 1963 suffix tests and Kupiec suffix prediction, and contextual tag n-gram statistics) via smoothed linear interpolation as advocated in the Markov-source framework, so a single wrong lexicon entry cannot force an error. (2) Lexicon-error-tolerant emission model: replace the hard constraint that a word may take only its listed tags with a soft prior that gives listed tags high prior mass but leaves a small leak probability for other open-class tags conditioned on the word suffix class, letting Baum-Welch recover valid tags the lexicon omits and down-weight spurious ones. (3) Unsupervised target-domain self-adaptation: for each new document or genre, run extra Baum-Welch iterations on the target text itself, initialized from the source-trained model, adapting emission and transition parameters to the target distribution, a cross-genre step the in-domain train/test protocols never perform. (4) Calibrated uncertainty and selective abstention: use per-token forward-backward posterior marginals as a confidence score, calibrate it, and when confidence is low output a ranked ambiguity set or defer to a downstream parser (as in Hindle 1989) instead of a forced single tag, turning silent errors into flagged low-confidence decisions. Evaluate beyond aggregate accuracy with robustness diagnostics: cross-genre transfer (train on one Brown genre, test on another); systematically corrupted or incomplete lexicons (randomly delete or add ambiguity-class entries); error concentration on unknown and rare classes; and confidence calibration plus the accuracy-versus-abstention trade-off. Success is smaller degradation under shift and lexicon corruption plus well-calibrated confidence that retains high accuracy on kept tokens, addressing the gap between in-domain benchmark accuracy and reliable tagging of genuinely unrestricted, noisy, out-of-vocabulary text."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a scope mismatch: prior statistical taggers assume single in-domain corpus, complete lexicon, matched distribution, and forced single-tag decisions, all of which fail on genuinely unrestricted text; secondary failure_risk_gap because silent worst-case errors and lack of calibrated confidence are central. The method is dominated by robustification (four components reducing brittleness to lexical error and genre shift, plus calibrated abstention), with relax_extend_scope as secondary (self-adaptation and soft priors extend to noisier, broader regimes). Bottleneck is precisely identified (accuracy hides failure on unknown words, rare classes, out-of-domain). Not surface stitching since components are integrated around a specific reliability mechanism."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"a-simple-rule-based-part-of-speech-tagger-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two mature but separate strands attack lexical-category disambiguation, and each rests on narrow, poorly transferable assumptions (a scope mismatch). Statistical/Markov taggers (Church 1988; Jelinek 1985; the 1986 phoneme-to-text model; Kupiec 1989; the 1992 practical tagger) assume all relevant context is captured by a fixed short window of adjacent category transitions, that emission depends only on the current category, and that one genre corpus (Brown) represents unrestricted text. These assumptions fail exactly where the models fail: Kupiec's own error analysis (\"to\" preposition vs. infinitive marker; \"The period of...\" adjective vs. noun) shows residual errors are phrase-level and long-distance, precisely what the local Markov assumption excludes. His fix, hand-designed state chains from linguistic intuition, does not scale or transfer. Rule/parser-based methods (Klein and Simmons 1963; Greene and Rubin 1971; Hindle 1989) see phrase structure and long-distance context but are deterministic, tied to one hand-built grammar, and corpus/parser-bound. Hindle argues the real question is whether the needed linguistic information can be acquired from text, noting stochastic taggers succeed without reference to syntactic structure. The gap: no framework unifies these so that structural/long-distance constraints are acquired automatically, added only where the Markov assumption empirically breaks, and kept inside one graded, vocabulary- and genre-robust probabilistic model.","method":"Build a self-refining tagger that unifies unsupervised HMM tagging with automatically acquired symbolic phrase-structural rules, using the HMM's own systematic errors as the bridge between the two literatures. Step 1: train a Kupiec/Cutting-style HMM with word equivalence classes via Baum-Welch on untagged text, handling unknown words with Klein and Simmons-style suffix/morphology cues to keep vocabulary independence. Step 2: locate where the Markov assumption breaks by flagging low-margin Viterbi decisions and systematic disagreements on a small held-out sample, clustering them into recurrent error patterns, automating the error catalog Kupiec built by hand. Step 3: for each cluster, adapt Hindle's rule-acquisition procedure to induce a symbolic context template grounded in shallow phrase structure from Church's noun-phrase parser (phrase boundaries, distance to head, function-word anchors), so rules encode the long-distance/phrasal context the local model misses. Step 4, the synthesis: compile each acquired rule not as a hard override but as an automatically generated state-chain augmentation that unfolds the offending HMM state along the rule's context, then re-estimate by Baum-Welch, so symbolic phrase constraints decide where extra conditioning is warranted while probabilities decide how strongly, and a rule takes effect only if data support a distinct usage. Step 5: iterate train, error-mine, acquire, compile, retrain until residual systematic errors plateau, yielding a compact data-driven set of phrase contexts rather than uniformly higher-order models. Evaluation targets the scope mismatch: cross-genre transfer (train on one corpus, test on another) versus fixed-order HMMs and parser-bound rules; ablations isolating gains from structural augmentations; head-to-head comparison of automatically acquired state chains against Kupiec's hand-built ones and Hindle's deterministic rules on shared errors; and the phoneme-to-text task as a downstream test of the unified statistical-plus-grammatical model. Success: recover parser-level phrase accuracy while keeping the resource-light, corpus-portable, graded character of HMM taggers."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.87,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames two separate literatures (statistical/Markov taggers and rule/parser-based methods) as disconnected strands to be unified, with the HMM's own systematic errors as the bridge — clear bridge_opportunity, with a scope_mismatch secondary (narrow, non-transferable assumptions). The core move is synthesis_unification: reconciling symbolic phrase rules with probabilistic HMMs into one model, with relax_extend_scope secondary (cross-genre robustness, weaker assumptions). Not surface stitching because the integration is mechanistically grounded — rules compiled as data-supported state-chain augmentations rather than bolted-on overrides. Bottleneck is precisely identified: the local Markov window failing on phrase-level long-distance dependencies."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"The sources form a lineage of regime-specific optimal allocation policies. Lai & Robbins (1985) prove the universal O(log n) regret lower bound with a KL constant and give matching UCB rules only for specific families. Agrawal (1995) builds sample-mean UCB indices optimal for one-parameter exponential families. Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) give dual-problem indices for parametric populations with unknown nuisance parameters. Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) note that the achievable rate and correct strategy change with the bandit postulates (known family vs. bounded support vs. only finite moments), while the Lai-Robbins bound applies across all. Ishikida & Varaiya (1994) and the Gittins allocation-indices book address discounted/average-reward and arm-acquiring settings with index rules that are optimal but hard to compute; Q-learning for bandit problems (1995) and Sutton's RL introduction (1998) show Gittins-type indices can be learned by reinforcement learning. The unexamined premise across these works is that the deployer already knows which regime holds and pre-commits to the matching policy. In practice this is unknown: misspecification either silently forfeits a policy's regret guarantee or is needlessly conservative. No source detects the operative regime online, deploys the tightest valid asymptotically-efficient index, and reports a continuously valid optimality guarantee. This matters for the clinical-trial and online-allocation applications these papers invoke, where guarantee validity is what a deployer needs.","method":"Build a deployable adaptive-allocation engine that unifies the regime-specific optimal policies of the source literature behind one interface, selects among them from data, and emits a live regret certificate. Five components. (1) Problem-spec and streaming interface: the user declares objective (finite/infinite horizon; average vs. discounted reward) and any hard prior knowledge; rewards stream per arm, and new arms can enroll over time (arm-acquiring bandits, per Ishikida-Varaiya). (2) Regime monitor (novel core): per arm it maintains empirical moments and CDF and runs sequential goodness-of-fit and moment-tail tests to certify membership in a nested lattice of classes: A known one-parameter exponential family, B bounded support of unknown shape, C only finite p-th moment, D discounted-Bayesian; each certification carries a confidence level from the large-deviations machinery Agrawal uses. (3) Index synthesizer: for the tightest certified class it instantiates the matching efficient index: KL and sample-mean UCB (Lai-Robbins, Agrawal) for A; Burnetas-Katehakis dual-problem indices for parametric-with-nuisance and finite-support; Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric confidence-bound indices with their guaranteed rates for B and C; and for class D, Gittins indices computed by a built-in Q-learning and dynamic-programming module (Duff, Watkins per Sutton), making the Gittins-optimal policy deployable without a closed form. (4) Hot-swap meta-controller: as certification tightens or breaks it switches to the tightest valid index and defaults conservatively to the nonparametric index whenever a stronger assumption loses certification, keeping the deployed policy always sound; it uses the average-reward index extension of Ishikida-Varaiya for the streaming case. (5) Regret-certificate tracker: it continuously outputs the finite-time regret bound valid under current certification and the Lai-Robbins KL lower bound, exposing the live optimality gap, and logs counterfactual guarantee-void events where a pre-committed fixed policy would have lost its guarantee. Evaluation: a simulation harness sweeping arms across all four regimes (including regime shifts and heavy tails) plus a clinical-trial-style replay, comparing the platform against each fixed policy committed a priori, measuring regret, mistake counts, and the fraction of runs in which each fixed policy's stated guarantee was actually valid versus the platform's always-valid certificate. The deliverable is the open engine itself."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.62,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap identified is that prior policies assume a known regime is pre-committed—an unrealistic assumption/scope limitation (scope_mismatch), and the disconnected regime-specific policies could be bridged (bridge_opportunity). The central deliverable is an open engine/platform that unifies existing policies behind one interface with a regime monitor and certificate tracker (artifact_system), integrating separate literatures (synthesis_unification). The construction largely assembles existing index policies into one system, which carries some flavor of A+B stitching, though the online regime-detection and hot-swap certificate mechanism is a genuine novel component. The bottleneck (unknown regime forfeiting guarantees) is fairly specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior works give an asymptotic-only theory of the stochastic bandit. Lai and Robbins (1985) proved the log-n regret lower bound and built KL-based upper-confidence index policies; Agrawal (1995) made the indices sample-mean-based; Burnetas-Katehakis (1996) generalized optimal adaptive policies. Gaps: guarantees hold only as n grows so nothing is known at finite horizons; indices need the reward family (exponential families, or a distribution-specific large-deviation KL contraction); and the RL sources use epsilon-greedy heuristics with no regret theory. Room remains for a finite-time, distribution-free, trivially computable policy plus the first finite-time analysis of epsilon-greedy.","method":"Study index policies for rewards bounded in the unit interval whose exploration bonus comes from Hoeffding-type concentration, not distribution-specific rate functions. UCB1 plays the arm maximizing empirical mean plus square root of (2 ln n divided by play count). Prove a finite-time regret bound by bounding suboptimal-arm plays: split each play into optimal-arm underestimate, suboptimal-arm overestimate, and under-sampling; bound the first two with Hoeffding and a union bound over counts whose tails sum to a constant, yielding expected plays near eight ln n over the squared gap plus a constant, hence regret near the sum of eight ln n over gaps, uniform in n and independent of KL constants. Add refinements: an empirical-variance Bernstein pad, and an epoch variant whose constant approaches the Lai-Robbins optimum. Prove epsilon-greedy with per-step epsilon decaying like one over n attains log-n finite-time regret. Validate empirically versus Agrawal and Gittins indices on Bernoulli and normal arms."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior bandit theory holds only asymptotically and requires distribution-specific KL/large-deviation constants; the proposal targets finite-time, distribution-free guarantees under weaker assumptions (bounded rewards), which is a scope_mismatch. Secondary evidence_gap reflects the absence of finite-horizon guarantees. The central move is proving new finite-time regret bounds via Hoeffding/Bernstein concentration (formal_derivation), which also relaxes assumptions to broader reward classes (relax_extend_scope). Precisely identified bottleneck (asymptotic-only, KL-dependence). Not stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior works give bandit policies with asymptotic guarantees but no unified finite-time empirical comparison. Lai-Robbins 1985, Agrawal 1995, Burnetas-Katehakis 1996, and Yakowitz-Lowe 1991 prove log-n regret under different assumptions; Gittins 1989, Ishikida-Varaiya 1994, and Berry-Fristedt 1985 prove discounted-index optimality; Q-learning 1995 and Sutton-Barto 1998 give heuristics. Gaps: when the log-linear regret regime begins and whether empirical slopes match theoretical KL constants is unknown; policies are siloed by criterion and assumptions with no apples-to-apples comparison; robustness of parametric indices under misspecification versus nonparametric policies is unmeasured.","method":"Build a Bandit Policy Atlas benchmark comparing the Lai-Robbins KL index, Agrawal sample-mean index, Burnetas-Katehakis dual index, Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric index, Gittins discounted index, and an epsilon-greedy or Q-learning baseline over a factorial grid of distribution family, reward gap, arm count, and horizon. Four diagnostics: asymptotic-onset and KL-constant recovery via regret-versus-log-n fits; a misspecification-robustness matrix running parametric indices on mismatched families against the nonparametric policy; a cross-criterion map testing each policy under both regret and discounted reward; and a tuning-sensitivity sweep. Deliver phase diagrams of which policy dominates each region plus tables of onset horizons and recovered constants, turning asymptotic theory into finite-time empirical guidance."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a missing apples-to-apples finite-time empirical comparison of policies proven only asymptotically, plus unmeasured onset horizons and misspecification robustness — an evidence gap, with secondary scope_mismatch on asymptotic assumptions. The central move builds a benchmark with phase diagrams, diagnostics, and comparative studies (empirical_mapping); it also reconciles siloed policies across criteria (synthesis_unification secondary). Not superficial stitching since the benchmark asks specific mechanistic questions like KL-constant recovery."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"All of the regret analyses in this corpus are *asymptotic*. Lai & Robbins (1985) prove the celebrated liminf_n R_n/log n ≥ Σ (μ*−μ_j)/I(θ_j,θ*) lower bound and construct index rules that meet it only \"as n→∞\"; moreover their indices require the entire reward history and are tailored to specific parametric families (normal, Bernoulli, Poisson, exponential). Agrawal (1995) simplifies these to sample-mean-based upper-confidence-bound (UCB) indices, but the guarantee is still purely asymptotic (Theorem 2.2 bounds limsup_n E[T_n(j)]/log n), is proved via large-deviations lemmas, requires tuning an infinite triangular array {a_ni}, and its optimal constant depends on the unknown Kullback–Leibler number (hence on distributional knowledge). Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) give asymptotically optimal but family-specific \"dual\" indices; Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) give nonparametric but again asymptotic rates; Ishikida & Varaiya (1994) and the Gittins-index line address discounted/average-reward optimality, not finite-horizon regret.\n\nThis leaves a concrete gap. No result here bounds the expected regret of a *single, simple, distribution-free* policy *for every finite n*, with explicit numerical constants. This matters because (i) asymptotic statements of the form limsup R_n/log n ≤ c hide lower-order terms and burn-in periods that can be arbitrarily large at any horizon a practitioner actually faces; (ii) the achieved constants require knowing the reward family or a KL number, which defeats the purpose of \"learning\"; and (iii) the sequences {a_ni} and history-dependent indices are cumbersome to implement. The corpus itself gives the two ingredients needed to close the gap but never combines them: a matching Ω(log n) lower bound (Lai–Robbins), and the observation (Yakowitz–Lowe, Agrawal) that under a boundedness/moment postulate one can control the number of suboptimal pulls via tail inequalities.","method":"Contribution type: a formal derivation — a non-asymptotic regret theorem for a minimal index policy, plus a conceptual taxonomy that separates asymptotic from uniform (finite-time) optimality.\n\n1. Formal model and conceptual distinction. Fix K arms with rewards in [0,1] (bounded postulate, as in Yakowitz–Lowe). Let Δ_j = μ*−μ_j and T_j(n) the pulls of arm j. Define three nested notions of optimality and organize the prior work into this taxonomy: (a) *consistency* (n^{-1}ES_n→μ*, Lai–Robbins eq. 1.12); (b) *asymptotic order optimality* (limsup R_n/log n < ∞, Agrawal/Burnetas–Katehakis/Yakowitz); (c) *uniform (anytime) finite-time optimality*: there exist explicit constants such that R_n ≤ f(n) for EVERY n≥1. The claim is that (c) is strictly stronger and has never been established in this corpus; the derivation targets (c).\n\n2. The policy. UCB-index rule: play each arm once; thereafter at round n pull argmax_j [ x̄_j + √(2 ln n / T_j(n)) ]. The index uses only the sample mean (answering Agrawal's simplification goal) and a *deterministic, family-independent* confidence radius, eliminating the tuned array {a_ni} and the history-dependent, KL-specific indices of Lai–Robbins.\n\n3. Key lemma (derivation). Using only the Chernoff–Hoeffding inequality for bounded variables, P(|x̄_{j,s}−μ_j| ≥ √(2 ln n / s)) ≤ n^{-4}, derive that a suboptimal arm j is pulled at round n only if one of three events holds: the optimal arm's index under-estimates μ*, arm j's mean over-estimates μ_j, or arm j has been pulled fewer than ℓ_j = ⌈8 ln n / Δ_j²⌉ times. Bounding the first two by a summable tail (Σ_t t·t^{-4}) gives the deterministic-threshold argument.\n\n4. Main theorem (finite-time bound). E[T_j(n)] ≤ 8 ln n / Δ_j² + 1 + π²/3, hence for every finite n,\n   R_n ≤ Σ_{j:Δ_j>0} ( 8 ln n / Δ_j ) + (1 + π²/3) Σ_j Δ_j.\nThis holds uniformly in n with fully explicit constants and no distributional knowledge beyond boundedness.\n\n5. Matching and tightening. (a) Compare with the Lai–Robbins bound: the derived bound is O(log n) in n, matching their lower-bound *order* at all horizons, with a distribution-free 1/Δ_j constant that upper-bounds the KL-based constant via Pinsker's inequality — making explicit the price of family-independence. (b) Derive a worst-case (distribution-free over Δ) corollary R_n = O(√(K n log n)) by optimizing over the Δ_j. (c) Generalize the confidence radius to √(α ln n / T_j(n)) and derive the exploration–exploitation trade-off: prove the bound holds for any α>1, with the constant 8 replaced by 2α/Δ_j and the additive term by 1 + 1/(α−1)·(something), exposing how the leading constant degrades as α→1 and quantifying robustness.\n\n6. Feasibility. All steps are elementary (Hoeffding + union bound + geometric/ζ(2) series summation) and self-contained given the corpus; the policy is trivially implementable and can be validated empirically against Agrawal's and Lai–Robbins' rules to show smaller finite-horizon regret and absence of burn-in, confirming the asymptotic-vs-finite-time distinction the theorem formalizes."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.94,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior guarantees are purely asymptotic and family-specific — a mismatch between the analysis regime (n->infty, known KL) and what practitioners at finite n need; there is also a puzzle-like contradiction that asymptotic optimality hides arbitrarily large burn-in. The central move is a non-asymptotic regret theorem via Hoeffding + union bound, plus a conceptual taxonomy separating asymptotic from finite-time optimality — clearly formal_derivation. Extending guarantees to weaker assumptions (distribution-free, every finite n) supports relax_extend_scope as secondary. Bottleneck is precisely identified (asymptotic-only, KL-dependent constants); not superficial stitching though it does combine a known lower bound with tail inequalities."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"This corpus proves O(log n) regret is optimal for the bandit, with a Kullback-Leibler constant (Lai & Robbins 1985), and gives attaining index policies: Agrawal's (1995) sample-mean upper-confidence indices with a log inflation width, and Burnetas & Katehakis's (1996) KL-dual indices. Gittins indices (1989; Ishikida & Varaiya 1994) are exact only for discounted Bayesian problems with known priors; exact finite-horizon DP (Berry & Fristedt 1985) is intractable, and Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) note Bayes-optimal solutions are hard to compute. Three gaps: (1) optimality is asymptotic and horizon-agnostic, so the inflation width and constants are untuned for a finite known horizon T where finite-sample regret is very sensitive to them; (2) Burnetas-Katehakis indices need a KL-projection optimization per arm per step; (3) no source treats index/exploration-schedule design as an optimization or search problem tuned to horizon and instance distribution, though Holland's adaptive search and Q-learning-for-bandits show policies can be discovered by search. This leaves room to keep KL-efficiency while minimizing finite-horizon regret and cutting computation.","method":"Cast horizon-aware index-policy design as offline search anchored on KL-optimal structure, deployed with amortized look-ahead allocation. (1) Parametric family: index I_a = mean_a + c(theta)*phi(N_a, t, T, KLgap_a; theta), constrained so that as T grows phi reduces to the Lai-Robbins/Agrawal/Burnetas-Katehakis asymptotic width (preserving asymptotic efficiency), while for finite T it damps exploration as t approaches T and shifts budget to small-gap arms. (2) Offline meta-optimization: over a training distribution of instances (varied gaps, arm counts, horizons; Bernoulli, exponential-family, nonparametric finite-support), use derivative-free search (genetic algorithm per Holland, or CMA-ES/Bayesian optimization) to find theta minimizing Monte-Carlo finite-horizon regret, made efficient by racing/successive-halving screening and common-random-number variance reduction, with a penalty forbidding regret above a fixed multiple of the Lai-Robbins bound. (3) Amortized computation: precompute the Burnetas-Katehakis KL-dual index offline as an interpolated function of (mean, count) so per-step use is a lookup; each step also solve a small convex subproblem allocating the T-t remaining pulls to minimize an upper-confidence regret bound from plug-in KL estimates, using its marginal values to scale the index near the horizon end, then play the max-index arm. (4) Evaluate against UCB/Agrawal, Burnetas-Katehakis, and Gittins across horizons and arm counts, checking recovery of KL-optimal constants as T grows plus lower finite-horizon regret and cheaper per-step cost."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.62,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as asymptotic optimality not matching finite-horizon regimes (scope mismatch) plus per-step computation cost (resource bottleneck). The central move casts index-policy design as offline derivative-free search/meta-optimization tuned to horizon and instance distribution, which is optimization_search, with a relax/extend-scope flavor (finite-T conditions). There is some superficial stitching of GA/CMA-ES onto KL-index structure, but a specific bottleneck (untuned inflation width for finite T) is identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The classical route to O(log n) regret in stochastic multi-armed bandits relies fundamentally on light-tailed reward assumptions and on the *sample mean* as the summary statistic. Lai & Robbins (\"Asymptotically efficient adaptive allocation rules\") and Burnetas & Katehakis (\"Optimal adaptive policies\") build indices from upper confidence bounds whose optimal constants come from Kullback–Leibler / large-deviation rate functions; Burnetas–Katehakis's key assumption (A2) explicitly requires estimators whose deviations are controlled \"as the mean of i.i.d. random variables with finite moment generating function in a neighborhood of zero,\" verified via large deviations. Agrawal's \"Sample mean based index policies with O(log n) regret\" makes the dependence on the sample mean explicit and states that \"all subsequent results ... are based entirely on ... large deviations,\" using the cumulant generating function c_p(θ)=log∫e^{θx}p(dx) being finite and steep — i.e., a finite MGF, hence essentially light (sub-exponential) tails; its worked examples are one-parameter exponential families (Gaussian, Bernoulli, Poisson).\n\nYakowitz & Lowe (\"Nonparametric bandit methods\") pinpoint exactly where this breaks. When only finite moments are assumed (heavy tails), a sample-mean rule can only guarantee a *polynomial* deviation bound P(d,n)=C/n^α (Chebyshev/Fuk–Nagaev), which forces their test-time schedule to grow as x(n)=O(n^{1/(1+α)}); only in the bounded-arm (exponential-tail) case do they recover x(n)=O(log n). Crucially, they prove this is not an artifact of loose analysis: for the sample mean one \"cannot improve on the Chebyshev bound\" uniformly over variance-1 distributions. Thus, under realistic heavy-tailed rewards (finance, queueing/network delays, insurance losses), the entire asymptotically-efficient O(log n) theory collapses to polynomial regret, and no index policy in these works attains logarithmic regret. The gap is that the bottleneck is the *estimator*, not the bandit principle — yet every one of these works hard-wires the sample mean into the index.","method":"Relax the light-tail assumption underpinning O(log n) index policies by decoupling the bandit index from the sample mean and rebuilding it around a *robust* mean estimator that concentrates exponentially even under only a finite (1+ε)-moment condition. Concretely:\n\n1. Robust index construction. For each arm a with T_a(t) observations, replace the sample mean m_a in the UCB index with a robust location estimate μ̂_a: (i) a median-of-means estimator (split observations into k≈⌈c·log t⌉ blocks, take the median of block means), and/or (ii) an adaptively-truncated empirical mean with truncation level b_t chosen to trade bias against variance under the assumed moment. Define the index g_a(t)=μ̂_a + r_a(t), and play argmax_a g_a(t), preserving the simplicity of Agrawal-style sample-based indices.\n\n2. Confidence width from robust concentration, not from the MGF. Choose the inflation r_a(t) using the exponential deviation guarantee of the robust estimator: under only finite variance σ², median-of-means satisfies P(|μ̂_a−μ_a|>d) ≤ exp(−c·T_a·d²/σ²), i.e., precisely the Yakowitz–Lowe \"form (3.1b)\" exp(−τn) that they could previously obtain only for *bounded* arms. Under a weaker (1+ε)-moment assumption, use the truncated estimator's bias-corrected tail bound (via Fuk–Nagaev) to obtain an analogous near-exponential bound. This lets r_a(t) ≈ C·σ̂_a·sqrt(log t / T_a) with an empirically estimated robust scale σ̂_a.\n\n3. Regret analysis by substitution into the existing frameworks. Because the robust estimator restores an exponential P(d,n), plug it into (a) the Yakowitz–Lowe test-time recursion x(n)=2ΣP(d,x(j)) — whose solution is O(log n) exactly when P is exponential — and (b) the Burnetas–Katehakis assumption (A2), which only requires Σ P(|θ̂−θ|>ε)=o(log n): the robust estimator makes (A2) hold for heavy-tailed nonparametric families without a finite MGF. This yields a Σ_a O(σ_a²·log n / Δ_a) regret bound for arms with only finite variance, and a graceful (1+ε)-moment version, extending asymptotically-efficient O(log n) allocation from light-tailed exponential families to heavy-tailed arms.\n\n4. Matching lower bound and a \"robust divergence\" constant. Mirror Lai–Robbins/Burnetas–Katehakis by deriving a class-restricted lower bound for heavy-tailed families and identifying the leading constant as a robust analogue of the KL number (a variance/moment-based information quantity that plays the role Agrawal's large-deviation rate function played in the light-tailed case), characterizing when the robust index is asymptotically optimal.\n\n5. Weaker-knowledge and broader-scope extensions. (i) Unknown scale: estimate σ̂_a robustly online. (ii) Unknown moment order ε: calibrate the truncation level by a Lepski-type rule so the policy adapts to the heaviest admissible tail. (iii) Infinite-arm reservoirs: extend Yakowitz–Lowe's \"infinitude of arms\" section, where robust estimation now permits pulling from heavy-tailed arm populations while retaining rate guarantees.\n\nFeasibility: the method reuses the exact index-policy machinery and proof templates of these sources; only the estimator and its concentration input change, and simulations against heavy-tailed reward distributions (e.g., Pareto, Student-t) can directly demonstrate the transition from the polynomial n^{1/(1+α)} regret of sample-mean rules to the logarithmic regret of the robust index."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is a scope mismatch: prior O(log n) index policies hard-wire the sample mean and require light-tailed (finite MGF) assumptions that collapse under realistic heavy-tailed rewards. The core move is relaxing that assumption by swapping in a robust estimator that restores exponential concentration, extending the existing proof frameworks to weaker moment conditions—clearly relax_extend_scope, with robustification secondary via robust estimators. Not surface stitching: the substitution of a robust estimator into the concentration bottleneck is a precise mechanistic identification (bottleneck is the estimator, not the bandit principle)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works are classical bandit theory built on one primitive: the sample mean plus a confidence bonus. Lai-Robbins (1985), Agrawal (1995), Burnetas-Katehakis (1996), and Yakowitz-Lowe (1991) all prove logarithmic regret only under light tails (an MGF or bounded arms), a known reward range, and clean i.i.d. data. Gap: these sample-mean indices are brittle. With heavy tails (finite variance, no MGF) the large-deviation proofs fail, and a single adversarial or error outlier per arm can distort the index and lock onto a bad arm; scale must also be known. Real clinical trials and adaptive experiments have outliers, heavy tails, and misspecified scale, yet no listed work degrades gracefully instead of catastrophically.","method":"Robustify the index policy by replacing the sample mean with a robust estimator and using robust confidence widths, keeping logarithmic regret under only finite variance while tolerating an eta fraction of corrupted rewards per arm. For each arm compute a median-of-means or trimmed-mean estimate, then play the arm with the largest value of that estimate plus a bonus. Derive the bonus from median-of-means concentration, which depends on variance alone (handling heavy tails without an MGF), plus a term proportional to eta times a robust scale so it provably brackets the true mean under contamination. A scale-free variant estimates scale online from the interquartile range of bucket means, removing the known-range assumption. Prove finite-time regret equal to the classical logarithmic term plus a controlled linear-in-eta contamination floor, with a matching lower bound that the floor is unavoidable, recovering classical constants as eta goes to zero. Evaluate against sample-mean UCB and Yakowitz-Lowe under heavy tails, adversarial outliers, and misspecified ranges."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.86,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"Gap is framed as brittleness of sample-mean indices under heavy tails/outliers/misspecified scale (failure_risk_gap), with a scope aspect since assumptions are unrealistic. Central move is robustifying the estimator to keep logarithmic regret under weaker assumptions while tolerating contamination, plus formal bounds. Precise bottleneck: MGF/light-tail assumption and outlier sensitivity of sample mean."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The sources describe three disconnected views of one object, a per-arm index from that arm's own history. The Bayesian Gittins tradition (Berry and Fristedt 1985; allocation-indices review; Ishikida and Varaiya 1994) is exactly optimal, decomposing N arms into N one-dimensional indices, where an arm's index is the retirement pension making one indifferent between continuing and quitting; but it needs a known prior and fixed discount, is hard to compute, and lacks regret bounds. The frequentist tradition (Lai and Robbins 1985; Agrawal 1995; Burnetas and Katehakis 1996; Yakowitz and Lowe 1991) uses Kullback-Leibler upper confidence bounds achieving optimal logarithmic regret from the sample mean alone, but is undiscounted and never linked to the retirement value. The RL tradition (Q-learning for bandit problems 1995; Sutton and Barto; Holland) learns indices on-line by stochastic approximation, only for the discounted case and without regret guarantees. No source unifies these three justifications of the same quantity.","method":"Propose a calibrated confidence index unifying the three views. Define each arm's index as the retirement pension at which continuing equals quitting (Ishikida and Varaiya), computed under a data-driven posterior and effective discount beta; this equals the Gittins index for fixed prior and discount. Prove that as beta approaches one, with concentration scaled so the exploration budget equals log n, this index converges to the Lai-Robbins and Agrawal Kullback-Leibler upper confidence bound, showing the retirement fixed point and the confidence supremum are the same variational problem, first for exponential families then nonparametrically. Estimate it on-line by a Q-learning restart recursion using only the sample mean and play count. Anneal beta with each arm's play count so the index shifts from a Gittins exploration bonus to the log-n confidence width; play the largest index. Using Agrawal large-deviation lemmas and Ishikida-Varaiya convexity, prove optimal logarithmic regret while matching Gittins in the discounted regime, and validate that it recovers tabulated Bernoulli Gittins indices and confidence-bound regret across parametric and nonparametric arms."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames three disconnected traditions (Bayesian Gittins, frequentist KL-UCB, RL Q-learning) as views of the same per-arm index that no prior work unifies — a clear bridge_opportunity, with an explanatory element asking why these are the same quantity. The core move is proving they are the same variational problem and deriving a unified index with regret bounds, i.e., synthesis_unification backed by formal_derivation (convergence proofs, large-deviation lemmas, convexity). Not superficial stitching because it proves a substantive equivalence rather than concatenating methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works form two historically separate streams rarely operationalized in one tool. A frequentist regret stream builds upper-confidence / large-deviation index policies for the undiscounted horizon: Lai & Robbins' asymptotically efficient rules, Agrawal's sample-mean O(log n) indices from Kullback-Leibler large deviations, Burnetas & Katehakis' dual-problem indices, and Yakowitz & Lowe's nonparametric strategies, all targeting KL-calibrated logarithmic regret with little or no prior. A Bayesian discounted stream builds Gittins dynamic-allocation indices (Gittins, Berry & Fristedt, Ishikida & Varaiya), exactly optimal for geometrically discounted reward via per-arm retirement problems, but needing a prior, heavy dynamic programming, and tied to the discounted (not regret) criterion. A reinforcement-learning stream (Sutton, Watkins' Q-learning for bandit problems, Holland) shows Gittins-type indices can be learned model-free by solving the per-arm stopping problem, but gives no finite-time regret guarantee. These literatures are disconnected on three axes: objective (regret vs. discounted vs. average reward, only partly bridged asymptotically by Ishikida & Varaiya), assumptions (KL/parametric vs. Bayesian prior vs. model-free), and machinery (confidence bounds vs. dynamic programming vs. temporal-difference learning). No artifact lets a practitioner take an arbitrary, possibly nonparametric arm and obtain one index that is exploration-aware like Gittins, model-free like Q-learning, and provably logarithmic-regret like Lai-Robbins. The bridge opportunity is to unify these streams in one deployable engine and expose that the confidence inflation of frequentist indices and the value-of-information of Gittins indices are two views of the same exploration bonus.","method":"Build BRIDGE-INDEX, a modular open-source index-policy synthesis engine whose central contribution is the artifact plus a new hybrid Bootstrapped Gittins-UCB (BGU) index. Layer (a) nonparametric belief: per arm keep an empirical reward distribution and a Bayesian-bootstrap/Dirichlet posterior over it, needing no parametric family, generalizing Yakowitz-Lowe with Pollard's empirical-process tools and replacing the parametric priors Gittins methods require. Layer (b) index computation: per arm solve the one-armed retirement stopping problem for a Gittins-type index model-free via a lightweight Q-learning/value-iteration routine (Watkins, Sutton) run on bootstrap rollouts of the posterior rather than a known kernel. Layer (c) regret calibration: combine the discounted Gittins-type index with a large-deviation/KL confidence term (Agrawal, Burnetas-Katehakis), annealing the effective discount toward 1 with horizon so the index reduces to a KL upper-confidence bound in the undiscounted limit, converting a discounted-optimal quantity into an O(log n)-regret one and unifying value-of-information and confidence-inflation views of exploration. Layer (d) harness: reimplement Lai-Robbins, Agrawal, Burnetas-Katehakis, Yakowitz-Lowe, pure Bayesian Gittins, and plain Q-learning as baselines so any arm model runs under all policies through one interface. Deliverables: (i) a theorem that annealed BGU inherits Agrawal-style O(log n) KL-optimal regret while approximating the Gittins index at fixed discount, using Ishikida-Varaiya's discounted-to-average-reward asymptotics as the crossing point; (ii) experiments over exponential-family, heavy-tailed, and nonparametric bounded arms comparing regret, discounted return, and compute, showing one learned index tracks Gittins early and Lai-Robbins late; (iii) a released deployment workflow turning \"give an arm sampler, get a calibrated policy\" into one call. This makes the three communities interoperable inside one calibrated, model-free, nonparametric, regret-guaranteed system."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames the gap as three disconnected literatures (frequentist regret, Bayesian Gittins, RL Q-learning) that could be unified, which is a clear bridge_opportunity. The construction move is synthesis_unification—combining these streams into one hybrid index and claiming they are two views of the same exploration bonus—with a secondary artifact_system deliverable (BRIDGE-INDEX engine). There is some risk of surface stitching since much of the design reimplements and layers existing methods, but the annealing-of-discount mechanism to convert Gittins to KL-UCB is a specific unifying claim, raising bottleneck specificity above generic."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Two bandit literatures are disconnected. The statistics/large-deviations tradition (Lai and Robbins 1985; Agrawal 1995; Burnetas and Katehakis 1996; Yakowitz and Lowe 1991) proves index policies attain order log n regret with a Kullback-Leibler-optimal constant, but only asymptotically and often needing the reward-distribution family. The reinforcement-learning tradition (Sutton and Barto; Duff's Q-learning for bandits; Gittins indices; Holland) treats bandits as the exploration testbed but uses simple distribution-free heuristics such as epsilon-greedy and softmax, or discounted Bayesian Gittins indices, with no undiscounted finite-horizon regret guarantee. A practitioner with a fixed finite budget needs a guarantee valid at every n, no distributional knowledge, and constant per-step cost. Neither stream delivers this: no source gives a finite-time, distribution-free logarithmic regret bound for a simple sample-mean index policy, nor a finite-time account of when RL heuristics are near-optimal. Bridging the two yields provably good, practical exploration.","method":"Transplant the confidence-bound principle of Lai-Robbins and Agrawal into a finite-time, distribution-free algorithm. Define UCB1: for rewards in the unit interval, at step n play the arm maximizing its sample mean plus the square root of two times ln n divided by its pull count. Prove a bound uniform in n: expected regret at most eight times the sum over suboptimal arms of ln n over the gap, plus a constant times the sum of gaps, using only Chernoff-Hoeffding tails, requiring no distribution family and constant time per step. Add a variance-aware UCB-Tuned variant using empirical variance in the radius. Then give epsilon-greedy with a decreasing schedule of order arms over squared-gap over n a matching finite-time logarithmic regret proof, bridging RL heuristics to the statistics theory. Validate empirically against epsilon-greedy, softmax, and Gittins/Q-learning baselines on Bernoulli and bounded instances, reporting finite-horizon regret distributions."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.62,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior index policies achieve log n regret only asymptotically and require distributional knowledge; the proposal seeks finite-time, distribution-free guarantees (scope_mismatch), while also connecting statistics and RL traditions (bridge_opportunity secondary). The core move transplants confidence-bound principles into a finite-horizon, distribution-free regime with weaker assumptions (relax_extend_scope), delivered via new regret bounds/proofs (formal_derivation). Precise bottleneck identified (no finite-time distribution-free log bound), not boilerplate, and the bridging is substantive rather than superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The corpus reveals three mature but disconnected literatures on the same problem of sequentially allocating pulls among stochastic arms. Frequentist asymptotic index policies (Lai & Robbins 1985; Agrawal 1995; Burnetas & Katehakis 1996; Yakowitz & Lowe 1991) optimize regret and give an instance-dependent Kullback-Leibler lower bound and UCB rules attaining it, but almost entirely asymptotically. Bayesian/Gittins-index work (Berry & Fristedt 1985; Gittins 1989; Ishikida & Varaiya 1994) proves index optimality under discounted reward, a different objective. RL/AI heuristics (Sutton & Barto 1998; Q-learning for bandits 1995; Holland 1992) use epsilon-greedy, softmax, Q-learning, and evolutionary search without guarantees. The bridge opportunity: these streams use incompatible objectives, assumptions, and evaluation practices, so no one has used Lai & Robbins's exact computable KL lower bound as a common yardstick to compare a Gittins index, a Q-learning learner, a genetic searcher, and nonparametric UCB rules on one empirical map. This matters because the theory is asymptotic while practitioners work in finite time: we do not know at which horizons the O(log n) constants govern behavior, how far each family sits from the lower bound in finite time, or how they trade off under misspecification and tuning.","method":"Empirical Mapping: build an open benchmark and diagnostic suite placing all three traditions on one theory-anchored scale. A common harness reimplements frequentist indices (Lai-Robbins UCB, Agrawal sample-mean, Burnetas-Katehakis dual-index, Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric), Bayesian/Gittins indices computed by dynamic programming at several discount factors, and RL/AI heuristics (epsilon-greedy, softmax, Q-learning for bandits, a genetic-algorithm searcher), each with an identical choose-arm/observe-reward API. A controlled instance grid varies distribution family (Bernoulli, Poisson, exponential, Gaussian, bounded nonparametric, heavy-tailed), gaps, arm count K, variance, and horizon n over several orders of magnitude, plus a misspecification axis where parametric policies face violated assumptions. Theory-anchored metrics compute the Lai-Robbins lower bound via the exact KL number and report each policy's finite-time regret as a normalized regret-to-lower-bound ratio, the empirical regret slope in log n, the crossover horizon where log-linear behavior begins, and discounted-reward performance, so all objectives are commensurable by scoring every policy on both regret and discounted criteria. Diagnostics map heuristics' sensitivity to free parameters and parametric indices' robustness under misspecification, attaching confidence bands across many replicates. Synthesis produces phase diagrams showing which family dominates as a function of instance features and regressions relating normalized regret to those features, releasing the benchmark, trajectory datasets, and phase-diagram atlas. This gives the disconnected communities a shared computable yardstick and common finite-time evaluation, revealing where asymptotically optimal indices, Bayesian Gittins rules, and RL/evolutionary heuristics actually win or lose."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal frames the gap as three disconnected literatures (frequentist, Bayesian/Gittins, RL/AI) that could be compared on a common theory-anchored yardstick, and notes finite-time evaluation is missing (evidence_gap). The central move is building a benchmark and diagnostic suite with phase diagrams and normalized regret metrics (empirical_mapping), with a synthesis flavor from unifying objectives. The re-implement-everything-and-compare framing carries some stitching risk, though the KL lower bound anchor gives it a specific yardstick. Note the actual historical paper was a formal finite-time regret bound derivation; this recasting is empirical-mapping oriented."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Across the provided literature the identical stochastic multi-armed bandit problem is analyzed by two mature but largely disconnected \"index\" theories, plus a third learning-based community, each with its own optimality criterion.\n\n(A) Bayesian dynamic-allocation-index theory: the Gittins–Jones dynamic allocation index / break-even value A(F,A) developed in Berry & Fristedt's \"Bandit problems\" (1985) and Gittins' \"Multi-armed bandit allocation indices\" (1989). For geometric discounting this decouples k arms into k one-armed problems and is exactly optimal for discounted Bayes reward. Duff's \"Q-learning for bandit problems\" (1995), together with the RL program of Sutton (1998) and Holland's adaptive systems (1992), shows these indices can be *learned online* via temporal-difference/Q-learning. But this stream's optimality notion (discounted Bayes reward) says nothing about finite-horizon regret, the discount factor β is an exogenous modeling constant, and the online RL exploration is heuristic with no regret guarantee.\n\n(B) Frequentist adaptive-allocation theory: the Lai–Robbins (1985) asymptotic lower bound Σ(μ*−μ_j)/I(θ_j,θ*), Agrawal's (1995) sample-mean upper-confidence index, Burnetas–Katehakis (1996) dual-KL indices attaining nm*−M(θ)log n, and Yakowitz–Lowe (1991) nonparametric rates. This stream gives exact asymptotic regret optimality through KL/large-deviation *confidence* bonuses, but has no notion of prior, discounting, value function, or online value learning; its indices come from concentration, not from optimal lookahead.\n\nBoth streams compute the same object — index = sample mean + an uncertainty bonus — yet no formal derivation links the Gittins \"prospective\" bonus (value of information under posterior lookahead, driven by β) to the KL \"confidence\" bonus (driven by allowed horizon n). The bridge opportunity: connect the Bayesian/RL value-learning community with the statistical regret community so that (i) online Q-learning agents inherit provable Lai–Robbins/Burnetas–Katehakis regret optimality, and (ii) the discount factor — currently an arbitrary constant — is given a principled, regret-optimal, horizon-dependent meaning.","method":"Contribution is a formal derivation unifying the two index theories and their optimality criteria, with a learnable corollary for the RL community.\n\n1. Taxonomy / conceptual distinction. Formalize any arm index as I_a = μ̂_a + Bonus_a, and distinguish two bonus generators: (i) a *prospective* bonus B_G(state; β) = the Gittins break-even excess over the posterior mean, defined by the discounted one-armed stopping problem of Berry–Fristedt/Gittins; (ii) a *confidence* bonus B_C(state; n) = the KL inflation radius of Burnetas–Katehakis/Agrawal. This isolates what each community actually optimizes and exposes them as two parameterizations (β vs. n) of one quantity.\n\n2. Correspondence theorem. For single-parameter exponential-family arms with conjugate priors, derive the vanishing-discount (β→1) asymptotic expansion of B_G via a Laplace/large-deviations analysis of the stopping problem that defines the Gittins index (reusing the large-deviation lemmas Agrawal already employs). Prove that under the horizon-tied annealing schedule 1−β_n ∝ 1/log n, the leading-order Gittins exploration radius coincides, up to o(1), with the KL confidence radius that yields the Lai–Robbins constant. This is the formal bridge: annealed-discount Gittins index ≈ KL-UCB index.\n\n3. Consequence theorem (\"vanishing-discount regret\"). Show that the policy playing the annealed-discount Gittins index attains regret nμ*−ES_n = M(θ)log n + o(log n), matching the Lai–Robbins lower bound and the Burnetas–Katehakis constant M(θ). This gives a single objective bridging discounted Bayes optimality and frequentist regret optimality, and endows β with a regret-optimal interpretation (β as an inverse-log-horizon exploration temperature).\n\n4. Learnable corollary. Because Duff-style Q-learning already estimates per-arm one-armed-bandit values, show that a temporal-difference update with the derived discount schedule β_n and posterior-based optimistic initialization *provably* realizes the KL-optimal index — converting heuristic RL exploration into asymptotically efficient exploration. Prove a necessity result: mis-scaled discounts (fixed β, or 1−β decaying too fast/slow) yield linear regret or a suboptimal constant, characterizing the admissible schedules.\n\n5. Scope and verification. Verify the exponential-family assumptions for Bernoulli, normal, and exponential arms; use Agrawal's contraction principle and Yakowitz–Lowe finite-moment/bounded-support conditions to extend the correspondence to nonparametric bounded arms. Complement the proofs with simulations confirming that annealed-discount Q-learning tracks KL-UCB regret and that the predicted β_n schedule is tight, and quantify the finite-time bias term.\n\nThis addresses the gap by supplying the missing derivation that makes the Bayesian/RL index and the frequentist confidence index one theory, giving RL agents regret guarantees and giving discounting a regret-based justification."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as two disconnected index theories (Bayesian/Gittins-RL and frequentist Lai-Robbins/KL) that compute the same object without a formal link — a bridge opportunity, with an explanation-gap flavor (why the bonuses coincide). The core move is unifying the two theories via a correspondence theorem plus derivations (formal_derivation as secondary). The bottleneck is precise: the missing derivation tying discount annealing 1-beta~1/log n to KL confidence radius. Not superficial stitching since a nontrivial asymptotic correspondence is proposed."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two research communities have, for decades, circled the same core question — how to allocate a scarce budget of trials among competing options whose payoffs are unknown — yet they have never been properly connected.\n\n(1) The regret-optimal bandit community. Lai & Robbins (1985) established the O(log n) regret lower bound and asymptotically efficient allocation rules; Agrawal (1995) reduced these to simple sample-mean upper-confidence-bound (UCB) indices with the same O(log n) regret; Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) derived asymptotically optimal indices as solutions to dual problems, including for nonparametric discrete distributions; Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) gave nonparametric index rules with guaranteed convergence rates; and the Gittins-index line (Gittins 1989; Ishikida & Varaiya 1994; Berry & Fristedt 1985) proved index optimality for discounted and arm-acquiring bandits. This literature produces finite-time, provable guarantees on how many trials are \"wasted\" on inferior options.\n\n(2) The evolutionary-search / genetic-algorithm community. Holland's schema analysis (Adaptation in Natural and Artificial Systems, 1992) explicitly justified the genetic algorithm as an implicit solution to a multi-armed bandit: competing schemata (hyperplane partitions of the search space) are \"arms,\" and fitness-proportional selection is argued to allocate reproductive trials near-optimally via an exponentially-increasing rule derived from a two-armed-bandit heuristic. Sutton (1998/1992) confirms Holland's genetic algorithms and classifier systems are historically part of the same reinforcement-learning family that later produced Q-learning for bandits.\n\nThe bridge opportunity: Holland's bandit justification predates and never adopted the regret-optimal index machinery. Fitness-proportional selection is the exponential-allocation heuristic that Lai–Robbins-style analysis shows is generally NOT log-regret optimal, so canonical evolutionary search carries no finite-time guarantee on evaluations spent on inferior regions. Conversely, the bandit-index literature never took up Holland's structured, hierarchical, arm-generating search space as an application — its arms are typically a small fixed flat set. Neither community connected schema refinement (which continually creates new candidate partitions) to the arm-acquiring bandit theory of Whittle/Berry-Fristedt/Ishikida-Varaiya. Closing this gap matters because black-box combinatorial optimization is dominated by evaluation cost, and a principled, regret-bounded allocation of evaluations across schemata would give evolutionary search the sample-efficiency guarantees it has lacked, while giving bandit theory a rich, high-dimensional, arm-acquiring testbed.","method":"Proposed method: Index-Guided Hyperplane Search (IGHS) — replace the exponential fitness-proportional allocation at the heart of Holland's schema theory with provably efficient bandit index policies, and treat schema refinement as an arm-acquiring bandit. This is an optimization/search contribution: the algorithm is an adaptive resource-allocation scheme for the finite budget of fitness evaluations.\n\n1. Schemata as bandit arms. Following Holland, partition the search space by hyperplanes: at any node, a set of competing schemata (e.g., fixing a coordinate/factor to each of its values, conditioned on already-fixed coordinates) are the \"arms.\" Pulling an arm = drawing one candidate consistent with that schema and evaluating its (bounded, unknown-distribution) fitness. This directly instantiates the informal bandit that Holland only argued heuristically.\n\n2. Regret-optimal allocation instead of proportional selection. Allocate each successive evaluation to the schema with the highest index rather than in proportion to observed fitness. Use Agrawal's sample-mean UCB index for the bounded/nonparametric case and the Burnetas–Katehakis dual index (and Yakowitz–Lowe nonparametric index) where finer distributional structure is available. By Lai–Robbins/Agrawal this guarantees that evaluations spent on inferior schemata at each node grow only as O(log n), yielding the finite-time sample-efficiency bound canonical GAs lack.\n\n3. Refinement as arm acquisition. When a schema's index dominates, refine it by fixing an additional coordinate, spawning a new, finer set of competing sub-schemata — i.e., new arms appear over time. Crossover/mutation likewise propose genuinely novel schemata. Model the whole process as an arm-acquiring/superprocess bandit (Whittle 1981 via Berry–Fristedt; Ishikida–Varaiya 1994), and use the nested-index / retirement-pension optimality results to decide the principled trade-off between exploiting refined arms and acquiring newly generated ones (the retirement value sets an explicit exploration budget for novelty).\n\n4. Handling non-stationarity. Because conditional fitness distributions shift as partitions are refined and the population concentrates, track them with the discounted Gittins index formulation (Ishikida–Varaiya's discounted/average-reward extensions) or windowed sample means, keeping indices valid under drift.\n\n5. Analysis and evaluation. (a) Theory: compose per-node O(log n) regret across the refinement hierarchy to prove a bound on total evaluations wasted on suboptimal schema paths, and contrast it analytically with the exponential-allocation regret of fitness-proportional selection — making precise where Holland's heuristic is suboptimal. Use Pollard-style empirical-process / large-deviation tools (as Agrawal does) for the nonparametric case. (b) Experiments: on standard combinatorial black-box benchmarks (e.g., deceptive/trap functions, NK-landscapes, max-sat), compare IGHS against canonical fitness-proportional GA, a flat UCB bandit over full solutions, and Gittins-index baselines, measuring fitness reached per evaluation budget and empirical regret. Ablate the three ingredients (index vs proportional allocation; arm-acquisition rule; drift tracking) to isolate the contribution of each bridged idea.\n\nThis addresses the gap by importing finite-time regret optimality into evolutionary search and, reciprocally, supplying the bandit-index literature with a concrete, hierarchical, arm-acquiring optimization problem, unifying Holland's schema theory with Lai–Robbins/Agrawal/Burnetas–Katehakis/Gittins index policies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as connecting two disconnected communities (regret-optimal bandits vs. Holland's genetic-algorithm schema theory), a clear bridge_opportunity; evaluation-cost/sample-efficiency framing gives a resource_bottleneck secondary. The core move is unifying schema theory with bandit index policies (synthesis_unification), with an adaptive resource-allocation/search mechanism as secondary. There is some risk of A+B stitching since it maps existing UCB/Gittins indices onto existing schema arms, but the arm-acquiring refinement hierarchy and joint analysis add genuine integration, so moderate stitching score. The bottleneck (exponential fitness-proportional allocation being non-log-regret-optimal) is identified fairly precisely."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two disconnected bandit literatures appear in these sources. The Bayesian discounted tradition (Gittins 1989; Ishikida and Varaiya 1994; Berry and Fristedt 1985) gives the Gittins index, an exact optimal calibration of an arm's learning value, but only under a known prior, a conjugate exponential family, and discount below one, and it is costly. The frequentist regret and UCB tradition (Lai and Robbins 1985; Agrawal 1995; Burnetas and Katehakis 1996; Yakowitz and Lowe 1991) builds prior-free indices from sample means and KL confidence bounds achieving optimal order log n regret, but only asymptotically, undiscounted, with a heuristic finite-time exploration bonus. Burnetas and Katehakis note their indices came from Bayes dynamic programming then simplified, and Duff's Q-learning for Bandit Problems (1995) with the RL tradition (Sutton 1998; Holland) shows Gittins indices can be learned model-free. Yet nobody has connected Gittins-optimal calibration to the KL-confidence machinery, nor unified the discounted and undiscounted regimes. Practitioners must choose between a computable heuristic UCB bonus and an optimally calibrated but model-bound Gittins index, with no interpolation between impatient discounted and patient long-horizon objectives.","method":"We propose a Nonparametric Optimistic Gittins Index making Gittins-style calibration work under prior-free UCB assumptions. The Gittins index is the retirement value at which one is indifferent between continuing an arm and taking a fixed reward forever under discount gamma, classically solved against a conjugate posterior. We relax this three ways. First, replace the conjugate posterior with the empirical distribution F-hat, a nonparametric belief in the Yakowitz-Lowe finite-moment setting, plus a KL confidence ball built with Agrawal and Burnetas-Katehakis machinery, and compute the index optimistically as the maximum over distributions in that ball of the discounted retirement value; the confidence set supplies exploration and the stopping value supplies calibration. Second, treat gamma as an explicit knob: gamma below one gives discounted-optimal behavior while gamma toward one with ball width scaled per Lai-Robbins recovers average-reward behavior targeting the optimal log n constant, so one policy spans both regimes. Third, compute the index model-free by treating the stopping subproblem as an arm-local belief MDP with transitions from bootstrap resampling of F-hat, solved by extending Duff's Q-learning, applicable to bounded and finite-moment arms including the nonparametric and unknown-variance cases Burnetas-Katehakis left open. We validate by proving order log n regret with the KL-optimal constant as gamma approaches one and recovery of the exact Gittins index in the conjugate limit, characterizing the gamma versus ball-width trade-off, and benchmarking against UCB, Burnetas-Katehakis indices, exact Gittins, and Q-learning indices on Bernoulli, heavy-tailed, and discrete-support arms."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two disconnected bandit literatures (Bayesian discounted Gittins vs frequentist UCB/regret) that could be connected, a clear bridge_opportunity, with secondary scope_mismatch (Gittins bound by conjugate priors and known discounts). The central move is reconciling/unifying these traditions into one index (synthesis_unification), with relaxing assumptions to nonparametric prior-free settings as secondary. There is some risk of A+B stitching (Gittins index + KL confidence balls + Duff Q-learning), hence moderate surface_stitching, though the interpolation via gamma is a genuine unifying axis. Bottleneck (choice between computable heuristic vs optimally calibrated but model-bound) is moderately specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works form three largely disconnected research streams that all revolve around the *index* as the organizing object of bandit decision-making, yet almost never talk to each other:\n\n(1) Frequentist regret minimization. Lai & Robbins (1985) derive the O(log n) regret lower bound with a constant fixed by the Kullback–Leibler number; Agrawal (1995) and Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) build upper-confidence-bound (UCB) index policies that attain it, and Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) push toward nonparametric arms. The optimality of these indices, however, is tied to *correct specification* of the reward-distribution family (e.g., one-parameter exponential families). Agrawal explicitly notes that his sample-mean indices, obtained via a large-deviations \"contraction principle,\" recover the optimal KL constant only for exponential families and are otherwise merely a lower proxy — i.e., robustness to misspecification is bought by sacrificing efficiency.\n\n(2) Bayesian dynamic allocation. Gittins (1989), Berry & Fristedt (1985), and Ishikida & Varaiya (1994) show the Gittins index is exactly optimal for the discounted criterion. But this optimality presumes a *correct prior* and is computationally heavy; it is brittle when the prior or the discount model is wrong, and it is disconnected from the regret/KL machinery of stream (1).\n\n(3) Learning-by-simulation. Q-learning for bandits (1995), Sutton & Barto (1998), and Holland (1992) offer stochastic-approximation and evolutionary ways to *compute* indices from experience, but with no statistical optimality or robustness guarantees, and no link to the sharp KL bounds of streams (1)–(2).\n\nThe bridge opportunity: no work connects the large-deviations/KL calibration of the frequentist community, the index-optimality of the Bayesian community, and the online-estimation machinery of the RL community into a single index that is *provably robust to misspecification* of both the reward family (UCB's weak point) and the prior/discount model (Gittins' weak point). This matters because in practice the reward family is unknown and priors are guesses; both classical index policies can fail badly precisely where the other might succeed, and neither degrades gracefully.","method":"Propose a **Distributionally Robust Index (DRI)** that unifies and robustifies UCB and Gittins indices, computed online by stochastic approximation.\n\nCore construction. For each arm a with n_a observed rewards and empirical distribution F̂_a, build an *ambiguity set* U_a(t) = { G : D(G ‖ F̂_a) ≤ ρ(n_a, t) } around the empirical law (a KL or Wasserstein ball), taking the empirical/nonparametric law as center in the spirit of Yakowitz & Lowe rather than assuming a parametric family. Define the arm's index as an *optimistic-robust* value:\n  I_a(t) = sup_{G ∈ U_a(t)} V(G),\nwhere V(G) is the criterion-specific value of an arm whose reward law is G. This single template specializes across the disconnected literatures:\n  - Regret criterion: V(G) = mean(G) → the sup is solved by convex duality using exactly Agrawal's large-deviations rate function, recovering KL-UCB but *without* needing to know the reward family.\n  - Discounted criterion: V(G) = Gittins index of an arm with law G → a \"robust Gittins index\" that replaces reliance on a single prior with a worst-case set.\n\nCalibrating the radius (the robustification knob). Set ρ(n_a, t) ≈ (log t)/n_a so the ball shrinks at the large-deviations rate. This is the key device that *closes Agrawal's efficiency gap*: because the ambiguity set is sized by the KL rate function, the robust index stays tight enough to match the Lai–Robbins constant asymptotically while remaining valid for any distribution in a broad nonparametric class. The radius directly trades robustness against efficiency, giving a graceful-degradation guarantee absent from both classical policies.\n\nOnline computation (bridging the RL stream). Solve the inner worst-case problem online via a Q-learning / stochastic-approximation recursion (Watkins; Sutton & Barto): for the discounted case, run a restart-in-state value recursion for the Gittins index nested with an adversarial-perturbation step that reweights sampled rewards to the worst case within U_a via the dual variables. For high-dimensional or infinite-arm settings (Yakowitz's infinite-population extension), use a Holland-style population/genetic search over the ambiguity set as a heuristic inner solver.\n\nGuarantees and evaluation. (i) Prove a finite-time regret upper bound matching the Lai–Robbins/Agrawal lower bound uniformly over a nonparametric family, using Agrawal's large-deviations lemmas. (ii) Prove a *robustness* theorem: bounded regret/value degradation as a function of the true misspecification gap, whereas KL-UCB under a wrong family and Bayesian Gittins under a wrong prior have unbounded degradation. (iii) Show the exact reductions to KL-UCB and to the classic Gittins index in the well-specified limits, demonstrating the unification. (iv) Empirically compare against KL-UCB, sample-mean UCB, and Gittins on correctly specified, misspecified-family, heavy-tailed, and misspecified-prior instances to show DRI is the only policy robust across all regimes."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames three disconnected index literatures (frequentist regret, Bayesian Gittins, RL simulation) that fail to talk to each other, a clear bridge_opportunity, with a secondary failure_risk_gap around misspecification brittleness. The method builds a single unifying index template (synthesis_unification) that reduces to KL-UCB and Gittins in limits, with robustification via ambiguity sets as a secondary move. There is some risk of surface stitching since the proposal ties together many named prior works into components, but the KL-rate radius calibration to close Agrawal's efficiency gap is a concrete mechanism, giving moderate bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about unifying three bandit literatures.","method":"Test method describing a unified confidence tilted index."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The classic UCB finite-time analysis replaces asymptotic regret guarantees with finite-time bounds (scope/evidence gap), and the core move is deriving logarithmic regret bounds (formal_derivation). The stub proposal text is placeholder/generic ('test motivation','test method'), lowering confidence; framing as 'unifying literatures' hints at synthesis but the substantive contribution is the index and its bound derivation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"test","method":"test method content here"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.35,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal content is placeholder ('test'), so labels are inferred from prior-work context on finite-time bandit regret analysis, which typically extends asymptotic guarantees to finite-time bounds (scope) via formal derivation of regret bounds. No actual content to assess."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Classical bandit papers prove many asymptotically efficient index policies with log n regret constants tied to KL numbers, but under disjoint assumptions and with no common way to measure and compare their finite-horizon behavior.","method":"Build a finite-horizon benchmark simulating diverse arm families and running all these policies, reporting efficiency ratios, floor-gap ratios versus the Lai-Robbins bound, log-linearity onset horizons, and per-arm regret attribution with confidence bands."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is the absence of a common way to measure and compare finite-horizon behavior of policies proven under disjoint assumptions (evidence_gap, with scope_mismatch from asymptotic-only regimes). The method builds a benchmark reporting efficiency ratios and diagnostics against the Lai-Robbins bound, a clear empirical_mapping/benchmarking move. Note this proposal is not the actual finite-time-analysis paper (which derives UCB bounds); it is a benchmarking reframing."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The bandit works here form a chain of asymptotic optimality theorems, each under different assumptions and each yielding a different index rule. Lai and Robbins (1985) give the O(log n) lower bound with a KL constant and policies for exponential families. Agrawal (1995) gives simpler sample-mean UCB indices that match the KL-optimal constant only for one-parameter exponential families, otherwise using a provably suboptimal contraction constant. Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) give dual-index policies optimal for discrete finite-support families but leave normal-with-unknown-variance open. Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) give nonparametric rules with only some computational experience. Gittins-index theory (1989 book; Ishikida and Varaiya 1994) targets a Bayesian discounted objective, and Q-learning-for-bandits (1995) yet another framework. The evidence gap: the field lacks a common yardstick to observe and compare what these policies actually do at finite horizons. No one systematically measures how far realized finite-horizon regret sits from the KL lower bound, the horizon at which the asymptotic log-slope engages, how much the contraction constant loses versus the KL-optimal one, how each policy degrades when assumptions are violated, and compute cost and regret variance. The Berry-Fristedt bibliography confirms existing simulations are fragmentary, mostly two-arm Bernoulli, never unified across policy families or distributions. Without this evidence one cannot audit which guarantee translates into finite-sample performance.","method":"Build a unified, reproducible benchmark and diagnostic suite comparing the index policies from these sources on common ground. Policy library from a shared interface: Lai-Robbins KL-UCB, Agrawal sample-mean UCB with both KL-optimal and contraction constants, Burnetas-Katehakis dual-index, Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric index, the Gittins index with uniform and geometric-discount approximations, Q-learning-for-bandits, plus baselines (equal allocation, greedy, Thompson-style randomization). Environment grid: distribution class (Bernoulli, Gaussian known and unknown variance, exponential, bounded finite-support discrete, heavy-tailed finite-moment), arm count from 2 to many, gaps from well-separated to near-tied, horizons across several decades of n, many seeds each. Diagnostics per policy-environment cell: mean cumulative regret with confidence bands; an efficiency ratio equal to realized regret over the Lai-Robbins KL lower-bound curve; a burn-in horizon where the empirical log-n slope first matches the asymptotic constant; a contraction-loss metric differencing sample-mean versus KL-optimal constants to test Agrawal's suboptimality empirically; a misspecification-robustness score from running assumption-specific policies out of assumption (exponential-family UCB on heavy-tailed arms, Burnetas-Katehakis on normal unknown variance); regret variance and upper-quantile risk; per-step compute. Pattern analysis aggregating into empirical maps of dominance regions, heatmaps of efficiency ratio and burn-in horizon versus gap size and arm count, and frequentist-UCB versus Bayesian-Gittins comparison when objectives align, testing hypotheses such as contraction cost appearing only outside exponential families. Deliver an open, extensible benchmark with fixed seeds, the KL-lower-bound reference, and standardized diagnostics so new policies can be audited against the same map. This converts isolated asymptotic theorems into accumulated, comparable finite-sample evidence, quantifying the theory-practice gap and localizing where each guarantee holds or breaks."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames a missing common yardstick to observe/compare/audit finite-horizon regret across policies — an evidence gap; the chain of conflicting asymptotic theorems adds a puzzle/contradiction flavor. The central move is building a unified benchmark with diagnostics and empirical maps (empirical_mapping), integrating disconnected policy families onto common ground (synthesis_unification secondary). It is a genuine measurement contribution rather than a superficial A+B stitch; the bottleneck (finite-sample vs KL-lower-bound gap, contraction-constant cost, burn-in horizon) is precisely identified. Note the actual 2002 paper (UCB1) is a theorem, but this framing is evaluative."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Every policy in this corpus is certified by the same kind of guarantee: an asymptotic constant times log n. Lai and Robbins (1985) prove the floor with KL number I(theta_j,theta*); Agrawal (1995) gives sample-mean index policies whose constant is a contraction of KL, admittedly suboptimal; Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) obtain the exact optimal constant M(theta)=sum(mu*-mu_a)/K_a(theta) via a minimum-discrimination index; Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) give nonparametric rates; Gittins-index results target discounted optimality. This is an evidence gap: these constants live in the limit and require the unknown theta, so from a single finite run one cannot observe how far a policy is from the information floor or whether the asymptotic regime is reached; the policies use incommensurable yardsticks so there is no like-for-like way to audit, compare, or diagnose wasted exploration; and no accepted decomposition attributes accrued regret to distinguishable causes. The field proves asymptotic optimality but cannot measure finite-time efficiency from data, which matters for the clinical-trial and machine-learning settings these papers motivate.","method":"A Formal Derivation: a unified regret-accounting model, an efficiency functional, a decomposition theorem, and an observable auditor with concentration guarantees, built from objects in these sources (KL number I, Agrawal contracted KL, Burnetas-Katehakis K_a, large-deviation change-of-measure). (1) For any uniformly-fast index policy with inflation function g, decompose E[T_j(n)] into an information floor log n / I(theta_j,theta*), a slack term of extra pulls from the gap between the policy confidence inflation and the true KL ball, and an o(log n) transient; this yields a four-way taxonomy: information floor, confidence slack, misspecification, transient. (2) Using change-of-measure and large-deviation lemmas of Lai-Robbins and Agrawal, define the effective discrimination rate I_g induced by the index and the efficiency ratio rho_j = I_g / K_j(theta) in (0,1]; derive R_n = sum over suboptimal arms of (mu*-mu_j) log n /(rho_j K_j(theta)) + o(log n), and prove rho_j=1 recovers the Burnetas-Katehakis optimum, Agrawal contraction yields explicit rho_j<1, and nonparametric conservatism is a bounded rho-loss, placing all policies on one yardstick. (3) Since I and K need unknown theta, derive a plug-in floor estimator from each arm empirical KL or empirical likelihood and an observed regret proxy; via self-normalized concentration grounded in the convergence-of-stochastic-processes and mathematical-statistics sources, prove finite-time confidence bands for the online efficiency ratio and rho_j, plus a diagnostic stopping test flagging with controlled error whether the run entered the log-n regime and whether measured slack exceeds the minimum. (4) Instantiate on Bernoulli, exponential-family, and finite-support arms to get closed-form rho_j for Lai-Robbins UCB, Agrawal index, and Burnetas-Katehakis dual index, and simulate to confirm coverage. This converts asymptotic theta-dependent constants into a single efficiency scale rho, a causal decomposition of regret, and an online calibrated auditor for observing, benchmarking, and comparing finite-time exploration efficiency of any index policy from its own trajectory."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as an evidence gap: asymptotic theta-dependent constants cannot be observed, audited, or compared from a single finite run, with incommensurable yardsticks. The construction is a formal derivation (decomposition theorem, efficiency functional rho, concentration bounds, plug-in estimators). Unification of disparate policies onto a single yardstick is a strong secondary. Not superficial stitching because it derives genuinely new objects (efficiency ratio, decomposition) rather than gluing components. High bottleneck specificity: the precise limiting factor (unobservable asymptotic constants requiring unknown theta) is named exactly."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the evidence gap in finite-time bandit regret.","method":"Test method using optimization and search to audit policies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The classic contribution moves from asymptotic O(log n) regret guarantees to finite-time bounds, a scope/regime extension, delivered via formal derivation of regret bounds. The proposal text is minimal placeholder ('Test motivation') but the prior-work context clearly points to finite-time regret analysis. Opportunity is a scope mismatch (asymptotic vs finite-time) with evidence-gap flavor; method is formal derivation of bounds, not genuine optimization/search despite the placeholder wording."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the evidence gap in bandit regret constant auditing.","method":"Test method that relaxes assumptions with an empirical likelihood plug in index and a benchmark."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Prior work established asymptotic O(log n) regret; the finite-time analysis addresses a scope/assumption gap (asymptotic vs finite-time bounds). The classic paper's contribution is deriving finite-time regret bounds, hence formal_derivation. The proposal text is a placeholder ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), lowering confidence and bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Classic bandit index policies prove O(log n) regret only under specific distributional assumptions, with constants tied to the KL number of the assumed family. There is no shared way to measure, benchmark, or audit how they behave when assumptions are violated by heavy tails, contamination, or near-tied means.","method":"Build a robust index policy using median-of-means estimators and distribution-free empirical-Bernstein confidence widths, plus a benchmark suite that stress-tests classic policies across misspecification conditions and reports regret-inflation and exploration-calibration diagnostics."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior O(log n) regret proofs relying on narrow distributional assumptions that break under heavy tails/contamination (scope_mismatch), plus a lack of ways to benchmark/audit behavior under misspecification (evidence_gap). The core move builds a distribution-free robust index policy to reduce failure under assumption violations (robustification), paired with a stress-test benchmark suite (empirical_mapping). Combination of median-of-means + empirical-Bernstein + a benchmark is somewhat A+B stitching but addresses a specific brittleness bottleneck."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bandit research is fragmented across Bayesian Gittins-index, frequentist KL-regret UCB, RL Q-learning, and evolutionary paradigms, each with its own objective and metrics. The evidence gap: no common instrument exists to observe, measure, and benchmark how much exploration each policy actually performs relative to the information-theoretic minimum.","method":"Build a unifying exploration-accounting benchmark that decomposes every policy into an exploitation term plus an exploration bonus, scores them under discounted, regret, and average-reward objectives on shared testbeds, and audits their exploration against the Lai and Robbins KL lower bound to compute over-exploration ratios and regret attribution."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is the lack of a common instrument to observe/measure/benchmark exploration across paradigms (evidence_gap), motivated by fragmentation across literatures (bridge_opportunity secondary). The method builds a benchmark that decomposes, scores, and audits policies against the KL lower bound — empirical_mapping (diagnostics/benchmarking) with a synthesis_unification element across paradigms. Note this reframes the classic finite-time UCB analysis as a benchmarking exercise, giving it some A+B stitching flavor."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: four bandit index families (Gittins, Lai-Robbins/Agrawal KL-UCB, Katehakis-Burnetas dual, Duff Q-learning) are each near-optimal by a different mechanism, but no source explains why they behave similarly or what their exploration bonus encodes.","method":"Test method: build IndexScope, a workbench that computes all four indices on identical bandit states, decomposes each into mean plus exploration bonus, and tests whether the bonuses share a single KL currency."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as missing an explanation for why four different index families behave similarly and what their exploration bonus encodes (explanation_gap), with a clear bridging motive across disconnected index-policy literatures (bridge_opportunity). The method centrally reconciles/unifies these separate mechanisms under a common KL currency (synthesis_unification), operationalized via a comparative workbench that decomposes and measures each index (empirical_mapping). Not superficial stitching since the aim is a genuine unifying account, though the KL-currency hypothesis is a specific bottleneck claim."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: explanation gap about why sample-mean index policies lose regret optimality outside exponential families.","method":"Test method: derive a T-restricted KL rate function to explain the regret gap and identify minimal sufficient statistics."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an explanation gap (why sample-mean index policies lose optimality outside exponential families), with a scope-mismatch undertone. The method derives a KL rate function and identifies sufficient statistics, a formal derivation move, with scope extension secondary. Precise bottleneck identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works form a fragmented theory of bandit index policies, each proving asymptotic optimality yet leaving unexplained WHY these provably equivalent policies behave differently before the asymptotic regime. Lai and Robbins (1985) give the O(log n) regret lower bound with a leading constant set by a Kullback-Leibler (KL) number and matching UCB policies for exponential families. Agrawal (1995) builds simpler sample-mean UCB indices achieving O(log n) regret, but notes his constant is optimal ONLY for one-parameter exponential families and otherwise derived via a contraction principle, generically loose by an unknown amount. Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) define the truly optimal nonparametric constant M(theta) via dual problems, and Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) give nonparametric strategies with different rates. In parallel, Gittins-index theory (the 1989 book; Ishikida and Varaiya 1994) gives Bayesian-optimal indices for the discounted criterion, and Q-learning and RL (1995; Sutton and Barto 1998) offer another mechanism. Three phenomena go unexplained. Constant gap: nobody has quantified how much regret Agrawal's contraction costs versus the Burnetas-Katehakis optimal constant, nor which measurable features (distance from an exponential family, tail heaviness, variance) drive that loss. Rate-behavior mismatch: all guarantees are asymptotic with hidden burn-in terms, so the finite-horizon ordering of policies and the crossover horizon at which asymptotic KL ordering emerges is opaque. Criterion mismatch: it is unclear when and why a Bayesian-optimal Gittins index is beaten by frequentist UCB indices under undiscounted regret. The literature supplies rates and constants but no mechanistic account connecting them to observed finite-time regret, which matters because practitioners must choose among these policies at finite horizons where the theory is silent.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map, a bandit regret atlas, that measures and causally attributes the finite-time behavior of the index-policy families and turns their theoretical constants into a diagnostic account. Step one, a unified policy library: reimplement under one interface Lai-Robbins exponential-family UCB (KL-optimal constant), Agrawal sample-mean UCB (contraction constant), Burnetas-Katehakis dual-index policy (optimal nonparametric M(theta)), Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric strategy, the Gittins discounted index, and Q-learning for bandits; each exposes its per-arm index and confidence width at every step so internal behavior is observable. Step two, a designed instance grid: vary the levers the theory implicates, including number of arms, gap structure (single dominant versus near-tied arms), reward law (Bernoulli, Gaussian across variances, finite-support discrete, heavy-tailed and bounded non-exponential-family laws) parameterized by an explicit distance from a one-parameter exponential family, and horizon length from pre-asymptotic to deep-asymptotic; for each cell compute the theoretical leading constant each policy targets and the KL-based optimal floor. Step three, regret-decomposition diagnostics: split cumulative regret into unavoidable exploration predicted by the KL floor, excess exploration from over-wide confidence indices (the constant gap), burn-in cost, and under-exploration or mis-identification cost, tracking per-arm suboptimal pull counts against the floor over time. Step four, causal attribution: treat the measured constant gap and crossover horizon as responses and regress them on instance features using sensitivity analysis and controlled interventions (hold gap fixed while sweeping exponential-family distance) to test hypotheses, centrally that Agrawal's contraction loss grows monotonically with distance from an exponential family and vanishes exactly for exponential-family laws, and that Gittins undiscounted-regret suboptimality is governed by the mismatch between its effective discount and the horizon. Step five, deliverables: phase diagrams over instance space showing which policy dominates where, empirical calibration of realized versus theoretical leading constants quantifying the contraction penalty as a function of measurable features, and a map of crossover horizons explaining when asymptotic KL ordering takes over. This mapping fills the explanation gap by converting the corpus's asymptotic constants into a measured, mechanistic account of why asymptotically-equivalent bandit policies diverge in finite time and which features cause it; it is feasible via simulation and grounded entirely in the provided works."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal frames the gap as a missing mechanistic account of WHY asymptotically-equivalent bandit index policies diverge in finite time (explanation_gap), with a secondary lack of measurement/diagnostics connecting theoretical constants to observed regret (evidence_gap). The central move is building a systematic empirical map/atlas with regret-decomposition diagnostics and causal attribution across a designed instance grid (empirical_mapping); reimplementing disparate policy families under one interface adds a synthesis/unification dimension, though it serves the mapping rather than being the deliverable. The bottleneck is precisely specified (contraction loss vs KL-optimal constant, crossover horizon, exponential-family distance). Not superficial stitching since the unification is instrumental to measurement, not the contribution itself."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The prior work forms a coherent lineage on the stochastic multi-armed bandit, and it converges on one striking empirical/theoretical regularity: good index policies incur regret that grows like log n. Lai & Robbins (1985) prove that log n is the unavoidable rate and identify a Kullback–Leibler constant as the governing quantity, but only as a liminf over n→∞. Agrawal (1995) shows sample-mean-only index policies attain O(log n) \"asymptotically,\" with a constant obtained from the KL-optimal one by a \"contraction\" principle. Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) again give an n m*(θ) − M(θ)log n + o(log n) expansion valid only as n→∞, and Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) prove asymptotic optimality with \"guaranteed convergence rates\" but no explicit horizon-dependent statement.\n\nThis leaves a genuine EXPLANATION GAP. The literature tells us the limiting rate and the limiting constant, but does not explain *why* the log n law emerges, *what mechanism* produces it, or *how* regret actually behaves at the finite horizons at which bandits are run. Concretely, four things are unexplained: (i) the asymptotic constants (KL numbers, M(θ)) are only meaningful in the limit and can be arbitrarily loose or even vacuous for small/moderate n, so they do not account for early behavior; (ii) it is unclear how much of the incurred regret is the irreducible \"learning cost\" versus transient over-exploration, and what causal quantity trades the two off; (iii) it is not explained why replacing full distributional knowledge with the sample mean plus a confidence correction is *sufficient*, i.e., what property of the estimator carries the argument; (iv) the required amount of exploration as an explicit function of the horizon n and the per-arm play count is never isolated. Because these are asymptotic-only accounts, they cannot answer the mechanistic question \"why does this work, and work at time n?\"—which is exactly what a practitioner or theorist needs to trust and tune such policies.","method":"Contribution type: a formal, non-asymptotic explanatory derivation that replaces the asymptotic \"why\" with a finite-time causal account.\n\n1. Conceptual decomposition (taxonomy). Formalize regret as R_n = Σ_{j:Δ_j>0} Δ_j · E[T_j(n)], where Δ_j = μ* − μ_j is the suboptimality gap and T_j(n) the play count. This isolates the single object that must be explained: E[T_j(n)], the expected number of pulls of each suboptimal arm. Introduce a conceptual distinction between (a) the *confidence-failure* events (the estimator being far from its mean) and (b) the *decision* events (a suboptimal index exceeding the optimal one), and argue every suboptimal pull is attributable to one of these.\n\n2. Objective / policy class. Define a distribution-free index of the form I_j = X̄_j + r(n, T_j), i.e., sample mean plus an explicit exploration radius, generalizing the sample-mean index policies of Agrawal and the bounded-arm setting of Yakowitz–Lowe. Treat r(·) as an unknown function to be *derived*, not assumed.\n\n3. Formal derivation (the mechanism). Using only a concentration/large-deviation inequality for bounded rewards (Chernoff–Hoeffding, in the spirit of the \"few key lemmas from large deviations\" Agrawal invokes), derive the smallest radius r(n,s) = c·sqrt(ln n / s) that makes two things simultaneously true: the confidence-failure probability, summed over the horizon via a union bound, is O(1) (finite, horizon-independent); and once a suboptimal arm j has been pulled more than ~ (ln n)/Δ_j² times, its index provably drops below the optimal arm's index with high probability. Prove the central theorem: for all n (not merely n→∞),\n   E[T_j(n)] ≤ (8 ln n)/Δ_j² + (1 + π²/3),\nyielding R_n ≤ Σ_{j:Δ_j>0} (8 ln n)/Δ_j² + O(Σ Δ_j). The proof mechanistically explains the log n law: the ln n numerator is exactly the confidence width needed to survive a union bound over n rounds, and the 1/Δ_j² is the sample size at which concentration separates arm j from the optimum—so log n regret is the *price of maintaining valid confidence over a horizon of length n*, not an asymptotic accident.\n\n4. Reconciliation with the KL account. Show how this distribution-free constant relates to the Lai–Robbins/Burnetas–Katehakis KL constant: prove that for bounded rewards Pinsker-type inequalities lower-bound the KL number by Δ²/2, explaining Agrawal's \"contraction\" gap as the difference between an estimator-agnostic variance proxy and the distribution-specific KL rate, and delimiting exactly when the two coincide. Provide a gap-regime taxonomy (large-gap \"identification\" regime vs. small-gap Δ ≈ sqrt(1/n) \"pooling\" regime) and derive a complementary distribution-free bound R_n = O(sqrt(n · K · ln n)) uniform over gaps, explaining why the instance-dependent log n constant can appear misleading when gaps shrink with n.\n\n5. Validation. The theorem is self-contained and checkable; additionally, simulate the derived policy against the asymptotically-optimal KL-index policies of the cited works across horizons, empirically confirming that the finite-time bound tracks realized regret where the asymptotic constants do not, thereby demonstrating that the derivation supplies the missing causal/mechanistic explanation of the log n phenomenon at finite time."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an explanation gap: the literature gives asymptotic rates/constants but does not explain why log n emerges or how regret behaves at finite horizons. Secondary scope_mismatch since asymptotic-only accounts are unrealistic for finite-horizon practice. The core move is a non-asymptotic formal derivation (theorem, bound, exploration radius derivation), with relax_extend_scope as the finite-time extension of asymptotic results. Highly specific bottleneck: E[T_j(n)] as the object to explain, with ln n/Delta^2 mechanism precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bandit theory shows O(log n) regret with a leading constant set by Kullback-Leibler information (Lai and Robbins 1985), yet different index rules realize different constants on the same instance. Agrawal (1995) proves sample-mean-only indices are optimal only for one-parameter exponential families and otherwise attain a strictly suboptimal contracted constant, while Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) recover the true nonparametric constant via dual KL-minimization over the full empirical distribution, and Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) give still other constants. What is missing is an explanatory account of why and by how much discarding information beyond the sample mean costs efficiency, and which distributional features drive this contraction gap. Practitioners default to mean-based UCB for simplicity with no principled way to know when it silently sacrifices constant-factor reward. Prior works fix the endpoints but never characterize the mechanism, magnitude, or determinants of the gap.","method":"Cast index design as optimization and search over a parametrized family of statistic-to-index maps, used both to explain and to close the contraction gap. Define a family indexed by phi that selects which empirical functionals feed the index, from sample mean alone, to mean plus variance, to quantiles, up to a full empirical-KL projection onto a screened set of reference measures, plus an inflation schedule; Agrawal mean-only UCB and Burnetas-Katehakis dual-KL indices are the endpoints. Offline explanatory search over a designed grid of distribution families labeled by interpretable features solves the Burnetas-Katehakis dual for the optimal constant and evaluates Agrawal contraction for the mean-only constant, computes their ratio, and uses variance-based sensitivity screening to attribute the gap to specific features, yielding a decomposition explaining why the loss varies. An online bandit-over-indices meta-search spends a vanishing exploration budget to estimate each arm's features, predicts its gap from the offline map, and adaptively picks the cheapest phi within epsilon of optimal, reverting to mean-UCB when the gap is negligible and escalating to dual-KL indices only where warranted, with the estimated dual-KL value as screening surrogate and an exploration schedule keeping meta-selection cost o(log n) so asymptotic optimality is preserved. Validate that the meta-policy tracks Burnetas-Katehakis regret where the gap is large and mean-UCB efficiency where it is small, and that observed per-instance loss is predicted by the feature decomposition."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.62,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The core gap is explanatory: why and by how much discarding information beyond the sample mean costs efficiency, and which distributional features drive the contraction gap between endpoints (Agrawal vs Burnetas-Katehakis). This is an explanation_gap, seeded by the puzzle that different index rules realize different constants on the same instance. The method casts index design as a parametrized family with offline sensitivity attribution and an online meta-search, but the central contribution is a formal characterization/decomposition of the gap mechanism, hence formal_derivation with optimization_search as the constructive move (bandit-over-indices meta-search, screening). Bottleneck is precisely identified (KL-contraction from mean-only statistics)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bandit theory in these sources is complete only asymptotically. Lai and Robbins (1985) prove a log n lower bound with a Kullback-Leibler constant and matching index policies; Agrawal (1995) gives simpler sample-mean index policies reaching O(log n); Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) extend optimality to broader families; the nonparametric-methods paper (1991) confirms the log n barrier nonparametrically. Every result is of the form: for fixed theta, as n goes to infinity, characterizing the limiting slope of regret over log n and its constant, not the finite-horizon behavior that governs real applications like clinical trials with a finite patient stream. This is an explanation gap: the literature states the asymptotic rate but not why the exploration term forces logarithmic regret at every finite n, how regret decomposes across arms, gaps and horizon at practical sample sizes, or why the simple sample-mean policies lose the optimal constant. It matters because an asymptotically optimal constant can be misleading early, and the optimal policies need strong structure: a known parametric family and the whole observation history or large-deviation index computations. No existing account explains why regret is controlled under weak, realistic assumptions uniformly over the horizon.","method":"Build a finite-time, distribution-free explanatory theory of index-policy regret that makes the prior asymptotic results hold under weaker assumptions and uniformly over all n. Relaxations: replace known parametric family with only bounded or sub-Gaussian rewards; replace limits at infinity with bounds valid at every finite n; replace history and KL-based indices with a policy storing only each arm running sample mean and play count. Analyze the policy playing the arm that maximizes its sample mean plus a confidence radius equal to the square root of alpha times ln n over that arm play count, the radius derived from Hoeffding or Chernoff concentration rather than the true KL number. The core is an explanatory decomposition of expected pulls of a suboptimal arm into a deterministic exploration threshold of order alpha ln n over the squared gap, after which the arm inflated mean provably falls below the optimal arm index, plus a summed tail-probability term for concentration failures, each bounded by explicit computable constants, yielding regret at most a sum over suboptimal arms of a constant times ln n over the gap plus a constant. This answers the why by exhibiting the concentration-driven separation threshold producing log n growth at every n, showing how arm count and gaps enter, and comparing the Hoeffding radius to the KL rate to pinpoint where the sample-mean policy constant exceeds the Lai-Robbins optimum. Extend with a variance-adaptive Bernstein radius explaining when variance rather than range drives regret and a horizon-agnostic variant bounded uniformly in n, and validate by simulation across Bernoulli, bounded, and truncated heavy-tailed rewards, checking predicted versus observed per-arm pulls and regret curves and recovering the classical asymptotic constant as the limit."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior results hold only asymptotically for fixed theta under known parametric families; the proposal targets finite-horizon behavior under weaker (bounded/sub-Gaussian) assumptions, which is fundamentally a scope mismatch, with a strong secondary explanation-gap framing (why log n regret at every finite n). The method relaxes assumptions and extends validity uniformly over the horizon (relax_extend_scope), delivered via explicit finite-time bounds and a concentration-based decomposition (formal_derivation). Bottleneck is precisely identified: the exploration threshold from concentration replacing KL indices."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Classical stochastic bandit theory yields index/UCB policies with O(log n) regret whose constant is governed by a Kullback-Leibler / large-deviations rate (Lai and Robbins 1985; Agrawal 1995; Burnetas and Katehakis 1996). But each construction's optimality is silently conditioned on a correctly specified reward model: Agrawal's sample-mean index attains the optimal constant only for one-parameter exponential families and otherwise uses a suboptimal contraction of the KL number; Burnetas and Katehakis require the functional form to be known and leave normal-with-unknown-variance open; Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) get distribution-free rates only under bounded or finite-moment assumptions and are rate-optimal only when bounded; Berry and Fristedt (1985) treat robustness only via Bayesian priors. This leaves an explanation gap: we have asymptotic guarantees but no mechanistic account of why and how much these asymptotically optimal policies degrade and vary in finite horizons under misspecification (heavy tails, wrong family, unknown variance, near-tied arms). Is failure driven by confidence inflation, by contraction bias, or by estimation variance? Because the regret constant is itself a functional of the assumed law, practitioners cannot tell when an index policy is trustworthy, which matters for the clinical-trial and adaptive-control applications these works target.","method":"A unified theory-plus-policy that explains and robustifies index policies against distributional misspecification. First, an explanatory decomposition: using Agrawal's large-deviations lemmas, decompose finite-horizon regret of any KL-index policy into three attributable terms, namely estimation variance, confidence-inflation (the a_n schedule), and a specification-bias term from the contraction that maps the true law onto the assumed family's rate function. Derive how the bias term scales with divergence between the true law and the assumed family, giving a causal account of when regret blows up (predicting near-tied arms and heavy tails amplify bias while inflation dominates early), and derive an online per-arm diagnostic that estimates the bias term to flag untrustworthy indices. Second, robustification: replace the family-dependent index with a distributionally robust index, defined as the worst-case plausible mean over an ambiguity set of laws consistent with the sample (an empirical-measure KL ball intersected with Yakowitz-Lowe moment and support constraints), solved via the Burnetas-Katehakis dual machinery but without committing to a single family; using the empirical measure targets the optimal constant Agrawal notes is recoverable modulo continuity and directly covers the normal-unknown-variance case left open. Third, guarantees: prove that when the truth lies in the shrinking ambiguity set the robust index retains O(log n) regret and drives the specification-bias term to zero, and derive an explicit price-of-robustness bound in which excess regret increases with the ambiguity radius, turning unexplained finite-time variability into a tunable quantity. Fourth, calibration and validation: give a data-driven rule for the ambiguity radius that balances the estimation and bias terms, then validate on simulations across exponential-family, heavy-tailed, bounded, and unknown-variance normal arms, checking the diagnostic predicts where classical indices fail and the robust index removes those failures at bounded cost."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal frames its gap as a missing mechanistic account of why/how much asymptotically optimal index policies degrade in finite horizons under misspecification (explanation_gap), with a secondary trustworthiness/failure concern. The central move is a formal regret decomposition, bias-scaling derivation, and robust-index guarantees with a price-of-robustness bound (formal_derivation), coupled with a distributionally robust policy (robustification). It identifies precise bottleneck terms (specification-bias contraction), so bottleneck_specificity is high; it uses established machinery but non-superficially, so low stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about unifying bandit index policies.","method":"Test method: a KL-budget variational framework unifying Gittins, UCB, and Q-learning indices."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.66,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal explicitly aims to unify separate bandit index policies (Gittins, UCB, Q-learning) via a KL-budget variational framework, signaling a bridge opportunity across disconnected methods. The method move is synthesis/unification with formal derivation. Stub-like 'test' phrasing and generic unification framing raise surface-stitching concern; bottleneck is vaguely specified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"\nBandit index policies (Lai-Robbins 1985, Agrawal 1995, Burnetas-Katehakis 1996, Yakowitz-Lowe 1991) assume a correctly specified reward family, cumulant conditions, or bounded moments, and give only asymptotic guarantees. Under heavy tails, contamination, misspecification, unknown variance, or nonstationarity their confidence terms miscalibrate and regret can become unbounded, with no runtime detection of assumption failure and no reproducible brittleness measure, a reliability and safety risk for uses like allocating competing clinical treatments.\n","method":"\nBuild BanditGuard, a deployment runtime plus reproducible brittleness benchmark that makes bandit index policies auditable, self-monitoring, and robust; the software artifact is the central contribution. It wraps any index policy (Lai-Robbins, Agrawal, Burnetas-Katehakis, Gittins, UCB); per-arm streaming monitors (tail-index and empirical cumulant estimators from Agrawal large deviations and Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametrics, a contamination detector, a change-point detector) emit calibration scores comparing the assumed confidence width to a data-driven empirical-Bernstein width; a controller keeps the native index when valid, else substitutes robust nonparametric bounds, windowed statistics under drift, and a conservative safe-exploration fallback capping per-round risk, with a governor logging certifiability; a benchmark injects controlled violations at tunable severities and reports regret distribution, calibration error, catastrophic-failure rate, and detection latency across seeds.\n"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The gap is framed as brittleness/reliability when bandit assumptions fail (heavy tails, contamination, misspecification) with safety risk, squarely failure_risk_gap; secondary is scope_mismatch since prior work relies on narrow assumptions. The central deliverable is BanditGuard, a deployment runtime plus benchmark artifact, hence artifact_system with robustification secondary. It stitches together many existing estimators and detectors into a wrapper, giving a moderate surface-stitching flag."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Classic bandit index policies give only asymptotic logarithmic regret under strong tail assumptions, so they can silently lock onto a suboptimal arm at finite horizons and miscalibrate under misspecification, with no reliability certificate.","method":"Build a robust index policy using a truncated or median of means estimator with an empirical variance width, prove a non asymptotic high probability regret certificate via a time uniform martingale bound, and add an online self test that widens exploration when deviations exceed the assumed schedule to cap catastrophic lock in."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.68,"confidence_paradigm":0.62,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that classic index policies give only asymptotic regret under strong tail assumptions and can lock onto suboptimal arms at finite horizons (scope_mismatch), with a reliability/brittleness concern (failure_risk_gap). The method makes bandit policies work under weaker assumptions (heavy tails via median-of-means, misspecification) with a non-asymptotic certificate, primarily extending scope, supported by formal martingale bounds. Robustification is also present but the central move is functioning in broader/weaker-assumption regimes."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The classic bandit index policies in these works give only asymptotic mean-regret guarantees under strong assumptions. Lai and Robbins require exponential families and a KL constant that blows up as arm gaps shrink. Agrawal is optimal only for exponential families and otherwise loses via a contraction. Burnetas and Katehakis need finite-support models and leave normal unknown variance open. Yakowitz and Lowe need finite moments or bounded rewards. Gittins needs known priors and discounting. In clinical trials, adaptive control, and online learning these assumptions are routinely violated. This is a failure and risk gap: no study characterizes how brittle these policies become under misspecification, how often they lock onto a bad arm, how heavy-tailed regret becomes, how miscalibrated their confidence bounds are, or how far finite-time behavior departs from the asymptotic promise. No empirical map tells a practitioner which policy is reliable in which regime.","method":"Build a reproducible stress-testing benchmark that empirically maps finite-time reliability and failure of these bandit policies. Reimplement each index rule plus epsilon-greedy and Q-learning baselines. Vary stress axes drawn from their assumptions: wrong reward family, heavier tails, shrinking gaps toward near ties, more arms, shorter horizons, and nonstationary drift. Measure beyond mean regret: the full regret distribution and upper quantiles, the chance of catastrophic lock-in, seed-to-seed variance for reproducibility, calibration of each confidence bound, and the ratio of observed regret to the policy own asymptotic prediction. Deliver heatmaps of safe versus failure regions, a brittleness profile per policy, a taxonomy of failure modes tied to each assumption, and guidance for choosing policies under model uncertainty."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal frames the gap as brittleness/misspecification of existing bandit policies under violated assumptions (failure_risk_gap), also noting no empirical map exists (evidence_gap). The method is a stress-testing benchmark that empirically maps reliability and failure regimes, diagnosing calibration and lock-in—classic empirical_mapping. Notably this ignores the actual known contribution of the seminal paper (finite-time UCB regret bounds via formal_derivation), instead reimagining it as a benchmarking study. Not stitching; identifies concrete failure axes tied to assumptions."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The entire corpus optimizes one criterion: the expectation of cumulative regret. Lai and Robbins (1985) give the O(log n) lower bound on E[R_n] via the KL number; Agrawal (1995) builds sample-mean index policies attaining O(log n) expected regret with large-deviation lemmas; Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) characterize uniformly-fast policies optimal in expected reward; the Gittins-index results concern expected discounted reward; Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) give asymptotically optimal mean suboptimal-selection rates. A search confirms none analyze the variance or tail of regret. This is a Failure/Risk gap. The motivating applications, sequential clinical trials and treatment allocation, are safety-critical, where a single realization determines harm, not a long-run average. Efficient index policies attain low mean regret precisely by occasionally over-committing to an inferior arm when rare large-deviation events inflate its confidence index, making realized regret heavy-tailed. Two policies indistinguishable in expected regret can differ enormously in worst-case behavior and reproducibility. Expected-regret optimality thus gives no reliability or safety guarantee, and the field lacks any formal object describing when and how badly an asymptotically efficient policy fails on a given trajectory.","method":"Develop a formal theory of distributional (risk) regret that upgrades the corpus mean-only guarantees to guarantees about the whole regret distribution. First, a taxonomy: treat regret R_n and per-arm suboptimal-pull counts N_i(n) as random variables and define graded reliability criteria, namely expected-regret efficiency (classical), tail reliability (control of the probability that R_n exceeds (1+delta)E[R_n], plus a CVaR functional), and robustness (control of Var(R_n)); formally distinguish mean-optimal from risk-optimal policies. Second, a risk lower bound impossibility theorem: extend the Lai-Robbins change-of-measure/KL argument from E[N_i(n)] to the law of N_i(n), proving any uniformly-fast consistent policy must have Var(N_i(n)) growing at least like log n and an unavoidable upper tail on N_i(n) beyond (1+delta) log n divided by the KL number I(theta_i, theta*), yielding a fundamental mean-tail trade-off so no policy is simultaneously expected-regret optimal and light-tailed. Third, a matching family and Pareto frontier: introduce a one-parameter family of sample-mean index policies generalizing Agrawal with an exploration-inflation function, and using Agrawal large-deviation lemmas derive simultaneous upper bounds on E[R_n] and on the probability that R_n exceeds x, giving an explicit achievable frontier between the expected-regret constant and a tail-risk exponent, with a risk-efficient constant that is a risk analogue of the KL constant expressed via the Burnetas-Katehakis dual-index formulation. Fourth, an operational objective: define J equal to E[R_n] plus lambda times a CVaR/tail penalty, derive the optimizing index in variational form, and prove the resulting policies lie on the frontier. Fifth, scope: verify regularity assumptions for one-parameter exponential families and bounded or finite-support nonparametric distributions, matching the settings of Agrawal, Burnetas-Katehakis, and Yakowitz-Lowe, so results plug into existing guarantees. The deliverable is lower-bound, matching-upper-bound, and Pareto-characterization theorems that convert expected-regret efficiency into certified reliability with a tunable safety-efficiency dial."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a reliability/safety concern: expected-regret optimality gives no tail/variance guarantee, and efficient policies produce heavy-tailed realized regret in safety-critical settings (failure_risk_gap). It also notes no prior work measures/characterizes variance or tails (evidence_gap secondary). The method is a formal theory: taxonomy, impossibility/lower-bound theorems extending Lai-Robbins, matching upper bounds, Pareto frontier, variational objective (formal_derivation). It also extends mean-only guarantees to the whole distribution and to nonparametric settings (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottleneck identified: heavy-tailed regret from occasional over-commitment via large-deviation events."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about bandit brittleness under misspecification.","method":"Test method about adaptive search over exploration widths."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The classic finite-time bandit analysis context suggests deriving regret bounds (formal_derivation), but the placeholder proposal text about brittleness under misspecification and adaptive search is generic. Opportunity leans scope/failure gap; method leans formal with optimization search. Low confidence due to placeholder content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Failure/Risk gap. Every allocation rule in this corpus builds an arm's index from the sample mean of clean i.i.d. rewards, inflated by a KL or large-deviations radius: Lai and Robbins (1985) for exponential families, Agrawal (1995) reducing these to purely sample-mean indices, optimal adaptive sequential-allocation policies, and Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) relaxing to finite-moment arms but still centering on the empirical mean via Chebyshev and Fuk-Nagaev bounds. This is brittle and unsafe. The sample mean has zero breakdown point: one corrupted or heavy-tailed reward can arbitrarily inflate an arm's index, so a small fraction of faulty or adversarial feedback (transcription errors in the clinical trials these papers invoke, click fraud, malicious ratings, sensor faults) can drive the policy onto an inferior arm and silently destroy the O(log n) guarantee. Sharp constants also require knowing the reward family, so misspecification quietly voids guarantees. Yakowitz-Lowe still relies on the empirical mean and gives only loose asymptotic rates under heavy tails, and none of these works consider adversarial corruption; the only robustness in the corpus (Berry and Fristedt) is Bayesian robustness to prior misspecification. Reliability, security, and reproducibility of these classic index policies under noisy, corrupted, or misspecified rewards is thus an open failure gap in the safety-critical settings they motivate.","method":"Relax and extend scope: robust upper-confidence-bound index policies that keep the Lai-Robbins and Agrawal guarantees under weaker assumptions. First, weaken assumptions from bounded exponential-family rewards to only a finite (1+epsilon) moment per arm plus up to an eta-fraction of arbitrarily corrupted samples per arm. Second, replace the sample mean in Agrawal's index with a robust location estimator from that arm's own history (median-of-means or an alpha-trimmed mean), preserving the cheap per-arm index structure. Third, replace the KL and large-deviations inflation with a confidence radius derived for the robust estimator, extending Agrawal's large-deviations lemmas and Yakowitz-Lowe's Fuk-Nagaev and Bernstein machinery to the tail of median-of-means and trimmed means under contamination, and prove the inflated robust index remains a valid upper confidence bound so it plugs into Agrawal's general upper-bound theorem and the Lai-Robbins lower bound. Fourth, prove finite-time regret bounds: a robust O(log n) exploration term plus an additive bias term growing smoothly with contamination eta and tail-heaviness, recovering the classical O(log n) when eta is zero and rewards are light-tailed. Fifth, give a data-driven calibration of block count, trimming fraction, and inflation schedule so guarantees hold without knowing the reward family, addressing misspecification and reproducibility. Sixth, validate on clinical-trial-style allocation and machine or strategy selection with injected outliers, heavy-tailed rewards, and adversarial reward-poisoning, comparing regret and worst-case suboptimal-pull counts against the sample-mean UCB indices of Agrawal and Yakowitz-Lowe."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as brittleness of sample-mean index policies under corruption/heavy tails (failure_risk_gap), with a scope-mismatch angle on narrow assumptions. The core move replaces the sample mean with robust estimators and re-derives guarantees to reduce brittleness (robustification), while also weakening assumptions (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottleneck identified: zero breakdown point of the sample mean voiding O(log n) guarantees."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bandit index policies rely on empirical means, which are brittle to outliers, adversarial reward corruption, and heavy tails; Yakowitz-Lowe show logarithmic regret collapses to polynomial under only finite moments, and none of the works defend against contamination or misspecified tails.","method":"Swap the empirical mean in UCB index policies for a robust estimator such as median-of-means or a trimmed Catoni M-estimator, build a matching robust confidence radius scaled with log n, and prove logarithmic regret under heavy tails plus graceful linear-in-corruption degradation, with Lepski-type adaptation when the corruption level and moment order are unknown; validate against Agrawal UCB and Yakowitz-Lowe under Pareto rewards and reward poisoning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is identified as brittleness of empirical-mean UCB to outliers, corruption, and heavy tails (failure_risk_gap), with the observation that logarithmic regret collapses under weak moment assumptions (scope_mismatch). The central move swaps in robust estimators with matching confidence radii and proves regret under heavy tails and corruption (robustification), extending guarantees to weaker moment conditions (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottleneck (mean estimator fragility) identified; not superficial stitching since the robust estimator plus confidence radius plus proof is integrated."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Foundational bandit works give only asymptotic or assumption-dependent guarantees that are unreliable at finite horizons. Lai-Robbins 1985, Agrawal 1995, and Burnetas-Katehakis 1996 achieve O(log n) regret only asymptotically with constants set by unknown KL numbers and assume a known parametric family, so performance cannot be certified at a fixed n and misspecification can break it. Gittins indices (Gittins 1989; Berry-Fristedt 1985; Varaiya 1994) need discounting and a correct prior and are brittle to prior misspecification. Yakowitz-Lowe 1991 gives only asymptotic nonparametric rates, and the Q-learning and RL strand (Sutton-Barto; Holland) only asymptotic convergence. None offers distribution-free finite-time high-probability regret control, so users cannot know how much to trust a policy at fixed n, on unknown distributions, or under misspecification.","method":"Build a unified confidence-bound bandit index that gives finite-time reliability certificates and bridges frequentist, Bayesian Gittins, nonparametric, and RL strands. The index is empirical mean plus a concentration padding (Hoeffding or empirical-Bernstein) instead of a KL term; this padding is both a distribution-free surrogate for the Lai-Robbins large-deviations inflation and a frequentist version of the Gittins exploration premium, matched up to constants by a confidence radius. Using Pollard 1984 empirical-process tools, prove a non-asymptotic KL-free O(log n) expected-regret bound for all finite n over a nonparametric class, a high-probability any-time bound on suboptimal pulls via time-uniform peeling, and asymptotic recovery of the Lai-Robbins and Burnetas-Katehakis rate. Show parametric and Gittins indices go linear under misspecification while this index stays logarithmic. Validate on Yakowitz-Lowe Bernoulli testbeds and RL bandit environments, reporting certified bounds and full regret distributions against Gittins, Lai-Robbins, nonparametric, and Q-learning baselines."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior guarantees are asymptotic and assumption-dependent (known parametric family, discounting, correct prior), unreliable at finite horizons and under misspecification — a scope_mismatch, with a secondary evidence_gap around certifiable finite-time guarantees. The core move is making O(log n) regret hold non-asymptotically, distribution-free, and under misspecification (relax_extend_scope), executed via new finite-time bounds/proofs (formal_derivation). Bridging framing is present but the substantive contribution is extending guarantees, not just stitching literatures. Bottleneck (KL-free concentration padding replacing large-deviations inflation) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"A puzzle sits at the heart of this literature on asymptotically efficient bandit index policies. Lai & Robbins (\"Asymptotically efficient adaptive allocation rules\") prove an O(log n) regret lower bound whose leading constant is the Kullback–Leibler number M(θ), and construct upper-confidence-bound (UCB) index policies that hit it — but only when the parametric family (essentially one-parameter exponential families) is known a priori. Three later works then send flatly contradictory signals about whether that optimal constant survives when the family is unknown:\n\n(1) Agrawal (\"Sample mean based index policies with O(log n) regret\") builds a fully general index that uses only the sample mean, but proves it must pay a strict \"contraction principle\" penalty: its constant is a contraction of the KL number and is provably suboptimal except for one-parameter exponential families. Message: generality COSTS optimality.\n\n(2) Burnetas & Katehakis (\"Optimal adaptive policies for sequential allocation problems\") define a distribution-agnostic \"dual\"/plug-in index (a KL-constrained optimization over the empirical reward measure) and prove it attains the exact optimal constant with NO parametric assumptions — for nonparametric discrete distributions with finite support. Message: generality is FREE.\n\n(3) Yet Burnetas & Katehakis can only verify their sufficient conditions for finite-support discrete arms and explicitly leave the normal-unknown-variance case (the canonical continuous model) as an open problem; Yakowitz & Lowe's nonparametric methods likewise attain the optimal rate only for bounded arms. So the very case practitioners care about — continuous, unbounded, possibly heavy-tailed rewards — is exactly where the \"generality is free\" claim silently breaks.\n\nThese conflicting claims have never been reconciled empirically, because every one of these contributions is a pencil-and-paper asymptotic theorem with no shared implementation or benchmark; and the parallel model-free route (Q-learning for bandits, Sutton & Barto's RL framing, Gittins indices) optimizes a discounted criterion disconnected from the regret constant, so it cannot arbitrate the dispute. The gap that matters: is distribution-free attainment of the optimal KL constant a real phenomenon or a mirage that collapses on continuous/heavy-tailed rewards, and is the plug-in empirical index's failure on unbounded supports fundamental or a fixable coverage problem? No deployable artifact exists to answer this.","method":"Build OmniIndex, a self-calibrating, distribution-free bandit index engine plus a unified benchmark harness, as the central artifact. The system turns the scattered family-specific index constructions into one deployable pipeline and adds a data-driven safeguard aimed squarely at the continuous/unbounded case that breaks the theory.\n\nCore engine (per arm, each round):\n1. Maintain the empirical reward measure p̂_a from the samples observed so far.\n2. Compute an \"empirical rate-function UCB\" by solving the Burnetas–Katehakis dual: index U_a = max over distributions q of mean(q) subject to KL(p̂_a ‖ q) ≤ (log t)/T_a(a) (t = time, T_a = pulls of arm a). This is a finite-dimensional convex program over the empirical support — directly implementable, no parametric family assumed.\n3. Tail/support safeguard (the novel component addressing the open normal-unknown-variance failure): because on unbounded supports the empirical measure never \"sees\" the tail, the plug-in KL confidence set fails to cover the true distribution and the index loses its upper-confidence property. OmniIndex augments p̂_a with an adaptive \"ghost mass\" at an inflated support endpoint whose location/weight is set by an online-estimated tail/scale statistic, so the confidence set provably contains distributions with the estimated variability. The inflation is auto-tuned by a coverage monitor.\n4. Coverage monitor / self-calibration: hold out a fraction of each arm's samples and empirically test how often the constructed index actually upper-bounds the held-out mean; drive the ghost-mass inflation and confidence radius with a controller to hit a target coverage (e.g., 1−1/t), giving a data-driven, family-free calibration in place of the parametric assumptions that the theory needed.\n5. Robust fallback selection: run, in shadow mode, a bounded-arm sample-mean contraction index (Agrawal) and a parametric KL index (Lai–Robbins-style) when a family is confidently identified; an online model-selection layer picks among engine variants by a cross-validated regret proxy.\n\nTheory-grounded justification hooks: use empirical-process/uniform-convergence tools (Pollard, \"Convergence of stochastic processes\") to argue the empirical rate function converges uniformly and to size the ghost mass; use likelihood-ratio/empirical-likelihood results (from mathematical statistics) to relate the KL-constrained program to valid confidence sets.\n\nBenchmark harness (the second half of the artifact): a reproducible testbed instantiating each theoretical policy under one interface — parametric KL-UCB, sample-mean contraction UCB, empirical dual index, OmniIndex with safeguard, and a Q-learning/Gittins model-free baseline — evaluated across (a) finite-support discrete arms (where theory says the dual index is optimal), (b) exponential-family arms, (c) normal arms with unknown variance, and (d) heavy-tailed arms. We measure realized regret and, crucially, the empirical leading constant regret/log(n) versus the Lai–Robbins M(θ).\n\nHow this resolves the puzzle: the harness directly tests whether \"generality is free\" (Burnetas–Katehakis) or \"generality costs optimality\" (Agrawal) as reward distributions move from finite-support to continuous/heavy-tailed, isolating exactly where the plug-in index's optimal-constant claim degrades. OmniIndex's coverage-calibrated safeguard is the concrete mechanism for recovering upper-confidence validity — and thus near-optimal-constant regret — in the normal-unknown-variance and heavy-tailed regimes that the source theory leaves open, converting an unproven asymptotic dispute into a measured, deployable result."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as reconciling contradictory theoretical claims (Agrawal 'generality costs' vs Burnetas-Katehakis 'generality is free'), a clear puzzle_contradiction, with a secondary evidence_gap since no shared benchmark exists to arbitrate. The method builds OmniIndex plus a benchmark harness as the central deliverable (artifact_system), with heavy empirical_mapping via the comparative testbed. The precise bottleneck—plug-in empirical index failing to cover unbounded/heavy-tailed support—is well identified (score 3). Some surface stitching risk since it assembles existing index policies under one interface, but the ghost-mass safeguard and coverage monitor add a genuinely new mechanism."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"A paradox runs through this body of work on the infinite-horizon frequentist multi-armed bandit. Lai & Robbins (1985) proved that the *optimal* O(log n) regret constant is an information-theoretic quantity — the Kullback–Leibler number of the full reward distribution — suggesting that to be optimal a policy must, in effect, learn the whole distribution of each arm. Two later camps take opposite stances on this, and both fail in the regime practitioners care about most (unbounded rewards, unknown/heavy-tailed spread).\n\n(1) The \"simplicity\" camp uses only the sample mean. Agrawal (1995) shows sample-mean UCB indices attain O(log n) but with a *contracted* KL constant that is provably optimal only for one-parameter exponential families and strictly suboptimal otherwise; Yakowitz & Lowe's (1991) sample-mean rule is rate-optimal only for bounded arms, and merely \"rate-guaranteed\" under finite moments. So robustness costs constant-factor optimality.\n\n(2) The \"full-distribution\" camp achieves the optimal constant. Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) build indices from a dual KL-projection over the full model and reach the optimal constant — but only for finite-support discrete or known-variance families, and they explicitly leave the *Gaussian-with-unknown-variance* case as an open problem (one assumption unverified). Their method needs the model class and a heavier optimization.\n\nHere is the contradiction: theory says optimality requires the whole distribution, yet the whole-distribution method is exactly the one that cannot handle unbounded, unknown-variance rewards, while the robust sample-mean method that *can* run there is provably suboptimal. Meanwhile the reinforcement-learning view (Sutton 1992; \"Q-learning for bandit problems\", 1995) treats a bandit as a degenerate MDP and explores with sample-mean value estimates plus epsilon-greedy/optimism — inheriting the suboptimal-constant problem with no principled fix. So neither \"use only the mean\" nor \"use the whole distribution\" is right, and the gap is widest precisely where it matters.","method":"Propose a *moment-budgeted empirical-KL index policy* that interpolates continuously between the sample-mean and full-distribution extremes, with the budget chosen adaptively from data.\n\nCore index. For arm a with T_a observations, replace Burnetas–Katehakis's full-distribution KL projection with a *moment-constrained* empirical-likelihood projection. Define the index as the largest candidate mean μ such that there exists a distribution that (i) matches the arm's empirical estimates of the first r moments to within data-driven tolerances and (ii) lies within an empirical KL/likelihood ball of the observed sample. By convex duality this reduces to a low-dimensional optimization over only r+1 Lagrange multipliers (one per retained moment), so computation scales with the moment budget r, not with support size or a parametric family. At r=1 this provably collapses to Agrawal's sample-mean/contraction index (recovering its robustness and O(log n) guarantee under a single moment condition, à la Yakowitz–Lowe); as r grows toward the full empirical distribution it recovers the Burnetas–Katehakis optimal KL constant. The optimal Lai–Robbins constant is thus attained whenever the retained moments span the directions that determine the true KL divergence.\n\nAdaptive moment budget. Run r online: start at r=1 and increment r only when a concentration test certifies that the r-th empirical moment is estimated reliably enough that adding its constraint tightens the confidence bound by more than its estimation error. This yields graceful degradation — the policy never pays for moments the data cannot support — and turns \"how much of the distribution do you need?\" into a self-tuned, per-arm decision rather than an a priori modeling choice.\n\nResolving the open case. For the Gaussian-unknown-variance / general unbounded case that Burnetas–Katehakis leave open and that sample-mean methods handle only suboptimally, instantiate r=2 (mean + variance) with a *self-normalized* deviation bound so the confidence width uses the estimated variance rather than a known bound. We conjecture and will prove this two-moment index attains the correct KL constant for the Gaussian family and a near-optimal constant for sub-Gaussian/finite-variance arms, closing the open regime.\n\nAnalysis and evaluation. (a) Prove an O(log n) regret upper bound whose constant is the r-moment \"partially contracted\" KL, and show it converges to the Lai–Robbins bound as the adaptive budget grows, quantifying the exact optimality gap as a function of retained moments. (b) Show r=1 reproduces Agrawal's constant and r=2 resolves the Gaussian-unknown-variance case. (c) Bridge to RL: drop the index in place of optimistic Q-values in the bandit Q-learning/epsilon-greedy loop to give that framework its first optimal-constant exploration rule. (d) Empirically compare against sample-mean UCB (Agrawal), full-distribution KL indices (Burnetas–Katehakis), and epsilon-greedy Q-learning on bounded, Gaussian-unknown-variance, and heavy-tailed arms, measuring both regret and per-step compute to demonstrate the simplicity–optimality trade-off is largely illusory once the moment budget is chosen adaptively."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a contradiction: theory says optimality needs the full distribution, yet the full-distribution method fails exactly in the unbounded/unknown-variance regime where the robust mean-only method is suboptimal (puzzle_contradiction), with a strong scope_mismatch component (methods break in unbounded/heavy-tailed regimes). The core move is a continuous interpolation that unifies the sample-mean (Agrawal) and full-distribution (Burnetas-Katehakis) extremes into one moment-budgeted index, reconciling the two camps and bridging to RL exploration - synthesis_unification. It also extends prior work to weaker assumptions/broader regimes (relax_extend_scope). Formal derivation (regret bounds) is present but subordinate to the unification framing. Bottleneck is precisely identified (which moments span KL directions), not stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about bandit optimality contradiction.","method":"Test method about an empirical benchmark of bandit policies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation stated as an optimality contradiction (asymptotic vs finite-time regret bounds), and the classic contribution is finite-time regret bounds (formal derivation), though the proposal text mentions empirical benchmarking. Placeholder-like proposal text lowers confidence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"A contradiction runs through the classical bandit literature. Lai and Robbins (1985) showed the unavoidable O(log n) regret constant is governed by the KL number I(theta_a, theta_star), and Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) gave its exact optimal form M equals sum over arms of Delta_a divided by K_a, where K_a is the infimum of I(theta_a, theta_prime) over alternatives whose mean exceeds mu_star, achieved only by indices solving full-distribution KL dual problems. Yet Agrawal (1995) showed that index policies depending on an arm's history only through its scalar sample mean already achieve O(log n) regret, attaining the exact optimal constant for one-parameter exponential families while being strictly suboptimal otherwise, via a contraction of KL, namely I1_p(x) equals the infimum of KL(nu, p) over distributions nu whose mean equals x. This is a paradox: KL is the fundamental quantity, and a single scalar provably suffices for optimality in one regime but provably wastes exploration in another. The field treats this as a dichotomy: simple but generally suboptimal (Agrawal; Yakowitz and Lowe 1991, optimal rate only for bounded arms) versus optimal but full-distribution (Lai-Robbins; Burnetas-Katehakis). Missing is an explanatory account of what the mean discards, why exponential families are the precise boundary of sufficiency, and which minimal statistic restores optimality. Closing this converts an all-or-nothing choice into a tunable, quantified tradeoff between simplicity and regret optimality.","method":"Introduce a formal moment-sufficiency hierarchy unifying Agrawal, Lai-Robbins and Burnetas-Katehakis as endpoints of one continuum, deriving the exact price of a low-dimensional statistic. Ontology: for a K-dimensional statistic Phi equals (phi_1, ..., phi_K), for example the first K moments, define the class Pi_K of index policies summarizing each arm only through the empirical Phi; Agrawal is Pi_1 with Phi being the identity, and full-distribution policies are Pi_infinity. Central object: the level-K KL contraction IK_p(t), defined as the infimum of KL(nu, p) over distributions nu with expected Phi equal to t; by Sanov large deviations this is the sharpest confidence rate constructible from Phi, and its minimizer is the maximum-entropy exponential tilt matching t, giving a finite convex dual over K plus one multipliers. Effective divergence: DK_a, the infimum of KL(nu, p_a) over alternatives whose mean, seen through Phi, exceeds mu_star; prove the best attainable constant in Pi_K is M_K equals sum over arms of Delta_a divided by DK_a, matching Burnetas-Katehakis with K_a replaced by DK_a. Monotonicity theorem: adding moments adds equality constraints, shrinking the feasible set and raising the infimum KL, so M_1 is at least M_2 is at least M_infinity equal to M_LR, and the gap M_K minus M_infinity, namely sum over arms of Delta_a times (one over DK_a minus one over Dinf_a), is the explicit price of moment truncation. Sufficiency-boundary theorem: M_K equals M_infinity if and only if the information projection onto the set where expected Phi equals t stays inside the true family for all critical alternatives, equivalently if and only if the family together with its critical alternatives is a K-parameter exponential family whose sufficient statistic is spanned by Phi; this explains Agrawal's paradox as the K equals 1 case. Constructive corollary MOMENT-UCB: track empirical Phi and set each index to the supremum of the mean over distributions nu whose contraction IK evaluated at expected Phi is at most (log n) divided by N_a, computed via the K plus one dimensional exponential-family dual, generalizing Agrawal's inflated mean and Burnetas-Katehakis's dual indices. Prove a matching upper bound, regret at most M_K log n plus o(log n), via Agrawal-style large-deviations lemmas, plus a Pi_K-restricted lower bound establishing M_K as the class optimum. The result is a taxonomy of policies indexed by statistic dimension, a theorem locating exponential families as the exact sufficiency frontier, and a tunable knob trading estimation cost for provable regret."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.93,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a paradox/contradiction (scalar mean provably sufficient in one regime, provably wasteful in another) with a missing explanatory account of the sufficiency boundary, so puzzle_contradiction primary with explanation_gap secondary. The method constructs a formal moment-sufficiency hierarchy with theorems, bounds, and a KL-contraction ontology (formal_derivation), while unifying Agrawal, Lai-Robbins, and Burnetas-Katehakis as endpoints of one continuum (synthesis_unification secondary). The unification is substantive derivation, not superficial stitching, and identifies a precise limiting factor (moment truncation cost)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation for the bandit optimal-constant paradox described above.","method":"test method: empirical large-deviation index via KL-constrained optimization."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The classic result establishes finite-time (rather than only asymptotic) regret bounds for bandit index policies, extending prior asymptotic guarantees to a stronger regime, which fits scope_mismatch with a puzzle/tradeoff flavor around optimal constants. The core move is a formal derivation of regret bounds. Proposal text is thin/test-like, raising boilerplate."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"A contradiction runs through this bandit literature. Lai-Robbins showed the optimal log-n regret constant is a KL quantity attainable only when the reward distribution family is known. Burnetas-Katehakis generalized this optimal constant but their index still needs the family, and they cannot even verify their condition for normal arms with unknown variance. Agrawal dropped the need for the family with a sample-mean index but attains the optimal constant only for exponential families, otherwise paying a strictly larger contraction constant. Yakowitz-Lowe are fully nonparametric under finite moments but reach only the optimal rate for bounded arms. So the optimal constant is provably achievable yet every method either needs parametric knowledge we lack or forfeits optimality, and a benign continuous family defeats the optimal machinery. This matters because the KL bound is meant to price ignorance exactly, but no policy pays that price when the family is unknown and continuous.","method":"Attain the optimal Burnetas-Katehakis constant from the empirical distribution alone: index each arm by the largest mean among distributions supported on its observed reward values whose KL divergence from its empirical distribution is at most log-n over the number of pulls, then pull the arm with the largest index. This keeps Agrawal's data-only simplicity but replaces his contraction of the KL number with the exact nonparametric KL constraint that defines the optimal constant. Analyze it via empirical Sanov-type large deviations and empirical-process tools rather than parametric large-deviation lemmas, proving the index is an asymptotic upper confidence bound and that suboptimal pulls grow at the optimal KL rate, which resolves the normal-unknown-variance case left open by Burnetas-Katehakis. Establish guarantees along a ladder of weaker assumptions: bounded support, sub-exponential arms via adaptive truncation with bias correction, and heavy-tailed finite-moment arms via winsorized empirical-KL constraints. Provide a matching lower bound beyond known families, asymptotic efficiency within uniformly-fast policies, and simulations where the empirical index tracks the optimal constant while sample-mean and parametric indices do not."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a contradiction: the optimal KL constant is provably achievable yet every existing method either needs parametric knowledge or forfeits optimality (puzzle_contradiction), with a strong scope-mismatch component about restrictive family/support assumptions. The core move relaxes parametric assumptions to attain the optimal constant nonparametrically from empirical distributions across a ladder of weaker conditions (relax_extend_scope), backed by new large-deviation analysis, matching lower bounds, and efficiency proofs (formal_derivation). Not surface stitching: it replaces a specific mechanism (contracted KL number) with the exact empirical-KL constraint, a precise bottleneck."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Lai and Robbins (1985) proved the O(log n) regret bound with a Kullback-Leibler constant and gave index policies attaining it; Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) sharpened this to uniformly-fast optimality; Agrawal (1995) gave a simpler version depending only on the sample mean inflated by a large-deviation amount. The contradiction: these policies are sold as optimal and general, yet their guarantees rest on fragility. Agrawal's proof relies entirely on large-deviation lemmas needing a steep cumulant generating function, i.e. an exponentially light tail or exponential family, while Lai-Robbins and Burnetas-Katehakis require the exact parametric family to be known. The design that hits the optimal constant, a sample-mean index tuned to a light-tailed family, is exactly what makes it brittle: a few corrupted observations or a heavy-tailed arm (Pareto, Student-t, common in finance, latency, clinical response) can inflate or deflate the index arbitrarily and turn O(log n) into near-linear regret. Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) relax the parametric assumption but attain the optimal rate only for bounded arms and ignore contamination. Thus asymptotic efficiency and robustness appear to trade off, and no policy here is at once distribution-agnostic, robust to heavy tails and outliers, and O(log n) with a near-optimal constant. This matters because in clinical allocation occasional corrupted or extreme outcomes are the norm, making a provably optimal but easily derailed policy untrustworthy.","method":"Build a Robust large-deviation UCB index policy that decouples the estimator from the confidence inflation. Replace the sample mean in Agrawal's index with a bounded-influence robust estimator (median-of-means, trimmed mean, or Catoni M-estimator) per arm, and re-derive the index inflation from concentration bounds valid under only a finite 1-plus-epsilon moment, replacing Agrawal's steep-cumulant bound with sub-Gaussian-type robust deviation bounds, so the index stays a valid upper confidence bound even without a moment generating function. Parameterize by a per-arm corruption fraction epsilon and prove a regret bound that degrades continuously in epsilon and the tail index rather than breaking. Show the leading constant recovers the Lai-Robbins and Agrawal optimal constant in the light-tailed uncontaminated limit. Because the tail index and epsilon are unknown in practice, add an online diagnostic comparing sample mean to robust estimate and monitoring empirical tail behavior to self-tune the number of blocks or trimming level, removing the need to specify the family. Prove O(log n) regret and the epsilon-degradation bound using empirical-process tools in the spirit of Pollard (1984), and compare empirically against Agrawal, Lai-Robbins, and Yakowitz-Lowe across clean, heavy-tailed, and contaminated regimes."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a tradeoff/contradiction (optimal but brittle) but centers on brittleness under heavy tails and contamination, hence failure_risk_gap primary with puzzle_contradiction secondary. The method robustifies UCB by replacing the estimator with bounded-influence estimators and re-deriving bounds under weaker moment assumptions (robustification primary, relax_extend_scope secondary). The bottleneck (sample-mean index fragility to heavy tails/outliers requiring light tails) is precisely identified. Not surface stitching: it re-derives concentration bounds and self-tuning diagnostics rather than bolting components together."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The bandit literature has produced two families of \"provably optimal\" index policies that, paradoxically, disagree with each other. On the Bayesian / dynamic-programming side, the Gittins allocation index (Multi-armed bandit allocation indices; Multi-armed bandit problem revisited) is exactly optimal for the discounted-reward objective by decomposing an N-dimensional problem into N one-dimensional retirement problems, and Ishikida & Varaiya surprisingly show the same index rule is also asymptotically optimal under the average-reward criterion; moreover it can be computed model-free by reinforcement learning (Q-learning for bandit problems). On the frequentist side, Lai & Robbins (Asymptotically efficient adaptive allocation rules), Agrawal (Sample-mean index policies), and Burnetas & Katehakis (Optimal adaptive policies for sequential allocation) build indices from Kullback-Leibler / large-deviation confidence bounds that are asymptotically efficient for *regret* with the optimal KL constant.\n\nHere is the contradiction. Both are called \"optimal index rules,\" yet they are derived from entirely unrelated principles (optimal-stopping calibration vs. KL confidence sets), they prescribe different indices, and neither optimality notion implies the other: the Bayes-optimal Gittins index carries no guarantee on the Lai-Robbins regret constant and discards nothing but also proves nothing about learning loss, while the regret-optimal UCB index ignores prior information and says nothing about discounted optimality. Worse, a second paradox lives *inside* the frequentist camp: Agrawal's simple sample-mean index attains O(log n) regret but, in general (beyond one-parameter exponential families), only with a *suboptimal* constant obtained through a KL \"contraction,\" whereas Burnetas & Katehakis recover the *optimal* constant only by solving a distribution-specific KL dual with extra assumptions and heavier computation. So simplicity, generality, and constant-optimality cannot currently be had together, and Bayesian versus frequentist optimality point in different directions. Why should two \"optimal\" indices disagree, and can a single object explain and reconcile them? This matters because practitioners must otherwise choose between prior-exploiting Bayesian optimality and distribution-free regret guarantees, and because the gap leaves no simple, general, model-free rule that is simultaneously regret-constant-optimal.","method":"Introduce a single unifying object — a distributionally-robust Gittins index defined on empirical KL-confidence balls and learned online by reinforcement learning — and show that both the Bayesian Gittins index and the frequentist KL-optimal UCB index are special limits of it.\n\n(1) Reconciling construction. For each arm, set up a per-arm \"calibration\" restart MDP exactly in the Gittins style: the state is the arm's empirical reward distribution (nonparametric, finite-support/finite-moment, following the Yakowitz-Lowe and Burnetas-Katehakis settings), and the index is the retirement/fair-charge value that makes pulling indifferent to retiring. The one change from classical Gittins is that the continuation value is evaluated not under a fixed Bayesian posterior but *optimistically over a KL / large-deviation confidence set* of plausible reward distributions of radius r_t = log t / T_a(t) around the empirical distribution. Concretely the index is the retirement value of an optimal-stopping problem whose per-step reward is sup{ mean(q) : KL(empirical || q) <= r_t } — i.e., the Burnetas-Katehakis optimistic mean is embedded as the instantaneous continuation reward of a Gittins retirement problem.\n\n(2) Unification theorem (resolving the puzzle). Prove that this robust index reduces to (i) the classical Bayesian Gittins index when the confidence set collapses to a trusted posterior (radius -> 0 with prior weight), and (ii) the Burnetas-Katehakis KL-dual index — hence the Lai-Robbins optimal regret constant, in the *general* nonparametric case, not only exponential families — when the radius is calibrated to log t and the discount factor is driven to 1 (the average-reward limit for which Ishikida & Varaiya already proved Gittins-index optimality). This exhibits the two literatures as two limits (confidence radius and discounting) of one index, explaining precisely *why* the classical indices differ and removing Agrawal's contraction loss by using the exact KL ball rather than its contraction.\n\n(3) Model-free computation. Extend Duff-style Q-learning for bandits from posteriors to empirical KL-balls: learn the retirement value of the calibration MDP by temporal-difference/Q-learning on the empirical-distribution state, so the index is obtained without solving a family-specific dual and without knowing the distribution class. This gives a rule that is simultaneously simple (index type, sample/empirical-distribution based), general (nonparametric), and constant-optimal — the combination the current tradeoff forbids.\n\n(4) Analysis, assembling the four toolkits. Prove asymptotic efficiency (regret matching the Lai-Robbins/Burnetas-Katehakis lower-bound constant) and the reduction results by combining: Agrawal's large-deviation lemmas to control the KL ball; the interchange/retirement-index optimality arguments (Multi-armed bandit problem revisited) for the stopping problem; Q-learning convergence (Watkins, via the RL introduction) for the learned index; and empirical-process uniform-convergence tools (Convergence of stochastic processes) to control empirical KL over the confidence ball. \n\n(5) Validation. Empirically compare the learned robust Gittins index against UCB/Lai-Robbins indices, Burnetas-Katehakis dual indices, and the exact discounted Gittins index across Bernoulli, exponential-family, and non-exponential nonparametric arms, verifying (a) it tracks the discounted-optimal policy at small radius/high discount and (b) attains the optimal regret slope and constant at the log-t radius, thereby demonstrating the reconciliation in practice."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed around a contradiction: two 'optimal' index rules disagree, plus an internal frequentist paradox on simplicity/generality/constant-optimality tradeoff. This is puzzle_contradiction, with the disconnected Bayesian and frequentist literatures giving a secondary bridge_opportunity flavor. The method constructs a single unifying object showing both indices as limits, plus a unification theorem — synthesis_unification, with formal_derivation secondary (theorems, reductions, bounds). Though it combines four toolkits, the reconciliation via a genuinely novel robust-Gittins-index object with proved reductions is more than A+B stitching, hence low stitching score. Bottleneck (Agrawal contraction loss, KL constant suboptimality) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Optimal bandit policies are too costly to deploy at scale; cheap ones are suboptimal; no budgeted system exists.","method":"Build a bandit library caching precomputed indices in O(1) lookup tables and auto-selecting the cheapest policy meeting a regret target under a hardware budget."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The motivation frames a resource bottleneck (optimal policies too costly to deploy at scale) alongside a tradeoff between cost and optimality. The proposed method is a bandit library caching precomputed indices with auto-selection under hardware budget, making a concrete system the central deliverable, with an optimization/allocation flavor. Note this is far from the historical UCB finite-time analysis paper; the proposal reads as a deployment engineering artifact rather than a theoretical contribution."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"The applications motivating this corpus (sequential clinical trials and allocation of scarce, costly treatments/experiments; Lai and Robbins 1985, Yakowitz and Lowe 1991, Berry and Fristedt 1985) are resource-bottleneck problems: every arm pull spends an expensive, strictly limited resource. Yet nearly all policies here (Lai and Robbins 1985, Agrawal 1995, Burnetas and Katehakis 1996) are built for the non-Bayesian infinite-horizon regime, minimizing asymptotic O(log n) regret with confidence-bound inflation calibrated to elapsed time. These guarantees are vacuous when the total budget N is small and fixed: the log-n inflation keeps exploring as if the horizon were unbounded, wasting scarce pulls and never cashing in learning as the budget runs out; and the optimal exploration constant needs the KL number / full distribution family, which tiny samples cannot supply. The only horizon-aware alternatives (finite-horizon DP and Gittins indices; Berry and Fristedt 1985, Ishikida and Varaiya 1994) are Bayesian and computationally prohibitive, a compute/prior-elicitation bottleneck Agrawal 1995 also flags for history-dependent UCBs. So no policy is simultaneously budget-aware, distribution-free/sample-mean-based, and cheap enough for the scarce-sample regime that motivates the field.","method":"Propose a Budget-Aware Sample-mean Index (BASI) policy for a finite-budget bandit with known small total pulls N. At step t with remaining budget R=N-t, each arm's index equals its empirical mean plus an inflation g(n_j,R), where g uses Agrawal 1995's large-deviation / empirical-likelihood upper-confidence construction (sample-mean-only, computed as a cheap one-dimensional dual in the spirit of Burnetas and Katehakis 1996). The key change: replace the time-based allowance (about log n) with one tied to remaining budget R, so exploration is large when much horizon remains and decays to zero as R approaches 0, automatically shifting from exploration to exploitation as the resource is spent. Steps: (1) prove a value-of-remaining-budget result showing the optimal exploration term must vanish as R approaches 0, motivating a schedule like log R or information-gain-per-remaining-pull instead of log elapsed time; (2) keep per-step cost linear in the number of arms, with no dynamic programming or priors; (3) support bounded/nonparametric arms per Yakowitz and Lowe 1991; (4) add a batched/delayed-feedback variant that spends the budget in K batches and recomputes indices only K times, cutting compute and deployment friction. Analysis: derive non-asymptotic finite-N regret bounds via Agrawal's large-deviation lemmas, identifying small-N and many-arm regimes where budget-aware inflation provably beats the finite-N restriction of log-n policies while staying within a bounded factor of the Gittins/DP optimum at far lower cost. Validation: simulate small-N clinical-trial-like settings (Bernoulli and bounded arms, many arms relative to budget), reporting simple and cumulative regret plus compute/wall-clock cost against Lai-Robbins, Agrawal UCB, Burnetas-Katehakis, and exact Gittins/DP."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that existing asymptotic O(log n) policies assume infinite/unbounded horizon and are vacuous in the small-fixed-budget regime motivating the field (scope mismatch), with resource scarcity as the driving concern. The method adapts index policies to work under the weaker/narrower finite-budget setting by replacing time-based inflation with budget-aware inflation and deriving non-asymptotic bounds (relax/extend scope, plus formal derivation of finite-N regret bounds). The bottleneck (log-n inflation keeps exploring as if horizon unbounded, wasting scarce pulls) is precisely identified. Some stitching flavor since it recombines Agrawal's LDP construction with budget-tied schedules, but the core reframing is substantive."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about bandit index policy resource costs.","method":"Test method: empirical benchmark of bandit policies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"The classic finite-time bandit result derives regret bounds that hold at finite horizons rather than only asymptotically (scope mismatch, formal derivation). However the proposal text is a placeholder ('Test motivation', 'empirical benchmark'), so labels lean on context. Boilerplate high due to stub content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about resource bottleneck in bandit index policies.","method":"Test method proposing a resource indexed theory of index policies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder/test content ('Test motivation', 'Test method'), so labels are inferred from prior-work context on multi-armed bandit index policies. The classic contribution here (finite-time regret bounds) fits scope_mismatch (prior asymptotic-only results extended to finite-time regime) with formal_derivation as the method (bounds/theorems). Low confidence due to boilerplate proposal content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Classic bandit works such as Lai-Robbins, Agrawal UCB, Burnetas-Katehakis, the Gittins index, and Yakowitz-Lowe minimize regret in the number of pulls under unit cost. None address a fixed experimental budget with heterogeneous unknown per-pull costs and parallel batches, the real bottleneck in screening applications like clinical trials and materials or drug candidate search, where the optimal indices are also expensive to compute (Gittins needs dynamic programming; Burnetas-Katehakis solve a dual each step). Progress in these applications is limited by scarce, costly, slow experiments, so counting pulls is the wrong resource metric.","method":"Reformulate adaptive allocation as a budget-constrained search maximizing discovered reward per unit cost. Maintain a cost-normalized index per arm: a large-deviations upper confidence bound on the mean (using only sample mean and pull count, so updates are constant time and avoid Gittins or dual dynamic programming) divided by an online estimate of that arm's unknown per-pull cost, with confidence inflation set via a Burnetas-Katehakis-style contraction dual in a cost-normalized Kullback-Leibler sense. Each round, choose the parallel batch by solving a budgeted knapsack that allocates spend to maximize aggregate marginal information (uncertainty reduction about the best arm) per unit cost, subject to remaining budget and batch size, solved greedily by spending on the highest information-per-cost arm until constraints bind. Adapt the Lagrange multiplier pricing the budget online by search so projected spend exactly exhausts budget B at the horizon, shifting from exploration to exploitation as budget depletes. Prove a logarithmic-in-budget cost-normalized regret bound with a cost-weighted Kullback-Leibler constant, using Agrawal large-deviations lemmas and the Lai-Robbins lower bound, plus a matching lower bound. Evaluate on screening tasks with heterogeneous unknown costs and batches, comparing cost-normalized regret and best-candidate-found-within-budget against unit-cost UCB, Gittins, and Burnetas-Katehakis baselines under equal spend, and report compute saved by the sample-mean indices."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as classic bandit work relying on unrealistic unit-cost assumptions and pull-counting metrics that mismatch real screening applications with fixed budgets, heterogeneous costs, and batches (scope_mismatch), with the underlying limiting factor being scarce/costly experiments (resource_bottleneck). The core move extends bandit policies to a budget-constrained, cost-normalized regime with new confidence bounds (relax_extend_scope), backed by a formal regret bound and matching lower bound (formal_derivation). It identifies a precise bottleneck (wrong resource metric plus expensive optimal indices) rather than superficially stitching methods, though it does combine several existing tools."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"There is a hard trade-off in this bandit literature between the sample cost of a policy (expensive suboptimal pulls) and its compute/knowledge cost. Lai and Robbins (1985) and Agrawal (1995) attain the optimal O(log n) regret constant only by assuming a known reward family (one-parameter exponential families), unavailable in noisy real deployments. Agrawal's sample-mean index is cheap but outside exponential families its constant is only a suboptimal contraction of the KL number, wasting scarce costly experiments. Burnetas and Katehakis (1996) recover the optimal nonparametric constant but restrict to finite-support populations and solve a KL dual optimization for every arm at every epoch, a compute bottleneck growing with arms and horizon. Yakowitz and Lowe (1991) are nonparametric under finite-moment conditions but still solve auxiliary equations and lack the optimal constant. So no policy is at once sample-optimal, cheap to run at scale, and valid under weak realistic assumptions (unknown distributions, noisy or delayed or batched costly feedback). Because each pull is a scarce costly experiment and compute is itself constrained, this joint resource bottleneck, not asymptotic regret order, limits practical use.","method":"Build an amortized empirical-KL index policy that makes the optimal Burnetas-Katehakis and Lai-Robbins guarantee hold under weaker assumptions and far less compute. First, a distribution-free index: keep each arm's empirical reward measure and define its index as the largest mean reachable within an empirical-KL ball of radius (log n)/T_a(n) around that measure, computed against the raw empirical distribution rather than a known family or finite support, using Agrawal's large-deviation lemmas plus empirical-process concentration to cover general bounded and truncated light-tailed rewards. Second, amortized approximate computation: replace the exact per-epoch dual solve with an incremental warm-started convex solver that maintains certified upper and lower bounds on the true index, recomputing an arm only lazily when its pull count crosses a doubling threshold or its empirical measure shifts beyond tolerance epsilon_n, reusing cached bounds otherwise, turning per-epoch per-arm exact solves into a bounded amortized number of cheap updates. Third, an optimality-preserving schedule: shrink epsilon_n on a log-n schedule and always play the certified upper bound, and prove this keeps the upper-confidence-bound property so suboptimal arms are pulled only about M(theta) log n times and the optimal constant survives both empirical estimation and approximation, yielding an explicit compute versus sample-cost frontier. Fourth, extended scope: lazy refresh naturally handles batched and delayed feedback, heterogeneous per-arm pull costs under a fixed budget via cost-weighted regret with KL balls scaled by cost, and large or streaming arm sets. Validate with theory giving cost-weighted O(M(theta) log n) regret under nonparametric, delayed, budgeted conditions and with simulations against exact Burnetas-Katehakis and Agrawal's contraction index, measuring regret and number of optimizations to show matched sample-optimality at a fraction of the compute."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.68,"confidence_paradigm":0.62,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation frames a joint sample-cost/compute bottleneck where no policy is simultaneously sample-optimal, cheap, and valid under weak assumptions, making resource_bottleneck primary with scope_mismatch (known-family/finite-support assumptions) secondary. The method extends optimal guarantees to weaker nonparametric, delayed, budgeted conditions (relax_extend_scope) while the amortized warm-started solver with lazy recomputation is an efficiency/compute-reduction move (optimization_search). Precise bottleneck identification (per-epoch KL dual solves, contraction constant) merits high specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bandit index policies minimize costly wasted pulls in scarce-sample sequential experiments (clinical trials, expensive A/B tests, materials discovery), where the binding resource bottleneck is the number of expensive observations spent on suboptimal arms. But the asymptotically efficient policies achieve O(log n) regret only under a correctly specified distribution family: Lai-Robbins and Burnetas-Katehakis calibrate their optimal constant and dual indices to a known family, and Agrawal's sample-mean UCB attains the optimal KL constant only for one-parameter exponential families (else a suboptimal contraction constant); nonparametric methods relax assumptions at a rate penalty. Under misspecification, heavy tails, or the small-sample regime that dominates when pulls are expensive, these KL-based confidence bounds miscalibrate, causing over-exploration that burns scarce samples or lock-on to a wrong arm giving catastrophic regret. No existing policy is simultaneously sample-frugal and robust to misspecification, so practitioners with costly experiments and uncertain distributional knowledge cannot trust these guarantees where failure costs most.","method":"We propose a Distributionally-Robust Upper-Confidence Index (DR-UCI) that keeps O(log n) frugality while hardening against misspecification and finite-sample brittleness. Each arm's index is the worst-case optimistic mean over an ambiguity set: distributions within a divergence ball (KL or Wasserstein radius rho_a) of the empirical distribution, intersected with weak nonparametric constraints (bounded support or a finite-moment bound). This index is a valid upper confidence bound simultaneously over all candidate distributions, so no single family must be correct. It is computed as a one-dimensional convex dual, generalizing the Burnetas-Katehakis dual-index construction and reusing Agrawal's large-deviations lemmas to calibrate confidence inflation, keeping per-step cost near standard UCB. The reliability mechanism is an adaptive radius: rho_a is driven by a running sequential goodness-of-fit test against a nominal model, shrinking toward zero to recover the Lai-Robbins/Burnetas-Katehakis optimal constant and full frugality when the model fits, and inflating to prevent premature lock-on when misspecification or tail anomalies appear, so robustness is paid for only when needed. Analysis via large deviations proves regret of the form M_robust log n + o(log n) matching the optimal constant under correct specification with rho_a to 0, and staying bounded for any distribution in the ambiguity set, converting catastrophic worst-case regret into controlled bounded loss, plus a bound on extra sample cost from the adaptive radius. We benchmark against Lai-Robbins, Agrawal UCB, and Burnetas-Katehakis under correct specification, adversarial misspecification, and heavy-tailed or contaminated rewards, reporting regret and wasted suboptimal pulls at small horizons; success is near-optimal sample cost when correct and dramatically reduced worst-case wasted pulls under misspecification."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as brittleness under misspecification and finite-sample regimes causing catastrophic regret (failure_risk_gap), with a secondary scope_mismatch since existing guarantees rely on correctly-specified families. The central move is distributional robustification via ambiguity sets and adaptive radius to prevent failure while preserving O(log n) frugality (robustification), with relax_extend_scope as it makes prior policies work under weaker assumptions. Precise bottleneck (miscalibrated KL bounds, over-exploration/lock-on) is identified, so high specificity. Combines DR ambiguity sets with bandit indices but this is a substantive extension, not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: bandit index methods are fragmented and costly to deploy.","method":"Test method: unify Gittins and UCB indices into one precomputed lookup table."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":3,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Test proposal frames the gap as fragmented, costly bandit index methods and proposes to unify Gittins and UCB indices into one lookup table, a superficial A+B combination. Opportunity reads as scope/deployment mismatch; method is synthesis/unification with an artifact flavor. Clear surface stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about scope mismatch in bandit policies.","method":"Test method building a software artifact."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.5,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Motivation flags scope mismatch in bandit policies (asymptotic vs finite-time regret bounds). The classic UCB finite-time analysis is fundamentally a formal derivation of regret bounds, though the stub says 'software artifact.' Given the prior-work context on regret analysis, formal_derivation fits the actual contribution better than artifact_system. Stub is boilerplate/placeholder text."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about structured bandits and the independence-across-arms scope mismatch.","method":"Test method: similarity-pooled UCB index sharing information across arms in a metric space."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation targets the independence-across-arms assumption as a scope mismatch, and the method extends UCB to a structured metric-space regime with information sharing, extending prior work to a broader setting."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap. The prior works all establish O(log n) regret for bandits but only under narrow, poorly transferable boundary conditions. Lai & Robbins (1985) prove optimality only as n goes to infinity and only for known single-parameter exponential families, with constants equal to Kullback-Leibler numbers that require the true distribution. Agrawal (1995) uses sample-mean indices but still an asymptotic O(log n) with large-deviation constants. Burnetas & Katehakis (1996) relax the parametric form yet remain an n-to-infinity limit and leave a normal-variance assumption open. Yakowitz & Lowe (1991) give nonparametric asymptotic rates, and the Gittins line (allocation-indices review; Ishikida & Varaiya 1994) optimizes infinite-horizon discounted/average reward via costly dynamic-programming indices. None address the practical regime: finite, often short horizons; unknown or only-bounded distributions; many arms; and no knowledge of the KL constants governing the bounds. There is no account of when the asymptotic log-n regime begins, how much regret accrues before it, how fragile the constants are under misspecification, or how these index families compare head-to-head at realistic budgets. The theory's boundary conditions mismatch practice, leaving finite-budget deployment without guidance.","method":"Empirical mapping study: a systematic simulation benchmark and diagnostic suite charting the finite-time behavior of the corpus policies and where their asymptotic guarantees hold or break. Testbed: bandit instances varying horizon n (tens to millions), number of arms K, gap structure (one large gap, uniformly small gaps, clustered near-optimal arms), reward family (Bernoulli, normal with unknown variance, finite-support discrete, heavy-tailed with finite moments), plus misspecification where a policy is fed the wrong family. Policy panel on equal footing: Lai-Robbins KL upper-confidence indices, Agrawal sample-mean indices, Burnetas-Katehakis dual indices, Yakowitz-Lowe nonparametric strategies, Gittins discounted indices, and epsilon-greedy/Q-learning baselines. Diagnostics from many Monte Carlo runs: empirical regret curves with fitted growth coefficient versus the KL lower bound; a crossover horizon where observed regret first tracks the log-n slope; sensitivity to tuning and misspecification; distribution-free worst-case regret over each family. Deliverables: phase-diagram heatmaps over (n, K, gap, family) showing which policy dominates in each region and where asymptotic theory is predictive versus misleading, quantifying the pre-asymptotic penalty of KL-based constants. Synthesis: use the patterns to isolate the minimal ingredients giving regret uniform over the whole horizon and robust to unknown distributions, namely a simple sample-mean-plus-confidence-radius index using only bounded support, and empirically validate it attains near-optimal regret where parametric/asymptotic policies falter. This yields a reproducible empirical map of finite-time, misspecification-robust performance to guide policy selection for a given budget."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as scope mismatch: asymptotic guarantees under narrow assumptions fail to transfer to finite, short-horizon, unknown-distribution regimes; secondary evidence_gap since no head-to-head benchmark exists. The reframed proposal method is an empirical mapping study (phase diagrams, diagnostics, regret curves) though the historical paper actually derived UCB bounds; the stated method emphasizes systematic benchmarking, with relax_extend_scope secondary via the goal of a horizon-uniform robust index. Specific bottleneck (KL-constant fragility, pre-asymptotic penalty, crossover horizon) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope mismatch in the objective. Every asymptotically-optimal bandit theory in the corpus defines the best arm, and hence regret, only through expected reward and the largest mean. Lai-Robbins (1985) prove liminf R_n/log n >= sum (mu*-mu_j)/I(theta_j,theta*) using KL distinguishability of MEANS; Agrawal (1995) builds sample-mean index policies whose optimal constant is a large-deviations contraction of that KL number; Burnetas-Katehakis (1996) show the optimal index is the dual K(j)=inf KL(P_j||Q) subject to mean(Q)>=mu*; Yakowitz-Lowe (1991) and Gittins-index work (Ishikida-Varaiya 1994) likewise optimize expected reward. This risk-neutral, mean-only ranking is a narrow boundary condition for the very applications cited (clinical trials, adaptive control, finance), where variance and tail risk change which arm is preferable and decision-makers are risk-averse. The mismatch is structural: the KL machinery is silent once ranking depends on higher moments; tellingly, Burnetas-Katehakis explicitly leave the Gaussian unknown-mean-AND-variance case as an open problem. Thus there is no known fundamental regret limit and no provably efficient policy when best is defined by a risk-adjusted criterion.","method":"A Formal Derivation generalizing the mean-only theory to an arbitrary law-invariant risk functional, recovering classical results as the risk-neutral boundary. (1) Model: arm j has unknown P_j; fix a law-invariant risk functional rho (mean-variance mu-c*sigma^2, entropic/exponential utility, spectral/CVaR as instances). Define rho*=max_j rho(P_j) and rho-regret R(n)=sum over t of (rho* minus rho of the chosen arm). Define consistent (uniformly-fast) policies relative to rho. (2) Fundamental limit (theorem plus proof): define the constrained information K_rho(j)=inf KL(P_j||Q) subject to rho(Q)>=rho* with Q in the model class, the generalization of the Burnetas-Katehakis dual index with the mean constraint replaced by rho. Via a change-of-measure and Wald-likelihood argument (the Lai-Robbins Theorem-1 template) prove: for any consistent policy, liminf R(n)/log n >= sum over suboptimal j of (rho*-rho_j)/K_rho(j). (3) Matching policy (theorem plus proof): a risk-adjusted upper confidence index, index_j = sup of rho(Q) over Q in a KL-ball of radius about log n / N_j(t) around arm j empirical law. Using Agrawal's large-deviations contraction lemmas applied to rho, prove these are valid upper confidence bounds for rho and that the index policy attains the lower bound, establishing efficiency and tightness of K_rho. (4) Regularity and taxonomy: identify conditions on rho (monotonicity under stochastic dominance, quasi-convexity, continuity in the KL topology) that make K_rho positive and finite; classify risk functionals by which admit O(log n) risk-regret. (5) Boundary case and open problem: show rho=mean collapses K_rho to the Lai-Robbins constant, positioning classical theory as the risk-neutral edge of a functional family; derive closed-form K_rho and indices for mean-variance and entropic utility, and an explicit constrained-KL for the Gaussian unknown mean and variance case, resolving the Burnetas-Katehakis open assumption within the risk-aware formulation; characterize how risk-aversion reshapes which arm is hard to distinguish and thus the regret constants. Feasibility: KL lower bounds, contraction/large-deviations lemmas, and constrained-KL dual indices all appear in the corpus; the contribution is the unifying derivation for general rho, the efficiency proof, and the special-case computations."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.95,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a scope mismatch: mean-only risk-neutral ranking is a narrow boundary condition inadequate for risk-averse applications. The method is a formal derivation generalizing Lai-Robbins/Burnetas-Katehakis to arbitrary law-invariant risk functionals with lower bounds, matching policy proofs, and taxonomy; secondary is relax_extend_scope since it broadens the objective to weaker/richer criteria. Precise bottleneck (KL machinery silent for higher moments) identified. Not superficial stitching—reuses established proof templates but for a genuinely new formulation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The classic bandit works here share narrow boundary conditions that mismatch real use. Optimality is asymptotic: Lai and Robbins (1985), Agrawal (1995), Burnetas and Katehakis (1996), Yakowitz and Lowe (1991), and Ishikida and Varaiya (1994) prove O(log n) or index-rule optimality only as n grows, giving no prescription for a fixed finite horizon, which the Bandit problems (1985) monograph shows behaves quite differently. The exploration width also depends on distribution constants assumed known a priori: Lai-Robbins and Burnetas-Katehakis assume a known exponential family and use the exact Kullback-Leibler number; Agrawal's UCB conditions require large-deviation rate constants; Yakowitz-Lowe require a hypothesized moment or boundedness constant and admit one must start at a sensible point since rates depend on the hypothesized bandit postulates. Misspecification is costly and asymmetric: over-stating the rate causes chronic over-exploration, while under-stating risks locking onto a suboptimal arm and linear regret. Rewards are also assumed stationary and i.i.d. The gap: no principled way to choose the exploration configuration when the reward family, its rate or moment constant, and even the horizon are unknown, which is exactly where finite-sample performance is decided.","method":"Treat the exploration tuning of an index policy as something to be optimized and searched online rather than fixed a priori, yielding a self-tuning, horizon-aware bandit needing no known family or rate constant. First, define a parameterized index family: UCB-style indices g(theta) that nest the Lai-Robbins, Agrawal, and Yakowitz forms, where theta has an inflation coefficient c, an assumed rate or moment constant rho, and a schedule shape s that shrinks the width with the number of pulls and with the remaining horizon; classic policies are special points. Second, make rho data-driven by estimating the local rate function online from each arm's rewards via empirical large-deviation and empirical-likelihood estimates, reusing Agrawal's large-deviation lemmas and the Yakowitz-Lowe moment and boundedness bounds, with uniform sample-path validity justified by empirical-process tools (Convergence of stochastic processes, 1984); this turns the fixed distribution constant into a self-calibrating width. Third, run a horizon-aware meta-search over theta: wrap the base policy in a policy-over-policies scheme that allocates the finite budget across screening candidates using racing and successive-halving on a slow timescale, comparing them by an online pseudo-regret proxy (a gap-weighted suboptimal-pull count from running estimates) and eliminating dominated configurations so budget concentrates on the best exploration level for the actual instance and horizon. Fourth, couple two timescales: the fast timescale plays arms and updates statistics while the slow timescale adjusts theta by gradient-free stochastic search on the proxy, framed as a small meta-bandit or stochastic-approximation problem in the reinforcement-learning and Q-learning-for-bandits spirit; because s reads the remaining horizon, exploration tapers near the deadline, and drift in estimated rates or means triggers reallocation, giving robustness to mild non-stationarity. Finally, benchmark against fixed-constant Lai-Robbins, Agrawal UCB, and Yakowitz-Lowe under correctly specified families, misspecified constants, and short or drifting horizons, targeting recovery of the correct KL-optimal O(log n) rate when the family is known, a bounded competitive ratio versus the best fixed theta in hindsight for finite n, and avoidance of the linear-regret failure under under-specified constants. This addresses the scope mismatch by discovering, via online optimization and screening, exactly the constants and finite-horizon schedule that prior work assumes away."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior bandit work relying on narrow assumptions (asymptotic optimality, known distribution family/rate constants, stationarity, no finite horizon), a clear scope_mismatch, with a secondary failure/risk concern (misspecification causing linear regret). The method treats exploration tuning as an online optimization/search problem (meta-search over theta, racing, successive-halving, two-timescale stochastic search), making optimization_search primary, while extending the policies to weaker assumptions (relax_extend_scope) is secondary. The bottleneck is precisely identified (fixed a-priori constants and horizon-unawareness). Not surface stitching since components are integrated around a coherent self-tuning scheme."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about nonstationary bandits.","method":"Test method about recency-weighted large-deviation UCB."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Sparse test-like content: nonstationary bandits (relaxing stationarity assumption of prior UCB work) with a recency-weighted large-deviation UCB. Gap is scope mismatch (stationary regime too narrow); method extends UCB to nonstationary setting, likely with regret bounds (formal derivation). Combining recency-weighting with large-deviation UCB reads somewhat like stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Placeholder proposal text; inferring from prior-work context on multi-armed bandits. The classic contribution is finite-time regret bounds replacing asymptotic guarantees (scope_mismatch/evidence_gap), achieved via formal derivation of bounds. Low confidence due to empty proposal fields."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"finite-time-analysis-of-the-multiarmed-bandit-problem-2002","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior bandit guarantees rely on narrow assumptions. Lai-Robbins (1985), Agrawal (1995), Burnetas-Katehakis (1996), and Yakowitz-Lowe (1991) give only asymptotic, n-to-infinity log-n optimality, with no control for a fixed small number of plays. The first three also require a known parametric reward family with Kullback-Leibler or dual-optimization constants, failing under unknown or misspecified families. The Gittins line (Gittins 1989; Ishikida-Varaiya 1994; Berry-Fristedt 1985) needs full Bayesian priors, geometric discounting, and expensive per-state indices. No single result gives a trivially computable policy whose regret guarantee holds at every finite n, needs no reward-family knowledge, and still attains log-n growth, though target applications live in exactly that finite, distribution-agnostic regime.","method":"Unify three strands into one bounded-reward index policy. Take the upper-confidence idea of Lai-Robbins and Agrawal and the large-deviation tools they and Yakowitz-Lowe use: each arm index equals its empirical mean plus a bonus sqrt of c times ln n over its play count, the bonus from a finite-sample Hoeffding or Chernoff bound rather than a Kullback-Leibler constant. Store only mean and count per arm and pick the largest index, realizing the Gittins own-state index in constant time. Prove a non-asymptotic regret bound for every horizon n and any bounded distribution, of order the sum over suboptimal arms of ln n over the gap, by pairing a deterministic bonus-below-gap argument with a tail union bound, replacing the asymptotic guarantees of Lai-Robbins, Agrawal, and Burnetas-Katehakis. Add a variance-adaptive Bernstein bonus using empirical variance and show it interpolates toward the arm-specific large-deviation constant, reconciling the distribution-free constant with the asymptotically optimal one. Relate the bonus to the Gittins index of Berry-Fristedt and Ishikida-Varaiya as a prior-free learning premium, mapping finite-horizon discounting to finite-n regret. Validate on Bernoulli, truncated-normal, and bounded heavy-tailed arms including the finite-support families of Burnetas-Katehakis and Yakowitz-Lowe, comparing the unified index, its variance-adaptive form, Gittins indices, and epsilon-greedy across horizons. The result is one simple memory-light policy that is simultaneously finite-time, distribution-free, and log-n optimal."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is found via narrow assumptions of prior work (asymptotic-only, parametric-family-dependent, Bayesian prior-requiring), a clear scope_mismatch, with a contradiction-flavored puzzle of reconciling distribution-free vs asymptotically-optimal constants. The central move is proving a non-asymptotic regret bound via finite-sample tail bounds—formal_derivation—while extending guarantees to weaker assumptions (relax_extend_scope). Though it unifies strands, the deliverable is a new theorem/bound, not mere stitching. Bottleneck (finite-n, distribution-free, log-n) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"The sources contain two grounded but disconnected traditions. The Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network (Ridella et al., 1997) unifies representations: appending one extra input equal to the squared norm of x lets an MLP unit act as either a surface-based hyperplane or a prototype-based hypersphere with an interpretable center, radius, and gain, decided by optimization. It is cheap (one extra weight), hardware-friendly (obtained by augmenting the training set), interpretable, and has Cover-capacity and VC-dimension bounds. But it is trained by backpropagation (local minima, no margin-based capacity control) and only for classification. The support-vector tradition (Vapnik's Statistical Learning Theory and support-vector function estimation; Schölkopf et al.'s SVM-vs-RBF comparison; Saunders et al.'s dual-variable ridge regression) provides what CBP lacks: convex training, explicit Structural Risk Minimization capacity control, automatic center/weight selection, and a unified view of classification, regression, and operator equations, but via implicit kernels, dense support-vector expansions, heavier inference, and poor interpretability. The comparison paper's successful hybrid (SV-selected centers plus backprop weights) shows the traditions are complementary, yet no artifact fuses CBP's explicit, low-dimensional, interpretable, deployable circular augmentation with convex SRM-controlled support-vector or dual-ridge training, nor extends circular representations to regression. This forces a choice between interpretable-but-locally-optimal CBP and accurate-but-opaque heavyweight kernel machines.","method":"Build CircML, a training-and-deployment system whose central artifact is a Circular Support Vector Machine (CSVM) pipeline that treats the CBP augmentation as an explicit feature map fed to convex learners. Module 1, Augmentation: map x to z equal to the concatenation of x and the squared norm of x, adding one dimension so any linear convex learner becomes a hypersphere or prototype learner. Module 2, Convex trainer with a shared interface: fit z with a max-margin SVM or dual-variable ridge regression for global optima, supporting classification, regression, and operator-equation targets. To exceed single-sphere expressivity, offer two composition modes: a circular kernel combining the explicit augmented inner product with a Gaussian kernel, and a two-stage mode where a Gaussian-kernel SVM selects a few support vectors as candidate centers that seed a compact bank of circular units re-fit convexly, giving an SRM-guided interpretable analogue of the hybrid system that succeeded on USPS. Module 3, SRM model selection: use the CBP-derived Cover and VC capacity expressions as explicit capacity estimates to choose the number of units and regularization by minimizing a risk bound. Module 4, Rule extraction: invert learned weights into circular parameters (center, radius, gain), emitting readable prototype and boundary rules and flagging collapsed-gain surface units versus prototype units. Module 5, Compact deployment: prune to the fewest units meeting the SRM bound and export a network needing only one extra input, targeting MLP-style hardware. Evaluate on the USPS digits benchmark against MLP, clustering-RBF, and Gaussian-kernel SVM, plus regression tasks, measuring test error, retained units and support vectors, inference cost, and rule fidelity. This delivers CBP's cheap, interpretable, deployable circular representation under the support-vector tradition's convex optimization and capacity control, generalized beyond classification."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.83,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two disconnected traditions (CBP circular augmentation and support-vector/dual-ridge learning) as complementary, and the gap is found by contrasting interpretable-but-local CBP against accurate-but-opaque kernel machines (bridge, with a tradeoff/contradiction flavor). The core move fuses these traditions into a unified pipeline (synthesis_unification), delivered as a concrete CircML/CSVM system (artifact_system secondary). The idea leans toward stitching known components (CBP feature map + convex learners), earning a moderate surface-stitching flag, though the shared explicit-feature-map reframing gives it some genuine integration."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Three strands of the provided literature developed largely in isolation, and their intersection exposes a concrete gap.\n\n(1) Statistical Learning Theory and the Support Vector method (Vapnik, \"Nature of Statistical Learning Theory\" 1995; \"Support Vector Method of Function Estimation\" 1998) give convex, sparse, margin-maximizing classifiers whose capacity is controlled data-dependently by the radius–margin VC bound (Theorem 5.1: h ≤ min([R²A²], n)+1, with R the radius of the sphere enclosing the mapped data and A a bound on ‖w‖). But the feature map / kernel is chosen a priori; there is no principled, learned decision about whether a \"surface-based\" (hyperplane) or \"prototype-based\" (spherical/RBF) decision rule is appropriate, and expressive kernels (e.g., Gaussian) inject very large (effectively infinite-dimensional) capacity.\n\n(2) The SVM-vs-RBF study (Schölkopf et al. 1997) shows on USPS digits that an SVM with a Gaussian kernel beats classical RBF networks and even a hybrid, and that the SV method automatically places prototype \"centers.\" Yet it still requires a fixed rich kernel and yields many support vectors; it does not address which representational paradigm the data actually warrant, nor how to obtain that choice cheaply.\n\n(3) Circular Backpropagation (CBP) networks (Ridella et al. 1997) elegantly unify the surface-based and prototype-based paradigms by a single, minimal input augmentation x → (x, ‖x‖²): a linear unit in this augmented space realizes hyperspheres, and the model exhibits \"paradigm plasticity\" — the coefficient on ‖x‖² decides, during learning, whether the unit behaves like a hyperplane or a prototype. The authors even analyze the model's VC dimension and Cover capacity. However, CBP is trained by non-convex backpropagation performing empirical risk minimization, so the promised VC/capacity advantage is never exploited during learning, and paradigm selection is left to an opaque, local optimizer.\n\n(4) Kernel ridge regression in dual variables (Saunders et al. 1998) provides a closed-form, regularized dual solution but is non-sparse and says nothing about paradigm selection or margin-based capacity control.\n\nNo prior work connects CBP's minimal, interpretable circular augmentation with SVM-style, radius–margin capacity control and sparsity. This matters because CBP identifies the single cheapest feature that spans the gap between hyperplane and RBF classifiers, and SLT provides exactly the tool (a computable radius–margin bound) needed to choose along that spectrum in a principled, convex way — a synthesis none of these works performs.","method":"Propose the Circular Support Vector Machine (C-SVM): a maximum-margin classifier built on CBP's explicit finite feature map, together with a theoretically grounded, convex replacement for CBP's \"paradigm plasticity.\"\n\n1. Feature map and model. Map inputs by φ_β(x) = (x, β·‖x‖²), the CBP circular augmentation with a single scalar paradigm/scale parameter β ≥ 0. Learn a soft-margin separator sign(w·φ_β(x) + b) in this (d+1)-dimensional space. Equivalently this is an SVM with the explicit \"circular kernel\" k_β(x,x') = x·x' + β²‖x‖²‖x'‖², whose decision surfaces are hyperspheres. β = 0 collapses the machine to a linear (surface-based) SVM; large β emphasizes the prototype/spherical (RBF-like) direction. Because φ_β is finite and explicit, training, prediction, and geometry are all cheap and interpretable.\n\n2. Convex, data-dependent paradigm selection via the radius–margin bound. Because the map is explicit, the radius R_β of the smallest sphere enclosing {φ_β(x_i)} and the margin (‖w_β‖) are directly computable in closed/low-cost form for any β. Use Vapnik's Theorem 5.1 to form the capacity proxy R_β²·‖w_β‖² and select β (and the regularization constant C) by minimizing this radius–margin bound over a 1-D grid / gradient search — each inner solve being a standard convex SVM QP. This turns CBP's non-convex, optimizer-dependent paradigm plasticity into a convex, SRM-justified model-selection procedure: the data themselves determine, through the tightest generalization bound, whether a hyperplane or a hypersphere (and everything between) is warranted. Crucially, unlike the Gaussian kernel, the circular map adds only one dimension, so the enclosing radius and effective capacity increase minimally — potentially yielding tighter bounds and far fewer support vectors than Gaussian-kernel SVMs for problems whose class structure is (approximately) spherical.\n\n3. A fast closed-form variant. Provide a least-squares/dual-ridge counterpart: solve kernel ridge regression in dual variables (Saunders et al.) with the circular kernel k_β, giving a closed-form (K + λI)⁻¹y solution and enabling the same radius–margin-based selection of β and λ without a QP. This trades the QP's sparsity for O-closed-form speed, letting us empirically characterize the sparsity-vs-scalability tradeoff of the two learners on the same circular representation.\n\n4. Evaluation. Reproduce the USPS handwritten-digit protocol of the SVM-vs-RBF study. Compare C-SVM (QP and dual-ridge variants) against (i) linear SVM, (ii) Gaussian-kernel SVM, (iii) classical RBF networks, and (iv) backprop-trained CBP/MLP, on: test error; number of support vectors / free parameters; the selected β (does capacity-minimization recover a surface-based vs prototype-based rule matching the data?); and the correlation between the computed radius–margin bound and observed test error (does the bound track generalization and thus validate automatic paradigm selection?). Ablate β selection (fixed vs bound-minimizing vs cross-validated) to isolate the value of SLT-driven paradigm plasticity.\n\nThis directly fills the gap: it imports SVM/SLT capacity control and sparsity into CBP's minimal, interpretable circular representation, and it makes CBP's paradigm plasticity convex and theoretically grounded via the radius–margin bound, while offering a closed-form dual-ridge alternative for scale."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as connecting three disconnected literatures (CBP circular augmentation, SVM/SLT capacity control, kernel ridge regression), a bridge_opportunity; there is a secondary tension that CBP's promised VC advantage is never exploited during non-convex training (puzzle/contradiction). The core move synthesizes these strands into C-SVM, replacing CBP's plasticity with a convex radius-margin selection, hence synthesis_unification with formal_derivation (radius-margin bound as capacity proxy). Some risk of surface stitching since it's an A+B recombination, but the specific bottleneck (convex paradigm selection via computable radius-margin bound on a minimal 1-D feature) is identified with reasonable specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: the sources contrast surface-based and prototype-based classifiers and lack a systematic map of when each wins.","method":"Test method: build a benchmark sweeping the circular-backpropagation coefficient and SVM kernel type to map generalization against dataset structure and capacity bounds."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The motivation frames a missing systematic map of when surface-based vs prototype-based classifiers win (evidence_gap), with an underlying contrast/tradeoff. The method builds a benchmark sweeping parameters to map generalization against structure, which is empirical_mapping. Combining two existing classifier families in a benchmark has a mild stitching flavor and moderate genericness."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two research lineages in these sources describe the same geometric fact from opposite ends but never meet formally. (1) Ridella et al.'s Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network augments a multilayer perceptron with a single extra input equal to the sum of squared inputs (‖x‖²), turning hyperplane discriminants into hyperspherical ones. This gives the network \"paradigm plasticity\": a single learned coefficient continuously interpolates between the surface-based paradigm (open half-space boundary) and the prototype-based paradigm (bounded ball around a center/radius, like RBF). But CBP is trained by plain backpropagation (empirical risk minimization); its capacity control is only a worst-case hidden-unit / VC-dimension count, and the plasticity coefficient is fit with no principled regularization or margin. (2) Vapnik's Support Vector method and Schölkopf et al.'s SVM-vs-RBF study obtain capacity control through Structural Risk Minimization: for canonical hyperplanes in a feature space, Theorem 5.1 bounds the VC dimension by min(⌈R²A²⌉, n)+1 (R = radius of the smallest enclosing sphere of the mapped data, A = weight-norm ≈ 1/margin), and Schölkopf shows an SV-RBF that automatically selects centers/weights beats clustering+backprop RBF on USPS. Yet in the SVM framework the \"paradigm\" (linear vs. localized-prototype) is fixed a priori by the kernel choice; the Gaussian kernel is infinite-dimensional and its center/radius geometry is only implicit, and there is no explicit, minimal-dimensional, interpretable lift that lets the paradigm itself be selected by SRM. The gap: no formal object connects CBP's interpretable, learnable surface↔prototype plasticity to margin-based statistical learning theory, and no theorem quantifies how the plasticity coefficient trades capacity (R) against margin. Closing this gap matters because it would (a) explain when the extra ‖x‖² feature actually helps, (b) replace CBP's uncontrolled backprop fitting of the plasticity term with a principled SRM rule, and (c) give SVMs a cheap, finite-dimensional, geometrically interpretable route between linear and prototype classifiers — exactly the regime (few high-dimensional samples) Vapnik emphasizes.","method":"Develop a formal, margin-theoretic unification of the surface-based and prototype-based paradigms via an explicit one-parameter \"spherical lift,\" and derive from it an SRM principle for paradigm selection.\n\n1. Formal model (the circular lift and its kernel). Define φ_λ(x) = (x, (λ/2)‖x‖²) ∈ R^{n+1}, giving the kernel K_λ(x,x') = ⟨x,x'⟩ + (λ²/4)‖x‖²‖x'‖². Prove K_λ is positive definite (sum of the linear kernel and a rank-structured product-of-norms kernel), hence usable in any dual SVM/dual-ridge solver. A linear classifier ⟨v,φ_λ(x)⟩+b with v=(w,β) has input-space boundary c‖x‖²+w·x+b=0 with c=λβ/2.\n\n2. Equivalence theorem (conceptual distinction, ERM vs SRM). Prove that the decision function of a max-margin SVM using K_λ is exactly a CBP circular unit, and give the explicit bijection between the SVM dual solution and CBP's \"circular parameters\": center = −w/(2c), radius² = ‖w‖²/(4c²) − b/c, gain = c. Establish the conceptual distinction geometrically: c=0 ⇒ unbounded (surface) decision region; c≠0 ⇒ bounded ball (prototype) region. This positions CBP-backprop as the empirical-risk instance and the proposed \"Support Vector Circular Machine\" (SVCM) as the maximal-margin/SRM completion of the same model family.\n\n3. Invariance corollary (when plasticity matters). Prove that if data are norm-normalized (‖x‖ constant) the quadratic term is constant and φ_λ collapses to the linear model, so surface and prototype paradigms coincide; therefore the extra representational capacity is governed precisely by the spread of squared norms. Formalize a scalar \"plasticity budget\" tied to Var(‖x‖²), predicting exactly when the augmentation can and cannot help.\n\n4. Capacity derivation and the SRM paradigm-selection rule. Note that φ_λ maps to R^{n+1}, so the unconstrained VC dimension is n+2 for every λ — the augmentation cannot cause dimensional blow-up (unlike full quadratic/polynomial lifts CBP warns about). Then apply Vapnik's radius-margin bound in feature space: h_λ ≤ min(⌈R_λ² A_λ²⌉, n+1)+1, where R_λ is the radius of the smallest sphere enclosing {φ_λ(x_i)} (computable by the enclosing-sphere QP given in the SV-function-estimation source) and A_λ = 1/γ_λ with γ_λ the SVM margin. Derive the one-parameter structure S_λ and the SRM objective λ* = argmin_λ R_λ²/γ_λ². Analyze this objective's behavior in λ (limits λ→0 recovering the linear SVM bound; growth of R_λ vs. gain in γ_λ) and give an envelope-theorem expression for its derivative so λ* can be found by a cheap 1-D outer search around repeated SVM solves.\n\n5. Regression extension. Instantiate the same lift in dual (kernel) ridge regression to obtain a spherical/circular regressor, with the identical R_λ²/γ_λ²-style bound guiding selection of λ, connecting the classification and function-estimation views.\n\n6. Validation plan. Empirically compare CBP-backprop, linear SVM, Gaussian-kernel SVM, and the derived SVCM (with SRM-selected λ) on the USPS-style and UCI datasets used in the source papers, measuring test error, number of support vectors/centers, and the tightness of the derived R_λ²/γ_λ² bound as a predictor of the empirically best λ. Success criteria: (a) the derived λ* tracks the empirically optimal paradigm; (b) SVCM matches or beats CBP where norm-spread is high and reduces to the linear SVM where it is low; (c) interpretable center/radius parameters are recovered via the equivalence theorem."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly identifies two disconnected lineages (CBP and SVM/SRM) describing the same geometric fact but never formally connected — a clear bridge_opportunity, with a secondary explanation_gap (explaining when the extra feature helps). The core move is a formal object: a spherical lift, positive-definite kernel proof, equivalence theorem, invariance corollary, and an SRM derivation — formal_derivation, with synthesis_unification as the reconciliation of the two paradigms. Though it combines CBP and SVM, the connection is a proven equivalence and shared capacity bound, not superficial stitching, and it pinpoints a precise mechanism (Var of squared norms governs plasticity)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"SVMs solve a convex QP that minimizes a test-error bound, but the outer hyperparameters (Gaussian width gamma, C, and epsilon for regression) are not set by the QP and are still chosen by heuristics or costly cross-validation grids (Scholkopf et al.; Vapnik). The theory offers cheap surrogates rarely used for search: the support-vector-count bound and a closed-form leave-one-out kernel bound from one trained model (Zhang). This leaves room to replace grid search with a principled, efficient search driven by these bounds and the smooth solution path.","method":"Propose SAAHS, a search framework selecting theta=(C, gamma, epsilon, kernel) by adaptively minimizing a theory surrogate. Surrogate: train the QP once per theta and compute S from that solve, the support-vector fraction plus the closed-form leave-one-out kernel bound, with an epsilon-insensitive analogue for regression, so each evaluation is one solve not k-fold CV. Adaptive search: model S over a log-scaled box with a response surface and pick the next theta by expected improvement. Efficiency: warm-start each QP from the nearest solved model along the C and gamma path and screen non-support-vectors using factorization updates, so re-solves are cheap. Multi-fidelity: rank candidates by cheap S, then run true CV only on top survivors and recalibrate. Evaluate on digit and benchmark tasks versus grid CV and fixed-width heuristics, targeting equal accuracy at far fewer solves."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is the costly hyperparameter search via CV grids (resource_bottleneck), with the underused theory surrogates as an evidence/validation angle. The central move is an adaptive search framework using expected-improvement surrogate optimization, warm-starts, and multi-fidelity screening—squarely optimization_search. Bottleneck is precisely identified (hyperparameters unset by QP, cheap LOO bound replacing k-fold)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two lineages appear in these sources. (1) The Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network of Ridella et al. shows that augmenting the input of a linear unit with a single extra feature — the squared norm ||x||² — lets one unit represent both hyperplane (surface-based) and hyperspherical/prototype (RBF-like) decision boundaries, \"unifying\" the two paradigms while raising the VC dimension only minimally (from d+1 to d+2). (2) The statistical-learning/SVM lineage (Vapnik; SV method of function estimation; ridge regression in dual variables; SVM-vs-RBF comparison) provides margin/SRM-based capacity control and dual (kernel) training that extend cleanly to regression and to automatic center selection.\n\nEach lineage leaves a concrete gap that the other could fill. CBP is (a) restricted to classification, (b) trained by non-convex backpropagation, so its central promise — \"paradigm plasticity,\" i.e. choosing where to sit between hyperplane and prototype — is left to gradient descent with local minima and no capacity guarantee; (c) applied only to the raw input space with one fixed quadratic term, and never given a principled model-selection rule despite its clean VC-dimension analysis. Conversely, the SVM comparison paper shows Gaussian-kernel SVMs win but require choosing a width and correspond to an essentially unbounded VC dimension; there is no interpretable, finely graded family of function classes whose capacity grows in small, provable increments. This matters precisely in noisy, small-sample regimes, where an over-powerful kernel overfits and where one wants the smallest capacity increase over a linear model that still captures spherical/cluster structure. No source combines CBP's minimal, interpretable capacity increment with convex SV training, regression, and SRM-based selection.","method":"Relax and broaden CBP by recasting its circular augmentation as a \"circular kernel\" inside the convex support-vector / dual-ridge framework, turning it from a single non-convex classifier into a general, noise-tolerant estimator with explicit capacity control.\n\n1) Circular feature map and kernel. Define the augmentation φ_λ(x) = (x, √λ·||x||²) and the induced kernel k_λ(x,x') = ⟨x,x'⟩ + λ·||x||²||x'||², with a scalar λ≥0 that continuously interpolates between the pure linear machine (λ=0, VC = d+1) and the spherical machine (λ>0, VC = d+2). Because the augmentation is just one extra coordinate, the resulting SVM/ridge solution is a hyperplane in feature space, i.e. a hypersphere/quadric of the restricted CBP form, but now obtained by convex optimization with a global optimum — removing CBP's local-minima dependence.\n\n2) Broaden the loss/task. Instantiate the circular kernel in (a) the maximal-margin SVM for classification, (b) the ε-insensitive SV method for regression, and (c) dual ridge regression. This extends CBP — defined only for classification via backprop — to noisy regression and to the robust, margin-based setting, so the \"paradigm plasticity\" survives under label noise and outliers.\n\n3) SRM ladder with provable increments. Replace CBP's gradient-driven paradigm choice with Structural Risk Minimization over a nested structure. Build the structure two ways: along λ (linear ⊂ circular), and greedily by adding spherical features anchored at candidate centers, each addition provably increasing VC dimension by one. Select λ, the margin/regularization, and the number of spheres by minimizing a VC-dimension-based generalization bound (or cross-validation as a practical surrogate). This gives an interpretable capacity ladder with minimal increments, in contrast to the width-tuned, high-capacity Gaussian kernel.\n\n4) Kernelized generalization (weaker-assumption scope). Generalize the augmentation to any base kernel k by defining k̃(x,x') = k(x,x') + λ·k(x,x)·k(x',x'), i.e. augment an arbitrary RKHS with its own norm feature. This adds \"spherical\" capability to any kernel machine at the cost of only +1 VC dimension, letting practitioners take a proven linear or low-degree model and grant it minimal prototype-style capacity without moving to an unbounded-VC kernel.\n\n5) Evaluation. Compare circular-kernel SVM/ridge against (i) CBP trained by backprop, (ii) plain MLP, (iii) classical RBF with clustered centers, and (iv) Gaussian-kernel SVM, on the USPS digit task from the comparison paper plus controlled synthetic classification/regression benchmarks with injected label noise and small sample sizes. Key hypotheses: the circular kernel matches or beats CBP and RBF while giving convex training and, in high-noise/small-sample regimes, generalizes better than the Gaussian-kernel SVM at far lower capacity; the SRM ladder recovers the correct surface-vs-prototype regime automatically and yields interpretable center/radius parameters via the CBP weight-to-circular-parameter transformation. This directly addresses the gap: CBP's minimal, interpretable capacity increment now operates under weaker assumptions (convex, noisy, regression, arbitrary base kernels) with principled SRM capacity control."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly identifies two disconnected lineages (CBP and SVM/SRM) each leaving gaps the other could fill, a bridge_opportunity framing. Secondary scope_mismatch since CBP is restricted to classification and non-convex training. The central move is synthesizing the two into a circular kernel within the convex SV framework (synthesis_unification), while also relaxing/extending CBP to regression, noise, and arbitrary base kernels (relax_extend_scope). Bottleneck is precise: minimal +1 VC increment vs unbounded Gaussian kernel. Not superficial stitching because the combination reframes CBP augmentation as a kernel with genuine derivational payoff (convexity, provable increments)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The support vector framework unifies classification, RBF, and regression under Structural Risk Minimization (Vapnik 1998, 1995), and dual-variable ridge regression (Saunders 1998) and the SVM-vs-RBF comparison (1997) show kernel methods generalize well. But all fix the loss shape and its parameters in advance, coupled to an assumed noise model. Vapnik states this: squared loss (dual ridge) is optimal only for Gaussian noise; the epsilon-insensitive linear loss is Huber's minimax choice under noise uncertainty; Huber's smooth loss is robust only for a contamination mixture whose proportion, and hence its transition point, must be known in advance. In practice noise is unknown, often heavy-tailed, heteroscedastic, or contaminated by outliers and mislabels. Under such misspecification these methods are brittle: squared loss gives outliers unbounded quadratic influence and no sparsity; even the epsilon-insensitive loss grows without bound in the residual, so a few outliers dominate the fit and corrupt the support vector set; and a single global epsilon mis-sizes the tube under heteroscedastic noise. None of the provided works give a data-driven way to adapt the loss and epsilon to unknown noise while keeping capacity control and sparsity. That is the gap.","method":"Propose Robust Adaptive-Loss Support Vector Regression, a robustification of the SV and kernel-ridge family with three coupled parts. First, a bounded redescending insensitive loss that keeps an epsilon dead zone for sparsity, transitions Huber-like for moderate residuals, and saturates beyond a cutoff so gross outliers get near-zero influence, a regime none of the three losses Vapnik lists provides; its shape parameters interpolate between quadratic, epsilon-insensitive, Huber, and redescending. Second, data-driven locally adaptive epsilon and cutoff, set as multiples of a robust noise scale (median absolute deviation) estimated in kernel-weighted local neighborhoods, removing the homoscedastic global epsilon and the requirement of a known contamination proportion. Third, iteratively reweighted quadratic programming: because the loss is non-convex, solve a sequence of standard box-constrained SV dual QPs (the fast solver Vapnik describes), where per-example weights from the linearized loss drive tail outliers to near-zero weight; initialize from an L1 or epsilon-insensitive fit to avoid poor optima. Capacity stays controlled by the norm of w under SRM, and the regularization constant plus loss-shape and scale multipliers are chosen by cross-validation against the SRM risk bound, retaining sparsity and generalization guarantees. Evaluate robustness explicitly with the paper set baselines: regression under Gaussian, heavy-tailed, asymmetric, heteroscedastic, and outlier-contaminated noise, measuring error, empirical breakdown point, support vector set stability, and sparsity, versus dual ridge, fixed-epsilon SVR, and fixed-Huber SVR; USPS digit classification with injected label noise versus fixed-loss SVM and RBF; and an ablation isolating each component. Success means matching the best fixed-loss method when its noise assumption holds while sharply reducing degradation and preventing support vector corruption under contaminated, heavy-tailed, or heteroscedastic noise."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed around brittleness under noise misspecification (outliers, heavy tails, heteroscedasticity) where fixed losses fail, a clear failure/risk gap, with secondary scope_mismatch since prior methods assume unrealistic noise models. The method is centrally a robustification: a bounded redescending loss plus adaptive scale and reweighted QP to reduce outlier influence. Extending to weaker/broader noise conditions is secondary. Specific bottleneck (loss shape coupled to assumed noise model, unbounded outlier influence) is precisely identified, not a superficial combination."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"CBP networks (Ridella 1997) unify surface-based and prototype-based classifiers via a squared-norm augmented input and a plasticity coefficient, but train by backprop with no capacity control. SVM and kernel methods (Vapnik; dual ridge regression) give margin-based SRM and RBF prototypes but pick the surface-vs-prototype kernel a priori. No work bridges the CBP learnable continuum with kernel SRM.","method":"Show the CBP squared-norm augmentation is exactly a Mercer kernel equal to the inner product plus the product of squared norms. Define a one-parameter kernel homotopy from linear through circular to Gaussian RBF generalizing CBP plasticity. Solve in the SVM and dual-ridge framework so prototypes and weights follow from margin maximization. Select the homotopy parameter by minimizing the radius-margin VC bound. Map solutions back to CBP geometry and to VC and Cover capacity analyses. Validate on USPS digits versus linear SVM, RBF SVM, CBP-backprop, and RBF-backprop."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.86,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as no work bridging the CBP learnable classifier continuum with kernel SRM (bridge_opportunity). The core move unifies these two literatures by showing CBP augmentation is a Mercer kernel and constructing a homotopy connecting them within the SVM framework (synthesis_unification), with formal derivation of the kernel equivalence and VC bound selection as secondary. Not superficial stitching since it derives a genuine kernel equivalence and continuum."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about bridging CBP networks and SVM kernel methods.","method":"Test method building a circular kernel machine toolkit."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.5,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation is explicitly about bridging CBP networks and SVM kernel methods (bridge_opportunity), with method synthesizing the two into a kernel machine, plus a toolkit artifact. Test/placeholder text limits specificity; the A+B combination framing suggests moderate stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Bridge opportunity between two late-1990s literatures that both invoke Vapnik's theory but never connect their machinery. Stream A: the neural circular-unit / Circular Backpropagation (CBP) work (Ridella et al. 1997), which augments the MLP with one extra feature, the squared norm of x, so each unit represents a hypersphere. This yields an explicit, low-dimensional, interpretable, differentiable feature map unifying surface-based (hyperplane) and prototype-based (RBF/spherical) paradigms, with derived VC-dimension and Cover-capacity formulas. But CBP is trained by ordinary backprop, with capacity controlled only crudely by the number of hidden units; its capacity results are post-hoc analysis, not a training objective, and there is no margin or SRM criterion. Stream B: the kernel/SVM/kernel-ridge community (Vapnik 1995/1998; Scholkopf-Burges-Vapnik RBF-vs-SVM; Saunders dual ridge regression), offering convex, dual-variable, margin-maximizing fits that minimize a VC bound (SRM), but with feature geometry fixed a priori: the kernel shape is chosen in advance and RBF-SVM centers are restricted to training points. Gap: CBP has adaptive, interpretable spherical geometry but a weak, non-convex training principle; SVM/kernel-ridge have a principled convex SRM fit but frozen geometry with data-point centers. No work marries CBP's trainable circular feature map with kernel methods' convex, VC-bound-driven estimation, even though CBP already supplies the exact VC/Cover-capacity terms an SRM objective needs. Bridging them could yield classifiers with few adaptive, interpretable spherical prototypes fit under convex capacity control with real generalization guarantees.","method":"Adaptive Circular Kernel Machine (ACKM): use CBP circular units as a trainable feature map, fit with kernel-ridge/SVM convex machinery, and select capacity via CBP's own formulas. Step 1, explicit circular kernel: the augmentation z(x) built from 1, x, and the squared norm of x is a finite-dimensional feature space where every linear separator is a hypersphere or hyperplane; define K_circ as the inner product of z(x) and z(y). Dual-variable ridge regression on K_circ gives a convex, closed-form single-sphere classifier as the minimal bridge instance. Step 2, bank of learnable prototypes: K circular units with learnable centers, radii, and gains produce features phi_k(x). Unlike RBF-SVM, centers are free continuous parameters not tied to training points, typically far fewer than support vectors, each interpretable as a sphere or, when the quadratic coefficient vanishes, a hyperplane (CBP paradigm plasticity). Step 3, convex inner fit with SRM: given features, solve the read-out layer by dual-variable ridge regression or a margin-maximizing quadratic program (globally solvable); set the regularization strength and K by Structural Risk Minimization, plugging CBP's VC-dimension and Cover-capacity expressions in as the explicit complexity term, turning CBP's post-hoc analysis into active model selection the kernel literature lacks for this geometry. Step 4, alternating optimization: first freeze circular parameters and solve the convex weight problem in closed form or QP, then backpropagate the resulting margin/ridge loss into centers, radii, and gains via gradient descent, combining CBP representation learning with SVM/kernel-ridge estimation. Step 5, evaluation: reproduce the RBF-vs-SVM setup on USPS digits and standard benchmarks, comparing ACKM to classical RBF (k-means plus backprop), RBF-SVM, the SVM/backprop hybrid, and plain CBP. Metrics: accuracy; number of prototypes versus support vectors (compactness); interpretability of learned spheres; and how tightly the SRM/VC bound predicts test error, testing whether importing CBP's capacity formulas yields useful model selection."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as two disconnected literatures (CBP circular units and kernel/SVM machinery) that both invoke Vapnik but never connect, making this a bridge_opportunity. The central move is reconciling these into a unified classifier (synthesis_unification), with the VC/Cover-capacity formulas plugged into an SRM objective giving a formal derivation flavor. The A+B combination is somewhat explicit and identifiable as stitching CBP feature maps onto kernel-ridge fitting, but the identified mechanism (CBP supplying exact VC terms for an SRM objective) gives moderate specificity beyond superficial concatenation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two communities in these works pursue the same goal—flexible decision surfaces with controlled capacity—but stay disconnected. The neural-network tradition (Circular Backpropagation, Ridella et al. 1997; with Bishop 1995, Haykin 1994, Zurada 1992, Cherkassky 1998) augments a perceptron with one ||x||^2 term whose learnable coefficient continuously interpolates between a hyperplane (surface-based) and a sphere/prototype (RBF), trained by backprop and analyzed via VC dimension and Cover capacity. The statistical-learning/kernel tradition (Vapnik 1995/1998; kernel ridge regression, Saunders 1998; SVM-vs-RBF, Schölkopf 1997) achieves flexibility through implicit Mercer kernels and controls capacity via margin/SRM, with sparsity as support-vector count. The unexploited bridge: circular backprop's ||x||^2 augmentation is the minimal explicit feature map producing exactly the spherical geometry a Gaussian kernel produces implicitly. Both claim to unify polynomial/NN/RBF families, but along different axes and with incompatible capacity vocabularies (VC/Cover vs margin/SRM). Existing comparisons are narrow—Schölkopf compares three RBF variants on one dataset by accuracy alone; circular backprop gives theory plus small tests. No work connects explicit low-order augmentation to implicit kernels, translates the two capacity notions into comparable measurements, or tells practitioners when a cheap explicit augmentation matches an expensive kernel. This matters for obtaining kernel-like nonlinearity at perceptron-like cost and for giving both communities a shared empirical language.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map (a phase diagram) that places NN and kernel/SLT machines on one grid and measures them with common diagnostics beyond accuracy. Axis A, representation richness from explicit to implicit: linear perceptron; circular-backprop perceptron (one ||x||^2 term); explicit low-order polynomial augmentation; RBF net with k-means centers; Gaussian-kernel SVM; dual kernel ridge regression. Axis B, capacity-control principle: weight decay/early stopping, margin/SRM, Tikhonov ridge; where possible fit the same representation under each principle to separate representation effects from control effects. Diagnostics per machine-by-dataset cell: (1) test error and sample-size learning curves; (2) comparable capacity measures—empirical VC/Cover estimates via random-label memorization curves, margin distributions, and count of active units/support vectors/effective degrees of freedom; (3) decision-surface geometry—local curvature, number of boundary components, and fraction of boundary that is locally spherical, testing whether ||x||^2 augmentation reproduces the Gaussian kernel's geometry; (4) hyperparameter sensitivity surfaces. Protocol: use the USPS digit database (anchoring to Schölkopf) plus controlled synthetic 2-D problems with known boundaries for exact geometry metrics; include the SV-centers-plus-backprop-weights hybrid as a bridging control point; implement dual solves and stable capacity/margin computations using standard linear algebra (Cholesky/QR) and optimization routines from the corpus. Analyses addressing the gap: (a) overlay explicit-augmentation and kernel machines in a shared (capacity, geometry, error) space to find the regime—dimension, sample size, curvature—where the one-parameter circular augmentation matches Gaussian-kernel SVM at far smaller model size; (b) factor representation versus capacity control by fitting identical features under weight decay, margin, and ridge, quantifying how much SVM advantage is the kernel versus the SRM principle; (c) release the map, diagnostic code, and shared capacity/geometry metrics as a reusable comparative study translating VC/Cover and margin/SRM into the same measurable quantities, concretely linking the two literatures."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is explicitly about two disconnected communities (NN tradition vs kernel/SLT) pursuing the same goal with incompatible vocabularies — a clear bridge_opportunity, with a secondary evidence_gap since existing comparisons are narrow and lack shared diagnostics. The construction move is to reconcile/translate the two literatures into a common measurement space (synthesis_unification), operationalized as a systematic phase-diagram/benchmark study (empirical_mapping). Note the actual historical LS-SVM paper is a formal derivation, but this reframed proposal is a comparative synthesis study. Some risk of surface stitching since it juxtaposes circular-backprop and kernel machines, but the bridging claim (||x||^2 augmentation reproducing Gaussian geometry, translating VC/Cover vs margin/SRM) is a specific, non-trivial connection, so score 2."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"CBP's squared-norm augmentation and Vapnik's enclosing-sphere radius in the SVM radius-margin bound are the same circular object, but the neural-network and statistical-learning literatures never connect them; bridging gives CBP capacity control and SVMs an exact VC characterization.","method":"Define the circular kernel k(x,y)=inner(x,y)+lambda*norm(x)^2*norm(y)^2, prove a linear separator in it is a hypersphere and that Vapnik's enclosing sphere is linear there, then derive an exact-VC (n+2) SRM bound over lambda solved by dual kernel ridge regression."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly identifies that CBP's squared-norm augmentation and Vapnik's enclosing-sphere radius are the same circular object never connected across neural-network and statistical-learning literatures, a clear bridge_opportunity. The method reconciles the two via a shared circular kernel and derives an exact-VC bound (synthesis_unification with formal_derivation via proofs and SRM bound). Not superficial stitching since it proves an equivalence rather than concatenating methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"A bridge opportunity connects two isolated streams. Circular Backpropagation (Ridella et al., 1997) shows appending a norm-squared feature lets a linear/MLP machine slide continuously between surface-based (hyperplane/polynomial) and prototype-based (RBF) decision surfaces via one scalar paradigm-plasticity coefficient, but is trained by non-convex backprop with no capacity control. The kernel/SLT stream (Vapnik 1998 SV method; Scholkopf et al. 1997 SVM-vs-RBF; Saunders et al. 1998 dual ridge regression) gives convex training and radius-margin VC capacity control, but fixes the kernel family a priori. Since the RBF kernel is built from the same norm-squared term underlying CBP plasticity, the two are naturally linkable yet never linked. Gap: no method lets data choose the surface-to-prototype operating point while retaining convex training and VC-bound capacity control. This matters because kernel and hyperparameter choice is the dominant practical bottleneck.","method":"Build a searchable kernel continuum and pick the operating point by optimizing a VC bound. Step 1: define a low-dimensional kernel family K_theta interpolating from a dot-product/polynomial kernel (theta small, hyperplane paradigm) to a Gaussian RBF kernel (theta large, prototype paradigm), inspired by CBP norm-squared augmentation; theta is a continuous plasticity knob inside a positive-definite kernel. Step 2: for fixed theta and regularization C, solve convexly in dual variables via kernel ridge regression or the SV method, giving a global optimum per candidate representation. Step 3 (optimization contribution): select models by minimizing the radius-margin bound (radius-squared times weight-norm-squared, both kernel-computable) rather than blind cross-validation; search over theta and C with coarse screening then gradient/coordinate refinement, using Cholesky low-rank updates and warm starts so re-solving as theta shifts is cheap. Step 4: allow class/region-specific theta and support-vector-focused active search. Step 5: evaluate on USPS digits and UCI sets against fixed polynomial SVM, fixed RBF SVM, CBP, and tuned kernel ridge regression, reporting accuracy, selected theta, bound-vs-test-error correlation, and cost. This delivers one machine that reproduces CBP automatic paradigm selection, trains convexly, and chooses its representation by minimizing a VC bound, bridging the neural-network and kernel-SRM literatures through efficient optimization over a unifying kernel continuum."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames a bridge between two isolated streams (circular backprop plasticity and kernel/SLT convex training), so opportunity is bridge_opportunity, with resource_bottleneck secondary given the emphasis on kernel/hyperparameter selection cost. The method centrally unifies the two literatures through a kernel continuum (synthesis_unification), with optimization_search secondary via VC-bound model selection and efficient search. Some risk of A+B stitching (CBP norm-squared term + kernel family), hence surface_stitching flagged with moderate score, but the norm-squared linkage gives a fairly specific mechanistic bottleneck."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two communities have independently attacked the same problem — building flexible classifiers that can behave either as surface-based (hyperplane) or prototype-based (spherical/RBF) machines — but their key results have never been connected.\n\n(1) The neural-network / mapping-network community (Ridella, Rovetta & Zunino's Circular Backpropagation, and the broader MLP/RBF literature) discovered a remarkably cheap unification: augmenting a perceptron's input with the single extra feature ||x||² gives the \"circular unit,\" a model with \"paradigm plasticity\" — a single, backprop-trainable network whose learned parameters decide, per unit, whether to act as a hyperplane (surface paradigm) or as a hypersphere/prototype (prototype paradigm). Its virtues are interpretability, minimal parameter increase, and reuse of standard MLP training/hardware. Its weakness: it is trained by empirical risk minimization (plain backprop). The paper even derives the circular unit's VC dimension but only uses it for post-hoc comparison — capacity is never controlled during training, so the surface↔prototype choice can drift and overfit, especially in noisy, high-dimensional, small-sample regimes.\n\n(2) The statistical-learning / SVM community (Vapnik's SV method and Statistical Learning Theory; Schölkopf et al.'s SVM-vs-RBF comparison; Saunders et al.'s dual ridge regression) built margin-based structural risk minimization and dual/kernel training with generalization guarantees, and showed empirically (on USPS digits) that SRM-based training beats backprop-trained RBF networks. Its weakness: the representation paradigm is fixed a priori by the user's choice of kernel (linear vs Gaussian/RBF); the machine cannot itself decide, in a data-dependent way, that some regions are best explained by a surface and others by a prototype, and the resulting model is implicit and dense in support vectors rather than interpretable.\n\nThe bridge opportunity: each community's weakness is exactly the other's strength. CBP offers cheap, interpretable, adaptive surface↔prototype plasticity but no capacity control; SVM/SRM offers principled capacity control but a rigid, user-fixed paradigm. Nobody has connected the CBP augmentation to the SRM/margin machinery, even though the ||x||² augmentation is precisely an explicit, finite feature map that these dual methods could absorb.","method":"Relax two assumptions simultaneously: relax the SVM/kernel methods' assumption that the representation paradigm is fixed a priori, and relax the Circular Backpropagation model's assumption that training is unregularized ERM/backprop.\n\nStep 1 — A minimal, interpretable paradigm-tunable kernel. Adopt the CBP augmentation as an explicit feature map φ_λ(x) = [x ; √λ·||x||²] with a single non-negative \"paradigm\" parameter λ. This yields the valid, cheap kernel K_λ(x,x′) = (x·x′) + λ·||x||²||x′||². At λ=0 the feature space is linear (pure surface paradigm); as λ grows, a single hyperplane in feature space realizes exactly the CBP circular/hyperspherical unit (prototype paradigm). This lets any dual-variable learner inherit CBP's paradigm plasticity while remaining a one-extra-dimension, interpretable map — far cheaper than a full Gaussian kernel.\n\nStep 2 — Train with SRM/margin instead of backprop. Fit the classifier in dual variables using either margin maximization (SVM) or regularized least squares (dual ridge regression). Because increasing λ monotonically enlarges the admissible function class from hyperplanes to hyperspheres, the family {K_λ} forms a genuine nested structure S_0 ⊂ S_1 ⊂ … in the sense of Structural Risk Minimization. Select λ (and the regularization strength) by minimizing the corresponding margin/VC generalization bound — using the circular-unit VC-dimension expression already derived by Ridella et al. as the capacity term — rather than by letting backprop drive λ uncontrolled. This replaces CBP's post-hoc capacity assessment with in-training capacity control, and replaces SVM's manual kernel choice with a data-dependent paradigm selection.\n\nStep 3 — Multi-prototype extension (broader scope). Generalize the single circular feature to a small set of anchored terms φ(x) = [x ; ||x−c_1||², …, ||x−c_m||²], where anchors c_k are chosen by clustering or, following the SVM-vs-RBF hybrid, by the support vectors themselves. This spans multiple local prototypes while keeping an explicit, low-dimensional, interpretable map, and each learned coefficient/λ directly reveals whether a region is best explained by a surface or a prototype.\n\nStep 4 — Evaluation in the regimes where both prior methods struggle. Compare CBP-backprop, linear SVM, Gaussian-kernel SVM, dual ridge regression, and the proposed circular-SRM machine on (a) USPS handwritten digits (the benchmark of Schölkopf et al.) and (b) controlled noisy, high-dimensional, small-sample synthetic tasks that mix linearly- and spherically-separable structure. Metrics: test error, number of support vectors / effective parameters, the value of the tuned generalization bound, and an interpretability readout (learned λ and anchor coefficients indicating the chosen paradigm per region).\n\nExpected contribution: a classifier that attains CBP's adaptive surface↔prototype plasticity with SVM-grade generalization guarantees and far fewer parameters/support vectors than a Gaussian-kernel machine, thereby extending SRM to adaptively-chosen paradigms and extending the circular network to noisier, capacity-controlled regimes — a concrete bridge between the neural-network and statistical-learning literatures."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as connecting two disconnected literatures (CBP's paradigm plasticity vs SVM/SRM capacity control), each community's weakness being the other's strength — a clear bridge_opportunity. Secondary scope_mismatch appears via the fixed-paradigm/unregularized assumptions to be relaxed. The method centrally reconciles the two paradigms (synthesis_unification) by deriving a shared kernel/feature map, with relax_extend_scope as the explicit assumption-loosening move. The bridge is principled through a shared VC/SRM formalism (the ||x||^2 augmentation as an explicit finite feature map absorbed by dual methods), not a superficial A+B concatenation, so surface_stitching is low and bottleneck specificity is high (precise: capacity control during training vs post-hoc)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The Circular Backpropagation network computes an explicit closed-form VC dimension for its circular units but is trained by brittle backpropagation with local minima. Vapnik's SVM and dual ridge regression give convex capacity-controlled training but treat models as black-box kernels. These two literatures never connected, leaving room to robustify circular networks using statistical learning theory.","method":"Reframe the circular augmentation as a fixed feature map, train it with convex maximum-margin SVM and dual ridge regression for deterministic global optima, and use the known closed-form VC dimensions to build a Structural Risk Minimization ladder that selects capacity. Evaluate robustness to restarts, label noise, and dimensionality against backprop CBP, RBF, and Gaussian-kernel SVM on handwritten digits."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two disconnected literatures (circular backprop networks with closed-form VC dimension vs. convex SVM/dual ridge regression) that 'never connected,' making bridge_opportunity primary; the framing centers on the brittleness/local-minima failure of backprop, giving failure_risk_gap secondary. The method reconciles these lines by reframing circular augmentation as a fixed feature map trained convexly with SRM capacity control, which is synthesis_unification; the goal of deterministic global optima and robustness to restarts/noise supports robustification secondary. There is some A+B stitching flavor (circular units + SVM), but the closed-form VC dimension enabling an SRM ladder is a specific mechanistic lever, so moderate specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about bridging circular backpropagation and kernel methods.","method":"Test method combining the circular feature map with support vector machines."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":3,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('Test motivation','Test method') describing bridging circular backpropagation with kernel/SVM methods. The stated gap is connecting two lines of work (bridge_opportunity), and the move is combining them (synthesis_unification). Given the generic placeholder content and A+B combination framing, surface stitching and boilerplate are high, specificity low."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"These sources each justify a learning machine via statistical learning theory but with different, family-specific capacity arguments on different benchmarks. Vapnik grounds generalization in VC dimension and the support-vector-fraction bound; Scholkopf et al. rank SVM-RBF vs classical RBF only by accuracy on USPS digits without measuring capacity; Ridella et al.'s circular backpropagation net argues via worst-case hidden units and VC estimates on its own data; kernel ridge regression in dual variables and the SV function-estimation method add more norm and margin capacity terms. Evidence Gap: there is rich theory about what should predict generalization but no common instrument to observe, measure, and audit whether these indicators actually track the generalization gap on equal footing across surface-based, prototype-based, and kernel families over many datasets. Current comparisons are single-number, single-dataset accuracy contests that cannot say which bound is predictive, how tight it is, or whether automatic capacity control wins for the reasons theory names.","method":"Build a Capacity Observatory: an open toolkit, standardized protocol, and versioned results database instrumenting the model families in these sources. A unified wrapper implements MLP, circular-backpropagation nets, classical RBF, SV-RBF hybrid, Gaussian-kernel SVM, and dual kernel ridge regression identically. Capacity probes extract, on a common scale, weight-norm and data radius R, support-vector or prototype counts, full margin distributions, and empirical VC dimension via the maximal-deviation shattering procedure. Generalization is measured by a fixed protocol of repeated holdout, cross-validation, and learning curves with confidence intervals. An audit engine plots each theoretical bound against observed error, quantifies bound tightness and rank-correlation between each capacity indicator and the true generalization gap, and tests whether automatic SV capacity control gives lower measured capacity at equal accuracy than hand-tuned RBF or MLP. An accumulation layer stores dataset fingerprints, configs, probes, and metrics so evidence compounds and supports meta-analysis, including the USPS task. Validation reproduces the USPS SVM-vs-RBF and CBP-vs-MLP comparisons in-platform, then extends to standard datasets to report which capacity indicator is most predictive and whether support-vector and margin bounds are tight enough to guide model selection."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames the gap as lacking a common instrument to observe, measure, and audit whether capacity indicators track generalization across model families — an evidence_gap, with a bridging aspect across disconnected capacity arguments. The core move builds a standardized measurement toolkit, protocol, and comparative audit engine across many datasets, which is empirical_mapping (diagnostics/benchmarks/comparative studies), with the Observatory toolkit as a supporting artifact_system. Not superficial stitching since it establishes a unifying measurement protocol with specific probes (VC dimension via shattering, margin distributions, bound tightness) rather than concatenating methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"The field reports capacity bounds (VC dimension, Cover capacity, SVM margin bound) but never measures whether they predict test error, an evidence gap for auditing generalization bounds.","method":"Sweep capacity in a Circular Backpropagation substrate plus SVM and dual ridge, compare each theoretical capacity value to measured test error, and report bound tightness, rank correlation, and SRM selection regret."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is that capacity bounds are never measured against actual test error—an evidence/auditing gap. The method builds a systematic comparison across substrates measuring bound tightness, rank correlation, and selection regret, which is empirical mapping/diagnostics of a phenomenon. The reframing of a classic LS-SVM classifier paper as a bound-auditing study, plus the multi-substrate sweep, gives it a mild A+B stitching flavor."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"By the late 1990s a whole spectrum of \"kernel/prototype/surface\" learning machines had emerged, each advertised as theoretically grounded or empirically superior: the Gaussian-kernel support vector machine and its function-estimation variant, which automatically choose centers/weights to minimize an upper bound on expected error; classical RBF networks with k-means centers and backpropagated weights; the hybrid (SV centers + backprop weights); kernel ridge regression derived from ridge regression in dual variables; and the circular-backpropagation network, which explicitly unifies surface-based (perceptron) and prototype-based (RBF) representations and is analyzed via VC dimension and Cover capacity. In parallel, statistical learning theory supplies concrete capacity/generalization predictors — VC dimension, Cover capacity, the margin, the support-vector-count bound (E[error] ≤ E[#SV]/n), and regularization-based leave-one-out cross-validation bounds.\n\nThe evidence base tying these predictors to real behavior is, however, fragmentary and non-comparable. The flagship comparison study evaluates only three machines on a single corpus (USPS handwritten digits); the circular-backpropagation model is validated on its own separate experiments; kernel ridge regression and the SV function-estimation method are presented largely theoretically. Crucially, the theoretical capacity quantities are almost never *measured* alongside actual generalization on a shared testbed, and the different families are never placed under matched capacity. The field therefore lacks a systematic way to observe which SLT capacity measures actually track generalization, to audit when bounds are tight versus vacuous, and to compare \"automatic\" capacity control (SVM) against manual control (k-means + backprop, hand-tuned units/regularization) on equal footing. This gap matters because practitioners select among these interchangeable-looking machines and model-selection knobs with little empirical guidance about which theoretical predictor to trust.","method":"Construct a capacity–generalization empirical map: a controlled comparative benchmark that instantiates the full family of learners within one harness and logs theoretical predictors next to realized error across a common dataset suite.\n\n1) Unified model bank. Implement the machines as variants along a single axis from surface-based to prototype-based, exploiting the circular-backpropagation formulation as the unifying scaffold, and adding: SVM with Gaussian kernel, SV function-estimation (regression), kernel ridge regression (ridge in dual variables), classical RBF (k-means + backprop), and the SV-centers/backprop-weights hybrid. All share the same kernel/feature parameterization so that architectures are matched in size and speed.\n\n2) Systematic sweeps. On a common suite of classification and regression datasets (starting from the USPS digits used in prior work, plus additional benchmarks and controlled synthetic 2-D problems where capacity can be varied cleanly), sweep every complexity-control knob: Gaussian width σ, number of centers/hidden units, and regularization strength (SVM C and ridge λ). Use identical splits and cross-validation protocols across all machines.\n\n3) Instrumented diagnostics. At every configuration, record (a) realized quantities — train error, held-out/test error, and the train–test generalization gap; and (b) theoretical predictors — the empirical margin distribution, the number of support vectors and the E[#SV]/n bound, an estimated VC dimension and Cover capacity for the circular-unit model, and a regularization-based leave-one-out cross-validation error bound computed from λ (as in the kernel-method leave-one-out analysis). This yields a large dataset of (machine, configuration, predictor-values, generalization) tuples.\n\n4) Empirical mapping and audit. Analyze this dataset as the core contribution: measure rank correlation between each predictor and the realized generalization gap; identify regimes where each bound is informative versus vacuous; compare model families under matched estimated capacity to isolate whether SVM's automatic capacity control genuinely outperforms manual tuning, and whether the hybrid/circular-BP unification closes the gap; and produce diagnostic plots (predictor vs. error curves, tightness maps over the (σ, units, λ, C) grid).\n\n5) Deliverables. Release the diagnostic dataset, the benchmark harness, and a comparative report ranking capacity predictors by their empirical validity for model selection, thereby turning scattered, dataset-specific claims into an accumulated, auditable body of evidence."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.75,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as fragmentary, non-comparable evidence: theoretical capacity predictors are never measured alongside generalization on a shared testbed (evidence_gap), with a secondary aim of connecting disconnected learner families and theory streams (bridge_opportunity). The core move builds a controlled comparative benchmark logging predictors vs. realized error and audits bound tightness (empirical_mapping), scaffolded by unifying diverse machines along one axis (synthesis_unification). Not superficial stitching since the unification is used as a diagnostic harness with a specific auditing purpose; bottleneck (which capacity predictor tracks generalization) is reasonably specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"A recurring but untested claim runs through this literature: that seemingly different learning machines are secretly the same family living on a continuum between \"surface-based\" (global hyperplane/discriminant) and \"prototype-based\" (local, center/radius) representations. Schölkopf et al. and the SV function-estimation work assert that the SV machine \"contains polynomial classifiers, neural networks, and RBF networks as special cases,\" with the paradigm fixed a priori by the kernel choice. Ridella et al.'s circular backpropagation (CBP) network claims a \"paradigm plasticity\" in which a single quadratic input lets each unit slide between the perceptron (surface) and hypersphere (prototype) forms, and it proves the endpoint capacities exactly (VC = d+1 for the affine perceptron, d+2 for the circular unit). Kernel ridge regression in dual variables and Gaussian-kernel RBF machines are yet more members of the same broad club. Vapnik's statistical learning theory supplies capacity control (SRM) and the margin/radius VC bound h ≤ [R²/margin²].\n\nYet the field has no way to OBSERVE, MEASURE, or COMPARE where a *trained* machine actually sits on this surface↔prototype axis. \"Plasticity\" and \"contains as special cases\" are stated but never quantified: there is no model-agnostic coordinate on which an MLP, a CBP net, an RBF net, a linear/polynomial/Gaussian-kernel SVM, and a kernel-ridge machine can be placed side by side; no way to audit whether a deployed model is relying on local prototypes or global surfaces; and no capacity account that varies *continuously* along the axis rather than only at the two endpoints. Capacity theory treats the paradigm (architecture/kernel) as a designer's fixed choice, not as a learned, measurable property. This is an evidence gap: we cannot accumulate comparable evidence linking a model's representational regime to its capacity and generalization.","method":"Contribution is a formal derivation that turns \"paradigm plasticity\" and \"special-case\" folklore into a measurable, comparable, and capacity-linked quantity.\n\n1) Canonical form and representation theorem. Take the CBP stimulus as the canonical generalized-quadratic decision form g(x) = a·‖x‖² + wᵀx + b. Prove an embedding theorem: (i) the affine perceptron (a=0) and CBP circular unit are the endpoints; (ii) a degree-2 polynomial-kernel SVM decision function is exactly of this form; (iii) each term of a Gaussian-kernel RBF/SVM and of a dual-variable kernel-ridge machine, expanded to second order about its center, is a local instance of this form. This gives one shared coordinate system for machines that are otherwise incomparable.\n\n2) Paradigm (locality) index. Define a scale-invariant scalar ρ ∈ [0,1], ρ = |a|R / (|a|R + ‖w‖), where R is the data radius, and show it is invariant to input rescaling and to the CBP linear→circular parameter change (center/radius/gain of the equivalent hypersphere). ρ→0 ≡ pure surface (hyperplane); ρ→1 ≡ pure prototype (hypersphere). For multi-unit/multi-support-vector models, define the machine's \"paradigm spectrum\" as the distribution of ρ over units/support vectors, with audit statistics (mean locality, spectrum entropy).\n\n3) Interpolating capacity bound (core theorem). Derive an ρ-parameterized effective-capacity bound that (a) reduces to Cover/VC endpoints d+1 and d+2 from the CBP analysis, and (b) reduces to Vapnik's margin/radius bound h ≤ [R²/margin²] in the appropriate limit, by treating the quadratic term as lifting to an augmented feature space whose effective radius grows with ρ. This yields a continuous complexity coordinate: capacity as a monotone function of the paradigm spectrum, closing the gap between the two known regimes.\n\n4) Taxonomy and diagnostic protocol. Classify machine families by their induced ρ-spectra, and provide a post-hoc, retraining-free procedure to compute ρ-spectra directly from trained parameters of MLP, CBP, RBF, linear/polynomial/Gaussian SVM, and kernel-ridge models.\n\n5) Validation. On the USPS handwritten-digit benchmark used by the SVM-vs-RBF comparison and CBP experiments, empirically test that (i) the measured ρ-spectrum distinguishes the model families as predicted (e.g., linear SVM ≈ 0, Gaussian SVM/RBF near 1, CBP intermediate and data-dependent), and (ii) the derived ρ-capacity bound tracks the ranking of measured test error across models. Success criterion: the bound orders generalization consistently and the index exposes cases where nominally \"surface\" models have drifted local, and vice versa — providing the missing, comparable evidence linking representational paradigm to capacity."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is framed explicitly as an evidence gap: the field cannot observe, measure, or compare where trained machines sit on a surface↔prototype axis, and cannot accumulate comparable evidence linking representational regime to capacity. It also draws on disconnected model families (MLP, CBP, SVM, kernel ridge), giving a bridge_opportunity secondary. The core contribution is explicitly a formal derivation: a representation/embedding theorem, a scale-invariant index, and an interpolating capacity bound that reduces to known VC endpoints—hence formal_derivation primary. Because it unifies otherwise incomparable machine families into one coordinate system, synthesis_unification is a strong secondary. Bottleneck is precisely identified (no continuous coordinate/capacity account along the axis). Not mere A+B stitching since the unification is proven via a shared canonical form, not concatenated."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Every learning-machine family in these sources ships a theory-derived surrogate meant to guide model selection: Vapnik's radius-margin VC estimate (Support Vector Method of Function Estimation, eqs. 3.31/3.37), the closed-form leave-one-out kernel bound (Statistical Learning Theory 1998, eq. 17), the VC dimension and Cover capacity of circular-backpropagation networks, and the regularization parameter of ridge regression in dual variables. All are instances of Structural Risk Minimization from Vapnik's statistical learning theory. Yet there is almost no accumulated evidence about whether these surrogates work as model-selection instruments. The one head-to-head study here (Comparing SVMs with Gaussian Kernels to RBF Classifiers) fixes hyperparameters, trains once, and reports only final accuracies on a single dataset (USPS); circular-BP is actually tuned by cross-validation, not by its own capacity theory. Nobody measures how tightly each surrogate ranks configurations against true held-out error, whether a surrogate that works for SVMs transfers to RBF, circular-BP, or dual ridge regression, or in which regimes (kernel width, number of centers, regularization strength) it breaks down. Since these surrogates are exactly what SRM prescribes for choosing capacity, this missing evidence matters: without it we cannot know whether such bounds can replace expensive cross-validation, nor which surrogate to trust when families are compared. The sources derive the surrogates and show single-point performance but never audit or benchmark them as selection tools.","method":"Build a surrogate-guided adaptive model-selection search that both selects hyperparameters efficiently and accumulates evidence auditing each surrogate, across the four families in these sources: Gaussian-kernel SVM, classical RBF, circular-backpropagation MLP, and dual/kernel ridge regression. Step 1: define one comparable hyperparameter space per family (kernel width or scale, plus a capacity knob such as C, lambda, hidden-unit count, or number of centers). Step 2: use each family's own theory-derived surrogate as a cheap objective needing no held-out set: the radius-margin estimate via the enclosing-sphere QP (eqs. 3.33 to 3.37) for SVMs; the closed-form leave-one-out bound (SLT 1998, eq. 17) and a PRESS-style analytic leave-one-out for dual ridge regression; analytic VC and Cover capacity for circular-BP. Use efficient linear algebra from Matrix Computations (Cholesky factorization, rank-one leave-one-out updates, eigen-solves for the sphere radius) to make each surrogate evaluation far cheaper than a full retrain. Step 3: run coarse-to-fine successive-halving. Evaluate the surrogate on a coarse grid, prune all but the top fraction, refine around low-surrogate regions, and spend the expensive budget (full training plus independent validation or k-fold cross-validation) only on the surviving top-k configurations, turning SRM into an active screening procedure that allocates compute where the surrogate predicts good generalization. Step 4: audit layer. Log every pair of surrogate value and true error, and report per family and per regime the rank correlation, the selection regret (test-error gap between surrogate-chosen and cross-validation-chosen optimum), and compute saved versus full cross-validation, cross-tabulated to reveal where each surrogate is trustworthy and whether reliability transfers across families. Step 5: validate on USPS (as in the comparison paper) plus additional classification and regression datasets, benchmarking surrogate-guided search against full grid cross-validation and against fixed-hyperparameter baselines. This yields the missing measurements of surrogate reliability while operationally testing whether SRM-style bounds can steer efficient model selection."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as missing accumulated evidence: nobody has audited or benchmarked whether SRM-derived surrogates actually rank configurations against true held-out error, nor whether reliability transfers across families (evidence_gap), with a secondary motivation of replacing expensive cross-validation (resource_bottleneck). The central move is a systematic auditing/benchmarking study measuring rank correlation, selection regret, and transferability across families and regimes (empirical_mapping), operationalized via a coarse-to-fine successive-halving screening procedure (optimization_search). It bridges four learning-machine families, but the core contribution is measurement, not a superficial A+B combination."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: capacity bounds are not empirically audited across model families under noise.","method":"Test method: build a cross-family capacity audit that measures effective VC dimension under label noise and compares bounds to observed generalization gaps."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is that capacity bounds are not empirically audited across model families under noise (evidence_gap: lack of validation/comparison). The method builds a cross-family audit measuring effective VC dimension and comparing bounds to observed generalization gaps, a systematic diagnostic/measurement effort (empirical_mapping). Note: the test motivation/method appears unrelated to the prior-work titles about LS-SVM, but I classify what is stated."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The key open empirical question in these sources is whether the SET OF SUPPORT VECTORS is a stable, reproducible characteristic of the data — and the field has no way to observe, measure, or benchmark it. In \"The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory\" (§5.12.3), Vapnik reports that on USPS digits, polynomial, RBF, and neural-network SV machines share 80–85% of support vectors (Table 5.3) and explicitly flags as unresolved whether this holds for a wide set of real-life problems. Schölkopf et al. treat the SV set as the reusable \"important\" subset (SVs become RBF centers), and Vapnik's compression bound ties expected error to the number of SVs. Yet this evidence rests on one dataset and is reported only as clean test accuracy. No methodology, metric, or multi-dataset benchmark audits SV-set stability across kernel families (which the circular-backpropagation paper and Vapnik argue are interchangeable capacity-controlled machines), hyperparameters, resamples, or noise/perturbation. This matters because the compression bound and the \"which machine is best\" comparisons are only meaningful if the relied-upon points are a stable data property, not an artifact of one kernel/regularizer/sample. If which points become support vectors flips under noise or mislabeling, comparisons give false confidence and decision rules are brittle — a reliability failure current single-number evaluations cannot detect. Ridge regression in dual variables offers a non-sparse counterpoint, sharpening whether sparse SV selection actually buys stability. No source turns Vapnik's observation into a measurable, auditable quantity or uses it to make learning machines robust.","method":"A Support-Vector Stability audit-and-robustify framework with three parts. (A) Measurement/benchmark: for each training point define a stability score s_i in [0,1], the frequency it is selected as a support vector across an ensemble of conditions — kernel families (polynomial, Gaussian RBF, sigmoid/NN, circular-backpropagation machine), hyperparameter grids (width, degree, soft-margin C), bootstrap resamples, and controlled input perturbations and label flips. Aggregate agreement metrics (Jaccard overlap of SV sets, common-SV percentage as in Vapnik's Table 5.3, per-point selection frequency), run identically across several datasets to answer Vapnik's open question with reproducible evidence, and include kernel ridge regression (dual variables) as a non-sparse control. (B) Diagnosis: partition points into core SVs (high s_i, selected across nearly all conditions), borderline SVs (condition-specific), and fragile SVs (appear only under perturbation/noise); quantify each SV's influence on the margin/decision function by leave-one-out change, flagging fragile high-influence points as candidate outliers or mislabeled examples. (C) Robustification: convert stability into a per-point soft-margin cost C_i = C*g(s_i) with g increasing in s_i, so low-stability fragile points are capped and cannot dominate the boundary while core points get full weight; re-solve the dual QP with these box constraints to obtain a stability-regularized SVM built on the reproducible core. Evaluation targets robustness, not clean accuracy alone: degradation curves under label noise, input perturbation, and covariate shift, comparing the stability-regularized SVM against standard SVM, RBF, MLP/circular-BP, and kernel ridge; validation that the audit predicts injected mislabeled/outlier points; and a cross-dataset test of Vapnik's conjecture that high common-SV overlap co-occurs with robustness. This closes the gap by making an anecdotal observation a measurable, auditable, cross-problem quantity and using it to reduce brittleness to noise, outliers, and kernel/hyperparameter choice."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as the field lacking a way to observe/measure/benchmark whether SV-set selection is a stable data property (evidence_gap), with an explicit reliability/brittleness concern (failure_risk_gap). The central move is building a measurement/benchmark framework across datasets, kernels, and perturbations (empirical_mapping), with a secondary robustification step (stability-weighted soft-margin). Precisely identifies the bottleneck (SV-set stability as a measurable quantity underpinning compression bounds and comparisons). Not superficial stitching despite multi-part method."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works span a family of learning machines that are, on paper, deeply related but are studied in isolation. Vapnik's statistical learning theory (The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory; Statistical Learning Theory; The Support Vector Method of Function Estimation) argues that generalization is governed by the *capacity* of the function class — measured by the VC dimension, the growth function, or surrogate quantities such as the margin–radius ratio R²/γ² and the number of support vectors. The comparison paper (SVM with Gaussian kernels vs. RBF classifiers) reports the SVM as more accurate on USPS and attributes this to automatic capacity control via margin maximization. The circular-backpropagation paper explicitly computes analytic VC dimension and Cover capacity for a network that unifies \"surface-based\" (MLP) and \"prototype-based\" (RBF) representations by augmenting the input with ‖x‖². Kernel ridge regression in dual variables recasts classical ridge regression as a kernel machine, linking regularization strength to capacity.\n\nThe evidence gap is this: although each paper *invokes* a capacity measure to justify its machine, the field has no common, empirical way to observe and compare these capacity notions across machines on the same data, nor to test whether any of them actually predict generalization. Different papers use different proxies (analytic VC, Cover capacity, R²/γ², support-vector counts, ridge penalty), each computed for only one machine, so we cannot audit whether the SVM's advantage stems from capacity control or merely from its feature map, whether the analytic VC dimension of circular-BP tracks real error, or whether these theoretically \"equivalent\" machines occupy comparable capacity regimes. Without such measurement, the shared theoretical claim of structural risk minimization remains empirically unvalidated and the machines remain incommensurable.","method":"We propose a unifying framework plus a capacity-audit benchmark that reconciles these separate literatures under one formalism and then empirically measures whether their capacity notions predict generalization.\n\n(1) Unification. Cast every machine — MLP, circular-backpropagation network, RBF network, SVM with Gaussian kernel, and dual/kernel ridge regression — as regularized empirical risk minimization of a function linear in a feature space, f(x)=⟨w,Φ(x)⟩+b. Each machine is then specified by two orthogonal choices: (a) the feature map Φ (explicit augmentation vs. implicit kernel), and (b) the capacity-control mechanism (weight decay, number of hidden units, margin maximization, or ridge penalty). Crucially, we use the circular-BP augmentation Φ(x)=(x,‖x‖²) as an explicit \"control knob\" that interpolates between surface-based and prototype-based representations, letting us vary the feature map while holding capacity control fixed — thereby disentangling \"which feature space\" from \"how much capacity.\"\n\n(2) Common capacity instrumentation. For each trained machine on each dataset we compute, on a single footing, a panel of capacity/complexity proxies drawn from the sources: analytic VC dimension where a formula exists (circular unit/MLP), the margin–radius bound R²/γ², Cover-capacity estimates (fraction of random dichotomies the class can shatter), effective parameter/support-vector counts, the ridge/regularization strength, and — as a machine-agnostic anchor — an *empirically measured* VC dimension via Vapnik's experimental shattering procedure (fitting the maximum deviation between error on random-label subsamples and its expectation as a function of sample size). This yields, for the first time, all capacity measures for all machines.\n\n(3) Audit and synthesis. On common data (USPS digits as in the comparison paper, plus controlled synthetic problems where the true Bayes complexity is known), we sweep each machine's complexity knob and record measured test error alongside every capacity proxy. We then (i) test the rank correlation between each theoretical capacity measure and observed generalization across and within machines, (ii) check whether machines that are formally equivalent occupy the same measured-capacity regime, and (iii) attribute the SVM-vs-RBF gap to feature map vs. capacity control using the circular augmentation as a bridge. The output is a validated, cross-machine map from capacity measures to generalization, converting the disparate theoretical justifications of these works into a single, reproducible evidence base and a diagnostic for fairly comparing kernel and neural learning machines."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal identifies that capacity measures are invoked in isolation with no common empirical way to observe/compare them and test whether they predict generalization — a clear evidence_gap, with a strong bridge_opportunity secondary since disconnected machines/theories are being connected. The method centers on a capacity-audit benchmark measuring proxies across machines on common data (empirical_mapping), enabled by a unifying regularized-ERM formalism (synthesis_unification). Not surface stitching: it reframes machines under one formalism and uses the circular-BP augmentation as a disentangling control knob rather than gluing methods together."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two phenomena in these sources are established but unexplained. Schölkopf et al. (1997) show an SVM with Gaussian kernel beats a classical RBF net (k-means centers plus backprop weights) on USPS, with an SV-centers/backprop-weights hybrid in between. Their account is descriptive (support vectors sit at critical boundary points minimizing a risk bound) but gives no mechanistic reason why margin-driven center placement lowers test error versus clustering-driven placement, nor how much gain comes from placement versus margin optimization. Ridella et al.'s Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network has paradigm plasticity: one squared-norm input lets each unit interpolate continuously between a surface-based hyperplane and a prototype-based hypersphere/RBF representation, and they derive exact Cover capacity and VC-dimension. Yet they treat paradigm choice as an emergent by-product and never explain when or why a machine becomes prototype- versus surface-based, nor link it causally to capacity and margin. Vapnik's learning theory supplies the concepts (VC dimension, SRM, margin) only as worst-case bounds, not measured per-model drivers. The explanation gap: no unified mechanistic account connecting data geometry to chosen paradigm to effective capacity and margin to generalization, that would explain both the SVM center-selection advantage and when machines go prototype- versus surface-based. This matters because MLP, RBF, and SVM are special cases of one another, so their generalization differences should be explainable on common ground, not attributed to incomparable heuristics.","method":"Build a diagnostic workbench, a Representation-Paradigm Probe, as the central artifact, using the CBP network as one controllable substrate into which MLP, classical RBF, SVM with Gaussian kernel, and the SV-centers/backprop hybrid are embedded as constrained CBP instances (squared-norm coefficient near zero equals MLP/surface; large equals RBF/prototype; SV solutions mapped into CBP circular parameters). Three components. First, an instrumentation layer that, per model and per epoch, reports on identical axes a per-unit continuous paradigm index (the fitted weight on the squared-norm term), exact Cover capacity and VC-dimension from the CBP formulas, and the empirical margin distribution. Second, a controlled data generator varying the geometry hypothesized to drive paradigm choice: linear versus radial/clustered structure, class overlap, intrinsic dimension, and label noise, to chart which geometries push the network toward surface versus prototype solutions and how capacity and margin co-vary. Third, an intervention and ablation engine that performs surgery on the shared substrate: clamping the paradigm coefficient to force purely surface or prototype units; swapping center placement between clustering- and support-vector-selected locations while holding all else fixed; and re-optimizing weights with or without margin maximization. Measuring changes in capacity, margin, and test error after each intervention isolates the causal contribution of center placement, paradigm, and margin optimization, turning the existing hybrid comparison into a systematic causal decomposition. Validation uses USPS plus the synthetic geometries (including the paper's seven-point RBF failure case) to test concrete hypotheses, for example that the SVM advantage arises because support-vector placement plus margin maximization keeps measured effective capacity low while aligning the paradigm index to the data geometry, whereas clustering raises capacity without improving margin. All parts are implementable with era tools (backprop, QP-based SVM, closed-form CBP capacity and VC expressions), making the workbench a reusable system whose output is a mechanistic explanation rather than another accuracy table."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as an unexplained mechanistic gap (why margin-driven placement lowers error, when machines go prototype vs surface), an explanation_gap; the effort to explain MLP/RBF/SVM on common ground is a bridge_opportunity secondary. The method is a diagnostic workbench with instrumentation, controlled data generation, and causal interventions to measure per-model drivers of paradigm/capacity/margin—empirical_mapping (diagnostics, characterizing phenomena). The unification of MLP/RBF/SVM into one CBP substrate makes synthesis_unification secondary. Though a 'workbench artifact' is mentioned, its purpose is measurement and explanation rather than a deliverable system, so empirical_mapping over artifact_system. Precise bottleneck identified (isolating placement vs paradigm vs margin contributions)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior work shows SVM-RBF beats k-means RBF but does not explain why: is it boundary-anchored centers, margin-based capacity control, or the prototype-versus-surface paradigm? An explanatory account is missing.","method":"Use circular backpropagation's quadratic coefficient as a dial between surface and prototype units to factorially separate paradigm, center placement, and weight objective, and link them to VC and Cover capacity to explain the generalization gap."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is an explicit missing causal/mechanistic account for why SVM-RBF beats k-means RBF, a classic explanation_gap, with a puzzle-like surprising performance difference. The method constructs a formal factorial separation linking a tunable coefficient to VC/Cover capacity theory to explain the generalization gap (formal_derivation), supported by systematic factorial comparison (empirical_mapping). The bottleneck (paradigm vs center placement vs weight objective) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal body is placeholder text ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), so labels are inferred only from the title context. LS-SVM reformulates SVM with equality constraints solved via linear systems, suggesting a computational-tractability bottleneck addressed by a formal reformulation. Low confidence due to absent content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"CBP networks and SVMs both unify surface-based and prototype-based classifiers and beat classical RBF nets, but no work explains why norm-augmentation is near-optimal or how it relates to margin-based capacity.","method":"Prove that CBP's squared-norm augmentation is a feature map whose separators are input-space hyperspheres, derive a radius-margin VC bound for it, and show capacity-minimizing augmentation equals margin maximization, validated on USPS."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is a missing explanation for why norm-augmentation is near-optimal and how it relates to margin-based capacity (explanation_gap), tying together CBP and SVM lines (bridge secondary). The central move is proving the feature-map equivalence and deriving a radius-margin VC bound (formal_derivation), unifying two classifier frameworks (synthesis secondary). Precise bottleneck identified; not superficial stitching since a theorem connects the constructs."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"RBF networks, kernel ridge regression, and Gaussian-kernel SVMs share the same functional form: weighted sums of Gaussians on data points. The Scholkopf-Burges-Girosi-Poggio-Vapnik comparison shows the SVM beats a classical RBF, with a hybrid in between, attributing this to the SV algorithm minimizing a radius-margin capacity bound. This is an explanation gap: they show the SVM wins but give no causal account of why identical representations generalize so differently, since center selection, number of centers, kernel width, regularization, and the weight objective all change at once. No work decomposes which mechanism drives the advantage or when.","method":"Cast the RBF-hybrid-SVM continuum as one factorized design space with orthogonal axes whose extremes reproduce each source method: center-selection rule, number of centers, kernel width, regularization, and a loss-interpolation blending squared-error weights (dual ridge regression) with hinge weights (SVM). Screen configurations with the radius-margin capacity surrogate as the inner objective of a successive-halving active-search loop concentrating budget on promising uncertain configurations. Use search for explanation via capacity-matched attribution: fix the surrogate capacity and vary one axis at a time, then run a functional-ANOVA variance decomposition to quantify how much of the RBF-to-SVM gap each mechanism explains and how it shifts with sample size and noise. Validate by predicting which single-axis intervention on a classical RBF most reduces error on the USPS digit benchmark, adding the circular-backpropagation squared-norm feature as an axis."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a missing causal account of why identical Gaussian-kernel representations generalize differently (explanation_gap), stemming from conflicting evidence in the SVM-beats-RBF comparison (puzzle_contradiction secondary). The method constructs a factorized design space and runs functional-ANOVA variance decomposition to attribute the generalization gap to mechanisms — a systematic characterization/diagnostic move (empirical_mapping). The successive-halving active-search screening is a supporting optimization_search element. Bottleneck is precisely identified: which mechanism drives the advantage under capacity matching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation about the explanation gap between CBP and SVM RBF generalization","method":"test method extending margin theory to noisy augmentation regimes"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Motivation states an explanation gap between CBP and SVM RBF generalization; method extends margin theory to noisy regimes (formal derivation with scope extension). Content is a placeholder ('test motivation'/'test method'), yielding high boilerplate and low specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Explanation gap. The provided works establish that structurally different classifiers can reach comparable in-distribution accuracy while being motivated by distinct geometries and capacity-control principles: MLPs trained by backpropagation implement \"surface-based\" (hyperplane) decision rules; RBF networks implement \"prototype-based\" localized bumps; SVMs with Gaussian kernels (Schölkopf et al.) automatically place centers on boundary-critical support vectors and minimize a VC/SRM risk bound, achieving the best USPS accuracy; the circular backpropagation (CBP) network (Ridella et al.) unifies surface- and prototype-based paradigms via a single extra quadratic input term whose coefficient continuously interpolates between a hyperplane and a hypersphere, and it analyzes VC dimension and Cover capacity; kernel ridge regression in dual variables and the support vector method of function estimation frame all of this as regularized fitting; and Vapnik's statistical learning theory supplies the SRM/VC-bound account of generalization.\n\nWhat is conspicuously missing is a *causal/mechanistic* explanation of WHY these representations differ in behavior and reliability where it matters most in deployment — away from the training data. The SRM story bounds only i.i.d. test error, and every paper here measures exactly that. None explains why a surface-based unit extrapolates with unbounded, growing confidence into unseen regions while a prototype/localized unit produces a bounded, decaying response; why the SVM's boundary-focused, kernel-localized solution generalizes better than clustering-based RBF centers; or how the CBP \"circular coefficient\" that toggles paradigm relates to confidence far from data and to the margin/VC capacity that supposedly governs generalization. This gap matters because out-of-distribution overconfidence — confidently mislabeling outliers or shifted inputs — is the dominant trustworthiness failure of these classifiers, yet the theory in these works is silent about it. The CBP paper offers \"paradigm plasticity\" but analyzes only capacity and in-distribution performance; the SVM/RBF comparison reports accuracy but does not isolate which factor (center placement, kernel localization, or margin) causes the advantage.","method":"Use the CBP construction as both an explanatory probe and the basis for a robustified learning machine, because it exposes a single scalar knob — the coefficient c on the summed-squared-inputs term — that continuously moves a unit between the surface (hyperplane) and prototype (hypersphere) paradigms while remaining trainable by plain backpropagation (add one input to the pattern).\n\n(1) Mechanistic account. Derive, for a CBP/kernel unit, how the pre-activation stimulus grows with distance from the data as a function of c: for c≈0 (surface regime) the stimulus is affine and unbounded, driving saturating sigmoids to confident outputs arbitrarily far from data; for c bounded away from 0 (prototype regime) the stimulus is a downward quadratic in radius, producing a localized bounded bump whose confidence decays outside a hypersphere. Connect c to the Gaussian-kernel bandwidth of the SVM/RBF and to the VC/Cover-capacity results already in the CBP and SLT sources, yielding a testable hypothesis: OOD overconfidence is *caused* by surface-regime (low-|c|) units, not by capacity per se.\n\n(2) Robustification objective. Train a single hidden-layer network of CBP units with a structural-risk-style objective that (a) fits data via the usual loss with a dual/kernel-ridge regularizer on the linear weights, and (b) adds a \"paradigm penalty\" that pushes each unit toward the prototype regime (drives |c| up / caps radius) unless in-region data density justifies a surface unit. This biases the learned function to be localized and bounded in low-density regions, so confidence decays away from support — directly reducing overconfident errors on outliers/shift while preserving the boundary. Initialize/seed prototype centers from SVM support vectors (the boundary-critical points identified by the SVM/RBF paper) rather than k-means, and let backpropagation refine c per unit, giving a controlled interpolation between the clustering-RBF, hybrid-SV, and margin-SVM designs of that paper.\n\n(3) Diagnostic and validation. On USPS digits (matching the comparison paper) plus injected outliers/rotations and a rejection/OOD test set, run an ablation across the three families and across a sweep of the paradigm penalty strength, measuring in-distribution error, calibration, and confidence-vs-distance curves. The mechanistic claim is confirmed if per-unit |c| predicts the slope of confidence growth into empty regions, if surface-regime models show the worst OOD overconfidence at matched in-distribution accuracy and matched VC capacity, and if the paradigm-penalized model retains accuracy while flattening far-from-data confidence. This simultaneously explains *why* the representations differ in reliability and delivers a concrete, low-cost (one extra input + a regularizer) method that robustifies against extrapolation overconfidence."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a missing mechanistic/causal explanation of why surface vs prototype units differ in OOD confidence — an explanation_gap, with a secondary failure_risk_gap around overconfidence/trustworthiness. The core move derives a mechanistic account (how pre-activation stimulus grows with c, linking to VC capacity) — formal_derivation — coupled with a robustification objective (paradigm penalty to cap confidence away from data). It unifies CBP, SVM, RBF paradigms but the central contribution is the causal derivation plus robustified objective rather than pure synthesis. Bottleneck is precisely identified (the c coefficient / surface regime causing unbounded extrapolation)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The sources form a zoo of learning machines that all generalize well through architecturally distinct mechanisms, yet offer no shared causal account of why they work or why they differ. The perceptron/MLP is surface-based (hyperplanes); Gaussian RBF networks are prototype-based (clustered template centers); the Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network adds one parameter weighting the sum of squared inputs, giving paradigm plasticity (collapsing to a perceptron when that coefficient is small, to a hyperspherical prototype unit otherwise) and is reported to beat both MLP and RBF; the Gaussian-kernel SVM subsumes polynomial, neural-net and RBF classifiers and beats classical RBF by placing centers at margin-critical support vectors rather than clustered templates; dual ridge regression and the SV method of function estimation express estimators via kernels plus a regularizer. Vapnik's statistical learning theory (VC dimension, structural risk minimization, margin) is invoked separately by several works. The explanation gap: each paradigm is justified on its own terms and the empirical rankings are reported but not mechanistically explained. It is unresolved whether the true driver of generalization is feature-map geometry, center-placement rule, or a single shared capacity quantity (feature-space margin or weight norm, i.e. effective VC dimension) common to all. Without disentangling these, the field carries redundant paradigm-specific folklore for what may be one mechanism, and cannot say where modeling effort should go.","method":"Build a unifying framework re-expressing all five machine families (MLP/perceptron, Gaussian RBF network, CBP, Gaussian-kernel SVM, and dual kernel ridge regression) as one regularized linear estimator in a common feature space, characterized by three orthogonal axes. Axis one, the feature map: linear (perceptron), then linear-plus-squared-norm quadratic feature (CBP, shown to be a minimal polynomial-kernel augmentation), then full Gaussian-kernel space (RBF, SVM); this places CBP's single extra coefficient on a continuum between perceptron and kernel maps and unifies surface-based, prototype-based and kernel views. Axis two, center/basis placement: data-independent, clustering (k-means templates), or margin-critical (support vectors). Axis three, loss plus regularizer that sets capacity: squared-plus-ridge (dual ridge regression), hinge or epsilon-insensitive plus norm (SVM), or backprop plus weight-decay (MLP/RBF/CBP), all reduced to a common feature-space weight-norm penalty that, via the SLT bound the sources use, controls margin and VC dimension. Then test one causal hypothesis: generalization is governed mainly by the shared capacity quantity (margin or weight norm, an effective VC-dimension proxy), largely independent of paradigm label. Run a factorial morphing study interpolating one machine into another while jointly measuring, on common benchmarks such as the USPS digits from the SVM/RBF paper: the margin, a VC or Cover-capacity proxy using the CBP paper's closed-form capacities and the SLT bounds, and held-out error. Key ablations: fix the feature map and vary only center placement to isolate the placement axis; fix capacity and vary architecture across paradigms to test error invariance; sweep CBP's quadratic coefficient to trace the surface-to-prototype transition and check whether error tracks the capacity proxy rather than the paradigm. If test error collapses onto a single curve in the capacity quantity across all machines, the framework supplies the missing mechanistic explanation and reduces the paradigm zoo to one capacity-controlled kernel estimator; systematic residual deviations would localize a genuine second cause such as loss-induced support-vector sparsity, which the framework can then name precisely."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a missing mechanistic account of why architecturally distinct learning machines all generalize well (explanation_gap), with a strong secondary of connecting disconnected paradigm literatures (bridge_opportunity). The core move re-expresses five machine families as one regularized linear estimator in a common feature space, reconciling separate paradigms (synthesis_unification), grounded in a formal capacity/VC framework and derivations (formal_derivation). It is not superficial stitching because it proposes a unifying axis decomposition and a testable causal hypothesis; the bottleneck (shared capacity quantity as the true generalization driver) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"The learning machines in these works optimize in-distribution generalization but are brittle and over-confident on inputs outside the region supported by training data. Statistical Learning Theory (Nature of SLT; Statistical Learning Theory; Support Vector Method of Function Estimation) controls capacity via VC dimension and the SRM confidence interval, but these bounds are worst-case and describe the average risk of a function class, saying nothing about the reliability of an individual prediction or whether a test point lies in a data-covered region. SVMs and RBF classifiers (Comparing SVMs with Gaussian Kernels to RBF Classifiers) give large margins even for spurious inputs, and their only reject mechanism is an ad hoc threshold on the raw output. Dual ridge regression likewise gives point estimates with no per-input trust. Circular Backpropagation is the one source touching this: it augments the perceptron with a squared-norm term to form closed, bounded hyperspherical decision regions, cites rejection of spurious patterns, and derives their VC dimension and Cover capacity, yet it is trained by backpropagation with no margin control or calibrated confidence, while SVMs give margins and SRM confidence but open, unbounded regions. No artifact fuses bounded-support representation with margin-based complexity control to deliver calibrated per-input reliability and principled abstention. For high-stakes recognition like the USPS digit pipelines common to these papers, unreliable confidence and undetected out-of-distribution inputs are a direct safety and reproducibility concern.","method":"Build TrustKernel, a deployment-oriented toolkit that turns any kernel/SVM classifier into a reliability-aware, abstaining classifier with bounded trust regions. (1) Bounded-region classifier: adopt the Circular Backpropagation augmentation (append the squared norm as an extra coordinate) and train a maximum-margin SVM in this augmented space using the dual/kernel machinery of the SV method and dual ridge regression; a hyperplane there is a hypersphere in the original space, giving closed decision regions with a knob interpolating open-to-closed. (2) Support-envelope layer: concurrently fit a one-class support sphere enclosing training data in feature space with the same kernel and solver, defining an explicit trusted region; at inference compute both a signed margin (class confidence) and a containment score (novelty/OOD). (3) SRM-calibrated reject rule: combine the empirical margin with the SRM confidence-interval term instantiated using the VC-dimension and Cover-capacity formulas the CBP paper derives for hypersphere families, then abstain when inputs fall outside the envelope or below a chosen confidence operating point. (4) Diagnostics as software: emit risk-coverage curves, per-region reliability maps, and hyperparameter-sensitivity sweeps over kernel width, C, and augmentation strength. Evaluation: reproduce the USPS digit setup and compare against a plain Gaussian SVM, a classical RBF network, and a CBP network on clean accuracy, selective-prediction quality (area under the risk-coverage curve), out-of-distribution rejection (non-digit, corrupted, and shifted inputs, measured as abstained versus confidently misclassified), and stability of confidence under hyperparameter perturbation. Success is retaining SVM in-distribution accuracy while sharply cutting confident errors on spurious inputs and providing calibrated, reproducible per-input reliability."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed around brittleness, over-confidence, and undetected OOD inputs (failure_risk_gap), with an explicit bridge between CBP's bounded regions and SVM's margin/SRM confidence (bridge_opportunity). The core move fuses these disconnected approaches into a unified reliability-aware machine (synthesis_unification), delivered as a concrete toolkit artifact (artifact_system). The combination of CBP augmentation + one-class sphere + SRM reject rule reads somewhat as A+B stitching, hence a moderate stitching score, though it targets a fairly specific bottleneck (open unbounded decision regions lacking per-input trust)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel SVM classifiers built by structural risk minimization only report distance to the decision surface as confidence and this value is unbounded far from the data so they are overconfident on out of support inputs and none of the provided works give a per instance reliability guarantee.","method":"Pair an SVM decision function with a feature space enclosing sphere support function that equals the circular backpropagation unit and accept a prediction only when the point is inside the sphere and the margin is large otherwise abstain and calibrate confidence to decay outside the support."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an overconfidence/reliability failure: SVM confidence is unbounded far from data with no per-instance reliability guarantee (failure_risk_gap), tied to lack of a reliable confidence measure (evidence_gap). The method pairs an SVM with an enclosing-sphere support function to abstain outside support and decay confidence, primarily reducing overconfident failures (robustification), by combining SVM with circular backpropagation/support estimation (synthesis component, somewhat stitched). Bottleneck—unbounded distance far from data—is fairly specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works cluster around capacity-controlled learning machines: statistical learning theory and structural risk minimization (Nature of Statistical Learning Theory; Statistical Learning Theory; Support Vector Method of Function Estimation), kernel classifiers subsuming polynomials, neural nets and RBF networks (Comparing SVMs with Gaussian Kernels to RBF Classifiers), kernel ridge regression in dual variables (Ridge Regression in Dual Variables), and a unified mapping-network justified by VC dimension and Cover capacity (Circular Backpropagation Networks). Their promise is that controlling capacity guarantees good generalization regardless of dimensionality. Failure/Risk gap: this promise rests on point-estimate accuracy on a single benchmark (USPS) and asymptotic worst-case bounds; reliability is never characterized. Each machine hinges on fragile choices (kernel width, C/epsilon/ridge lambda, number of centers or units) and on solving a dual whose Gram matrix can be ill-conditioned (a numerical-reliability concern echoed in Matrix Computations). This leaves brittleness, reproducibility, and unreliable model-selection risks unaddressed: how sensitive is generalization to hyperparameters, subsampling, noise, and finite precision, and do capacity quantities (VC estimate via radius/margin, Cover capacity, margin, number of support vectors) predict robustness or only average accuracy? Since SRM selects models by capacity, if capacity fails to predict robustness the standard recipe is silently unsafe. No source measures this, yet these families are deployed for high-stakes recognition and their theory is invoked to justify trust.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map of the shared kernel/mapping family and test whether capacity measures predict robustness, not just accuracy. First, instantiate on a common footing SVMs (Gaussian and polynomial kernels), classical RBF networks, the SVM/backprop hybrid, kernel ridge regression in dual variables, and circular-backpropagation networks, treated as points in one capacity-parameterized family. Second, define perturbation axes: on USPS plus several standard datasets, vary hyperparameters (kernel width, C/epsilon/lambda, number of centers or units) over dense grids; training-subsample composition via resampling; label-noise and input-perturbation levels; and numerical conditioning (Gram condition number, diagonal regularization, solver precision). Third, measure robustness diagnostics beyond mean test error: error variance and quantile spread across resamples and perturbations, decision-boundary and support-vector-set stability, cross-model disagreement, noise-degradation slope, and reproducibility of the dual solution versus Gram condition number. Fourth, record capacity quantities (empirical VC via radius/margin ratio, Cover capacity, margin, number of support vectors) and quantify via correlation and ranking agreement how well each predicts each robustness diagnostic, separate from accuracy, directly testing the SRM assumption that low capacity implies safe, reproducible behavior. Finally, deliver an open reproducible robustness-evaluation protocol; per-machine empirical maps of regions where accuracy is high but robustness collapses and capacity bounds mislead; and a robustness-aware model-selection criterion augmenting SRM with predictive diagnostics plus Gram-conditioning guidance. The study reuses the sources' datasets and algorithms, requiring only controlled re-runs over a perturbation grid."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an unaddressed reliability/reproducibility concern: capacity-controlled machines are trusted on point-estimate accuracy and asymptotic bounds but never characterized for robustness (failure_risk_gap), and no source measures this (evidence_gap). The central move is a systematic empirical map with perturbation axes and diagnostics testing whether capacity predicts robustness (empirical_mapping), with a robustness-aware model-selection criterion as a secondary robustification aim. Precise bottleneck identified (capacity vs robustness prediction, Gram conditioning). Not surface stitching—reuses prior algorithms as objects of study rather than combining them naively."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel learning machines — support vector machines, RBF classifiers, and ridge regression in dual variables — are all justified by statistical learning theory: structural risk minimization bounds the EXPECTED test error using GLOBAL capacity quantities (the VC-dimension term R^2/margin^2, the radius of the enclosing ball, and the empirical risk). The comparison of Gaussian-kernel SVMs to RBF networks, the support-vector method of function estimation, and dual-variable ridge regression all share one decision-function form, f(x)=Σ α_i K(x,x_i)+b, and all inherit the same guarantee: on AVERAGE, over the input distribution, the machine is good.\n\nThis leaves a Failure/Risk gap that matters acutely in safety-critical or adversarial deployment, where what counts is whether a SPECIFIC prediction can be trusted. Three coupled risk sources are jointly unaddressed by the listed works. (1) Input brittleness: two test points with identical f(x) can have very different sensitivity to a small perturbation of x, because the local geometry (gradient of the kernel expansion) differs; yet f(x) is routinely (mis)used as an uncalibrated confidence, and the global margin certifies nothing per point. (2) Solution uncertainty: the coefficients α are obtained by solving a regularized linear system or QP built from the Gram matrix, which for Gaussian kernels is frequently ill-conditioned; finite-precision solving and the choice of hyperparameters (kernel width σ, ridge λ) make f itself uncertain — a numerical-linear-algebra fragility that SLT bounds silently ignore. (3) No principled abstention: SRM offers no per-instance rule for when a kernel machine should refuse to predict. The sources supply the full global apparatus (SLT/VC bounds, kernel expansions, dual/regularized formulations, RBF constructions) but provide no unified per-instance reliability formalism connecting the margin value, local kernel sensitivity, and numerical/parametric stability.","method":"Contribution type: a formal derivation of a per-instance RELIABILITY CERTIFICATE for kernel machines, plus bounds and a model-selection objective built on it. Everything is derived for the shared decision function f(x)=Σ α_i K(x,x_i)+b used by SVMs, RBF classifiers, and dual ridge regression.\n\n(1) Input-robustness theorem. For differentiable kernels, derive a closed-form local Lipschitz bound L(x)=Σ|α_i|·‖∇_x K(x,x_i)‖ (Gaussian kernel gives an explicit expression in ‖x−x_i‖ and σ). Prove a certified radius ρ_in(x)=|f(x)|/L(x): every input perturbation with ‖δ‖<ρ_in(x) leaves sign(f) unchanged. This converts the global margin into a per-point certified robustness radius.\n\n(2) Model-stability theorem. Treat α as the solution of the regularized dual system (K+λI)α=y (dual ridge) or the SVM QP. Using standard perturbation analysis, bound the coefficient perturbation via the condition number κ(K+λI) and derive Δf(x) ≤ ‖k(x)‖·‖δα‖ together with hyperparameter-sensitivity bounds |∂f/∂λ|, |∂f/∂σ|. Define an EFFECTIVE margin m_eff(x)=|f(x)|−Δf(x) and a combined certified radius ρ(x)=m_eff(x)/L(x) that simultaneously accounts for input perturbation and model/numerical uncertainty.\n\n(3) Selective-risk theorem. Define the abstention set A_τ={x: ρ(x)<τ}. Derive a bound on the CONDITIONAL error over the accepted region that refines the global VC/SRM bound by intersecting the capacity term with the per-instance certificate, and prove the accepted-region risk is monotone decreasing in τ. This gives a principled reject option with a guarantee, absent from the source works.\n\n(4) Reliability-aware model-selection objective. Formalize the choice of (σ,λ) as maximizing certified coverage P(ρ(x)≥τ) subject to a target bound on accepted-region risk. Show this makes explicit a CAPACITY–CONDITIONING trade-off that pure SRM ignores: larger σ or λ improve Gram-matrix conditioning and reduce Δf (more stable α) but shrink the margin/raise capacity, while small σ/λ do the opposite. The objective identifies the operating point that yields the most trustworthy predictions rather than the smallest average error.\n\nInstantiation and evaluation. Instantiate all four results for the Gaussian-kernel SVM, the RBF classifier, and dual ridge regression, reusing the USPS handwritten-digit benchmark from the SVM-vs-RBF study. Report risk–coverage (accept/reject) curves, empirical verification that predictions with ρ(x)≥τ resist bounded input perturbations and remain stable as λ and σ vary near the ill-conditioned regime, and comparison of the reliability-aware (σ,λ) selection against ordinary cross-validation. Because the certificate is a closed-form function of the already-computed kernel expansion and the Gram matrix, it adds negligible cost, making the framework directly applicable to the classical kernel machines in the sources."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as a per-instance reliability/risk problem left open by global SLT bounds (failure_risk_gap), with a strong explanatory undertone about why global margins fail to certify individual predictions. The central move is deriving closed-form theorems (Lipschitz bound, certified radius, selective-risk bound, model-selection objective), a clear formal_derivation, aimed at reducing brittleness/uncertainty (robustification secondary). Precise bottleneck identified: capacity-conditioning tradeoff, local kernel sensitivity, Gram-matrix conditioning. Not superficial stitching since it unifies three risk sources into one certificate via derivation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel machines (SVMs, kernel ridge regression, SV-based RBF networks) are central across these sources, and their theoretical footing (Structural Risk Minimization, Vapnik's support-vector-count bound E[P(error)] <= E[#SV]/(l-1), Zhang's leave-one-out kernel bounds, and VC/Cover-capacity analyses in Circular Backpropagation) is used almost only descriptively to explain generalization, not to choose hyperparameters. This leaves a Failure/Risk gap: generalization is dominated by hyperparameters the theory does not fix (kernel width sigma, trade-off C or ridge lambda, epsilon). The comparison paper notes the SV method auto-determines centers/weights/threshold, yet sigma and C are still set by hand or grid-search cross-validation. That makes models brittle and unreliable: grid CV is costly, high-variance and prone to overfitting the validation split on the small samples where kernels shine, and opaque about selection confidence. The bounds that could make selection principled are computable from a single trained model, but no source turns them into a reliable, efficient search. Closing this gap targets the brittleness and reproducibility risk of kernel-machine model selection.","method":"Build a bound-driven, uncertainty-aware optimization framework replacing grid-search cross-validation for hyperparameters theta = (sigma, C or lambda, epsilon) with a search minimizing closed-form generalization surrogates from a single model fit. Surrogate: assemble a differentiable objective J(theta) from bounds in the sources, namely Zhang's leave-one-out kernel bound (exact closed-form PRESS for ridge from one factorization of K+lambda*I) plus Vapnik's SV-count and radius-margin terms, each computed from one training solve (dual alpha, number of support vectors, Gram matrix), so evaluating J(theta) costs one fit not k retrainings. Linear algebra: compute LOO/PRESS and updates via rank-one Cholesky downdates and factorization reuse (Matrix Computations) for scalable inner loops. Gradient search where smooth: since Gram entries are differentiable in sigma and the dual solution is differentiable in theta via KKT/implicit-function conditions, derive analytic gradients of J and run gradient/trust-region optimization (Practical Methods of Optimization) in continuous space, avoiding grids. Screening where non-smooth: for the discrete SV-count term and non-smooth epsilon loss, use successive-halving that prunes unpromising theta regions using the cheap single-fit bound and allocates more compute to promising regions with warm-started continuation over sigma. Reliability control, the core contribution: treat J(theta) as an estimate with quantifiable dispersion from the spread of per-point LOO terms, and select theta by a risk-averse criterion argmin over theta of J(theta)+kappa*std(J(theta)), favoring hyperparameters whose good generalization estimate is stable, directly attacking selection brittleness and improving reproducibility. Validation: on the handwritten-digit and benchmark tasks from the comparison and circular-backpropagation papers, compare against grid-search CV on test error, number of training solves, and variance of selected-model performance across repeated splits; success is matching or beating CV test error at a fraction of the cost while reducing performance variance."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal frames the gap as brittleness/reproducibility of hyperparameter selection (failure_risk_gap), with cost of grid CV as secondary resource_bottleneck. The central move is a bound-driven optimization/search over hyperparameters replacing grid search (optimization_search), with the risk-averse selection criterion as robustification. Bottleneck precisely identified: theory used descriptively not for selection; sigma/C set by hand. Not mere A+B stitching—integrates bounds, implicit-function gradients, and reliability control into a coherent selection scheme."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about robustness gap in SVM and kernel ridge under unknown noise.","method":"Test method: adaptive robust dual kernel machine with learned local loss and corrected bound."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation centers on a robustness gap under unknown noise (failure/risk framing), with scope-mismatch flavor from unrealistic noise assumptions. Method builds an adaptive robust kernel machine with learned loss and corrected bound, primarily robustification, secondarily extending to noisier regimes. Some A+B stitching of SVM/ridge with robust loss."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation for robust ensemble of kernel and neural learners.","method":"Test method: build a bound-weighted robust ensemble with abstention."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":3,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is a placeholder ('Test motivation', 'Test method') describing a robust ensemble of kernel and neural learners with abstention. Framing centers on robustness/reliability of learners (failure_risk_gap) via a robustification move, with an ensemble that stitches together kernel and neural methods (synthesis). Content is generic and clearly a superficial combination with no specified bottleneck."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Failure/Risk gap in per-instance reliability. The kernel and neural machines in these works (SVMs with Gaussian kernels, RBF classifiers, dual kernel ridge regression, the SV method of function estimation, and MLP/circular-backpropagation networks) all emit point predictions with no trustworthy per-input reliability, causing brittleness: confidently wrong outputs on out-of-distribution or ambiguous inputs, and ad hoc abstention. The SVM-vs-RBF paper takes reject decisions from the maximal output before the sgn function (margin magnitude only), ignoring whether the input is supported by training data. Statistical Learning Theory's SRM yields only global, worst-case, distribution-free confidence intervals dominated by the worst function, too loose to certify a single prediction; kernel ridge regression and RBF regressors give no uncertainty. Two complementary reliability signals exist across these literatures but are never combined: a surface-based signal (margin |f(x)|) and a prototype-based signal (proximity to and density of training data and support vectors). A large-margin point far from all data is dangerously overconfident under margin-only scoring, while a point near data but near the boundary is genuinely ambiguous. No source reconciles these into a calibrated, theoretically grounded per-instance reliability estimate with a principled reject option.","method":"Build a unified per-instance reliability estimator bridging three strands in the sources: Vapnik's local risk minimization with vicinity functions K(x,x0;beta) and its joint SRM control of empirical risk, capacity and locality; the surface-based margin of kernel/SV machines (SVM, SVR, kernel ridge); and the prototype-based representation of the circular-backpropagation generalized neural unit, where the SVM feature-space hyperplane and the RBF prototype network are limiting cases and the circular coefficient interpolates between them. Steps: (1) express any machine (SVM, SVR, kernel ridge, RBF, circular-BP MLP) in the single generalized-unit formalism so one kernel defines both f(x) and geometry; (2) for a test point x compute a surface term from margin |f(x)| and a support term as a vicinity-weighted density of training/support vectors around x, using the model's own kernel as the vicinity function; (3) instantiate Vapnik's local risk inequality to obtain a per-instance guaranteed-risk bound conditional on x, namely vicinity-weighted local empirical risk plus a local capacity term, minimized jointly over empirical risk, VC term and locality beta, replacing the loose global SRM interval; (4) combine surface and support terms through this local bound into a calibrated reliability score R(x) and derive a reject threshold that provably controls conditional risk on accepted inputs, calibrating beta and the combination on held-out data and exploiting the closed-form leave-one-out of dual kernel ridge regression for efficiency; (5) apply uniformly to classification and regression. Evaluate on the USPS digit database used by the comparison paper and regression benchmarks, measuring calibration (reliability diagrams), OOD/outlier rejection and risk-coverage curves, against margin-only, density/prototype-only and global-VC-bound baselines it unifies. The synthesis makes the two reliability mechanisms mutually corrective (an input is trusted only when both far from the decision surface and well supported by data), grounded in a per-instance version of SRM rather than an untrustworthy worst-case global bound."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly a failure/risk gap in per-instance reliability (overconfident OOD predictions, ad hoc abstention), with a secondary bridge opportunity between two never-combined reliability signals. The method centrally unifies three distinct strands (local risk minimization, margin-based, prototype-based) into one generalized-unit formalism, making synthesis_unification primary; the per-instance local-risk bound and reject threshold derivation give formal_derivation as secondary. Not surface stitching because the combination is genuinely mutually corrective and grounded in a reformulated local SRM bound, with a precisely identified bottleneck (margin-only vs support-only signals; loose global vs per-instance bounds)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Puzzle/contradiction. Two lines in this corpus target the same hypothesis class (spherical/RBF-type decision surfaces) and both claim to beat classical RBF networks, yet via opposite principles. Ridella et al.'s circular backpropagation (CBP, 1997) adds exactly ONE feature, the squared norm of x, so a unit realizes a hypersphere; VC dimension rises only from n+1 to n+2, and this minimal increment of dimensionality is argued 'in many senses optimal' for generalization, trained cheaply by backprop. Vapnik's SVMs (1995/1998; Scholkopf et al. 1997) instead embrace unbounded, even infinite-dimensional kernel spaces, with a bound (expected number of support vectors over sample size) declared independent of the dimensionality of the space, governed only by margin, solved by QP with dense expansions. So the field simultaneously prescribes 'minimize added dimensionality' and 'dimensionality is irrelevant, only margin matters.' Dual ridge regression (Saunders et al. 1998) is fully dense while SV function estimation is sparse only via epsilon-insensitivity, crediting yet other mechanisms. These claims have never been reconciled under a common hypothesis class and training procedure. Which actually governs generalization of RBF-type classifiers: parsimony of an explicit feature map, or margin in a rich implicit space? This matters because it decides whether to ship small interpretable gradient-trained models or large kernel expansions.","method":"Build Circular Support Vector Networks (CSVN): one training framework/toolkit fusing CBP and SVM that also disentangles dimensionality from margin. (1) Explicit low-rank circular feature map phi(x) formed by concatenating x with its squared norm (the CBP augmentation). A linear separator here is exactly a hypersphere, equal to one CBP unit and a Gaussian-RBF-equivalent prototype (Ridella et al. prove this equivalence): deliberately the minimal, finite counterpart of the infinite Gaussian kernel. (2) Margin training by gradient descent, not QP: train circular units under the soft-margin objective (hinge loss plus norm regularization), Vapnik's capacity criterion, but optimized by backprop over phi(x); this injects SVM margin control into CBP's cheap training. (3) Constructive, capacity-bounded growth: start with one circular unit, iteratively add units covering margin-violating regions (each an interpretable center-plus-radius prototype); at each step compute BOTH the CBP VC/Cover-capacity estimate and the margin/support-vector bound, using them jointly as a stopping rule, yielding sparse RBF-like classifiers that are gradient-trainable and margin-regularized. (4) Unified toolkit/workflow: classical RBF, Gaussian-kernel SVM, dual ridge regression, SV regression, and CBP all become configurations over the same explicit circular feature map, selectable by loss (hinge, epsilon-insensitive, squared) and expansion size. Resolution of the gap: holding the hypothesis class (spherical) and optimizer (gradient margin) fixed while sweeping the number of explicit circular units/features, CSVN measures directly whether test error tracks added explicit dimensionality (CBP's claim) or only the achieved margin (SVM's claim), which is impossible when methods differ in both class and optimizer. Evaluate on the USPS digits used by Scholkopf et al. plus standard benchmarks against Gaussian-kernel SVM, classical RBF, and plain CBP on accuracy, model size (prototypes vs support vectors), and training cost. Beyond adjudicating the puzzle, the artifact delivers sparse, interpretable, gradient-trained RBF classifiers with statistical-learning-theory model selection, avoiding both QP scaling and CBP's lack of principled capacity control."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a contradiction between two lines (CBP's minimal-dimensionality prescription vs SVM's dimensionality-irrelevant/margin claim) targeting the same hypothesis class, so puzzle_contradiction is primary with bridge_opportunity secondary. The method fuses CBP and SVM into a unified framework where multiple prior methods become configurations of one feature map, which is synthesis_unification; the capacity-bounded adjudication and equivalence proofs add a formal_derivation flavor. Some superficial A+B combining (CBP augmentation + margin training) drives moderate stitching, but the explicit design to disentangle dimensionality from margin gives it a real conceptual purpose."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"A puzzle sits at the intersection of two 1997–1998 results that were never connected.\n\n(1) Schölkopf et al. (\"Comparing SVMs with Gaussian kernels to RBF classifiers\") show that on USPS digits a support-vector machine beats a backprop/k-means-trained RBF network. Their explanation is structural risk minimization (SRM): the SVM maximizes margin and thereby controls the *capacity* of the function class, whereas backprop only minimizes empirical error. The SVM literature (Vapnik; \"The support vector method of function estimation\") states the SRM principle sharply: generalization depends on the VC dimension of the chosen function set, \"regardless of the dimensionality of the space.\" Yet the very kernels used to realize SRM in practice — Gaussian and full degree-2 polynomial — embed the data in infinite- or O(d^2)-dimensional feature spaces and produce solutions supported on many support vectors.\n\n(2) Ridella et al. (\"Circular backpropagation networks\") show the opposite extreme: adding a *single* fixed feature, the squared norm ||x||^2, upgrades a linear perceptron to a full hypersphere/quadric classifier that unifies surface-based (hyperplane) and prototype-based (RBF-like) representations. Crucially, this \"circular unit\" has VC dimension only d+2 versus d+1 for a plane — a near-minimal capacity increase for genuine nonlinear power, which the authors argue is \"in many senses optimal.\"\n\nThe contradiction: the compact, provably low-VC-dimension representation that SRM theory says should generalize best is trained by Ridella et al. with plain backpropagation — pure empirical risk minimization, the exact procedure Schölkopf et al. show to be inferior and which is also prone to local minima. Meanwhile SRM is deployed through generic high/infinite-dimensional kernels that discard precisely the low-dimensional, low-VC structure that theory prizes. In short: the field applies margin control to the wrong (huge) feature space and applies the right (minimal) feature space with the wrong (ERM) training rule. Nobody married CBP's minimal circular feature to SVM's margin-based capacity control, so it is unknown whether SVM's practical advantage comes from big feature spaces or merely from margin plus the *right minimal* nonlinear feature.","method":"Propose the Support-Vector Circular Machine (SVCM): apply structural risk minimization directly in the compact circular feature space, resolving the ERM/SRM mismatch.\n\n1. Circular kernel. Use the explicit map phi(x) = (x, beta*||x||^2), of dimension d+1, corresponding to the Mercer-valid \"circular kernel\" k(x,x') = <x,x'> + beta^2 (||x||^2)(||x'||^2) (a sum of PSD kernels). This is the CBP augmentation, but now used as an SVM kernel rather than an extra backprop input.\n\n2. Max-margin circular classifier. Solve the soft-margin SVM quadratic program in this space. The solution is a maximum-margin hyperquadric; using Ridella et al.'s weight-to-circular-parameter map (their Table I) it reads out directly as a center, radius, and gain. Because the QP is convex, this yields a unique global optimum, removing the local-minima weakness of backprop-trained CBP while importing Vapnik's margin/SRM generalization guarantees onto a function class whose VC dimension is bounded by ~d+2.\n\n3. Automatic paradigm selection with a guarantee. The weight the margin optimizer places on the ||x||^2 coordinate governs the representation: near zero recovers a max-margin hyperplane (surface-based), nonzero gives a sphere (prototype-based). Thus CBP's \"paradigm plasticity\" is now driven by margin-based capacity control instead of by unsupervised backprop dynamics.\n\n4. Doubly-controlled capacity bound. Derive a generalization bound that takes the minimum of (a) the combinatorial VC bound using dim = d+2 from the CBP analysis and (b) Vapnik's margin bound. Use this bound to set C and beta, testing the hypothesis that the circular kernel attains SVM-level accuracy at a fraction of the effective capacity of Gaussian/degree-2 kernels.\n\n5. Expressiveness ladder via SRM. Since one quadric is limited, define a nested family S_m of sums of m max-margin circular units and select m by the SRM bound (not validation error alone). Construct S_m concretely as a two-stage analogue of Schölkopf's \"hybrid\": use the support vectors of the circular-kernel SVM as candidate sphere centers, fit a max-margin circular unit around each, and combine them with a max-margin linear output layer — a fully margin-trained CBP network.\n\n6. Regression variant. Instantiate the circular kernel inside epsilon-insensitive SV regression and dual (kernel) ridge regression, connecting to the function-estimation and dual-ridge sources, to test whether isotropic-quadratic features suffice for smooth function estimation.\n\n7. Experiments. Replicate Schölkopf et al.'s USPS protocol and the CBP benchmark datasets, comparing SVCM against (i) Gaussian-kernel SVM, (ii) full degree-2 polynomial SVM, (iii) backprop-trained CBP, and (iv) RBF+k-means, measuring test error, number of support vectors / free parameters, and training stability. The decisive test of the puzzle: if SVCM matches Gaussian-SVM accuracy while using a d+1-dimensional feature space and dramatically lower capacity, and simultaneously beats backprop-CBP, then the SVM advantage is attributable to margin plus the right minimal feature — not to high dimensionality — reconciling the two conflicting results."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a contradiction between two 1997-98 results (SRM applied to huge feature spaces vs. minimal circular feature trained by ERM), so puzzle_contradiction is primary with bridge_opportunity secondary since it connects disconnected literatures. The method marries CBP's circular feature with SVM margin control (synthesis_unification), backed by a derived doubly-controlled capacity bound (formal_derivation). It is not superficial stitching since the combination reconciles a specific theoretical mismatch and yields a novel Mercer kernel with a testable hypothesis; the bottleneck (margin applied to wrong feature space) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"A contradiction runs through these sources about *what actually causes good generalization* in nonlinear classifiers, and no study orthogonalizes the competing explanations.\n\n(1) Vapnik's statistical learning theory (The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory; Statistical Learning Theory; The Support Vector Method of Function Estimation) says generalization is bounded by empirical risk plus a confidence term that depends only on capacity (VC dimension / margin / weight-vector norm). This prescription is deliberately architecture-agnostic: capacity control (structural risk minimization) — not the choice of representation — should drive test performance.\n\n(2) Yet Schölkopf et al. (\"Comparing SVMs with Gaussian kernels to RBF classifiers\") observe that merely swapping the *representation* — choosing RBF centers by the SV algorithm versus k-means — lowers test error even when weights are trained classically, i.e., \"solely due to the lower value of the empirical risk; the confidence term... did not change.\" Their full SV machine changes both the representation (which points become prototypes) and the capacity-control regime (margin/QP) at once.\n\n(3) In apparent tension, Ridella et al.'s circular backpropagation (CBP) network claims to be \"in many senses optimal\" and to beat MLPs and Gaussian RBF networks purely by changing the *representational paradigm* (its \"paradigm plasticity\" interpolates between surface-based hyperplanes and prototype-based hyperspheres), while being trained by plain backpropagation with no explicit capacity control — and it justifies this via VC-dimension and Cover-capacity arguments.\n\nSo two camps explain the same phenomenon (better generalization) with different causes: one credits capacity control / margin (SLT, SVM, ridge regression in dual variables), the other credits representational paradigm (CBP, SV-vs-k-means center choice). Every existing comparison confounds these two axes — models differ simultaneously in *how they represent* the decision boundary and in *how they control capacity*. The risk-bound decomposition itself shows the empirical-risk and confidence terms can move independently, yet no work has mapped their interaction. Until representation and capacity control are varied orthogonally on a common substrate, we cannot say whether generalization obeys the architecture-agnostic SLT prescription or whether representational form has an effect even at matched capacity. This matters because practitioners choosing between RBF, SVM, and CBP-style models are given conflicting guidance about which knob to turn.","method":"Build a factorial diagnostic benchmark that orthogonalizes two axes on a single shared substrate, then decompose the variance in generalization to see which axis (and their interaction) drives it.\n\nCommon substrate. Exploit the CBP insight that a \"circular\" (prototype/spherical) classifier is just a *linear* classifier on an augmented feature map: phi_gamma(x) = [x, gamma*||x||^2]. This turns the representational paradigm into a single continuous dial that does not change the underlying data:\n- Axis A (Representation paradigm), gamma from 0 to large: gamma=0 gives the pure surface-based hyperplane (MLP-like); increasing gamma continuously introduces the hyperspherical/prototype behavior (RBF-like). Extend the prototype extreme with explicit Gaussian-RBF feature maps so the axis spans surface -> circular -> full prototype, exactly the paradigms the CBP paper unifies and the SVM/RBF paper contrasts.\n- Axis B (Capacity-control regime / learning principle) applied to the *same* representation: (i) plain empirical risk minimization by backpropagation (no capacity control), (ii) explicit L2 / ridge regularization solved in dual variables (kernel ridge regression), and (iii) margin-based structural risk minimization via the SVM quadratic program. These three are precisely the learning principles spanned by the source papers.\n\nMeasurements per grid cell. On multiple datasets — the USPS handwritten-digit database and the synthetic 2D ball/circle problem used by Schölkopf et al., plus additional standard benchmarks — record: train and test error; the generalization gap; and several *effective-capacity* diagnostics drawn directly from the sources: (a) the Cover-capacity fraction of shatterable dichotomies and VC-dimension estimates (CBP paper), (b) the achieved margin distribution and the norm of the weight vector that the SVM paper links to the confidence term, and (c) the number of active prototypes / support vectors.\n\nEmpirical map and analysis. Produce a 2D map (representation dial x capacity-control regime) of generalization and of each capacity diagnostic. Then run the controlled comparisons the literature never did:\n1. Hold effective capacity fixed (match VC/margin/weight-norm across cells by tuning regularization strength) and vary representation gamma — does test error still change? A positive result confirms the CBP claim that paradigm matters beyond capacity; a null result vindicates the architecture-agnostic SLT prescription.\n2. Hold representation fixed and vary the capacity-control regime — quantify how much test error tracks the confidence term as predicted by the risk bound.\n3. Variance decomposition (ANOVA) attributing generalization variance to Axis A, Axis B, and their interaction at matched capacity.\n\nThis directly resolves the confound: because representation is a feature-map dial and capacity control is an independently chosen learning principle, the study isolates whether the SV machine's advantage over RBF and CBP's advantage over MLP stem from representation, from capacity control, or from an interaction (e.g., prototype representations may benefit disproportionately from margin control). All components are implementable with the tools in the sources (backprop, dual ridge regression, SVM QP; VC/Cover-capacity and margin measurements), making the map feasible and its conclusions grounded in, and adjudicating between, the provided works."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap arises from a genuine contradiction: two camps (capacity-control vs representational paradigm) explain the same generalization phenomenon differently, and every comparison confounds the two axes (puzzle_contradiction), with a strong 'why does generalization improve' explanation-gap flavor. The construction is a factorial diagnostic benchmark that orthogonalizes representation and capacity control on a shared substrate and decomposes variance (empirical_mapping), leveraging the CBP insight that a circular classifier is a linear classifier on an augmented feature map to unify the paradigms (synthesis_unification). The bottleneck—the confound between representation and capacity control—is precisely identified, hence high bottleneck_specificity. Not superficial stitching since the axes are genuinely orthogonalized on a common substrate."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the paradox between Circular Backpropagation and SVM capacity control.","method":"Test method: define a circular SVM with kernel and derive a VC bound."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation framed as a paradox between Circular Backpropagation and SVM capacity control, suggesting puzzle_contradiction with a bridging flavor. Method derives a VC bound for a kernel-based circular SVM, a formal derivation, secondarily unifying two approaches. Content is thin ('test') and reads as an A+B combination, hence moderate stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Vapnik's SV theory promises validation-free, dimension-free model selection via the radius-margin capacity term (eq. 3.37 of \"The support vector method of function estimation\"), computable from training data alone; dual ridge regression and Zhang's leave-one-out analysis add an exact cheap LOO error equal in expectation to generalization error. So tuning kernel width and C should be principled and cheap. Yet in \"Comparing SVMs with Gaussian kernels to RBF classifiers,\" top USPS accuracy needs hand/grid-tuned width and C plus k-means centers, and the capacity bound is used only to rank a few fixed models, never to search; \"Circular backpropagation\" derives capacity results but tunes by backprop. The paradox: a computable objective meant to automate tuning is unused while grid search and validation splits dominate. Cause: the bound is treated as a per-model number, not a function of hyperparameters, and the cheap-LOO machine (dense ridge) is not the deployed sparse SVM.","method":"Recast model selection as continuous optimization over theta = (Gaussian bandwidths, optionally per-feature, and C). (1) Make the radius-margin bound R(theta) a smooth objective; its two quadratic programs (SVM dual for weight norm, enclosing-sphere program eqs. 3.32-3.36 for radius) have locally stationary multipliers, so by the envelope theorem dR/dtheta reduces to analytic kernel-matrix derivatives over active support vectors, enabling quasi-Newton search. (2) Use dual ridge regression's closed-form exact LOO as a cheap dense surrogate for coarse multistart global search. (3) Two-stage adaptive search: Stage A minimizes ridge LOO from several starts; Stage B refines theta on the deployed sparse SVM via R(theta) gradients, bridging cheap-dense and sparse-expensive machines. (4) Efficiency via Cholesky factorizations with rank-one updates and warm-started path-following QP re-solves. (5) Per-dimension bandwidths make R(theta) minimization perform validation-free feature scaling. Evaluate on USPS-style digits and 2-D benchmarks against grid-search+validation SVMs and k-means RBF, measuring accuracy, model fits, and cost."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a paradox: a computable capacity bound meant to automate tuning is unused while grid search dominates, with a precise diagnosis of the cause (bound treated as per-model number, LOO machine differs from deployed SVM). This is puzzle_contradiction with a resource/cost angle. The core move recasts model selection as continuous optimization over hyperparameters using gradients and multistart search, so optimization_search is primary; the envelope-theorem derivation of analytic gradients supports formal_derivation as secondary. Bottleneck is precisely identified. Not surface stitching despite combining ridge LOO and radius-margin—the bridging of dense-cheap and sparse-expensive machines is substantive."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the SVM CBP paradox.","method":"Test method about adaptive kernel geometry."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('Test motivation'/'Test method') so labels are inferred from context: LS-SVM reformulates SVM via least-squares/equality constraints, a formal reformulation move addressing computational burden. The 'paradox' framing suggests puzzle_contradiction. Low confidence due to stub content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation","method":"test method"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('test motivation'/'test method'), so labeling relies on prior-work context. The LS-SVM lineage reformulates SVM optimization as a set of linear equations (least squares, ridge regression dual), which is a formal reformulation reducing computational burden. Low confidence due to absent content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: paradox between capacity-controlled implicit SVM kernels and capacity-blind explicit circular backpropagation.","method":"Test method: unify explicit circular lift with margin and SRM training."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.62,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation is framed as a paradox/contradiction between capacity-controlled SVM kernels and capacity-blind circular backpropagation, with a bridging flavor. Method unifies the explicit circular lift with margin/SRM training, so synthesis_unification is central with formal_derivation secondary. Combining two existing paradigms edges toward surface stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel machines such as SVMs and dual kernel ridge regression are accurate but have an inference time resource bottleneck, because test cost and memory scale with retained training points. The SVM to RBF hybrid keeps one center per support vector, and k means RBF has no capacity guarantee, so deployment on constrained hardware lacks budget control. The Circular Backpropagation network is a fixed size backprop trainable model with known VC dimension and Cover capacity but has not been used to remove this cost.","method":"Build a compiler that converts a trained kernel machine into a fixed size Circular Backpropagation network. Train a teacher kernel machine and record its soft outputs and support vectors. Use the CBP capacity formulas to choose the smallest number of hidden units meeting a user resource budget, applying Structural Risk Minimization to the compact student. Initialize the circular units as prototypes by clustering the support vectors. Distill by backpropagation to match the teacher outputs. Output an accuracy versus footprint Pareto frontier and a deployable model, evaluated on USPS digits against the SV teacher, dense kernel ridge regression, the SV center RBF hybrid, and k means RBF."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as an inference-time resource bottleneck: test cost and memory scale with retained support vectors, and deployment on constrained hardware lacks budget control. The central move is building a compiler that converts a kernel machine into a fixed-size student network with a resource-budget-driven capacity selection and Pareto frontier, making it an artifact/system deliverable with a strong optimization/search component (budget-aware unit selection via capacity formulas). It combines CBP with kernel-machine distillation (some stitching), but the bottleneck is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel and support-vector machines give top accuracy but their cost scales with data: the SV quadratic program and dual ridge regression need an n-by-n kernel, dual ridge is fully dense, and Vapnik's bound ties model size to the growing number of support vectors. This is a memory, training-time, and inference-latency bottleneck at scale. Circular backpropagation shows one extra input (squared norm of x) cheaply gives RBF-like surfaces in a primal model with explicit capacity bounds, but no listed work fuses this cheap augmentation with closed-form ridge regression and the SV sparsity/SRM principle to make model size and inference cost independent of n.","method":"Budgeted Circular Ridge Machines: an explicit compact feature map trained in the primal so cost never scales with n. Generalize the circular augmentation [x, sqnorm(x)] by adding B prototype features sqnorm(x-c_j), which expand to sqnorm(x)-2 c_j dot x + const, interpolating from one circular unit to a full RBF net with B as an explicit resource knob. Choose B centers cheaply by k-means or SV-guided margin selection. Train by closed-form primal ridge: w=(Phi'Phi+lambda I)^-1 Phi'y with feature dimension m=d+1+B much smaller than n, giving O(n m^2) time, O(m^2) memory, no n-by-n kernel, and O(m) constant-cost prediction. Use the primal/dual ridge equivalence to relate the map to full Gaussian-kernel ridge and set lambda; use circular-unit VC/Cover bounds plus the expected-#SV/n bound via structural risk minimization to pick the smallest adequate B. Evaluate on the USPS digit benchmark and SV regression tasks, plotting accuracy versus model size, memory, training time, and inference FLOPs against full RBF-SVM, the SV/backprop hybrid, and dense kernel ridge regression, testing whether accuracy is preserved while resources stay flat as n grows."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a scaling/memory/latency bottleneck where kernel methods scale with n; that is a resource_bottleneck, with a secondary bridge_opportunity noting that circular backprop augmentation, closed-form ridge, and SV/SRM principles have not been fused. The central move makes kernel-like accuracy work at cost independent of n via an explicit compact feature map (extending scope to large-n regimes), with a synthesis flavor combining circular augmentation and ridge regression. The idea does stitch together identifiable prior components (circular units + dual ridge + SRM budgeting), so surface_stitching is flagged, but the bottleneck is precisely identified (O(n m^2), O(m) prediction), earning high specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The learner families in this corpus (SVMs with Gaussian/polynomial/sigmoid kernels, RBF networks with k-means centers, dual-variable kernel ridge regression, and circular-backpropagation networks that unify surface- and prototype-based schemes) are all point-expansion models that reach comparable, excellent accuracy. The binding constraint is not accuracy but resource cost. Training is dominated by an O(l^2) kernel matrix plus QP or backprop; the comparing-SVMs paper notes the machines are comparable in classification speed and memory yet differences are noticeable in training, but never quantifies this. Deployment cost is fixed by the number of support vectors/prototypes (prediction FLOPs and memory), and the largest hidden cost is model selection: kernel width, C/ridge lambda, and number of units are chosen by exhaustive grid search with full retraining. The corpus already contains cheap single-fit signals plausibly tracking cost and accuracy (Vapnik's E[#SV]/l bound, the closed-form leave-one-out of the dual ridge solution, and the VC/Cover-capacity formulas for circular-backpropagation nets), yet no work maps these diagnostics to measured compute, memory, and deployment cost across the unified family. A practitioner under a training-time, memory, or latency budget therefore cannot pick a method or hyperparameters without brute-force retraining. This is the resource bottleneck left open.","method":"Build an empirical accuracy-versus-resource map of the unified expansion-based family and turn it into a budget-aware, diagnostic-guided selector. First, on a shared suite (USPS digits plus lower-dimensional classification/regression tasks) train a matched hyperparameter sweep of hard/soft-margin SVMs with Gaussian, polynomial and sigmoid kernels, dual/kernel ridge regression, classical RBF-with-k-means, the SV-centers-plus-backprop hybrid, and circular-backpropagation nets. Second, instrument each configuration with resource metrics (training time/FLOPs, peak kernel-matrix memory, model size equal to the number of support-vectors/prototypes which sets prediction cost, and cumulative selection retraining budget) and a held-out error metric. Third, for each single fit also compute cheap grid-free diagnostics: margin, Vapnik's E[#SV]/l bound, the dual-ridge closed-form leave-one-out error, and circular-BP VC-dimension/Cover-capacity. Fourth, empirically quantify how well each cheap diagnostic predicts measured error and each resource cost, and assemble per-family Pareto frontiers of accuracy versus training FLOPs, memory, and prediction cost. Fifth, deliver and validate a selector: given a compute/memory/latency budget, use the fitted diagnostic-to-outcome map to predict the frontier-optimal method and hyperparameters from a few single fits, then measure the model-selection compute saved versus full cross-validated grid search at matched accuracy and report where each family dominates the frontier."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a resource bottleneck (training/memory/latency cost, model-selection retraining burden), with a secondary evidence_gap since prior work never quantifies these tradeoffs. The core move is building an empirical accuracy-versus-resource map with Pareto frontiers and diagnostic-to-outcome mappings (empirical_mapping), with a synthesis element uniting the expansion-based learner families. Bottleneck is precise (O(l^2) kernel matrix, #SV prediction cost, grid-search retraining). Not surface stitching despite the diagnostic reuse—the mapping and selector are the genuine contribution. Notably this diverges from the actual historical LS-SVM paper, which was a formal reformulation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The kernel machines across these works — SVMs for classification/regression, kernel ridge regression in dual variables, and Gaussian-kernel/RBF classifiers — share an unaddressed resource bottleneck: they build the n-by-n Gram matrix (O(n^2) memory, expensive QP) and output f(x)=sum_j alpha_j K(x,x_j)+b whose test-time cost and storage scale with the number of retained basis terms. The RBF-comparison paper notes SV training is an order of magnitude heavier, and this worsens with n. Critically, the amount of computation is uncontrolled: kernel ridge regression is fully dense (all n points appear at test time); SVM sparsity emerges implicitly from data and C, not settable in advance; RBF picks centers by k-means with no guarantee. Vapnik's bound E[error] <= E[#SV]/(n-1) ties sparsity to generalization but only describes it after the fact — it does not let a practitioner fix a compute/memory budget up front and know the resulting risk. No unified formal framework makes the representational budget an explicit, tunable design variable carrying a generalization certificate, which is exactly what deployment under fixed cost, memory, and latency requires.","method":"A formal-derivation framework for budget-constrained kernel expansions. (1) Conceptual distinction: separate the representation budget B (number of training points allowed in the expansion set S, |S|<=B, the sole driver of Gram-submatrix size, QP dimension, storage, and test-time cost) from statistical capacity (margin/coefficient norm, set independently). This taxonomy places existing methods as special cases: kernel ridge regression = B=n; SVM = B chosen implicitly by KKT; k-means-RBF = B fixed heuristically with no certificate. (2) Objective: minimize (1/n) sum_i phi(y_i f(x_i)) + lambda ||f||^2 over f(x)=sum_{j in S} alpha_j K(x,x_j)+b subject to |S|<=B, where phi is any convex surrogate (hinge, epsilon-insensitive, or squared loss); B is set by the user's compute/memory budget. (3) Theorem (budget compression bound): any solution is a compression scheme of size <=B, fully determined by the B chosen points. Generalizing Vapnik's leave-one-out argument behind E[#SV]/(n-1) — removing non-expansion points leaves the solution unchanged and each held-out error is charged to an expansion point — derive an SRM-style bound E[error] <= (B + capacity/margin term)/(n-B), monotone increasing in B. Fixing B a priori thus fixes an upper bound on expected test error, giving the missing design lever linking compute budget to accuracy; instantiate the capacity term using VC/Cover-capacity results from the circular-backpropagation unification. (4) Derived algorithm: since the bound is monotone in B, a forward-selection procedure adds one basis point at a time, each step picking the point most decreasing regularized empirical risk and re-solving only a small subproblem, replacing the O(n^2)-memory full QP with B small problems (about O(nB^2) time, O(nB) memory); every added point is a valid compression-set element, so the step-3 bound holds at each budget, yielding an anytime accuracy/cost curve with a certificate at every point. (5) Validation: on USPS digits and toy sets from the RBF-comparison and SLT works, check that the bound tracks test error as B varies, that at matched B the budgeted expansion beats k-means-RBF and full kernel ridge regression at a fraction of memory/test cost, and that it recovers SVM accuracy once B reaches the empirical support-vector count — confirming each classical method as a point on the derived budget curve."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is framed around a shared resource bottleneck (O(n^2) memory/QP, uncontrolled test-time cost) with a precise limiting factor: representation budget is not a tunable design variable with a generalization certificate. Secondary explanation_gap since it addresses why sparsity ties to generalization only after the fact. The central move is a formal-derivation framework: a conceptual distinction between budget and capacity, a theorem/bound generalizing Vapnik's argument, and a derived algorithm. It also unifies existing methods (KRR, SVM, RBF) as special cases, hence synthesis_unification secondary. Bottleneck is precisely identified; not superficial stitching since the unification is grounded in a derived bound."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Resource bottleneck. The kernel/support-vector family that dominates these sources delivers strong, theoretically justified accuracy (Vapnik, \"The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory\"; \"The Support Vector Method of Function Estimation\"; Schölkopf et al. comparing SVMs to RBF classifiers), but all of the concrete estimators here pay a severe and coupled cost in compute, memory, and deployment:\n\n1. SVM training is a quadratic program over the full n-point kernel matrix. The comparison paper explicitly notes the optimization \"requires us to work with potentially large matrices,\" forcing chunked processing and special large-scale QP solvers — i.e., training does not scale gracefully in n.\n2. Kernel ridge regression in dual variables (the \"Ridge regression learning algorithm in dual variables\" source) solves (K+λI)α=y, an O(n^3) dense linear system with an O(n^2) matrix, and — unlike the SVM — produces no sparsity: every training point is a basis center, so both memory and test-time cost grow with the full training set.\n3. Test-time cost is a first-class bottleneck: the SVM decision rule evaluates the kernel between a test point and every support vector; the paper resorts to a post-hoc \"reduced set\" approximation to make prediction affordable.\n4. The classical RBF alternative sidesteps QP cost by choosing centers with task-agnostic k-means clustering, but this spends the (fixed) center budget without regard to the classification/regression risk, so accuracy suffers.\n\nCrucially, statistical learning theory already tells us the resource we should be economizing on is directly tied to generalization: Theorem 5.2 bounds expected test error by E[#support vectors]/(l−1). So a model that uses fewer, better-chosen basis points is simultaneously cheaper to train, cheaper to store, cheaper to evaluate, AND expected to generalize at least as well. Yet none of the provided methods actually optimizes the model under an explicit compute/memory budget: SVM sparsity is an uncontrolled by-product of the QP, dual ridge regression has no sparsity at all, and RBF center selection is decoupled from the task. This leaves open a resource-allocation gap: how to build a kernel model that hits a target accuracy at a chosen, controllable train-time, memory, and test-time cost.","method":"Budget-constrained, risk-guided greedy center selection for sparse kernel ridge regression (a \"screen-and-allocate\" optimization procedure). The base learner is dual-variable ridge regression, but the solution is restricted to an actively grown working set S of m ≪ n selected basis points (columns of K), turning the O(n^3) dense solve into a cheap reduced problem.\n\nCore loop (active/adaptive design + resource allocation):\n1. Reduced solve. For the current working set S, fit the Nyström-style reduced kernel ridge model using only columns K_S, solving the small m×m regularized normal system rather than the full n×n system. Cost per fit is O(m^2 n) instead of O(n^3).\n2. Incremental updates (leverage \"Matrix Computations\" and \"Practical Methods of Optimization\" toolboxes). When a candidate point is added, update the factorization by a rank-one Cholesky/QR update instead of refactoring from scratch, so evaluating each candidate is cheap and the whole sweep stays near-linear in n.\n3. Screening/acquisition. Rank remaining points by a cost-normalized marginal-gain criterion: the reduction in the regularized dual objective (equivalently the residual/leverage score, computable in closed form from the current factorization) per unit of added compute. This is the search/optimization contribution — a greedy submatrix (column-subset) selection that directly targets the objective, unlike task-agnostic k-means center placement.\n4. Bound-aware stopping = compute allocation. Because #basis-points plays the role of #support-vectors in the generalization bound (Theorem 5.2), track a validation/PRESS-style leave-one-out estimate (obtainable in closed form for ridge regression) as m grows and stop when the marginal risk reduction per added FLOP/memory unit falls below a user-set threshold, or when the explicit budget (max m, max memory, max test-time kernel evaluations) is exhausted. This makes train cost, model size, and inference cost tunable dials rather than by-products.\n\nTwo efficiency accelerators grounded in the sources:\n- Circular-backpropagation feature augmentation: for Gaussian/RBF-type kernels, append the squared-norm feature (the single extra input of the CBP model) so a linear-in-augmented-features model cheaply approximates hyperspherical \"bumps,\" reducing the number of explicit kernel evaluations per candidate and per test point.\n- Reduced-set-by-construction: since selection is greedy and budgeted, the resulting model is already a small expansion, eliminating the need for a separate post-hoc reduced-set approximation of the decision rule.\n\nEvaluation. On the USPS handwritten-digit benchmark used by the comparison paper (and toy/regression tasks from the SV function-estimation chapter), compare against (a) full-QP SVM, (b) dense dual ridge regression, and (c) k-means-center RBF, plotting accuracy versus explicit budgets (training time, peak memory, test-time kernel evaluations). Success = matching SVM/kernel-ridge accuracy while using far fewer basis points and asymptotically lower train/memory/inference cost, with the achieved sparsity tracking the theoretical error bound. This addresses the resource bottleneck by turning kernel model construction into an explicit, budget-aware optimization over which few training points to spend compute on."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.88,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed around the coupled compute/memory/test-time cost of kernel/SVM methods (resource_bottleneck), with a precise bottleneck: O(n^3) dense solves, lack of sparsity, and test-time kernel evaluations tied to a generalization bound. The core move is a budget-constrained, risk-guided greedy column-subset selection with cost-normalized acquisition and bound-aware stopping — an optimization/search and resource-allocation paradigm. Though it draws on several sources (matrix updates, CBP features, ridge regression, SLT bounds), the central contribution is the adaptive selection/allocation procedure rather than mere combination, so surface stitching is low."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Resource-bottleneck gap. The sources show kernel machines grounded in statistical learning theory generalize excellently: the SV method minimizes an upper bound on test error (Vapnik works), and Scholkopf/Sung/Burges show a Gaussian-kernel SVM beats a k-means+backprop RBF net on USPS digits. But adoption is cost-limited, not accuracy-limited. SVM training solves a constrained QP; the comparison paper concedes it needs large matrices, chunked processing, and special algorithms for many support vectors, with O(n^2) memory and roughly O(n^3) time. The dual ridge regression paper gives a closed-form kernel predictor but inverts the full n-by-n kernel matrix and is fully dense, so all n points are stored and evaluated at test time. Circular backprop nets train cheaply but lack margin/VC capacity control. No method keeps the margin guarantees while running under tight compute/memory budgets in the large-n regime where exact QP and full inversion are infeasible.","method":"Budgeted Iteratively-Reweighted Ridge Support Vector learning: relax the SVM QP into a few cheap dual ridge-regression solves and extend dual ridge to be sparse, budgeted, and robust. (1) Approximate the hinge and epsilon-insensitive losses by iteratively reweighted quadratic losses; each iteration solves an SPD dual ridge system (K+lambda W^-1)alpha=y via conjugate gradient, reusing the dual-ridge machinery with weights that up-weight margin violators. (2) Replace the full kernel matrix with an incomplete-Cholesky/Nystrom low-rank factorization on a working set of m<<n basis points, cutting memory to O(nm) and time to O(nm^2). (3) Grow the budget greedily, adding the basis point that most reduces the SV/margin generalization bound and pruning points whose coefficients vanish, yielding a sparse predictor with far fewer than n basis vectors. (4) The same solver covers classification, regression, and Huber estimation as reweighting schedules and tolerates label noise. Evaluate on the USPS protocol plus a large/noisy regime, reporting accuracy, training time, memory, and basis-vector count versus exact QP-SVM, full dual ridge, and circular-backprop/RBF baselines as functions of m and n; target near-SVM accuracy and sparsity at a fraction of the cost where exact methods are infeasible, using the SRM bound as both selection criterion and generalization certificate."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.62,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a cost/compute-memory bottleneck (O(n^2) memory, O(n^3) time) preventing adoption despite good accuracy, which is resource_bottleneck; the tension between margin guarantees and tight budgets carries a puzzle/tradeoff flavor. The core method relaxes the SVM QP into cheap ridge solves and extends dual ridge to sparse/budgeted/robust regimes (relax_extend_scope), with strong optimization_search elements (low-rank factorization, greedy budget growth, CG). Some stitching of ridge regression + SVM + Nystrom, but integrated around a specific bottleneck. Bottleneck is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Resource bottleneck. The strongest predictors here are kernel machines whose cost is dominated by scarce compute and memory. Kernel ridge regression in dual variables has a clean closed-form rule but requires inverting the n-by-n matrix (K+lambda*I): O(n^2) memory, O(n^3) time, and its solution is fully dense, so test cost scales with the entire training set. SVMs are sparse and enjoy the E[number of support vectors]/(l-1) generalization bound, but the support-vector count is set by the QP, uncontrollable in advance, and grows with noise (Vapnik prefers the epsilon-insensitive loss precisely because it uses fewer support vectors than Huber); training is a large QP and C, epsilon, and kernel-width are brittle. Classical RBF classifiers choose centers by unsupervised k-means, ignoring labels and underperforming SVMs on USPS digits. Circular backpropagation nets give RBF-like, capacity-bounded predictors at cheap MLP cost but, as a backprop heuristic, offer no explicit resource budget or robustness guarantee. In resource-limited deployment (embedded or real-time inference, large or streaming n, tight memory), none of these lets a practitioner fix a hard budget on model size and training cost while staying reliable. This matters because deployment cost is dominated by test-time kernel evaluations and training kernel-matrix memory, exactly what dense KRR and data-dependent SVM sparsity leave uncontrolled.","method":"Robustification. Build a Budgeted Robust Kernel Machine whose complexity is capped a priori by a user-set budget B of kernel centers, converting an uncontrolled resource cost into a fixed one while adding mechanisms that reduce known failure modes. First, capacity-guided robust center selection: rather than unsupervised clustering or an unbounded QP support set, greedily add centers up to B, each chosen to most reduce an SRM-style upper bound equal to robust empirical risk plus a capacity penalty, using the margin and capacity terms (R^2 times squared weight norm, and the number-of-expansion-terms bound) from statistical learning theory; this ties the compact model to a generalization guarantee and guards against overfitting. Second, robust loss: fit coefficients with a Huber or epsilon-insensitive loss so outliers and label noise are downweighted. Third, numerically stable reduced solve: with centers fixed, solve only a B-by-B ridge-regularized least-squares system via Cholesky or QR, removing the ill-conditioning brittleness of inverting the full (K+lambda*I) and cutting training to O(n*B^2) time, O(n*B) memory, and test cost to O(B). Fourth, subsample ensembling: average several budgeted predictors trained on bootstrap subsamples to reduce variance from greedy selection and yield a predictive-disagreement uncertainty estimate that flags unreliable inputs. Evaluation: on USPS digits and standard regression sets, plot accuracy versus resource budget (test-time kernel evaluations, training memory) against full KRR, Gaussian-kernel SVM, k-means RBF, and circular backpropagation, then stress-test robustness by injecting label noise and outliers and perturbing kernel-width and regularization. Success means matching SVM and KRR accuracy at an order-of-magnitude smaller fixed model size, with markedly smaller accuracy loss under noise and hyperparameter misspecification."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The stated gap is that dense KRR and data-dependent SVM sparsity leave resource cost (memory, compute, test-time kernel evals) uncontrolled — a clear resource_bottleneck, with secondary failure_risk_gap around noise/hyperparameter brittleness. The construction caps complexity a priori with a budget B and adds robust loss and stable solves to reduce failure modes (robustification), with greedy budgeted center selection contributing an optimization_search flavor. The method assembles several known components (greedy selection, Huber loss, reduced solve, ensembling), giving moderate stitching, but the bottleneck is precisely identified (dense inversion cost, uncontrolled support-vector count)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Kernel machines grounded in statistical learning theory (Gaussian-kernel SVM, dual kernel ridge regression) give top accuracy but are resource-bound: SVM training solves a QP, dual ridge inverts an n-by-n kernel matrix, both dense so all points are retained, and tuning kernel width and C needs repeated re-solves; deployment stores many support vectors. Circular backpropagation shows that adding one explicit squared-norm coordinate turns hyperplanes into hyperspheres, unifying surface-based and prototype-based models cheaply with ordinary backprop, closed-form VC dimension and Cover capacity, and provable equivalence to Gaussian RBF networks. Thus RBF-like power is available through explicit low-dimensional features rather than costly implicit kernels. These literatures are unreconciled: circular backprop lacks margin and SRM selection, and SVM/kernel-ridge practice ignores cheap explicit features. No prior work offers a low-cost yet principled machine bridging them.","method":"Build a capacity-ordered feature ladder of explicit finite-dimensional maps generalizing the circular unit: level 0 is x, level 1 is x plus the squared norm (hyperspheres), higher levels add block-wise or randomized squared-norm and low-order product terms that per the circular-backprop proof approach a Gaussian-RBF machine, making linear SVM, RBF-SVM, and kernel ridge endpoints of one continuum. At each level of explicit dimension m, fit a regularized linear model (ridge closed-form or hinge margin) in the primal at cost linear in n via an m-by-m solve, avoiding the n-by-n kernel matrix and QP; when m exceeds n, use the Woodbury primal-dual identity (the same equivalence linking dual ridge to kernel ridge) to solve in the dual only when cheaper, yielding a compact weight vector instead of stored support vectors. Select level and regularization by analytic structural risk minimization using the closed-form VC dimension and Cover capacity per level, minimizing empirical risk plus the capacity term in one cheap sweep, replacing grid search over kernel width and C. Validate on USPS digits against Gaussian-kernel SVM, k-means RBF, and the hybrid, comparing accuracy, training time, peak memory, test-time model size and latency, and agreement of the SRM-selected model with the best cross-validated kernel model."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.68,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation frames a precise resource bottleneck (QP/n-by-n inversion, stored support vectors, grid search over kernel/C) while also explicitly noting two unreconciled literatures (circular backprop and SVM/kernel-ridge). The construction is a synthesis: it unifies surface-based and prototype-based/RBF models into a single capacity-ordered explicit-feature continuum with SRM selection, reconciling the two lines of work. Secondary relax_extend_scope reflects making kernel power available through cheaper explicit features. Bottleneck is very specifically articulated; not superficial A+B since the bridge is grounded in a provable equivalence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Corpus kernel/SVM results assume fixed a-priori kernels, batch offline training on small stationary benchmarks, and offline cross-validation, mismatching streaming, drifting, resource-bounded deployment.","method":"A self-tuning online kernel-ridge-regression engine that auto-selects kernel and regularization via a closed-form leave-one-out surrogate and keeps a budgeted basis-vector dictionary with rank-one updates."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"Motivation frames prior kernel/SVM work as assuming fixed kernels, batch offline training on stationary benchmarks—a scope mismatch to streaming, drifting, resource-bounded settings; secondary resource bottleneck via budgeted dictionary. Method extends kernel-ridge regression to online, self-tuning, budgeted operation (relax/extend scope), with closed-form LOO surrogate for kernel/regularization selection (optimization_search). Specific mechanism identified (rank-one updates, budget)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap between two neighboring lines. Ridella et al. (1997) circular backpropagation (CBP) shows that augmenting input x with one isotropic quadratic feature (the squared norm of x) gives paradigm plasticity: a linear machine interpolates between a surface-based classifier (a hyperplane) and a prototype-based one (a hypersphere or RBF bump), chosen by the data. But this lived only in a non-convex backprop-trained MLP with no operational capacity control (its VC and Cover results are post-hoc), local minima, and narrow validation. Conversely, the support-vector and statistical-learning-theory line (Vapnik 1995/1998; Scholkopf et al. 1997) supplies the missing capacity control through margin maximization and the radius-margin bound, and automatically places RBF centers minimizing a bound on test error, but the paradigm is frozen a priori in the kernel choice, a Gaussian kernel injects a large capacity increment, and its flagship validation is one narrow benchmark (USPS digits). Kernel ridge regression in dual variables (1998) shares the fixed-kernel limitation. Thus plasticity exists only without capacity control and capacity control only without plasticity; no method makes the surface-versus-prototype paradigm itself an object of convex, capacity-controlled model selection, and none is validated across diverse regimes. This matters because the appropriate paradigm and amount of sphericalness are unknown a priori: Gaussian kernels overshoot capacity while linear kernels underfit.","method":"Propose the Support Vector Circular Machine (SVCM), moving CBP plasticity augmentation into the convex SRM framework and making the paradigm the object of structural risk minimization. One, a capacity ladder: augment x with a single extra coordinate equal to the square root of lambda times the squared norm of x (equivalently a circular kernel equal to the dot product of x and z plus lambda times the product of their squared norms) and train a standard soft-margin SVM. Small lambda recovers the maximal-margin hyperplane; larger lambda gives hyperspherical prototype surfaces, adding only one feature dimension, a small tunable increment between a linear SVM and a full quadratic or Gaussian SVM. Two, SRM over the paradigm continuum: index a nested structure by lambda and pick lambda minimizing the radius-margin bound (enclosing-sphere radius squared times squared weight norm), the radius from the small enclosing-sphere QP in the SV function-estimation chapter and the weight norm from the SVM dual. Convexity gives a unique global solution per lambda, so selection walks a well-defined capacity ladder without local minima, turning CBP post-hoc VC analysis into an operational criterion. Three, a localized extension adding several circular features at candidate centers greedily while the bound improves, yielding an explicit sequence from one hyperplane to a full Gaussian-RBF SVM. Four, a regression variant applying the same augmentation to SV regression and dual-variable ridge regression. Five, broad validation across CBP Gaussian-mixture and vowel tasks, USPS digits, and added UCI benchmarks, reporting accuracy, support-vector count, capacity, and selected lambda. Feasibility: augmentation is a one-line change to any SVM or kernel-ridge solver."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a scope mismatch: CBP plasticity exists without capacity control and SVM capacity control exists without paradigm plasticity, with disconnected literatures suggesting a bridge. The core move fuses these two lines by embedding CBP's circular augmentation into the convex SRM/radius-margin framework, making the paradigm an object of model selection (synthesis_unification), while also extending scope via a lambda ladder and regression variants. The circular-kernel construction is a principled unification rather than superficial stitching, and the bottleneck (paradigm frozen a priori vs. no operational capacity control) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap. SVM theory rests on two strong claims: (1) its generalization bounds are essentially dimension-independent — the support-vector-count bound E[P(error)] <= E[#SV]/(l-1) and the radius-margin functional R^2*|w|^2 (Eq. 3.37 in \"The support vector method of function estimation\"; Sec. 5.6/5.7 in \"The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory\"), said to depend \"neither on the dimensionality of the space, nor on the norm of the coefficients\"; and (2) minimizing these bounds soundly selects among models and kernels (\"the model that minimizes the estimate (3.37) is selecting the best SV machine\"). But the supporting evidence lives in a narrow regime: separable/near-separable pattern recognition, essentially one benchmark (USPS digits), one kernel family (Gaussian), classification only. The influential verdict that \"the SV machine achieves the highest recognition accuracy\" (Scholkopf et al. vs RBF classifiers) comes from that same single dataset and kernel. Competing machines cited by these works — dual-variable kernel ridge regression, classical k-means+backprop RBF nets, and circular-backpropagation nets with known VC/Cover-capacity properties — are each evaluated under different losses, assumptions, and datasets, leaving no common comparison ground. This is a scope mismatch: theory and practice were validated only at flattering boundary conditions (low Bayes error, one modality, one kernel), yet practitioners transfer these bounds and single-benchmark verdicts to noisy, high-overlap, varying-dimensional, and regression settings where validity is untested. It matters because the practical appeal of SVMs — automatic capacity control and bound-based kernel selection without cross-validation — hinges on whether the bounds track test error outside the demonstrated regime.","method":"Build an empirical-mapping benchmark that tests where SVM generalization bounds and single-dataset comparative verdicts actually transfer. (1) Regime grid: controlled synthetic data generators sweeping the conditions prior work held fixed — input dimensionality, training-set size l, Bayes error/class overlap (separable to heavy noise), intrinsic vs ambient dimensionality, and task type (classification and regression) — plus real USPS digits as an anchor. (2) Common-footing models: per configuration, with matched preprocessing and tuned hyperparameters, train an SVM under several kernel families (Gaussian, polynomial, sigmoid), dual-variable kernel ridge regression, a classical RBF net (k-means centers + pseudoinverse/backprop), and a circular-backpropagation net, reusing the QP/optimization and matrix routines in the sources. (3) Instrument the bounds: for each fitted SVM compute the radius-margin estimate R^2*|w|^2 via the smallest-enclosing-sphere QP (Eqs. 3.33-3.36), the support-vector-count ratio bound E[#SV]/(l-1), and the SRM/VC estimate, alongside true held-out test error and cross-validation error. (4) Diagnostics along each regime axis: bound tightness (bound/true-error ratio), rank correlation between each bound and true test error as kernel hyperparameters vary, and selection regret (excess test error from choosing kernel and width/degree by minimizing the bound vs by cross-validation), directly testing the claim that bound minimization selects the best machine; also map when SVM's accuracy edge over kernel ridge regression, RBF, and circular-BP actually appears. (5) Deliverable: an empirical validity map over regime space showing where bound-based capacity control and kernel selection are reliable, where they degrade (hypothesized: high Bayes error, small l, regression, non-Gaussian kernels), and where the reported SVM-vs-RBF ranking reverses — giving regime-specific guidance on when to trust the bounds versus fall back to cross-validation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as SVM theory and comparative verdicts validated only under narrow, flattering boundary conditions (separable data, one dataset, one kernel), classic scope_mismatch; secondary is evidence_gap since it also concerns lack of common comparison ground. The method builds a systematic benchmark/regime grid instrumenting bounds against true error to map where they transfer — empirical_mapping. Specific bottleneck (bound-tracking outside demonstrated regime) is clearly identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation","method":"test method"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal fields are placeholder text ('test motivation'/'test method'), providing no substantive content. Inference is based only on prior-work context, which points to reformulating SVM classifiers via least-squares/ridge regression in dual variables, suggesting a computational efficiency motivation and a formal derivation move, but confidence is low given absent proposal text."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap. The kernel/large-margin methods represented in these sources are all justified by generalization theory but committed, in practice, to a single, hand-fixed model structure. Vapnik's SV method and Structural Risk Minimization (the-support-vector-method-of-function-estimation-1998, the-nature-of-statistical-learning-theory-1995) index capacity by a single scalar chosen along a predetermined nested chain, and the \"SV algorithm automatically determines centers/weights minimizing an upper bound\" only *after* the kernel family, kernel width, and the regularization/C are fixed by the user. The empirical comparison (comparing-support-vector-machines-with-gaussian-kernels-to-r) uses one global Gaussian width for all centers and contrasts SV-selected centers with k-means centers, again holding the kernel scale fixed. Circular backpropagation (circular-backpropagation-networks-for-classification-1997) introduces a single global radial term that interpolates linear and spherical decision surfaces, but that interpolation is a fixed architectural choice, not something adapted per problem. Kernel ridge regression in the dual (ridge-regression-learning-algorithm-in-dual-variables-1998) and the leave-one-out risk bounds for kernel formulations (statistical-learning-theory-1998) give closed-form solutions and computable error bounds, yet these bounds are used *descriptively* to justify a fixed machine rather than *prescriptively* to choose its structure. The shared, unrealistic assumption is that one global kernel scale, one regularization level, and one geometry (linear vs. radial) suffice — a poor fit for heterogeneous, multi-scale, mixed-feature real data. Consequently hyperparameters are set by expensive grid search or clustering heuristics that neither scale nor exploit the very bounds that motivate the methods. This matters because model-selection choices dominate real accuracy, and the gap between \"bounds that justify\" and \"bounds that select\" leaves substantial room for a principled, adaptive alternative.","method":"Turn the generalization bound itself into the objective of an efficient adaptive search over a richer, heterogeneous model structure — replacing grid search / clustering with bound-driven optimization. (1) Parameterize the structure with continuous knobs: an anisotropic/multi-scale kernel K(x,x') = exp(-Σ_d θ_d (x_d - x'_d)^2) with per-feature (or per-group) scales θ_d, a convex-combination weight vector over a small dictionary of base kernels, a circular-backpropagation-style coefficient α that continuously blends linear and radial (||x||^2-augmented) geometry, and the regularization λ (equivalently C). (2) For fixed structure, solve the machine in the dual closed form (kernel ridge regression: coefficients = (K+λI)^{-1}y; or the SVM dual), which crucially lets the leave-one-out residuals be read off from the diagonal of (K+λI)^{-1} without refitting. (3) Objective: a smoothed leave-one-out generalization bound — the LOO squared-error/margin form for regression and the convex-loss LOO risk bound of statistical-learning-theory-1998 for classification — evaluated on the dual solution. (4) Optimize all continuous knobs {θ_d, kernel weights, α, λ} by gradient descent, computing analytic gradients through the dual solution using standard matrix-derivative identities for the inverse, with Cholesky/eigen updates and iterative refinement from matrix-computations-1989 for stability. (5) Search/efficiency layer to beat grid search and to scale: (a) warm-start the dual re-solves along a regularization path; (b) use low-rank / incomplete-Cholesky (Nyström) approximations of K so each LOO-bound and gradient evaluation is cheap; (c) an active, greedy forward-backward screening that adds the candidate center/support vector whose inclusion most reduces the bound and prunes those with negligible dual weight, yielding a sparse machine whose support set is chosen by the bound rather than by clustering; (d) block-coordinate alternation between continuous-hyperparameter steps and discrete support-set updates. (6) Evaluation: on USPS handwritten digits (matching comparing-support-vector-machines-with-gaussian-kernels-to-r) and on datasets with deliberately mixed feature scales, compare against grid-searched fixed-width SVM, k-means-center RBF, and circular backpropagation, measuring test error, number of support vectors/centers, and total training+selection cost. The method directly addresses the scope mismatch by (i) letting kernel scale, geometry, and regularization adapt per feature/scale instead of globally, and (ii) making the generalization bound the search criterion, converting SRM from a one-dimensional fixed chain into an adaptive, resource-aware optimization over the model's structure."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames a scope-mismatch gap: prior kernel methods assume a single global kernel scale, regularization, and geometry, unrealistic for heterogeneous multi-scale data. Secondary resource_bottleneck arises from grid-search costs that don't scale. The method's central move is turning the generalization bound into an objective for gradient-based/greedy search over continuous structural knobs, plus efficiency layers (low-rank, warm-start, screening) — squarely optimization_search. Secondary relax_extend_scope since it makes SRM adaptive per-feature. Bottleneck is precisely identified: bounds used descriptively vs prescriptively. Components combine known pieces but into a coherent bound-driven optimization rather than superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Support-vector regression (Vapnik, \"The Support Vector Method of Function Estimation,\" 1998; \"The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory,\" 1995) fits real-valued functions with an epsilon-insensitive loss using a SINGLE globally fixed tube width epsilon chosen a priori, justified via Huber's minimax theory that assumes ONE homogeneous symmetric noise density everywhere. The least-squares and kernel-ridge baselines (quadratic loss; \"Ridge regression learning algorithm in dual variables,\" 1998; RBF baselines in \"Comparing SVMs with Gaussian kernels to RBF classifiers,\" 1997) assume even more strongly additive zero-mean constant-variance (homoscedastic) noise. This is a narrow, unrealistic boundary condition: in real regression, signal-processing, and time-series data the noise scale varies across the input domain (heteroscedasticity). Under a single global epsilon the tube is simultaneously too narrow in noisy regions (fits noise, destroys sparsity, spawns spurious support vectors) and too wide in clean regions (discards accurate data, biases the fit). None of the provided sources treats input-dependent noise; epsilon and the loss remain global constants and model selection is just choosing that one number. This leaves a concrete opening to relax the homoscedastic fixed-tube assumption so the well-founded SV/kernel machinery still works under spatially varying noise.","method":"Extend SVR from a single global epsilon to a locally adaptive data-estimated tube epsilon(x), turning the Huber/Vapnik noise-matching argument from global to pointwise while preserving convexity, kernelization, and sparsity. Feasibility rests on existing structure: in the primal (Eq. 3.45-3.46) epsilon already appears per constraint, and in the dual (Eq. 3.51) only through the linear term minus the sum of epsilon times (a_i + a_i-star). Replacing scalar epsilon with per-example epsilon_i changes this term to a per-point weighting, leaving the box constraints 0 to C and the quadratic form unchanged, so it remains a convex QP of the same size solvable with the same optimizers and Mercer kernels. Iterative EM-like procedure: (1) fit a standard small-epsilon SVR or kernel-ridge model and compute residuals r_i; (2) estimate a smooth local noise scale sigma(x) by regressing residual magnitudes or robust MAD on x with a second kernel smoother, yielding a nonparametric heteroscedastic noise map with no parametric noise form assumed; (3) set epsilon_i proportional to sigma(x_i) and optionally the penalty C_i inversely proportional to sigma, giving wide sparse tubes where noisy and tight tubes where clean; (4) re-solve the modified convex QP, recompute residuals, and iterate to a fixed point. Extensions in the same convex frame: asymmetric tubes for local skew/bias, a locally adaptive Huber transition point c(x), and a heteroscedastic nu-SVR controlling the local out-of-tube fraction. Evaluate on synthetic functions with controlled input-varying variance (sinc/Doppler) and real regression/time-series tasks against global-epsilon SVR, kernel ridge regression, and RBF baselines, measuring predictive risk, sparsity, calibration of the recovered tube to true sigma(x), and robustness across noise regimes. Since the method reduces exactly to standard SVR when sigma(x) is constant, it strictly generalizes prior work: matching it in the homoscedastic regime and dominating under realistic heteroscedastic noise. The hypothesis class of norm-bounded kernel expansions is unchanged, so structural-risk-minimization capacity bounds transfer with epsilon replaced by its sample average, only the empirical-risk tube being localized."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior SVR/kernel-ridge relying on a narrow homoscedastic fixed-tube assumption unrealistic for real heteroscedastic data (scope_mismatch), with attendant brittleness/spurious-SV failure (failure_risk_gap). The core move relaxes the global-epsilon assumption to input-dependent epsilon(x) preserving convexity/kernelization/SRM bounds, which is relax_extend_scope; the formal preservation of the convex QP and transfer of capacity bounds gives a formal_derivation secondary. The bottleneck (single global epsilon appearing per-constraint in primal, replaceable pointwise) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior kernel function-estimation work relies on narrow noise assumptions. Vapnik's SV method of function estimation (1998) uses an epsilon-insensitive loss with a single global tube width epsilon and penalty C, and its loss-choice justification requires homoscedastic normal noise (quadratic loss), symmetric noise (least-modulus loss), or a normal+symmetric mixture with fixed known contamination (Huber loss). Real noise is heteroscedastic, asymmetric, heavy-tailed, and of unknown scale, so a global epsilon is too wide in clean regions and too narrow in noisy ones, the estimator breaks under high-leverage outliers, and its predictive intervals are miscalibrated. Companion works share this: the RBF/SVM comparison (Scholkopf 1997) fixes kernel width heuristically, and dual ridge regression (Saunders 1998) uses a global L2 loss. This scope mismatch degrades accuracy, robustness, and calibration.","method":"Adaptive-Tube Robust Support Vector Regression. (1) Fit dual SV regression or dual kernel ridge regression to get residuals via kernel evaluations. (2) Fit a second kernel model to residual magnitudes for a spatially varying noise scale sigma(x), and to signed residuals for a local asymmetry index, distribution-free with no symmetry assumption. (3) Refit with per-example insensitivity epsilon_i = kappa*sigma(x_i) so the tube follows local noise, plus separate upper/lower slack penalties scaled to local skew, retaining the linear Huber tail but with a locally learned transition point replacing the assumed contamination proportion; the dual QP keeps Vapnik's structure with index-dependent box constraints and stays convex. (4) Alternate steps 2-3 EM-style until stable, combining outlier down-weighting with tube shrinkage to reduce breakdown. (5) Calibrate kappa on held-out data for distribution-free predictive bands at target coverage, selecting kernel width and base penalty by structural risk minimization. Evaluate against fixed-epsilon SVR, kernel ridge, and RBF networks on synthetic heteroscedastic/asymmetric/heavy-tailed data with injected outliers and on real benchmarks, reporting error, support-vector count, breakdown, and interval coverage; extend to classification label noise via region- and class-dependent C."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames prior kernel regression as relying on narrow noise assumptions (homoscedastic/symmetric/known-contamination) that fail under real heteroscedastic, asymmetric, heavy-tailed noise — a clear scope_mismatch, with a secondary failure_risk_gap (breakdown, miscalibration). The method extends SVR to weaker/broader noise conditions via per-example adaptive tubes (relax_extend_scope), with robustification (outlier down-weighting, breakdown reduction, calibrated intervals) secondary. The precise bottleneck (global epsilon too wide in clean regions/narrow in noisy) is well-identified, so bottleneck_specificity is high. Not surface stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"least-squares-support-vector-machine-classifiers-1999","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two mature but disconnected literatures address nonlinear classification. Kernel/statistical-learning machines (Vapnik's Nature of Statistical Learning Theory and Support Vector Method of Function Estimation; Scholkopf et al.'s SVM-vs-RBF study; ridge-regression-in-dual-variables and regularization networks) give convex, margin-maximizing dual/kernel solutions with structural-risk-minimization (SRM) guarantees. Neural mapping networks, notably the Circular Backpropagation (CBP) network of Ridella et al., give a data-adaptive machine with paradigm plasticity that interpolates between a surface-based representation (hyperplane/MLP) and a prototype-based one (hypersphere/RBF), with VC-dimension and Cover-capacity analysis. Scope mismatch: SVM/kernel practice assumes the representational geometry is fixed a priori. The user commits to one kernel, hence one paradigm (linear/polynomial = surface, Gaussian = prototype), before seeing data, and SRM bounds hold only for that pre-chosen family. A wrong paradigm choice hurts accuracy and interpretability, and cross-validating unrelated kernels gives no principled complexity ordering. CBP adapts the paradigm but only via backpropagation, forfeiting convexity, the kernel/dual trick, margin maximization, and SRM guarantees. Neither literature offers a single machine that adapts the surface-vs-prototype paradigm from data while keeping kernel machines' convex, SRM-grounded guarantees.","method":"Unify the literatures by noting that CBP's paradigm plasticity is exactly a feature map, liftable into the SVM/kernel-ridge framework. CBP augments x with the squared norm, so a linear discriminant of the form w.x + b*sqnorm(x) + w0 gives hyperplanes when b vanishes and hyperspheres otherwise, an explicit Mercer feature map, i.e. a circular kernel. Step 1: define a one-parameter Mercer kernel family interpolating surface-to-prototype, K_beta(x,y) = (x.y + c) + beta*sqnorm(x)*sqnorm(y), connected at its upper end to the Gaussian RBF (the prototype extreme in the SVM-vs-RBF paper), yielding a nested ladder linear, circular, RBF; beta is the SVM analogue of CBP's circular coefficient. Step 2: train by convex optimization, solving the standard SVM quadratic program (and, for regression, ridge regression in dual variables) with K_beta, inheriting the global optimum, support-vector sparsity, and automatic center selection while realizing CBP's adaptive hyperplane/hypersphere surfaces. Step 3: reconcile the two capacity analyses by combining CBP's VC-dimension and Cover-capacity results with SVM margin bounds to show how beta and the margin jointly control capacity; since varying beta traces genuinely nested function classes, select beta and the regularization constant C by SRM (minimizing the guaranteed-risk bound) rather than blind kernel-shopping cross-validation, restoring generalization guarantees to the adaptive machine. Step 4: validate on USPS handwritten digits (used in the SVM-vs-RBF study) and synthetic surface- vs prototype-structured problems, comparing the unified circular SVM against linear/polynomial SVMs, Gaussian-kernel SVMs, and backprop-trained CBP, testing whether SRM-selected beta recovers the correct paradigm per dataset, matches or beats fixed-kernel SVMs, avoids CBP's local minima, and yields interpretable decision surfaces. This bridges neural mapping networks and kernel/SRM theory: kernel machines gain CBP's data-driven paradigm plasticity, and CBP gains convex optimization, dual/kernel representation, and SRM model selection, removing the fixed-paradigm assumption constraining prior kernel work."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames two disconnected literatures (kernel/SRM machines and CBP neural mapping) that could be connected, with the core gap being that neither offers a machine that adapts the surface-vs-prototype paradigm while retaining convex SRM guarantees. This is a bridge_opportunity with an underlying scope_mismatch (fixed a-priori kernel geometry). The method is synthesis_unification: showing CBP's plasticity is a Mercer feature map and lifting it into the kernel framework, secondarily formal_derivation (defining the circular kernel family and reconciling capacity bounds). The unification is principled (a genuine nested kernel family with theoretical grounding), not superficial A+B stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior works form one lineage: activity-dependent ordered map formation (retinotectal plasticity), the simple-to-complex columnar architecture of visual cortex (Hubel and Wiesel), position-invariant grandmother-cell responses in inferotemporal cortex, and self-organizing hierarchies (Rosenblatt's four-layer perceptron; Fukushima's cognitron and neocognitron). All engineered systems are strictly feedforward and self-organize only isolated, pre-normalized patterns; the neocognitron needs one normalized pattern at a time and cannot segment superimposed patterns, complete occluded inputs, or attend within clutter. Yet Rosenblatt names selective attention and feedback from response units to association units as open problems and shows discrimination degrades under unit removal; inferotemporal recordings show task-dependent top-down modulation; retinotectal work shows descending connectivity forms and regenerates via activity-dependent competition. No source closes the feedforward hierarchy with a self-organized top-down pathway for attention, segmentation, and completion.","method":"Build NeoAttend, a simulated bidirectional neocognitron whose artifact is a closed feedforward-feedback loop. Ascending: neocognitron cascade of modifiable S-layers and shift-tolerant C-layers, self-organized by unsupervised competitive reinforcement to grandmother units. Descending: a mirror cascade from grandmother units back to input, initialized as the transpose of ascending weights and refined by the same activity-dependent Hebbian competition, grounded in retinotectal ordered-connection formation, giving a generative top-down template. Attention: each S-cell is gain-modulated by the co-located descending signal (inferotemporal modulation, Rosenblatt feedback); the winning grandmother unit projects its template down to enhance consistent cells and suppress others. A serial loop with inhibition-of-return isolates one object, suppresses its support, and re-runs to recognize superimposed or multiple patterns one at a time; the generative descending pathway completes occluded features. Evaluation: unsupervised training on a small character set, then tests on superimposed, occluded, noisy, and cluttered multi-character inputs, measuring accuracy and objects segmented against a feedforward-only baseline, plus lesion experiments removing S-cells to test graceful degradation and whether descending plasticity regenerates connectivity after damage."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.62,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as the feedforward neocognitron's inability to segment/complete/attend in cluttered realistic inputs (scope_mismatch), plus explicit bridging of disconnected lineages (retinotectal plasticity, IT top-down modulation, Rosenblatt feedback). The central move is building NeoAttend, a concrete bidirectional system artifact, drawing together those separate mechanisms. Precise bottleneck named (missing self-organized top-down pathway), but the transpose-mirror-plus-attention design leans toward stitching known components, hence moderate stitching score."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980) is the first hierarchical, shift-invariant, self-organizing pattern recognizer, grounded in the Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex cell hierarchy and cortical columns. It learns without a teacher by competitively selecting representative S-cells that are Hebbian-reinforced (from the cognitron). The paper reports two unresolved weaknesses: fragility (with ten digits, small parameter deviations or changes in presentation order critically hurt accuracy, and resembling patterns like X,Y,T,Z are hard to separate) and fixed capacity (cell-plane counts are hand-set and cap learnable patterns). Both stem from purely bottom-up unsupervised learning where every winning feature is reinforced equally regardless of task usefulness. The perceptron work (Block, Knight, Rosenblatt 1962) offers error-correction reinforcement, expectancy, and selective attention but lacks similarity and shift invariance. IT-cortex recordings (Gross 1972; the 1980 discrimination study) show top-of-hierarchy neurons are pattern-selective and modulated during active discrimination, implying task relevance shapes selectivity, which the neocognitron ignores. Retinotectal plasticity models (1974) show ordered connectivity self-organizes via activity-dependent competition with capacity regulation. No prior work combines the invariant hierarchy with a local reinforcement signal and capacity allocation for robust, task-adaptive self-organization.","method":"Add three local mechanisms to the neocognitron, preserving its S-cell/C-cell hierarchy and shift-invariant pooling, with no global backpropagation. One, reward-gated three-factor reinforcement: train as a discrimination task like the IT-cortex experiments, read last-layer C-cell responses, derive a scalar reward r for whether the winner matched the target, and scale each representative S-cell Hebbian update by r (pre times post times reward) so correct trials reinforce and errors depress the culprit representatives, an error-correction rule applied locally to the deep competitive layer. Two, activity-driven cell-plane allocation: detect S-planes where two categories persistently collide and, when errors persist, recruit a new small-weighted plane captured by the sub-feature that best separates them, an activity-gated growth rule inspired by retinotectal map formation, removing the hand-set plane count. Three, top-down expectancy gating: on ambiguous inputs, transiently boost selection of S-planes historically diagnostic for the competing categories. Evaluate by reproducing Fukushima's protocol on X,Y,T,Z and digits 0-9, measuring accuracy under shift and small distortion; robustness by varying inhibition efficacy, selectivity thresholds, and presentation order and comparing accuracy variance to the unsupervised baseline; and capacity by comparing recruited planes to the fixed count needed to match accuracy. Ablate each mechanism. Success is reduced parameter/order sensitivity, correct discrimination of resembling and many categories, and automatic plane counts, while retaining position-invariant, local, teacher-sparse learning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.66,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed around the neocognitron's reported fragility (parameter/order sensitivity, confusable patterns) and fixed capacity, a failure/risk gap traced to a precise mechanism: purely bottom-up unsupervised reinforcement that ignores task usefulness. Secondary is bridge_opportunity, drawing on perceptron error-correction, IT-cortex task-modulation, and retinotectal plasticity streams. The method robustifies by adding reward-gated local reinforcement, capacity allocation, and expectancy gating to reduce brittleness while preserving invariance; synthesis of the disparate mechanisms is a secondary move. Not surface stitching because mechanisms are specifically motivated by the identified limiting factor rather than arbitrarily bolted on."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Hubel and Wiesel described a graded cortical hierarchy of simple, complex, and hypercomplex cells with increasing invariance and feature complexity; Gross reported shape-selective, position- and size-invariant inferotemporal units. The perceptron, Cognitron, and Neocognitron were built to emulate this hierarchy but validated only qualitatively at the output layer, so no source measures whether their internal cells reproduce the graded quantitative signatures of the biological cells they claim to model. Closing this gap would show which architectural and learning choices produce brain-like tuning and where the analogy breaks.","method":"Build an in-silico electrophysiology benchmark and empirical map. Assemble a stimulus battery reconstructing canonical protocols: spots for receptive-field mapping, oriented bars swept over orientation, position, length, and width, and complex shapes at varied positions, sizes, and distortions. Self-organize a perceptron baseline, the Cognitron, and the Neocognitron on a shared corpus. Probe each internal unit as a recorded neuron, measuring receptive-field area, orientation bandwidth, position tolerance normalized by field size, size tolerance, distortion tolerance, selectivity, and feature complexity. Plot layer-by-layer metric trajectories, overlay values digitized from the source papers, classify each unit against the simple, complex, hypercomplex, and inferotemporal taxonomy, and report per-layer matching. Diagnose whether S-to-C alternation yields the position-tolerant jump, whether invariance grows gradually with depth, and where each model diverges from biology."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that these hierarchical models were validated only qualitatively at output layers, with no measurement of whether internal units reproduce graded biological tuning signatures — an evidence/measurement gap, with a secondary explanatory angle (which choices produce brain-like tuning). The central move builds an in-silico electrophysiology benchmark and empirically maps layer-by-layer tuning metrics against digitized biological values — clear empirical_mapping. Bottleneck is precisely identified (missing quantitative internal validation). Not surface stitching; the comparison is the deliverable, not an A+B combo."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Across the provided works there is a single recurring architectural idea: visual pattern recognition is achieved by a hierarchy that alternates *selectivity-increasing* stages with *tolerance-increasing* stages. Hubel & Wiesel (1962) describe how a complex cell is built by pooling over a set of simple cells with a common orientation but staggered positions, so that \"an edge of light would activate one or more of these simple cells wherever it fell within the complex field,\" yielding position tolerance. Fukushima's cognitron (1975) and neocognitron (1980) make this explicit and mechanistic: modifiable S-cells (simple/lower-hypercomplex) refine feature selectivity through an unsupervised \"winner-take-all + reinforce\" rule and an r.m.s.-type similarity measure, while fixed C-cells (complex/higher-hypercomplex) with connecting areas that \"become larger and larger for the hinder modules\" accumulate shift tolerance until, at the top, a single cell responds to a pattern \"not affected by position at all\" — the position- and size-invariant selective units Gross et al. (1972) and Sato et al. (1978) reported in inferotemporal cortex. Rosenblatt's perceptron (1962) is the baseline that lacks this cascade and is therefore \"severely affected by the shift in position.\"\n\nEvery one of these papers *asserts* a trade-off but none *derives* it. Fukushima states only that the pooling area \"should be determined with a compromise between the ability to differentiate similar patterns and the ability to tolerate the distortion of the pattern's shape\"; Hubel & Wiesel argue verbally that opposing effects are \"relatively weak\"; the neocognitron's number of cell-planes, layer count, and receptive-field growth are all set by hand. What is missing is a formal account of (i) how tolerance accumulates through a cascade of local pooling operators, (ii) the precise sense in which buying tolerance must cost discrimination, and (iii) a principled rule linking architectural resources (layers, pooling radii, number of cell-planes) to the number of patterns that can be recognized at a given invariance level. Closing this gap matters because it would turn the neocognitron's hand-tuned design choices into derivable quantities and give the informal \"grandmother-cell\" hierarchy a rigorous foundation.","method":"Develop an **invariance–selectivity calculus** for hierarchical simple/complex (S/C) cascades — a formal-derivation contribution comprising an ontology, three theorems, and a design rule, validated on a neocognitron simulation.\n\n1. Formal model and taxonomy. Represent the network as an alternating composition F = C_L∘S_L∘…∘C_1∘S_1 acting on input fields u:ℤ²→ℝ. Formalize the neocognitron's own equations: an S-operation as an r.m.s.-normalized template-matching map producing a feature response ϕ(similarity), and a C-operation as a local pooling (weighted-OR/max over connecting area D_l of radius ρ_l, with subsampling factor σ_l). Define a conceptual distinction — S-type operators are *resolution-refining, tolerance-neutral*; C-type operators are *tolerance-increasing, resolution-coarsening* — and make it precise by assigning each map a \"feature resolution\" r_l and a \"tolerance radius\" t_l as functionals of its kernels.\n\n2. Theorem 1 (tolerance accumulation). For the transformation group of translations (and, to first order, bounded smooth displacement fields modeling small distortions), prove that the top-layer tolerance obeys the recursion t_L = σ_L·t_{L-1} + ρ_L, giving a closed form t_L = Σ_l ρ_l ∏_{k>l} σ_k in input coordinates, and a Lipschitz-style bound: for any shift s with |s| ≤ t_L, ‖F(u∘shift_s) − F(u)‖ ≤ Σ_l κ_l·(residual mismatch at layer l), where κ_l depends on the pooling kernel's decay. This derives, rather than assumes, the neocognitron's growing receptive fields and Hubel–Wiesel's \"wherever it falls\" property.\n\n3. Theorem 2 (invariance–selectivity uncertainty relation). Show that a C-operation granting tolerance t necessarily maps any two inputs that differ only by displacements ≤ t at the pooled feature scale to responses within ε(t) of each other, so they become indiscriminable. Cast this as a conserved-budget inequality t_L · ρ_disc ≥ γ, where ρ_disc is the minimum feature-level separation still resolvable at the top and γ is a constant set by the pooling kernels — an \"uncertainty principle\" formalizing Fukushima's compromise: tolerance and discrimination cannot both be made arbitrarily fine.\n\n4. Theorem 3 (learning consistency and capacity). Prove that the neocognitron's unsupervised update (its Eqs. 7–8: reinforce the winning \"representative\" S-cell in proportion to its input) is a stochastic ascent on the expected r.m.s. similarity between S-templates and their winning inputs; hence at fixed points the K_l templates of a layer are the centroids of a K_l-way clustering of the layer's feature distribution. Combine with Theorem 2 to obtain a covering-number capacity bound: to recognize M patterns invariantly at tolerance t_L, the number of cell-planes must satisfy K_l ≥ N(feature distribution; ρ_disc(t_L)), the covering number at the tolerance-limited resolution. This yields an explicit design rule mapping (desired invariance, number of patterns) → (required layers, pooling radii, cell-planes).\n\n5. Validation. Re-implement the neocognitron (as Fukushima did on a digital computer), sweep pooling radii and cell-plane counts, and empirically trace the tolerance-vs-discrimination frontier, testing whether it saturates the predicted uncertainty bound and whether the covering-number rule predicts the minimal K_l needed for error-free recognition. Contrast against a Rosenblatt-style non-pooling perceptron to confirm it lies far inside the frontier, quantifying exactly what the S/C cascade buys.\n\nThis addresses the gap by converting the qualitative \"selectivity vs. tolerance\" intuition shared by Hubel–Wiesel, Fukushima, and the IT-cortex literature into an explicit bound, an objective the classic learning rule provably (approximately) optimizes, and a resource-to-performance derivation that the original works left as hand-set parameters."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that prior works assert but never derive the selectivity-tolerance tradeoff; the proposal seeks a missing formal/theoretical account (explanation_gap), with the trade-off itself framed as a puzzle. The central move is a formal calculus with theorems, bounds, and a design rule (formal_derivation), validated by simulation sweeps (empirical_mapping). Precise bottleneck (undelivered tolerance-discrimination bound, hand-set parameters) is clearly identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron self-organizes by winner-take-all reinforcement but is brittle: plane counts are hand-fixed (24 planes failed on ten patterns) and success depends critically on parameter values and presentation order. No prior work treats capacity, parameters, and exposure schedule as quantities to discover automatically.","method":"Recast self-organization as unsupervised search over capacity, parameters, and scheduling. Grow S-planes on demand when a feature is not matched above a novelty threshold, and merge/prune redundant planes. Tune the few per-layer parameters greedily bottom-up via coordinate search. Score configurations by a label-free objective of pattern separability plus jitter-invariance minus a plane-count penalty. Adaptively schedule which stimulus to present next by targeting the most ambiguous top-layer response. Validate on the paper's digit protocol against the fixed-24-plane baseline."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed around brittleness: hand-fixed plane counts fail, and success depends critically on parameters and presentation order (failure_risk_gap), with a resource/capacity bottleneck secondary. The core move recasts self-organization as unsupervised search over capacity, parameters, and scheduling with adaptive growth, pruning, coordinate search, and a label-free objective (optimization_search), also extending the model to auto-discover configurations (relax_extend_scope). Bottleneck is precisely identified (fixed plane counts, parameter/schedule sensitivity)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"gap","method":"approach"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The neocognitron addresses the failure of prior pattern recognition models to be invariant to positional shift, extending scope beyond fixed-position recognition. The central contribution is a concrete self-organizing neural network model (artifact/system) inspired by and bridging neurophysiological findings on visual cortex with computational recognition. Note: proposal fields are placeholder tokens ('gap','approach'), so labels rely on title context, lowering confidence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron achieves invariant recognition but its unsupervised self-organization is brittle; Fukushima notes small parameter or presentation-order changes critically affect performance, leaving a reliability gap.","method":"Add homeostatic competition among cell-planes, adaptive vigilance-based recruitment of fresh planes, and epoch-averaged consensus reinforcement to the neocognitron's S-cell learning, then evaluate reliability across randomized orders and parameters."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a reliability/brittleness problem: unsupervised self-organization is sensitive to parameter and presentation-order changes (failure_risk_gap). The method adds homeostatic competition, adaptive recruitment, and consensus reinforcement to reduce this brittleness and evaluates reliability across randomized conditions (robustification). It targets a precise bottleneck (order/parameter sensitivity of S-cell learning), not a superficial A+B mashup."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two foundational learning paradigms in this corpus were developed in parallel and never reconciled into a single principle. (1) Rosenblatt's series-coupled/cross-coupled perceptron (1962) learns categories through *supervised* error-correcting reinforcement rules with a teacher (and Rosenblatt explicitly flagged \"selective attention mechanisms,\" feedback from response units, and new reinforcement rules as open problems), but its response is, as the neocognitron paper itself notes, \"severely affected by the shift in position and/or by the distortion in shape\" of inputs. (2) Fukushima's cognitron (1975) and neocognitron (1980) achieve shift- and distortion-invariant recognition by *unsupervised* self-organization of a Hubel–Wiesel S-cell/C-cell hierarchy, but they cannot exploit category labels when available, cannot be told which cell should stand for which pattern, and — as the paper concedes — are brittle: with ten patterns \"a small deviation of the values of the parameters, or a small change of the way of pattern presentation, has critically influenced\" recognition, and the grandmother-cell-to-category assignment is essentially arbitrary. \n\nCrucially, the biological sources indicate that these two mechanisms coexist rather than compete. Inferotemporal-cortex recordings show high-level, position/size-invariant feature cells whose responsiveness is modulated while the animal *performs a discrimination task* (the 1972 and 1980 IT studies), implying a top-down/behavioral teaching signal reaching invariant visual representations. And the retinotectal neuroplasticity models (Meyer & Sperry, 1974), which Fukushima invokes to justify self-organization, show that ordered, target-matched connection maps form through activity-dependent plasticity — a mechanism for making a mapping *stable and reproducible* rather than arbitrary. No model in this literature unifies supervised error-correction with unsupervised invariance-building, nor uses a top-down task signal to stabilize the category mapping. Closing this gap matters because it would explain how invariant perception and label-/task-driven learning arise from one learning rule, and would fix the neocognitron's core weaknesses (brittleness, uncontrolled category assignment, inability to use supervision) while giving the perceptron the invariance it lacks.","method":"Propose a single hierarchical learning framework — a \"guided neocognitron\" — whose plasticity rule provably interpolates between unsupervised self-organization (cognitron/neocognitron) and supervised error-correction (perceptron), bridged by a top-down teaching pathway grounded in IT-cortex task modulation and retinotectal topographic plasticity.\n\n1. Shared architecture. Keep the neocognitron's bottom-up S-cell/C-cell cascade (Hubel–Wiesel hierarchy) as the invariance engine, and attach a perceptron-style decision/response layer (R-units) that reads the deepest C-layer. This physically joins the two literatures: invariant features flow up; category decisions are made by a trainable linear readout.\n\n2. Unified plasticity rule. Reformulate the neocognitron's \"representative S-cell\" selection-and-reinforcement step as a gated update: Δw = (competitive Hebbian term, exactly the neocognitron's winner-take-all reinforcement) × g, where g is a top-down teaching gate broadcast from the R-units back down the hierarchy. When no label is present, g≡1 and the rule is identical to neocognitron self-organization. When a label is present and the decision is correct, g reinforces the representatives that fed the correct R-unit; when the decision is wrong, g suppresses reinforcement of representatives feeding the erroneous unit and promotes runner-up candidates — this is Rosenblatt's error-correcting reinforcement expressed inside the competitive selection step. Prove the two limits analytically: teacher-absent → pure neocognitron; single trainable layer, no invariance pooling → pure perceptron error-correction. Intermediate supervision fractions yield a principled semi-supervised regime that operationalizes Fukushima's own conjecture that familiar (teacher-shaped) and unfamiliar (self-organized) patterns are processed by the same substrate.\n\n3. Stabilizing the mapping via retinotectal-style ordering. Make the top-down teaching connections (R-units → S-layers) themselves plastic under an activity-dependent, target-matching rule analogous to compressed/ordered retinotectal map formation. This forces the category-to-cell assignment to converge to a stable, reproducible topographic organization rather than the arbitrary, parameter-sensitive assignment of the original neocognitron, directly addressing its documented brittleness.\n\n4. Experiments (all reproducible with the original simulation setups). Train on shifted/distorted/noisy character sets. Compare four models: pure perceptron, pure neocognitron, a naive cascade (neocognitron features + separately trained perceptron readout), and the fully integrated gated model. Metrics: (a) recognition accuracy under position shift and shape distortion (tests whether supervision preserves the neocognitron's invariance); (b) reproducibility/stability of the category assignment across random presentation orders and parameter perturbations (tests the retinotectal-ordering claim vs. neocognitron brittleness); (c) label efficiency as the supervised fraction is swept from 0→100% (tests the unification/interpolation claim); (d) a biological prediction: switching the teaching gate on (\"discrimination mode\") should sharpen deep-layer cell selectivity relative to the ungated mode, mirroring the modulation reported for IT neurons during discrimination tasks.\n\nThis is a synthesis contribution: it reconciles the supervised (perceptron) and unsupervised (cognitron/neocognitron) learning traditions under one gated rule, and integrates neurophysiological hierarchy (Hubel–Wiesel), task-dependent high-level modulation (IT cortex), and activity-dependent topographic map formation (retinotectal plasticity) into a single coherent mechanism."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as two unreconciled learning traditions (supervised perceptron vs unsupervised neocognitron) that biological evidence suggests coexist — a bridge_opportunity, with secondary failure_risk_gap given the emphasis on neocognitron brittleness and arbitrary category assignment. The central move is synthesis_unification via a gated plasticity rule reconciling both paradigms, with a formal_derivation secondary (proving the two limits analytically). The proposal is more than superficial stitching: it introduces a genuinely unified update rule with a top-down gate and analytic limit conditions rather than just cascading modules (indeed it explicitly contrasts against a naive cascade baseline). Bottleneck specificity is high — it pinpoints the winner-take-all reinforcement step as the locus of unification and identifies parameter-sensitivity/arbitrary grandmother-cell assignment as the precise weakness."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Four evidence streams in these sources developed in isolation, and connecting them is a bridge opportunity. (1) Self-organizing recognizers: the cognitron/neocognitron build a feedforward S-cell/C-cell hierarchy mirroring Hubel and Wiesel's simple-to-complex cascade and ending in IT-cortex-like invariant cells, learned purely bottom-up without a teacher via winner-take-all reinforcement. (2) Teacher/reinforcement learning: Rosenblatt's perceptron (Principles of Neurodynamics; four-layer perceptron) formalizes reward-driven learning the neocognitron avoids. (3) Task-dependent physiology: Gross (1972) and Sato/Iwai (1980, IT units during discrimination) show IT responses are gated by the animal's task, which a fixed feedforward net cannot express. (4) Activity-dependent plasticity: retinotectal regeneration (Meyer and Sperry 1974), cited by Fukushima to justify self-organization, shows topographic maps re-tile after lesions. Gap: the neocognitron models ventral-stream anatomy but leaves its own stated open problems untouched (top-down completion of degraded patterns, task modulation, recovery after damage), precisely the phenomena in streams 2-4, which sit in its citation neighborhood yet were never unified with self-organizing hierarchies. Bridging them turns a static recognizer into a model of adaptive, behaviorally driven, self-repairing perception.","method":"Central contribution: a simulation platform, an Adaptive Neocognitron, extending Fukushima's cascade of modifiable S-layers and position-tolerant C-layers with three integrated subsystems, released as a reusable simulator with defined stimulus, task, and lesion protocols. (1) Top-down feedback: add reciprocal projections so an active higher C-cell primes the lower S-cells supporting it; inference runs settling iterations where top-down expectation boosts and lateral inhibition suppresses lower S-cell activity, giving attention and pattern-completion for occluded or degraded inputs. (2) Teacher-gated competitive learning: scale the reinforcement of the winning representative S-cell by a scalar reward from Rosenblatt's framework tied to whether the top-layer output matches the task target; with no reward it reduces exactly to the original unsupervised rule, spanning teacher-free self-organization and reinforcement learning and letting identical features be sharpened differently across tasks (an analogue of IT task modulation). (3) Activity-dependent regeneration: give S-planes a Sperry-style ownership rule where coverage of feature space is set by cumulative co-activation and competition, so surviving planes re-tile after lesions. Evaluation in digital simulation: (a) reproduce position/shape-invariant character recognition; (b) measure accuracy on noisy, occluded, partial stimuli with feedback on vs off to quantify completion; (c) train under two competing discrimination tasks and show tuning reorganizes with the rewarded task, comparing qualitatively to IT task-dependence; (d) lesion cell-planes and plot recovery of accuracy over continued exposure, comparing compressed re-tiling to Meyer and Sperry's retinotectal reprojection. Ablations isolate each subsystem and probe the neocognitron's flagged parameter sensitivity, making the bridging hypotheses testable in one runnable system."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames four isolated evidence streams sitting in a citation neighborhood that were never unified, making bridge_opportunity the clear primary; the open questions (why degraded completion, task modulation, recovery work) add an explanation-gap flavor. The method integrates top-down feedback, reward-gated learning, and regeneration into one runnable model reconciling separate mechanisms, so synthesis_unification is primary, with the reusable simulator platform as an artifact_system secondary. Some risk of A+B stitching since the design bolts three known ideas onto the neocognitron, but each is mechanistically motivated by specific cited phenomena, so score is moderate."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Two disconnected strands here hold complementary halves of a solution to learning invariant object representations. Strand A: Fukushima's neocognitron (1980), extending the cognitron (1975), builds an S-cell/C-cell cascade modeled on Hubel and Wiesel's (1962) simple/complex-cell hierarchy and reaching toward IT object cells (Gross, 1972). But it hard-wires C-cell invariance pooling to fixed spatial neighborhoods; its plastic S-cells self-organize only on instantaneous geometric similarity of static patterns. So it gets position invariance but only small tolerance to rotation/scale/deformation, and the paper admits that recognizing 10 patterns needed skillful presentation and delicate tuning: which features form an invariance class is imposed by the designer, not learned. Strand B: Block, Knight and Rosenblatt's perceptron analysis (1962) showed an unused principle: a network can autonomously learn transformation-equivalence classes from temporal contiguity (successive forms/positions of the same object, contiguous in time, get one response), plus cross-coupled feedback for selective attention and figure-ground. This machinery was never placed inside a deep self-organizing hierarchy. Two evidence streams bridge to biology: retinotectal plasticity models (1974), cited by Fukushima, show orderly wiring arises from correlated activity over time; IT recordings during discrimination (1980) show high-level responses are modulated by behavioral task. Joining Rosenblatt's temporal-contiguity-plus-feedback idea with Fukushima's Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy, grounded in activity-dependent plasticity and IT task modulation, directly attacks the neocognitron's core limitation: invariance imposed rather than learned.","method":"Build a neocognitron-style S/C hierarchy but make invariance pooling learnable from time and gated by top-down attention. First, a feature stage keeps S-cells that self-organize by winner-take-all Hebbian competition on the current input, yielding simple/hypercomplex-like detectors. Second, a temporal-trace pooling stage is the core novelty importing Rosenblatt's contiguity principle: replace fixed spatial C-cell pooling with C-cells whose afferents from S-cells are learned by a trace/persistence Hebbian rule, where each C-cell keeps a slowly decaying trace of its recent activity and a synapse strengthens when an active S-cell coincides with high postsynaptic trace. A smoothly transforming stimulus (translating, rotating, rescaling, deforming, changing viewpoint) activates a time-contiguous sequence of S-cells, which the rule binds to a common C-cell, thereby learning an invariance class instead of assuming a spatial one. Applied at every cascade level, low levels learn local geometric invariances and high levels learn IT-like object invariance, using the correlated-activity plasticity supported by the retinotectal models. Third, top-down cross-coupled attention combines Rosenblatt feedback with IT modulation: add feedback from higher layers giving multiplicative attentional gain to lower layers and gating the trace learning rate, and let a behavioral-relevance/reward signal bias which temporal groupings consolidate, aligning invariance classes with meaningful categories and aiding figure-ground, solving the neocognitron's arbitrary-category problem. Fourth, the protocol trains unsupervised on continuous transformation movies rather than static snapshots. Predictions: complex-like C-cells with position/phase invariance emerge though pooling was never wired in, matching Hubel and Wiesel; higher layers develop transformation-invariant object units resembling IT selectivity; reward-gated feedback reproduces task-dependent high-level modulation. Ablations remove the temporal trace (reverting to static geometric-similarity learning and losing non-positional invariance), remove attentional gating (invariance classes drift from behavioral categories), and vary the trace time-constant (predicting a speed/invariance trade-off). All components are simulable at the scale of the original neocognitron studies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two disconnected strands (Fukushima's hierarchy, Rosenblatt's temporal-contiguity/feedback) holding complementary halves of a solution, grounded in two biology streams — a clear bridge_opportunity. Secondary is scope_mismatch: the neocognitron's fixed spatial pooling and imposed invariance classes are a narrow, unrealistic assumption. The central move is synthesis_unification (joining temporal-trace learning with the Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy plus IT modulation), with relax_extend_scope secondary (making pooling learnable rather than hard-wired, trained on transformation movies). Bottleneck is precisely identified: invariance imposed vs learned, and the C-cell fixed pooling mechanism. The combination is explicitly A+B, hence surface_stitching flagged, but the trace-rule mechanism and ablations give real specificity, keeping the score moderate."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The corpus links two disconnected literatures: self-organizing artificial networks (Rosenblatt's perceptron 1962; Fukushima's Cognitron 1975/1981 and Neocognitron 1979/1980), judged on recognition performance, and quantitative neurophysiology (Hubel and Wiesel's cortex studies 1962/1965/1977; inferotemporal recordings 1972 and 1980; retinotectal plasticity 1974). The Neocognitron borrows the Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex/hypercomplex hierarchy and posits IT grandmother cells only qualitatively; no one has measured whether its emergent units reproduce the quantitative signatures of real neurons such as orientation bandwidth, simple-to-complex position invariance, end-stopping, receptive-field growth, and IT shift-tolerant selectivity. Bridging the two would reveal which biological cell classes each model layer recapitulates and whether unsupervised self-organization versus the supervised perceptron buys biological realism.","method":"Build a benchmark that applies classic electrophysiology stimulus protocols to the internal units of reimplemented perceptron, Cognitron, and Neocognitron models, extracts a fixed panel of neuronal tuning metrics (orientation bandwidth, on-off segregation, position-invariance index, end-stopping index, receptive-field size, direction selectivity, selectivity, and shift tolerance), and compares them layer by layer to digitized biological measurements to produce a correspondence matrix mapping each model layer onto retinal, simple, complex, hypercomplex, and IT cell classes, plus a developmental diagnostic checking whether topographic feature maps emerge as in retinotectal data."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as connecting two disconnected literatures (self-organizing networks vs quantitative neurophysiology) — bridge_opportunity — with a secondary evidence_gap since no one has measured whether model units reproduce biological tuning signatures. The method builds a benchmark applying electrophysiology protocols to model units, extracting a fixed panel of tuning metrics and producing a correspondence matrix: this is systematic measurement/diagnostic characterization (empirical_mapping), with the unification of the two fields as secondary. Not superficial stitching because the proposed metric-by-layer correspondence matrix is a concrete, non-trivial analytical construction. Bottleneck specificity moderate — specific tuning metrics named but the limiting factor is diffuse."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation for bridging neocognitron self-organization, Hubel-Wiesel ordered columns, and retinotectal map-formation theory.","method":"Test method: derive one energy objective unifying Hebbian feature learning, competition, retinotectal smoothness, and equivariance; prove weight-sharing and columnar maps as limits."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly seeks to bridge three disconnected lines (neocognitron self-organization, Hubel-Wiesel columns, retinotectal map formation), so the gap-finding pattern is bridge_opportunity, with an underlying desire to explain why weight-sharing and columnar maps emerge. The method is synthesis_unification via a single energy objective, backed by formal_derivation (proving weight-sharing/columnar maps as limits). The combining-three-frameworks framing risks superficial stitching, hence the elevated stitching score, though a unifying objective with proofs adds some depth."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"TESTMOTIV","method":"TESTMETHOD"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder (TESTMOTIV/TESTMETHOD), so labels rely on title/context. The neocognitron addresses shift-invariant pattern recognition, a scope limitation of prior models, and builds a concrete self-organizing network model inspired by visual cortex, suggesting artifact_system with synthesis of neuroscience findings. Low confidence due to missing content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron and cognitron learn a shift-invariant S-cell/C-cell hierarchy by learning without a teacher, forming categories only from geometric similarity via winner-take-all reinforcement of representative cells, with no behavioral relevance or top-down signal. Rosenblatt perceptron work develops the complementary reinforcement paradigm but lacks invariance. The physiology sources (Hubel and Wiesel hypercolumns, Gross inferotemporal grandmother-like neurons, and inferotemporal single units recorded during a monkey discrimination task) show recognition units are modulated by task and behavior, not geometry alone; retinotectal plasticity models supply activity-dependent competition. Gap: the neocognitron cites IT grandmother cells and retinotectal competition yet remains bottom-up, teacher-free, noise-fragile, and forms only geometry-aligned categories. No source links the competitive self-organizing hierarchy to reward and attention-modulated plasticity. Bridging them explains how an invariant hierarchy acquires behaviorally meaningful categories under noisy, sparsely-supervised conditions.","method":"Relax the neocognitron unsupervised, noise-free, geometry-only assumptions and extend it with sparse reinforcement and attention. Keep the S-layer and C-layer cascade for invariance. Add a three-factor plasticity rule gating representative-cell reinforcement by a global delayed reward signal from a discrimination task, so rewarded trials strengthen active representatives and unrewarded trials weaken them and recruit a fresh cell-plane, fusing reinforcement with competition as an analogue of outcome-gated retinotectal competition. Add top-down attentional gain from the grandmother layer biasing which S-columns win, modeling IT task-modulation and letting categories cut across geometric similarity. Train under noise and sparse reward on a task whose categories conflict with geometric clustering. Evaluate against pure neocognitron, plain perceptron, and a no-attention variant, measuring behaviorally-appropriate grandmother cells, robustness, sample efficiency, and invariance, comparing unit task-modulation to the IT data and hypercolumns."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as disconnected literatures (unsupervised invariant hierarchy vs. reinforcement paradigm vs. task-modulated IT physiology) that no source links, a bridge_opportunity, with a secondary scope_mismatch (neocognitron's geometry-only, noise-free, teacher-free assumptions). The central move is synthesis_unification: fusing reinforcement, attention, and competitive self-organization into one model, while relaxing/extending the neocognitron's assumptions is the secondary move. The A+B fusion of neocognitron + reinforcement + attention risks superficial stitching, though the three-factor plasticity mechanism is fairly specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.35,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal fields are placeholder text ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), so labels are inferred only from titles: a self-organizing neural network robust to positional shift, drawing on visual cortex architecture. Low confidence due to absent content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The perceptron tradition (Rosenblatt: reinforcement-driven, task-oriented, aiming at selective attention) and the neocognitron tradition (Fukushima: unsupervised self-organization of a position-invariant Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex-cell hierarchy that learns without a teacher and is purely feedforward) are disconnected learning literatures. Their cited neurophysiology is likewise split between Hubel-Wiesel feedforward receptive-field buildup and Gross's finding that inferotemporal neurons are modulated by the discrimination task, with retinotectal work framing plasticity as activity-dependent. No model bridges reinforcement/attention learning with an unsupervised invariant hierarchy, nor reconciles the feedforward-buildup and task-modulated evidence streams. Each tradition supplies what the other lacks: invariance versus behavioral steerability.","method":"Unify both traditions in one network governed by one plasticity law. Architecture: neocognitron S/C modules for invariance, capped by perceptron association/response stages, with top-down feedback from response back to cell-planes. Unified rule: synaptic change equals a Hebbian competitive term (neocognitron winner reinforcement) times two modulators, a reward signal and an attention gate. With neutral reward and no attention it reduces exactly to Fukushima unsupervised self-organization; with corrective reward at higher stages it reduces to Rosenblatt reinforcement, making learning with and without a teacher two regimes of one law. Feedback implements selective attention that biases which features are reinforced, so rewarded discriminations sculpt which invariant features and high-level categories form, modeling Gross task-modulated inferotemporal neurons; a retinotectal-inspired schedule stabilizes lower modules first while keeping upper modules plastic and reward-gated. Validation: on patterns varied in position, size, and shape, compare a pure neocognitron, a pure perceptron, and the unified model on shift-invariant discrimination accuracy, alignment of emergent categories with the rewarded task, and emergence of task-dependent modulation matching inferotemporal data."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames the gap as disconnected learning literatures (perceptron reinforcement vs neocognitron unsupervised invariance) and split neurophysiology evidence streams that no model bridges—clear bridge_opportunity, with a secondary explanation_gap around reconciling feedforward-buildup vs task-modulated neural evidence. The central move is unifying both traditions under one plasticity law that reduces to each as special regimes, a synthesis_unification, supported by a formal single-rule derivation. Some risk of surface stitching since it combines neocognitron modules with perceptron stages, but the unified plasticity law with reward/attention modulators offers a genuine mechanistic reduction rather than mere concatenation."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Every biologically-inspired recognition model in this corpus is justified by an asserted correspondence to real visual neurons, yet that correspondence is never measured. Hubel and Wiesel (1962) built their simple/complex-cell taxonomy on precise, reproducible protocols: mapping on/off subregions with spots, sweeping slit orientation where a 5 to 10 degree change abolishes a simple cell's response, testing movement direction, and separating simple from complex cells by position dependence versus invariance. Gross et al. (1972) characterized inferotemporal grandmother cells by size- and position-invariant responses to complex shapes. Fukushima's neocognitron and cognitron, and Rosenblatt's perceptron, explicitly claim their internal units correspond to simple, complex, hypercomplex, and grandmother cells, and that invariance and receptive-field size grow up the hierarchy. But the evidence is anecdotal: the neocognitron paper validates only that each final-layer C-cell fires for one trained digit and that this last layer is roughly position and size invariant; it never applies the neurophysiologists' stimulus batteries and classification criteria to its internal S and C cells. The field has no standardized instrument to observe an artificial network's units the way an electrophysiologist observes neurons, quantify how closely they match measured biological distributions, compare models on a common biological yardstick, or accumulate such evidence across model generations. This matters because these models' scientific purpose is to be clues to the neural mechanism of recognition, so biological plausibility must become empirical rather than rhetorical.","method":"Build NeuroProbe, a model-agnostic virtual-electrophysiology benchmarking platform that audits any layered recognition network against the neurophysiology in this corpus. First, a standardized stimulus battery of parametric generators reproducing the source protocols in retinotopic coordinates: spots for on/off mapping; oriented slits, edges, and bars swept over position, fine orientation steps, and length for end-stopping; moving stimuli for direction selectivity; and Gross-style complex shapes such as triangles, hands, and silhouettes rendered at varied positions and sizes. Stimuli map onto each model's input array so the same battery drives perceptron, cognitron, and neocognitron. Second, a virtual-electrode harness: a uniform API that records each unit's activation during the battery, reconstructing receptive-field maps via systematic sweeps and reverse correlation, orientation and direction tuning curves, and position and size response profiles, layer by layer, mimicking a microelectrode penetration through the hierarchy. Third, a metric library operationalizing the neurophysiologists' own criteria: an orientation-selectivity index and tuning half-width calibrated to the 5 to 10 degree standard, on/off subregion segregation as a simple-cell criterion, summation versus within-receptive-field position invariance as the simple-versus-complex criterion, an end-stopping index, a direction-selectivity index, and size and position invariance indices as the grandmother criterion. It auto-classifies each artificial unit into the biological taxonomy and summarizes receptive-field-size and invariance gradients across depth. Fourth, a reference database and scorecard: digitize reported biological distributions such as cell-type proportions, invariance, and tuning as targets, and compute a correspondence score measuring divergence between a model's per-layer property distributions and the biological reference. Output an auditable per-model scorecard and leaderboard that tests specific claims, such as whether the neocognitron S-layer shows simple-cell on/off structure and whether C-cells show graded complex and hypercomplex invariance and receptive-field growth, diagnoses deviations, and enables cumulative comparison of models and future variants. To validate, run NeuroProbe on the self-organized neocognitron reproducing its five-digit training regime, on the cognitron predicting weaker invariance, and on a trained perceptron, showing it recovers known qualitative differences as reproducible quantitative scores and surfaces mismatches invisible to output-only evaluation, turning untested biological-plausibility assertions into measurable, comparable, and accumulable evidence."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is that biological-plausibility claims are asserted but never measured (evidence_gap), with a contradiction flavor between rhetorical claims and anecdotal validation. The central move is building a standardized measurement/benchmark instrument that audits units against biological reference distributions (empirical_mapping), delivered as a platform (artifact_system, secondary). Precise bottleneck: no standardized instrument to observe artificial units like an electrophysiologist and quantify correspondence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"The self-organizing hierarchical models here (Rosenblatt's series-coupled perceptron, Fukushima's cognitron, and the neocognitron) justify their architecture by claiming their self-organized units resemble neurons from the visual neurophysiology papers: orientation-selective, increasingly position-invariant simple, complex, and hypercomplex cells (Hubel and Wiesel) and complex-feature, position and size invariant grandmother-like units of inferotemporal cortex (Gross et al. 1972; Sato et al. 1980). The neocognitron explicitly maps S-cells to simple and hypercomplex cells and C-cells to complex cells. Yet evidence for these claims is purely qualitative, resting on inspecting a few trained weight maps. There is no shared quantitative protocol that probes artificial and biological units with the same stimuli and scores them with the same metrics, no benchmark stimulus battery drawn from the physiology experiments, and no standardized measurement of how tuning properties progress layer-by-layer. So the field cannot observe or audit whether unsupervised self-organization genuinely reproduces neurophysiological tuning statistics, cannot validate the biological rationale motivating these architectures, and cannot compare model variants on common evidence. This is an evidence gap: we lack instrumentation to measure and accumulate comparable evidence for the biological-fidelity claims on which the modeling program rests.","method":"Build a neurophysiology-in-silico benchmark and diagnostic that applies the classic single-unit probing protocols uniformly to the artificial units of these models and scores correspondence with reported physiology. First, a curated stimulus battery reconstructs as digital input patterns the stimuli described in the physiology sources: oriented slits, bars, and edges swept over orientation, position, length, width, and contrast (Hubel and Wiesel protocol), stationary versus moving variants, plus complex object silhouettes as used for IT recordings; each class is parameterized so the same sweep can drive any layer. Second, standardized metrics are computed identically for every unit at every stage: orientation tuning curve and half-width bandwidth, orientation-selectivity index, position-invariance index, size-invariance index, stationary-versus-moving preference, and a feature-complexity score. This converts static weight maps into physiology-comparable tuning profiles. Third, a layer-wise fidelity comparison runs the battery on each model after self-organization to produce per-stage metric distributions and compares them to quantitative summaries extracted from the physiology papers, yielding per-stage correspondence scores and an invariance-growth curve across the hierarchy to test the claimed simple-to-complex-to-IT progression. Fourth, as a diagnostic, sweep architectural and training knobs (lateral-inhibition efficacy, plane-wise competition, number of stages, supervised perceptron layers versus unsupervised cognitron rule, and training-set composition) and measure how each changes correspondence scores and the invariance-growth curve. All models are fully specified and directly simulatable on the input arrays they were designed for, and the probing stimuli and target tuning descriptions are given in the sources, so no external data are needed. Deliverables are the reusable stimulus battery, metric definitions, and per-model per-layer fidelity reports."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.95,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal identifies a precise evidence gap: qualitative-only claims of biological fidelity lack a shared quantitative probing protocol and benchmark. This is squarely how the gap is found (missing instrumentation to observe/audit/compare). The method builds a benchmark stimulus battery, standardized metrics, and layer-wise fidelity diagnostics — classic empirical_mapping (measurement, benchmarking, characterization). While it applies physiology protocols to artificial units (a bridging flavor), the central deliverable is measurement instrumentation, not reconciling theories, so empirical_mapping dominates over synthesis_unification. Bottleneck is very specific (lack of common-stimulus, common-metric protocol)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The cognitron and neocognitron claim their cells resemble Hubel and Wiesel simple and complex cells and invariant inferotemporal neurons, yet this is asserted only qualitatively and never measured or benchmarked. This matters because the brain-like justification for these models rests on an unverified analogy.","method":"Build a virtual electrophysiology benchmark that probes units of the perceptron, cognitron, and neocognitron with digitized stimulus batteries from these sources and scores each layer against biological tuning and invariance statistics to form a layer to cortex map."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that the brain-similarity claim of these models is asserted qualitatively but never measured or benchmarked, an evidence gap; secondarily it bridges model units and neurophysiology. The method builds a virtual electrophysiology benchmark scoring layers against biological tuning statistics to form a layer-to-cortex map, i.e., empirical mapping/diagnostic quantification, with a synthesis element connecting model and biology."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The perceptron (Block, Knight, Rosenblatt 1962), cognitron (Fukushima 1975/1981), and neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), inspired by the Hubel and Wiesel 1962 simple-to-complex hierarchy, all rest on a claim of invariance (recognition unaffected by shift in position) produced by alternating feature-detection stages (S-cells/simple cells) and pooling stages (C-cells/complex cells). Yet the evidence is anecdotal and the field lacks any way to observe, quantify, compare, or predict invariance. The neocognitron is shown on a few hand-crafted patterns; Fukushima notes tiny parameter changes critically influenced performance, with no account of how much invariance the pooling ranges buy or how it grows with depth. The cognitron is called position-dependent and the neocognitron position-invariant, but no graded measure makes this more than a binary anecdote, and Hubel and Wiesel describe complex-cell position tolerance only qualitatively. There is no metric to audit invariance, attribute it to architectural parameters, compare these models on a common scale, or characterize the discriminability price of invariance.","method":"Introduce a formal operator-theoretic framework making invariance measurable and derivable. Model a network as a composition of alternating detection operators (correlation plus S-cell shunting inhibition) and pooling operators (spatial aggregation over a range, the C-cell operation), with stimulus variation as a group action G (translation exactly; bounded scale and distortion as near-isometries). Define two computable functionals: the Invariance Radius, the largest transformation magnitude keeping output change below a tolerance, and the Selectivity Margin, the minimal preserved separation between distinct patterns. Derive a compositional theorem for the network invariance radius after L modules as a recursion in pooling ranges, proving a detection-only stack (cognitron) has zero radius while radius grows monotonically with cumulative pooling. Derive a trade-off inequality: guaranteeing radius R collapses distinctions finer than a function of R. Give a taxonomy distinguishing invariance-by-pooling from invariance-by-learned-features with an orbit-versus-kernel criterion for guaranteed versus sampled invariance. Validate by measuring the two functionals on the perceptron, cognitron, and neocognitron under controlled transformations, testing the bounds and explaining Fukushima's parameter sensitivity as operation near the invariance-selectivity frontier."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that invariance claims are anecdotal with no way to measure, compare, or attribute — an evidence gap, with a secondary explanation gap (why parameter sensitivity, why cognitron vs neocognitron). The core move is an operator-theoretic formal framework with functionals, a compositional theorem, and a trade-off inequality (formal_derivation), validated by measuring functionals across models (empirical_mapping). Precise bottleneck identified (invariance-selectivity frontier, pooling recursion). Not superficial stitching; the formalism is the central construct."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Rosenblatt's multilayer perceptron and Fukushima's Cognitron and Neocognitron were each validated by only a few hand-picked demonstrations, and are motivated by Hubel and Wiesel's receptive-field hierarchy and inferotemporal single-unit selectivity. The field lacks ways to observe, measure, and accumulate evidence on two issues these papers flag. Parameter and curriculum sensitivity: the Neocognitron paper concedes that a small deviation of parameter values or presentation order critically determines whether self-organization succeeds, yet there is no audit of how each hand-set parameter (inhibitory efficacy, reinforcement speed, saturation, receptive-field sizes, number of planes) or curriculum governs success, how robust a configuration is, or how the architectures compare. Physiological correspondence: the models claim to reproduce the visual hierarchy only qualitatively, with no protocol to quantify whether emergent cells match receptive-field properties from Hubel and Wiesel and the IT studies, and no shared benchmark. This evidence gap means progress cannot be measured or compared, which matters because these models are the template for hierarchical invariance-building recognition and their unprincipled hand-tuning undermines inference to brain mechanisms.","method":"Build an optimization-and-search evaluation harness. Re-implement the three model families from their published equations as simulators exposing all free parameters and the training curriculum. Define response-property probes mirroring the physiology papers to yield a scorecard: orientation-selectivity index and receptive-field maps, a position-invariance index and distortion-tolerance curves, a top-layer category-selectivity and sparseness score, and recognition accuracy on distorted, shifted test sets. Use adaptive search such as Bayesian optimization and evolutionary search over parameters and curricula with this scorecard as objective, to map the fitness landscape, quantify each parameter's sensitivity and robustness by estimating the volume of high-performing space and gradients around the original hand-set values, and find Pareto-front configurations jointly maximizing recognition robustness and physiological correspondence. Run fixed-budget comparisons across architectures on shared stimuli and ablate mechanisms such as shunting inhibition, C-cell pooling, and competitive representative learning versus a retinotectal-style plasticity rule, to attribute which components are necessary for invariance and cortical-like responses. Release a versioned benchmark of metrics, stimulus batteries, and best-found configurations with sensitivity profiles. This closes the evidence gap by replacing hand-tuning with reproducible search that measures robustness, validates emergent representations against neurophysiological data, and accumulates comparable cross-architecture evidence."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.88,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as the field lacking ways to measure, benchmark, and audit these models (evidence_gap), with the parameter-sensitivity and unprincipled hand-tuning concern giving a failure_risk_gap secondary. The construction move builds a benchmark harness with response-property probes and scorecards to quantify and compare (empirical_mapping), driven by adaptive search over parameters/curricula (optimization_search secondary). Bottleneck is precisely identified (parameter/curriculum sensitivity, lack of physiological quantification)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation content here","method":"test method content here"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.42,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal body is placeholder text ('test motivation/method content'), so labels rely on title/prior-work context. The neocognitron addresses position-invariant pattern recognition (a scope limitation of prior perceptrons) via a self-organizing neural network model artifact inspired by visual cortex architecture. Low confidence due to missing content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"gap","method":"fix"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The neocognitron addresses the limitation that prior pattern recognition models were sensitive to positional shift (scope_mismatch), drawing on biological visual cortex architecture (bridge). The central contribution is a concrete self-organizing neural network model/artifact inspired by neurophysiology. Proposal text is minimal ('gap'/'fix'), so scores rely on title context."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Models like the perceptron, Cognitron, and Neocognitron claim their units mirror Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex/hypercomplex cells and inferotemporal neurons, but this correspondence is asserted by analogy and never measured with the neurophysiologists' own probing protocols. The field lacks a shared instrument to audit and compare whether model units actually develop these receptive-field properties.</parameter>\n<parameter name=\"method\">Build a unified virtual-electrophysiology benchmark: apply Hubel-Wiesel and IT stimulus protocols (oriented slits, moving bars, complex shapes across position/size) identically to units of re-implemented perceptron, cognitron, and neocognitron, and score each unit against operational simple/complex/hypercomplex/IT criteria to quantify per-layer correspondence and compare models.</parameter>\n</invoke>\n","method":"junk placeholder two"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that the claimed model-neuron correspondence is asserted by analogy and never measured with a shared instrument (evidence_gap), while connecting neurophysiology protocols with model units is a bridge. The core move is building a benchmark applying probing protocols to score units, i.e. systematic measurement/diagnostics (empirical_mapping), with a unifying comparison across models. Bottleneck is fairly specific (missing audit instrument)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about neocognitron sensitivity explanation gap.","method":"Test method building a simulation observatory platform."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('Test motivation', 'Test method'), giving little signal. Stated explanation gap about neocognitron sensitivity maps to explanation_gap; the deliverable is a simulation observatory platform, so artifact_system. Very generic/boilerplate content lowers confidence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"These works assert but never explain a striking fact. Rosenblatt's perceptron and Fukushima's cognitron are severely affected by shift in position, yet the neocognitron, which only inserts C-cell pooling layers between S-cell selectivity layers, becomes position-invariant and forms units responding to exactly one pattern. Fukushima justifies this only by simulation and rough sketches and admits the mechanism is unknown. Hubel and Wiesel merely describe why complex cells tolerate position over wider areas than simple cells, and inferotemporal recordings report invariant selective units with no generative account. The explanation gap is that there is no causal theory of why interleaving selectivity with pooling yields invariant selective units, why perceptron and cognitron fail, or what governs the invariance-selectivity trade-off. This matters because these are archetypal hierarchical vision models and the answer links their behavior to cortical simple-complex-IT tolerance scaling.","method":"Reimplement the four-layer perceptron, the cognitron with S-layers only, and the neocognitron with alternating S and C stages on common data. Test a two-factor causal hypothesis. Factor one, C-cell pooling, is hypothesized as the sole cause of positional tolerance, compounding across stages with pooling radii; vary pooling radius and stage count and delete C-layers. Factor two, competitive winner-take-all reinforcement with shunting inhibition, is hypothesized to control selectivity and decorrelation but not invariance; vary competition strength, representatives per plane, and inhibition, and lesion competition. Measure invariance range, selectivity purity, and dead or redundant plane counts. Crossing the factors decomposes cause, testing whether invariance depends only on factor one and selectivity only on factor two. Fit a scaling law from factor-one sweeps relating pooling radius and depth to invariance range, then check it against Hubel-Wiesel simple-to-complex receptive-field growth and inferotemporal tolerance, confirming that pooling causes invariance while competition causes selectivity."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames a missing causal/mechanistic account of why pooling-selectivity interleaving yields invariant selective units, and notes conflicting behavior (perceptron/cognitron fail while neocognitron succeeds), so explanation_gap primary with puzzle_contradiction secondary. The method is a two-factor causal decomposition via reimplementation and controlled sweeps/lesions measuring invariance and selectivity — empirical_mapping/diagnostic characterization — with a fitted scaling law checked against cortical data giving a formal_derivation secondary flavor. Precise bottleneck identified (pooling vs competition roles)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"TEST motivation.","method":"TEST method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.3,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal body is placeholder TEST text; labels inferred from titles suggesting a self-organizing network model for shift-invariant pattern recognition, but no substantive content to classify. Low confidence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior works establish a phenomenon they never explain. Hubel and Wiesel show simple-to-complex hierarchies where complex cells gain positional tolerance; Fukushima's cognitron learned features but was position-dependent, while the neocognitron gained position invariance and distortion tolerance by stacking learned S-layers with pooling C-layers whose shift allowance grows little by little, argued only verbally and by simulation. The explanation gap: there is no mathematical account of why graded local pooling accumulates into near-global invariance while preserving shape selectivity, why abrupt pooling destroys discriminability, why position and deformation tolerance co-emerge, and how tolerance growth must track receptive-field and feature-scale growth. This leaves pooling widths and depth heuristic and the essential mechanism unexplained.","method":"Formally derive the invariance-selectivity-deformation tradeoff in alternating simple/complex hierarchies. Model each stage as an S-operator (template matching at feature scale sigma plus threshold) composed with a C-operator (local pooling of radius w), with receptive field and stride growing with depth. Define invariance radius I, class-separation margin M, and deformation tolerance D. Prove an accumulation theorem that I grows additively with the sum of per-stage w; prove an invariance-selectivity bound where M degrades with the ratio w over sigma, so spreading tolerance across many stages keeps M positive while concentrating it collapses M, explaining cognitron and one-step grandmother-cell failure; prove a deformation corollary giving admissible displacement D from w and receptive-field size; and derive an optimal schedule for w and receptive-field growth maximizing I subject to a margin on M, predicting small-early larger-late growth. Add a taxonomy of exact invariance, graded local tolerance, and deformation robustness with a chaining lemma. Validate on the neocognitron's own equations, testing that collapsing pooling into one stage collapses M and that M and I track the bounds as depth and w over sigma vary."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.94,"confidence_paradigm":0.95,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly identifies a missing mathematical account of why graded pooling accumulates invariance while preserving selectivity, which is an explanation_gap; the contrast with abrupt-pooling failures (cognitron, grandmother-cell collapse) adds a puzzle/contradiction flavor. The method is centrally a formal derivation: theorems, bounds, a taxonomy, chaining lemma, and an optimal schedule, validated on the model's own equations. Bottleneck is precisely specified (w/sigma ratio governing margin degradation)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron shows unsupervised competitive self-organization yields shift- and distortion-invariant recognition in a Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex hierarchy, echoing invariant IT-cortex neurons. But there is an explanation gap: why it works, when it fails, and why its hand-picked parameter regime yields clean non-redundant complete coding is unknown. No theory explains the selectivity-invariance trade-off these parameters implement, when self-organization degenerates into redundant or incomplete coding, or how the regime must scale with pattern number and complexity. This matters because the same trade-off appears biologically in complex cells and IT neurons; a causal account would make the model principled rather than hand-tuned.","method":"Build a search and screening framework that reverse-engineers the causal law of neocognitron self-organization. Define emergent outcomes: recognition accuracy, shift-tolerance radius, feature-detector redundancy, representational completeness, per-stage selectivity. Treat per-stage parameters (inhibitory efficacy r_l, reinforcement speed q_l, saturation, C-cell blur d_l, S-column overlap, planes K_l, stage count) as a search space over the reimplemented model trained under randomized shifted presentations. Use fractional-factorial screening to find sensitive parameters and cross-stage interactions, then Bayesian optimization and active adaptive sampling at phase boundaries to map the success basin cheaply. Fit an interpretable sparse symbolic-regression surrogate from parameters to outcomes to extract causal drivers and scaling laws, defining the selectivity-invariance frontier. Validate by predicting parameter settings that preserve clean coding as pattern number and complexity scale, and by checking optimal-regime cells reproduce the simple-to-complex-to-IT selectivity progression. Deliverable: an optimization-discovered predictive account of why and when self-organization succeeds, plus a resource-allocation rule replacing trial-and-error tuning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as why the neocognitron works, when it fails, and why its hand-tuned regime yields clean coding — a missing causal/mechanistic account (explanation_gap), with a selectivity-invariance tradeoff flavor (puzzle_contradiction). The central move is a search/screening framework (fractional-factorial screening, Bayesian optimization, adaptive sampling) to map the success basin, making optimization_search primary; the interpretable symbolic-regression surrogate extracting scaling laws adds formal_derivation. Bottleneck is precisely identified (specific per-stage parameters and their trade-off). Not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980) shows a cascade of plastic S-cell feature detectors and fixed C-cell pooling units yields position- and distortion-invariant recognition, drawn from the Hubel and Wiesel (1962) simple/complex hierarchy and invariant grandmother-cell responses in inferotemporal cortex (Gross et al. 1972). Yet its competence is shown only by simulation, and Fukushima reports an unexplained fragility: recognition is critically influenced by small changes in parameters and in the way of pattern presentation, with no way to say how many cell-planes are needed. There is no causal account of why the S/C cascade creates invariance, why it generalizes to distortion, and why self-organization is so brittle. The prior cognitron (1975) lacked invariance for unanalyzed reasons, and the only rigorous theory in this lineage, Rosenblatt's perceptron convergence analysis (Block, Knight and Rosenblatt 1962), covers only shallow, supervised, position-sensitive nets, leaving the multilayer unsupervised invariance-forming regime unexplained. Without an explanation, design and training remain trial-and-error and the invariance cannot be trusted on realistic noisy inputs.","method":"Build a mechanistic theory of the S/C cascade, then relax its idealized assumptions so the account and model hold in broader, noisier settings. First, model each module as a winner-take-all reinforcement operator composed with a local pooling/blur operator. Track two measurable layer-wise quantities up the cascade: selectivity (discriminability between reinforced patterns) and position tolerance (pooling-induced invariance radius). Derive how their composition trades off as a function of inhibition strength, threshold, receptive-field growth, pooling width, number of cell-planes, and number of patterns, yielding an explicit operating point and a capacity/stability condition with a sharp phase boundary; the claim is that the reported brittleness is the network crossing this boundary into over-blurring or over-selectivity. Second, relax the idealizations under which the neocognitron was validated: replace clean isolated single-pattern presentation with noisy, partial, and overlapping multiple patterns; replace skillful presentation with arbitrary or adversarial order; and replace hand-tuned inhibition and thresholds with a homeostatic self-tuning rule that drives each layer to the derived operating point. Third, validate by re-implementing the neocognitron and cognitron, measuring selectivity and invariance radius layer by layer, testing the predicted phase boundary and capacity condition, and confirming the homeostatic rule restores robust invariant recognition in regimes where the original collapses. Anchor predictions against Hubel and Wiesel's measured receptive-field enlargement and IT invariant selectivity to explain when and why invariant selective units emerge."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a missing causal/mechanistic account of why the S/C cascade creates invariance and why self-organization is brittle (explanation_gap), with the brittleness/unreliability concern as secondary (failure_risk_gap). The central move is building a mechanistic theory with derived quantities, a capacity/stability condition, and a sharp phase boundary (formal_derivation), followed by relaxing idealized assumptions to noisier regimes (relax_extend_scope). The proposal identifies a precise bottleneck (phase boundary between over-blurring and over-selectivity), earning high specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), building on the cognitron and on Hubel and Wiesel's simple/complex-cell hierarchy, shows that shift- and distortion-invariant recognition can emerge from unsupervised self-organization: S-cells learn features by winner-take-all representative selection and greedy synaptic reinforcement, while C-cells blur responses to build invariance. Yet the paper reports an unexplained fragility: scaling to ten patterns, a small deviation of parameter values or a small change in how patterns are presented critically influences whether the self-organized network succeeds. Fukushima only conjectures too few cell-planes; no causal account explains why the same process sometimes yields a clean invariant discriminative code and sometimes collapses. This gap undermines reproducibility and trust, blocks principled scaling, and leaves unclear which ingredients (initial synapse values, presentation order, inhibitory efficacy r_l, C-cell tolerance/blur) cause invariance versus failure. Rosenblatt's perceptron lineage and Hubel and Wiesel's architecture motivate the design but leave the reliability of the emergent code unexplained.","method":"Build a diagnose-then-robustify framework for the neocognitron's self-organization. First, causal diagnosis: fix the architecture and systematically perturb four candidate causal factors (initial synapse values, presentation order and frequency, inhibitory efficacy r_l, and C-cell tolerance/blur radius) over many trials, scoring each with reliability metrics such as whether every last-layer C-cell responds to exactly one pattern, whether every needed feature is captured, and the invariance margin under shift, distortion, size change, and noise. This yields a causal map from ingredient to failure mode, testing the too-few-planes conjecture against alternatives like competition-driven representative oscillation. Second, mechanistic account: from the winner-take-all reinforcement dynamics across overlapping S-columns, formalize why a plane's representative can alternate between similar patterns or commit prematurely. Third, robustification, teacher-free: diversity-enforcing lateral inhibition plus principled cell-plane redundancy; adaptive self-tuning of the selection and inhibition threshold to hold S-cell selectivity in a target band; a consolidation rule that freezes a plane once it reliably wins; and C-cell-layer ensemble voting. Fourth, validation: rerun the perturbation battery to show accuracy and invariance become insensitive to parameter and presentation-order changes, the framework prevents the reported catastrophic failures, and the network scales from five to ten-plus patterns."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is an unexplained fragility (why self-organization sometimes collapses), a missing causal/mechanistic account, so explanation_gap primary with failure_risk_gap secondary since reproducibility/trust is at stake. The method first diagnoses via systematic perturbation (empirical_mapping) then adds mechanisms to reduce brittleness and stabilize the emergent code (robustification primary). Precise candidate causal factors are identified, giving high bottleneck specificity. Not superficial stitching; it deepens an existing model."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: the three literatures are linked only by analogy and lack a mechanistic account of why hierarchical invariance emerges.","method":"Test method: unify perceptron, cognitron, neocognitron, Hubel-Wiesel and retinotectal findings into two primitives P1 competitive learning and P2 staggered pooling, then ablate to show which primitive causes invariance."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation centers on a missing mechanistic account of why hierarchical invariance emerges (explanation_gap), with the observation that literatures are linked only by analogy (bridge_opportunity). The method unifies disparate literatures into two primitives and ablates them, primarily synthesis_unification with a formal reduction to primitives. The stitching of five literatures raises some superficiality concern, but the isolation of P1/P2 primitives and ablation gives moderate bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"test","method":"test method content"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.2,"confidence_paradigm":0.2,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal content is only placeholder ('test'/'test method content'), so no substantive signal exists. Labels are weak guesses informed by prior-work titles about neocognitron and position-invariant pattern recognition, which suggests a scope_mismatch opportunity and an artifact/model as deliverable, but confidence is minimal."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Neocognitron self organization is brittle: small changes in parameters or presentation order critically change recognition, and it cannot reject unfamiliar inputs, causing overconfident misclassification.","method":"Add consensus training over randomized presentation orders to keep only stable feature templates, redundant multi seed reinforcement with adaptive plane growth to remove the single winner point of failure, and an abstention readout using top layer response sharpness versus inhibitory signal to reject unfamiliar inputs. Evaluate on the paper digit and letter stimuli for reproducibility, robustness, and rejection."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as brittleness: sensitivity to parameters/presentation order, single-winner point of failure, and overconfident misclassification of unfamiliar inputs. This is a failure/risk gap. The method directly targets these failures via consensus training, redundant reinforcement, and abstention readout, making robustification the central move. Bottleneck is precisely identified (single-winner instability, no rejection mechanism)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Fukushima's cognitron and neocognitron pioneered position-invariant recognition and are ancestors of modern hierarchical recognizers, yet they were validated only on hand-picked stimuli, so their robustness claims are anecdotal and never measured across a controlled range. The neocognitron paper confesses, without quantifying it, that a small deviation of parameter values or of the way patterns are presented critically influences the self-organized network, and that ten-pattern recognition works only when parameters are properly adjusted and patterns skillfully presented. This is a Failure/Risk gap: the unsupervised self-organization may be brittle and non-deterministic across seeds, presentation order, and parameters; the selectivity-versus-tolerance trade-off set by the inhibition parameter is only called a needed compromise; and the claimed biological fidelity to Hubel and Wiesel receptive fields and IT-cortex invariant selectivity was never quantitatively checked. The prior works supply the models and biological targets but no systematic measurement of when, why, and how reliably they succeed.","method":"Reimplement the cognitron and neocognitron and build a reproducible stress-test benchmark that maps their reliability and failure surface. Component one, a reproducibility map: run self-organization over many seeds, randomized presentation orders, and parameter settings, measuring variance in accuracy, number of well-formed feature cell-planes, and the one-cell-per-pattern property, summarized as a stability index. Component two, an invariance envelope: apply a graded perturbation battery (translation, scale, rotation, elastic deformation, stroke thinning, occlusion, noise, contrast) and record continuous accuracy-degradation surfaces to locate breaking points. Component three, a selectivity-tolerance frontier: sweep the inhibition parameter and thresholds to chart the trade-off between discriminating confusable patterns and tolerating deformation. Component four, a biological-alignment diagnostic: compare emergent S-cell and C-cell receptive fields to quantitative targets from the neuroscience sources and test whether failure regions correlate with departures from biological organization. Release datasets, metrics, maps, and protocol as a reusable benchmark that converts anecdotal robustness claims into measured, reproducible evidence."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal identifies brittleness/non-determinism of self-organization and unquantified robustness as a failure/risk gap, closely tied to lack of systematic measurement (evidence gap). The core move is building a reproducible stress-test benchmark mapping reliability, invariance envelopes, and trade-off frontiers, which is empirical_mapping. The benchmark release is a byproduct rather than a novel artifact-system deliverable. Precise bottlenecks (inhibition parameter trade-off, seed/order variance, biological alignment) are named specifically."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about brittleness of Neocognitron self-organization and unbounded invariance.","method":"Test method proposing a formal operator model with a certified invariance radius theorem and a Lyapunov learning-stability theorem."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation centers on brittleness of self-organization and unbounded invariance (failure_risk_gap), with an implicit missing formal account (explanation_gap). The method introduces formal operator model with a certified invariance radius theorem and Lyapunov stability theorem, clearly formal_derivation, aimed at robustness guarantees."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), building on the cognitron (1975/1981), the perceptron (Rosenblatt 1962), and the Hubel–Wiesel functional-architecture hierarchy, learns position-invariant feature detectors \"without a teacher\" by repeatedly presenting patterns and reinforcing \"representative\" S-cells selected by a winner-take-all rule within S-columns. This self-organization is, by the author's own account, alarmingly brittle and non-reproducible: \"a small deviation of the values of the parameters, or a small change of the way of pattern presentation, has critically influenced upon the ability of the self-organized network,\" and correct recognition of even ten digits required parameters to be \"properly adjusted\" and patterns to be \"skillfully presented.\"\n\nThree interacting sources of fragility remain unaddressed: (1) the number of cell-planes per layer is fixed by hand (24 in every layer) and is explicitly conjectured to be insufficient, yet was never made data-driven — too few planes leave features uncovered, and no principled way exists to size the network; (2) the selectivity/inhibition parameters (e.g., the inhibitory efficacy r_l and the effective S-cell selectivity, the recurring \"pattern-selectivity\" problem of the cognitron) are hand-tuned, so cells easily become either \"dead\" (never selected as representatives, never reinforced) or promiscuous; (3) the winner-take-all representative selection makes the learned feature dictionary depend on initialization and on the order/positions of pattern presentation. The net effect is unreliable, poorly reproducible feature dictionaries with redundant or dead cell-planes and unstable downstream recognition. Reliability and reproducibility of the self-organized detectors are prerequisites for trusting such a recognizer, so this failure/risk gap is exactly what these works leave open: they demonstrate the capability but not a robust, repeatable way to obtain it.","method":"Replace the neocognitron's fixed, hand-tuned, order-sensitive self-organization with an optimization/search-driven, self-sizing procedure that certifies robustness, while keeping the S/C (simple/complex) hierarchy and unsupervised \"learning without a teacher.\"\n\n(1) Adaptive selectivity/inhibition tuning via online screening. Treat the S-cell selectivity threshold and the inhibitory efficacy r_l in each layer as free variables tuned online rather than fixed. During self-organization, monitor per-layer activation statistics that the model already produces (fraction of S-columns yielding a strongly responding representative, and the response margin between winning and runner-up cells). Use a simple bisection/feedback search to drive these statistics to target set-points that keep cells neither dead nor promiscuous, directly attacking the cognitron pattern-selectivity fragility.\n\n(2) Data-driven cell-plane allocation (grow/prune) to replace the fixed count of 24. Because all cells in a plane share one weight template, templates are directly comparable. When a presented pattern (feature) elicits no representative above threshold in any existing plane at a stage, allocate a new cell-plane (resource growth); when two planes' learned templates become near-duplicates, merge/prune them (redundancy removal). The network thus sizes itself per layer to achieve full feature coverage with minimal redundancy, testing the author's conjecture that more planes yield steadily better recognition.\n\n(3) Active/adaptive presentation scheduling to replace \"skillful presentation.\" Instead of a fixed or random order, an active-design scheduler chooses the next pattern and its position to maximize expected reduction in a coverage-gap score (prioritizing patterns/positions currently least represented in the dictionary), turning the ad hoc \"skillful\" schedule into a principled sampling policy.\n\n(4) Reproducibility screening as an outer optimization loop. Run several short self-organization trajectories under different seeds and presentation orders; define a robustness objective combining (i) recognition accuracy on shifted/distorted inputs and (ii) the variance of the final feature dictionary and accuracy across seeds/orders. Search over the remaining meta-parameters (learning rate q, receptive-field sizes, target set-points) to maximize this objective, yielding a configuration whose self-organized detectors are stable and repeatable.\n\nEvaluation follows the original paper's digital simulation protocol: self-organize on digit/letter sets with randomly shifted positions, then measure (a) recognition accuracy under shift and small distortion, (b) reproducibility (accuracy and dictionary-template variance across seeds/orders), and (c) counts of dead and redundant cell-planes, comparing against the fixed-parameter, fixed-24-plane baseline. Success is substantially reduced sensitivity to parameter perturbation and presentation order at equal or better accuracy, with an automatically chosen, non-redundant number of cell-planes — converting a fragile, hand-crafted self-organization into a robust, self-sizing, order-invariant one."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed around brittleness, non-reproducibility, and instability of the neocognitron's self-organization (failure_risk_gap). The core research move reduces these failures via adaptive tuning, self-sizing, and reproducibility screening (robustification), heavily leveraging feedback search, grow/prune allocation, active scheduling, and outer-loop optimization (optimization_search secondary). It precisely identifies mechanisms of fragility (dead/promiscuous cells, fixed plane count, order-sensitivity), earning high bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron is brittle and unreliable: Fukushima admits scaling to ten digits made it critically sensitive to small parameter changes and to presentation order, needing skillful presentation of clean data. It uses winner-take-all over a fixed preset number of cell-planes that fails silently when too few, a hand-tuned global inhibition parameter, and single-winner reinforcement, tolerating noise only at test time and giving no confidence output. This reproducibility and silent-failure risk is left open by prior works.","method":"Extend neocognitron self-organization to weaker assumptions while keeping the S-cell and C-cell architecture. Replace the fixed global inhibition parameter with per-plane thresholds adapting to each plane running activation statistics. Add a novelty test recruiting a new cell-plane when the best match is too low and merging duplicate planes so capacity grows with pattern diversity. Reinforce only features recurring across several noisy jittered occluded presentations via a running template to reduce order and noise sensitivity. Derive a confidence score from the final-layer top versus runner-up margin and total inhibition to enable abstention. Evaluate by reproducing the 1980 simulations then measuring output variance over random orders and parameter perturbations, accuracy and abstention under noise occlusion and imbalance, and scaling beyond ten patterns without retuning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as brittleness, silent failure, parameter sensitivity, reproducibility, and lack of confidence output (failure_risk_gap), with a secondary concern about the fixed preset assumptions and narrow clean-data regime (scope_mismatch). The method centrally reduces these failures via adaptive thresholds, novelty-based capacity growth, noise-robust reinforcement, and abstention (robustification), while extending self-organization to weaker assumptions (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottlenecks (global inhibition parameter, fixed cell-plane count, single-winner reinforcement) are identified, giving high specificity. Not superficial stitching since it modifies the core mechanism."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The self-organizing hierarchical pattern recognizers in this lineage — the neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), built on the cognitron (1975/1981), inspired by the Hubel–Wiesel simple/complex-cell hierarchy (1962, 1977) and Rosenblatt's perceptrons (1962) — achieve shift- and small-distortion-invariant recognition through unsupervised learning without a teacher. But the neocognitron paper itself exposes a brittleness/reliability gap it never resolves: with ten patterns, a small deviation of the parameter values, or a small change in the way of pattern presentation, critically degraded the ability of the self-organized network. Concretely: (i) many constants (inhibitory efficacies r_l, reinforcement speeds q_l, saturation alpha, selectivity thresholds) are hand-tuned by trial and error; (ii) learning is highly sensitive to stimulus presentation order; (iii) the deterministic winner-take-all representative selection can let one cell-plane capture two similar categories or leave categories unrepresented, giving unstable, non-reproducible feature dictionaries across runs; and (iv) the network always emits a confident C-cell decision with no signal that a noisy, distorted, ambiguous, or novel input (the illegible-letters open problem) is being recognized unreliably. None of the provided sources quantify or mitigate this: the cognitron shares the same winner-take-all hand-tuned-threshold rule, and the biological sources only motivate the architecture. This parameter- and schedule-fragility plus silent failure undermines trust in the model as both engineering recognizer and brain model, leaving clear room for a robustified, reproducible, uncertainty-aware self-organization.","method":"We robustify neocognitron-style self-organization by changing only the learning rule and readout, keeping the biological S-cell/C-cell hierarchy. (1) Homeostatic self-calibrating thresholds: replace fragile hand-set constants (r_l, q_l, alpha, selectivity thresholds) with adaptive values driven by running per-plane activation statistics, so each plane fires for a target fraction of presentations; the most brittle parameters self-tune to the data instead of being tuned by hand. (2) Diversity-promoting redundant committee selection: replicate each feature slot into K parallel cell-planes and reinforce a small set of representatives under a dissimilarity (lateral-inhibition) constraint forbidding two planes from converging onto the same feature template; unclaimed planes are recruited to under-represented features. This guarantees category coverage, prevents the X/Y/T/Z collapse where one plane absorbs two similar patterns, and makes the learned dictionary approximately order-invariant. (3) Order-averaged reinforcement: accumulate updates over a mini-batch/epoch and apply the average, with annealed set-points, decoupling learned templates from any single stimulus sequence. (4) Margin-based uncertainty gate: at the output, compute the top-vs-runner-up C-cell margin and a consensus score (agreement across the K redundant planes and across position-wise piecewise matches); when margin or consensus is low, abstain and flag uncertain/novel rather than force a decision, directly handling noise, distortion, and out-of-distribution inputs. (5) Reproducibility-first evaluation: reproduce the digit and X/Y/T/Z experiments and, for both original and robustified networks, measure accuracy variance across random parameter perturbations, across randomized presentation schedules and seeds, accuracy-vs-noise/distortion, and accuracy-vs-abstention (selective-risk) curves. Success = sharply reduced run-to-run and parameter-sensitivity variance, graceful noise degradation, and reliable abstention on ambiguous inputs, while matching baseline accuracy on clean data. All additions are local and biologically plausible (redundancy and lateral inhibition mirror the cortical column/hypercolumn organization the model already emulates) and feasible in the same digital simulation, converting a brittle, over-confident recognizer into a stable, self-calibrating, uncertainty-aware one."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly around brittleness, parameter fragility, order sensitivity, and silent overconfident failure — a clear failure_risk_gap identified from the original paper's own admissions. The method's central move is robustifying self-organization (homeostatic thresholds, diversity constraints, order-averaging, uncertainty gating) to reduce failures and instability, squarely robustification. It precisely names the limiting mechanisms (hand-tuned constants, winner-take-all collapse, presentation-order dependence). Though multi-component, the additions cohere around reliability rather than being a superficial A+B stitch."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The Cognitron and Neocognitron achieve shift-invariant recognition with an S-cell and C-cell hierarchy inspired by Hubel and Wiesel, but Fukushima reports a fragility gap: small changes in parameters or presentation order critically alter the self-organized network, and success required hand-tuning and skillful presentation. Its unsupervised winner-take-all learning has no teacher, no convergence guarantee, and no control over which class each C-cell learns, so it is non-reproducible and brittle. Rosenblatt perceptron work has error-correction with convergence proofs and graceful degradation under unit removal, but lacks shift and distortion invariance. Inferotemporal recordings show invariant selectivity modulated during discrimination, hinting reinforcement shapes invariant detectors. These reliable-but-not-invariant and invariant-but-brittle lines have never been reconciled.","method":"Unify the neocognitron invariant S and C cell hierarchy with the perceptron error-correction learning. Keep tied-weight S-planes and C-cell pooling for shift invariance. Replace unsupervised winner-take-all plasticity with a dual-signal rule: each S-cell weight update is the product of a bottom-up Hebbian term and a top-down perceptron-style error-correction signal propagated through the tied weights, making the class-to-C-cell mapping deterministic and reproducible. Add reinforcement-plus-decay stability to bound weights and yield a convergence argument. Gate the reinforcement to a discrimination phase, echoing inferotemporal modulation. Evaluate on the source papers digit and letter sets for reproducibility, brittleness under perturbation and distortion, and fault tolerance under unit removal, targeting perceptron-level reliability with neocognitron-level invariance."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a contradiction between reliable-but-not-invariant (perceptron) and invariant-but-brittle (neocognitron) lines that have never been reconciled, and the proposed move is to unify the two learning paradigms (synthesis_unification) with a robustification aim of reproducibility/convergence/fault-tolerance. The bottleneck (unsupervised WTA lacking teacher/convergence) is precisely identified. There is some risk of surface A+B stitching (neocognitron hierarchy + perceptron error-correction), but the dual-signal rule through tied weights is a specific mechanistic integration."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal body is placeholder text ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), so labels rely on title/prior-work context. The neocognitron addresses position-invariant pattern recognition (scope mismatch of prior perceptron models) by building a neural network model inspired by visual cortex architecture (artifact/system, bridging neuroscience and computation). Low confidence due to absent substantive content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"A puzzle runs across these works: two learning regimes each solve half the problem and fail at what the other achieves. The perceptron line (Rosenblatt's Principles of Neurodynamics; Block, Knight and Rosenblatt's four-layer series-coupled perceptron) learns by teacher-driven reinforcement and error-correction, giving reliable designer-controlled category assignment and provable convergence on an imposed dichotomy, but its responses collapse under shift in position and shape distortion. The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), built on the Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy and the cognitron, achieves the opposite through purely unsupervised competitive learning (winner-take-all selection of representative seed S-cells): striking position- and distortion-invariant recognition, yet with a surprising fragility. Fukushima reports that recognizing even ten patterns requires a human to skillfully present them and hand-tune parameters, where a small deviation of parameters or presentation order critically ruins the result, and, lacking a teacher, the network gives no control over which grandmother cell fires for which category. So invariance and controllable robust category learning arise from opposite regimes, and the mechanism buying invariance (no teacher) is what causes fragility and label ambiguity. Biology hints at a resolution: inferotemporal grandmother-like neurons (Gross et al. 1972) show responses modulated by whether the animal performs a discrimination task (Sato et al. 1980), suggesting a top-down task signal shapes the highest feature detectors. No model here combines the invariance-building unsupervised hierarchy with such a sparse top-down teaching signal.","method":"Reinforcement-gated competitive learning. Keep the neocognitron S/C cascade and its unsupervised representative-selection rule in the lower modules that build local features and positional tolerance, but govern the deepest S-layer with a Rosenblatt-style corrective-reinforcement rule driven by a category teacher, assigning the two conflicting requirements to different depths of one hierarchy. Steps: (1) Lower layers self-organize exactly as in Fukushima 1980, so invariance stays bottom-up. (2) Partition the deepest S-layer cell-planes into disjoint pools, one per target category, plus reserve planes. (3) Teacher-gated seed selection: on each labeled pattern compute the usual winning representative per S-column, but make a representative eligible for reinforcement only if it lies in the taught category pool; if the strongest response comes from a wrong pool, apply corrective reinforcement, strengthening the winning representative in the correct pool and depressing the erroneously winning plane. This applies the perceptron error-correction rule to the seed-selection step of competitive self-organization rather than to a linear readout. (4) Optional top-down attentional gate: the category signal biases which S-column supplies the seed, mimicking IT task modulation. Why it dissolves the paradox: invariance comes free from the unchanged unsupervised lower layers, while the top layer inherits perceptron guarantees of a designer-chosen one-cell-per-category mapping and convergence toward correct dichotomization; the teacher supplies the skillful presentation Fukushima gave by hand, so sensitivity to parameters and presentation order should drop. Evaluation: reproduce Fukushima digit and alphanumeric simulations and compare the unsupervised neocognitron against the reinforcement-gated variant on patterns learnable at fixed cell-plane count, sensitivity to parameter perturbations and shuffled presentation orders, controllability of the category-to-cell mapping, and retained shift and distortion invariance. Success means preserved invariance plus eliminated label ambiguity and flatter sensitivity curves."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a puzzle/tradeoff: two learning regimes each solve half the problem, with invariance and controllable robustness arising from opposite mechanisms; secondary failure_risk_gap because unsupervised fragility and label ambiguity are central. The method reconciles the perceptron error-correction line and the neocognitron unsupervised hierarchy into one architecture (synthesis_unification), assigning conflicting requirements to different depths, with robustification as the payoff (flatter sensitivity curves). Though it combines two prior systems, the integration is mechanistically motivated (teacher-gated seed selection at the deepest layer), not superficial stitching. Bottleneck is precisely identified: the no-teacher mechanism buying invariance is what causes fragility."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('Test motivation/method'), so labels rely on title/prior-work context. The neocognitron addresses shift-invariant pattern recognition (scope_mismatch: prior models fail to handle position shifts) motivated by visual cortex biology. Central deliverable is a self-organizing neural network model/artifact, with secondary bridging of neuroscience and computation. Low confidence due to empty proposal body."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"A paradox sits at the center of these works. Fukushima's neocognitron (1980) obtains position-invariant recognition through C-cell pooling whose defining rule is disjunctive: a C-cell \"responds strongly whenever at least one S-cell in its connecting area yields a large output,\" so a shifted pattern still fires the cell because a neighboring S-cell fires instead. This OR-over-position operation is exactly what discards where a feature is. Yet the paper itself concedes the opposite pressure: the inhibitory-gain parameter r_z must be set as a \"compromise between the ability to differentiate similar patterns and the ability to tolerate distortion,\" and the cognitron (1975) is described as recognizing patterns well precisely because it was NOT position tolerant. So invariance and selectivity are treated as antagonists tuned by hand.\n\nThe contradiction becomes acute when the model is placed against the biology it invokes. Fukushima cites inferotemporal neurons (Gross et al., 1972; Sato et al., 1980) that respond to highly specific complex shapes — hands, silhouettes, \"grandmother cells\" — and whose responses are \"scarcely affected by the position or the size of the stimuli.\" Hubel & Wiesel (1962, 1965, 1977) likewise describe a simple→complex→hypercomplex progression that simultaneously grows receptive-field size (invariance) and feature specificity (selectivity). Biology apparently attains both at once; the neocognitron's own pooling mechanism says you must trade one for the other, and Rosenblatt's perceptron analyses (1962) frame recognition capacity purely as a discrimination problem with no invariance machinery.\n\nThe gap: nowhere in this literature is there a formal account of why disjunctive pooling should destroy selectivity (the classic superposition/binding ambiguity — a pool that records \"feature present somewhere\" cannot tell a face from its scrambled parts), how severe that loss is, or under what conditions a hierarchy can escape it and recover the biological \"selective AND invariant\" regime. Because the tradeoff is left as a hand-tuned parameter rather than a derived quantity, there is no principled prescription for how invariance should be allocated across layers, and no explanation for the observed gradual receptive-field growth.","method":"Contribution is a formal model, a bound, and a resulting taxonomy/prescription for hierarchical S/C networks.\n\n1. Formal model. Represent a stimulus as a configuration: a multiset of local features f∈{1..K} at positions on a lattice. An S-stage is a conjunctive operator (AND) that fires only for a specific feature at a specific *relative* offset within its window; a C-stage is a disjunctive operator (OR) pooling one feature over a translation region of radius ρ. A depth-L network is an alternating cascade S_1 C_1 … S_L C_L (the neocognitron/Hubel–Wiesel scheme). Define two measurable quantities for the top layer: (a) translation tolerance T = size of the input-shift set over which the top code is invariant; (b) configurational selectivity, measured as the mutual information I(code ; exact configuration), equivalently the number N of distinct configurations mapped to distinct top codes without collision.\n\n2. Bound (the tradeoff theorem). Model a single OR-pool over a window of A positions as a channel that retains feature identity but marginalizes out within-window position. Derive that each such pool caps the retained configural information by removing up to log A bits per pooled feature, and that the probability of a \"false binding\" (two configurations differing only by rearranged features within a pool becoming indistinguishable) grows monotonically with A and feature density. This yields a per-stage invariance–selectivity inequality of the form (information lost) ≥ log(tolerance gained): you cannot buy translation tolerance A in one stage without paying ≈log A bits of configural discriminability. This formalizes Fukushima's r_z \"compromise\" as a hard bound rather than a tuning heuristic.\n\n3. Resolution of the paradox (the key derivation). Decompose total tolerance and total selectivity cost across depth. Because tolerance composes multiplicatively across stages (a shift is absorbed if it lies within any stage's cumulative pool) while the AND-stages between pools *re-bind* features into specific local relative configurations at the still-fine scale, the selectivity cost is only additive in the number of stages. Formally: to reach a target tolerance R, a single aggressive pool pays ≈log R bits, whereas L stages each pooling radius r with R≈r^L pay only ≈L·log r = log R bits *of within-window position* but preserve all *cross-window relative* configuration through the interleaved conjunctions. Prove that under a feature-sparsity condition (bounded features per pool window) the deep gradual hierarchy strictly dominates the shallow one: it achieves the same T with exponentially higher N. This is a formal statement of how \"selective AND invariant\" IT-type responses are possible — invariance built compositionally, not by one large blur.\n\n4. Optimal schedule and predictions. Casting \"maximize T subject to selectivity ≥ target\" as an optimization over the per-layer pooling radii {ρ_ℓ} yields, via the additivity of costs and multiplicativity of tolerance, an equalized (geometric) growth schedule: constant ratio ρ_{ℓ+1}/ρ_ℓ, i.e., receptive fields should expand gradually and by a fixed factor per stage — a derived explanation for the Hubel–Wiesel simple→complex→hypercomplex RF-growth progression and a concrete prescription for scheduling r_z / pool size layer-by-layer in the neocognitron (small tolerance increments per stage rather than one late invariant readout).\n\n5. Validation. (i) Analytic: prove the bound and the dominance theorem for the lattice model. (ii) Simulation on the neocognitron itself: vary the pooling schedule at fixed final tolerance and measure N (patterns kept separable) and false-binding rate on part-rearranged stimuli, testing the predicted geometric-schedule optimum and the superposition-catastrophe scaling with pool area. (iii) Physiological consistency: check that the predicted per-stage tolerance/selectivity accumulation reproduces the reported combination of position/size invariance and shape specificity in inferotemporal neurons and the graded RF enlargement in striate/prestriate cortex.\n\nThis turns the qualitative \"compromise\" acknowledged by Fukushima and the biological puzzle raised by Gross and Hubel–Wiesel into a derived tradeoff bound, and shows precisely which architectural discipline (many shallow, conjunction-interleaved pools on a geometric schedule) escapes it."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an explicit paradox: disjunctive pooling discards position (invariance) while destroying selectivity, yet biology achieves both, and Fukushima treats the tradeoff as a hand-tuned parameter. This is puzzle_contradiction with a strong explanation_gap component (why disjunctive pooling destroys selectivity, how deep hierarchies escape). The central move is a formal model, an invariance-selectivity bound/theorem, and derived optimal schedule—clearly formal_derivation. The optimization-schedule element is subsidiary to the derivation. Precise bottleneck (log-A information loss per pool, additive vs multiplicative composition) is identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about neocognitron selectivity-tolerance tradeoff versus supervised perceptron position sensitivity.","method":"Search the per-layer selectivity and tolerance schedule with an outer optimization loop while keeping unsupervised feature learning inner loop."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation frames a selectivity-tolerance tradeoff and contrasts with perceptron position sensitivity, a puzzle/contradiction framing with a brittleness/failure undertone. The method's central move is an outer optimization loop searching the per-layer selectivity/tolerance schedule while retaining unsupervised inner learning, clearly optimization_search. The tradeoff bottleneck is reasonably specific though not deeply mechanistic."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), grounded in the cognitron, Hubel-Wiesel, and inferotemporal grandmother-cell work, is celebrated for learning without a teacher, its warrant being robust autonomous biological self-organization such as retinotectal regeneration (Meyer and Sperry 1974). Paradox: the authors admit that with more classes, small parameter or presentation-order changes critically degrade it, and success needed skillfully presented patterns, tuned parameters, and a fixed pre-set number of cell-planes. So the most teacher-free paradigm is actually the most brittle and covertly engineered, contradicting the robust biology it models. It was shown only on clean single centered patterns, not novelty, clutter, or arbitrary order. Robustness of unsupervised feature formation, not just invariance, is what makes it a credible model of cortical development and a usable recognizer.","method":"Relax assumptions to make neocognitron self-organization robust. Add a per-column vigilance test: when no representative S-cell's normalized activation exceeds a similarity threshold, recruit a new cell-plane initialized to that feature instead of forcing a poor match, so capacity grows with data and late-introduced classes get detectors; merge duplicate planes and prune dead ones. Add homeostatic regulation: each plane adjusts its shunting-inhibition gain by how often it wins, spreading representation regardless of order or class frequency and removing the global tuned inhibition parameter. Broaden the regime with randomized order, noise, jitter, variable size, occlusion, and novel patterns. Evaluate variance of recognition across random parameter and order perturbations versus the fixed-plane baseline, sub-linear plane growth with class count, incremental learning without catastrophic reallocation, and a retinotectal-style self-repair test after removing planes. Baselines: original fixed-capacity neocognitron and a recruitment-only ablation without homeostasis."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a paradox: the most teacher-free paradigm is actually the most brittle and covertly engineered, contradicting the robust biology it models — a clear puzzle_contradiction, with secondary scope_mismatch (only shown on clean centered patterns). The method targets reducing brittleness of unsupervised feature formation via vigilance recruitment and homeostatic regulation (robustification), and broadens to noisier/novel regimes (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottleneck identified (global tuned inhibition, fixed cell-plane count, order sensitivity), so high bottleneck_specificity. Not superficial stitching; components are mechanistically integrated to fix the identified failure."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about neocognitron brittleness paradox.","method":"Test method about robustifying self-organization."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The stub references a 'brittleness paradox' motivating a failure/risk gap, with a puzzle/contradiction flavor, and the method aims at robustifying self-organization. Content is sparse and generic, limiting confidence and specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about invariance being hardwired versus learned.","method":"Test method building a unified hierarchy that learns both selectivity and pooling."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The gap concerns whether position-invariant recognition must be hardwired versus learned, extending prior recognition models to handle shift invariance (scope_mismatch), with an underlying question of mechanism (explanation_gap). The central move is constructing a concrete self-organizing hierarchical network model that learns both feature selectivity and pooling (artifact_system), inspired by unifying visual cortex architecture with neural network learning (synthesis_unification). Terse proposal text limits confidence."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Resource-bottleneck gap. These sources established a still-underexploited property: position-invariant pattern recognition can be acquired WITHOUT a teacher. Fukushima's cognitron and neocognitron show that repeatedly presenting unlabeled stimuli, plus local synaptic reinforcement and complex-cell (C-cell) pooling, builds shift tolerance mirroring the Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex/hypercomplex hierarchy, IT-cortex invariant selectivity, and activity-dependent retinotectal reorganization. Yet the REALIZATION of these models, not the theory, is the bottleneck. Compute/time: the neocognitron was only a serial digital simulation on tiny hand-curated stimulus sets, and its learning step (globally selecting one representative/seed cell per S-plane and reinforcing it) is inherently serial and unscalable. Usability: the number of feature planes and selectivity thresholds must be set by hand per layer, making experiments labor-intensive and non-reproducible. Deployment friction: the global winner-selection offers no path to a parallel physical device that learns online from a live sensor. Thus these models solve the labeling bottleneck but stay blocked by compute, scalability, tuning burden, and deployment. Nothing in the provided works removes these barriers: the perceptron needs supervised correction, and cognitron/neocognitron exist only as small serial simulations. This leaves clear room for a systems contribution.","method":"Artifact/System contribution: build a tiled, mixed-signal self-organizing cortical-column array (prototyped on FPGA plus analog front-end, with an open mapping toolchain) that physically instantiates the neocognitron's alternating S-cell/C-cell module stack so unsupervised, position-invariant recognition self-organizes online from a live camera stream, removing the serial-simulation, hand-tuning, and deployment bottlenecks. Components: (1) Column tiles: each tile realizes one hypercolumn/S-column with analog convolution over a fixed local connectable area (e.g. 5x5) implementing simple-cell receptive fields with shunting inhibition as in the neocognitron; tiles replicate across the field for spatial parallelism. (2) Local competitive plasticity: replace the global representative search with on-tile lateral-inhibition winner-take-all within each column, reinforcing the winner's synapses by the local Hebbian r.m.s.-cognitron rule, so learning is fully parallel and streams in real time. (3) Growth instead of manual allocation: an activity monitor commits a dormant plane as a new feature detector whenever all existing winners fall below a floor (inspired by retinotectal reorganization), removing pre-specified plane counts. (4) C-cell pooling tiles: fixed spatial averaging between modules gives progressive shift tolerance so deeper modules acquire IT-like invariance. (5) Self-tuning controller: a lightweight on-device loop adjusts each layer's selectivity threshold and reinforcement rate from running activity statistics (target one-winner-per-plane sparsity), removing manual tuning. (6) Toolchain: a description language to stack arbitrary S/C module depths, map them onto tiles, and log energy, wall-clock self-organization time, and accuracy. Evaluation: stream unlabeled character/shape and digit imagery and measure whether last-layer cells become one-pattern-selective and shift-invariant (reproducing the neocognitron result) but learned online; scaling of self-organization time and energy versus equivalent digital simulation as input size and plane count grow; and robustness of the growth and self-tuning mechanisms. Success: label-free invariant recognition self-organizing at frame rate at scales serial simulation cannot reach, with no manual plane allocation or threshold tuning, turning a proven-but-unscalable model into a deployable edge-vision artifact."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames the gap as a resource/deployment bottleneck: the neocognitron works in theory but is stuck as a serial simulation with hand-tuning and no path to parallel physical hardware. The central move is building a concrete mixed-signal FPGA+analog cortical-column array artifact with toolchain, clearly artifact_system. Local WTA replacing global search, growth mechanisms, and self-tuning address scalability/tuning specifically (high bottleneck specificity). Not mere A+B stitching since it re-engineers the learning rule for parallelism."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980) shows a Hubel-Wiesel-style hierarchy of S-cell/C-cell modules can self-organize without a teacher into a shift- and distortion-tolerant recognizer. But the paper is explicit that its limits are resource-driven, not conceptual. First, fixed capacity limited by memory: it hard-codes 24 cell-planes per layer, states 24 are not sufficient for recognizing ten different patterns, that more planes would likely help, but that simulating more than 24 planes has not been done because of the lack of memory capacity of the computer. Each plane also maintains a full retinotopic activation array, so dense S/C-cell arrays are the true memory wall. Second, high tuning and experimental burden: ten-class success held only provided that parameters are properly adjusted and stimulus patterns are skillfully presented, and a small deviation of parameter values, or a small change in the way of presentation, critically influenced the outcome. Selectivity thresholds, reinforcement speeds and presentation order are all hand-set and brittle. Thus the model's demonstrated capability cannot scale to more classes or larger inputs without prohibitive memory and manual tuning cost. The gap: let such a self-organizing hierarchy consume only as much memory and parameter-supervision as a task actually requires.","method":"Build a resource-adaptive, self-regulating neocognitron that keeps the S/C-cell hierarchy, weight-sharing within a cell-plane, and unsupervised winner-take-all representative reinforcement, but makes three rationed resources demand-driven. First, novelty-triggered plane recruitment: start each S-layer with zero or one plane; on each presentation run the existing representative-selection competition, and if the best existing plane's match to a strongly active S-column falls below a criterion, recruit a new plane seeded from that column's afferent pattern using the same reinforcement rule. Planes are added only for genuinely new features, so capacity grows to fit the data, no memory is wasted on empty or redundant planes, and allocation no longer depends on skillful presentation order. Second, homeostatic threshold auto-tuning: replace hand-set selectivity parameters with a per-plane control loop that tracks recent firing statistics and adjusts each plane's threshold to hold a target sparsity, sharpening promiscuous planes and loosening or pruning silent ones, removing brittle manual tuning. Third, sparse retinotopic instantiation: exploit progressive C-cell pooling and spatial sparsity by computing and storing S- and C-cell responses only where presynaptic C-cells are active; since a plane is one shared kernel, the recognizer becomes shared kernels plus a sparse active-site list, collapsing the dominant activation-memory cost. Evaluation: reproduce the original digital-simulation protocol (shifted and distorted digits 0-9, then confusable X/Y/T/Z), measuring accuracy, planes auto-recruited per layer, peak memory, and sensitivity to parameter and presentation-order perturbations, versus the fixed-24-plane hand-tuned baseline. Success: match or exceed baseline accuracy while recruiting only needed planes, using far less activation memory, and staying flat across randomized parameter initializations and presentation orders. All ingredients exist in the source; the contribution is making each demand-driven so the model scales under fixed modest memory and without expert tuning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly resource-driven (memory wall from fixed 24 planes, dense retinotopic arrays) plus brittleness from manual tuning, so primary opportunity is resource_bottleneck with secondary failure_risk_gap. The method extends the neocognitron to operate under fixed modest memory without expert tuning via demand-driven recruitment, homeostatic auto-tuning, and sparse instantiation—relaxing/extending its operating regime, with robustification against brittle parameters as secondary. Bottleneck is precisely identified (activation memory, plane capacity, tuning sensitivity). Ingredients come from the source but recombined into demand-driven mechanisms, not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The cognitron (Fukushima 1975/1981) and neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), grounded in the Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex-cell hierarchy (1962) and position-invariant inferotemporal responses (Gross 1972; Sato 1980), achieve unsupervised shift-invariant recognition, but their use is throttled by a resource bottleneck the papers themselves flag. The neocognitron recognizes ten patterns only when parameters are properly adjusted and patterns skillfully presented, with small parameter or presentation-order changes critically degrading it, and scaling past 24 cell-planes was impossible for lack of computer memory. Progress is thus limited by memory scalability, training burden, and blind parameter tuning, with no way to predict how much capacity or training a task needs. Prior works give mechanisms but no empirical map of how performance and invariance trade off against these resource costs, leaving the models costly, irreproducible, and impossible to provision rationally.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map (benchmark plus diagnostic) of the resource-performance frontier for these networks. Reimplement the cognitron and neocognitron as described, with S/C-cell modules, cell-planes, winner-take-all reinforcement, inhibitory ratio, selectivity threshold, and connectable-area size. Use standardized stimulus batteries of graded difficulty from the sources: digits 0-9; confusable sets like X/Y/T/Z; controlled shift, size, and distortion suites; and feature-complexity ladders motivated by the simple-to-hypercomplex progression and IT-cortex selectivity. Sweep three resource axes: cell-planes per layer for memory, number and order of presentations for training time and data, and core parameters. Measure accuracy and confusion structure, invariance range, convergence in presentations to stable weights, stability, and per-parameter sensitivity. Deliver empirical scaling laws and phase diagrams predicting minimal cell-planes and presentations as a function of pattern-set size and inter-pattern similarity, a sensitivity diagnostic ranking which parameters and presentation orders dominate failure, a head-to-head cognitron-versus-neocognitron comparison on one battery, and a capacity-planning predictor that estimates required resources for a target pattern set. This replaces trial-and-error tuning with measured up-front provisioning, and is feasible because results were originally simulation-based and modern hardware removes the 24-cell-plane ceiling."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a resource bottleneck (memory scalability, training burden, blind parameter tuning) flagged by the original papers, with a secondary evidence gap (no empirical map of tradeoffs). The core research move is building a systematic benchmark/diagnostic map of the resource-performance frontier — empirical_mapping — with resource-axis sweeps and capacity-planning prediction giving an optimization_search secondary. Precise bottleneck identification (cell-planes, presentations, parameters). Not stitching; it deepens rather than combines."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron self-organizes shift-invariant features but its scalability is a resource bottleneck: cell-planes per layer are fixed by hand, 24 was reported insufficient for ten patterns, and more could not be simulated due to lack of computer memory. No principle says how many feature planes a layer needs, forcing wasteful over-provisioning or failure-prone under-provisioning.","method":"Derive a formal per-layer capacity theory for simple and complex cell hierarchies. Model each S-layer as a normalized similarity vector quantizer and each C-layer as position quotient pooling. Show winner take all reinforcement is ascent on a competitive learning objective with a separation margin set by inhibition. Prove minimal cell planes per layer equals the covering number of the pooled feature space, with a recursion showing pooling shrinks it. Convert this into a novelty triggered grow and prune rule that builds a minimal covering, giving memory optimal capacity without hand tuning, validated on the neocognitron digit simulation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.78,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a resource bottleneck: fixed hand-set cell-planes, memory limits, no principle for how many feature planes are needed, forcing over/under-provisioning. This is a precise limiting factor (bottleneck_specificity 3). The core move is a formal capacity theory (covering number, competitive-learning objective, proofs), hence formal_derivation, with a grow-and-prune optimization rule as secondary. Not surface stitching since it derives new theory rather than combining two prior methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980), building on the cognitron (1975) and the Hubel-Wiesel simple/complex-cell hierarchy (1962, 1965, 1977), achieves self-organized position-invariant recognition, but the paper itself names concrete resource bottlenecks. Memory and compute: the number of cell-planes per layer is fixed by hand (24), and Fukushima states this was not sufficient for ten patterns, that more planes would help, but that this was not simulated because of the lack of memory capacity of the computer. Expert time and fragility: correct recognition needs parameters properly adjusted and patterns skillfully presented, and a small deviation of parameters or presentation order critically degrades the network. Training cost: self-organization requires uniform repeated presentation of the full stimulus set regardless of what is already learned. These bottlenecks (memory from over-provisioning planes, human tuning time, presentation cost) block scaling to more patterns. Prior works fix plane count, thresholds, and presentation order by hand and never treat their selection as something to discover efficiently, leaving room for an automatic, resource-frugal approach.","method":"Replace hand-tuned self-organization with a resource-adaptive procedure cast as optimization and search over plane allocation, thresholds, and presentation schedule, targeting equal-or-better recognition with the fewest planes, least tuning, and fewest presentations. Three mechanisms. Grow-and-prune plane allocation: keep winner-take-all representative reinforcement but make plane count data-driven; if a presented local feature is not covered above threshold by any existing plane, allocate a new S-plane seeded from that S-column, and periodically merge or prune planes with highly correlated response maps, converging to a minimal detector set that spends memory only where features occur. Automatic threshold search: the per-layer selectivity threshold controls granularity and plane count, so run a coarse-to-fine bisection or hill-climb driven by measured last-layer confusions, raising selectivity where categories stay confused and lowering it where planes are redundant, yielding a stable error-minimizing operating point. Active presentation scheduling: choose the next pattern and its shift to maximize expected novelty or current inter-class confusion, concentrating scarce presentations on informative examples and removing hand-crafted ordering. Evaluation reuses the original digital simulation on the paper tasks (digits 0-9 and the confusable X, Y, T, Z set), measuring planes and cells at convergence, presentations to convergence, accuracy, and robustness to parameter perturbation versus the fixed 24-plane uniform-presentation baseline. Success is matching or exceeding accuracy with markedly fewer planes and presentations while tolerating threshold perturbations."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.88,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly names concrete resource bottlenecks (fixed hand-tuned plane count limited by memory, expert tuning time, uniform presentation cost) that block scaling, so opportunity is resource_bottleneck, with secondary failure_risk_gap given the emphasis on fragility to parameter/presentation perturbation. The method recasts the self-organization as optimization and search over plane allocation (grow-and-prune), threshold search (bisection/hill-climb), and active presentation scheduling to minimize resources, clearly optimization_search. Bottleneck is precisely identified (over-provisioned planes, human tuning, presentation cost). Not superficial stitching since the three mechanisms serve a coherent resource-frugal objective."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima, 1980), extending the cognitron (1975) and modeled on Hubel & Wiesel's hierarchical simple/complex-cell (and hypercolumn) architecture of visual cortex, self-organizes a position-invariant pattern recognizer \"without a teacher.\" But its own conclusion exposes a stark resource bottleneck. First, the number of feature-detecting cell-planes per layer must be fixed and guessed in advance (24 in the paper). Fukushima reports that 24 was already insufficient for reliably recognizing just ten patterns, and that he could not even test larger networks \"because of the lack of memory capacity of our computer.\" Recognition capacity is thus provisioned by worst-case pre-allocation, and scaling is blocked directly by compute/memory. Second, the model works only when \"various parameters are properly adjusted and the stimulus patterns are skillfully presented,\" and \"a small deviation of the values of the parameters, or a small change of the way of pattern presentation, has critically influenced\" performance. In other words, unsupervised learning is nominally teacher-free but in practice demands expert hand-tuning of inhibition/threshold parameters and expert curation and ordering of the training stream — a heavy experimental, data-access, and deployment burden that undermines the \"learning without a teacher\" promise. These are the bottlenecks that limit the whole hierarchical self-organizing line of work: you cannot afford to pre-provision cell-planes for the worst case, and you cannot afford an expert to curate presentation order and retune parameters for every new pattern set or noisier, real input. The prior works leave this open: they establish the architecture and the winner-take-all \"representative\" reinforcement rule but assume a fixed capacity, clean curated presentation, and careful parameter setting.","method":"Relax the neocognitron's three fragile assumptions so the same hierarchical self-organization runs under a fixed compute/memory budget, without curated presentation, and under noise. (1) Demand-driven, growable-and-prunable cell-planes. Start each S-layer with a minimal set of planes. Reuse the model's existing representative-selection (per-S-column winner-take-all): when the winning S-cell in a column matches its best existing S-plane below a novelty threshold (normalized correlation of the input patch to that plane's learned weight profile), allocate a new S-plane seeded on that patch instead of forcing it into an ill-fitting plane; symmetrically, merge planes whose learned weight profiles become near-duplicates and prune planes that almost never win. Capacity then tracks the intrinsic feature complexity actually encountered, removing the need to pre-guess or pre-provision cell-planes and letting a small network cover more patterns within a bounded memory budget — the exact experiment blocked in 1980. (2) Self-tuning inhibition and selectivity. Replace the hand-set inhibition efficacy (r_l) and selectivity thresholds with running per-column normalization estimated online from recent S-cell response statistics (mean/variance), so a single adaptive rule replaces per-dataset parameter search, eliminating the reported critical sensitivity to parameter deviation. (3) Presentation-order and noise robustness via replay. Instead of relying on a skillfully ordered stream, keep a small bounded reservoir of high-response feature patches per plane and interleave replayed patches during reinforcement, decorrelating what each plane learns from the accidental order of the input stream; additionally reinforce under injected input noise/degradation so learned features are noise-tolerant. Evaluation: drive the model with an uncurated, randomly ordered, noisy stream of shifted/distorted patterns and compare position-invariant recognition accuracy, final cell-plane count, and total memory against the original fixed 24-plane neocognitron under identical budgets, and against ablations removing each component. Success criterion: match or exceed the fixed network's invariant recognition while (a) self-selecting far fewer planes for easy pattern sets and gracefully growing for hard ones under a memory cap, and (b) requiring no per-dataset parameter tuning or curated ordering — thereby extending the classic hierarchical self-organizing recognizer to weaker-assumption, resource-constrained, noisy, streaming regimes."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a resource bottleneck (fixed pre-allocation of cell-planes blocked by memory/compute) plus fragility to parameter tuning and curated presentation (failure/risk). The method relaxes the neocognitron's three fragile assumptions to run under weaker conditions—fixed budget, uncurated noisy streaming—which is relax_extend_scope, with a strong robustification component (self-tuning normalization, replay, noise injection). Bottleneck is precisely identified (24-plane pre-provisioning, r_l parameter sensitivity, presentation order). Not surface stitching; components are motivated by the specific limitations rather than bolted-on."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Fukushima's neocognitron learns \"without a teacher,\" which should be cheap since labels are the costly resource, but the paper shows this is illusory. For ten patterns the author reports that \"a small deviation of the values of the parameters, or a small change of the way of pattern presentation, has critically influenced upon the ability of the self-organized network,\" and that success required patterns be \"skillfully presented\" — so a working network demands many hand-tuned simulation runs, costly in compute, time, and expert labor. He also could not test more cell-planes \"because of the lack of memory capacity of our computer,\" using a fixed count (24) that wastes memory yet fails when wrong. The root cause is greedy winner-take-all \"representative\" seed-cell selection: the S-cell with the largest output monopolizes a feature plane, and which cell wins depends on random initial synapses, parameters, and presentation order, making feature allocation non-reproducible (duplicated features, orphan features never learned) and forcing over-provisioning and re-tuning. No listed source addresses this reliability problem. The opportunity is to remove the resource bottleneck by making teacher-less self-organization reliable and self-scaling.","method":"Robustify neocognitron-style S-cell/C-cell self-organization so one hands-off run reliably yields good features with minimal planes. Four components replace winner-take-all seeding. (1) Order-invariant batched reinforcement: accumulate candidate statistics over a full epoch and reinforce from pooled evidence, removing presentation-order sensitivity. (2) Margin-based soft competition: when top candidates in a column are within a tolerance band, reinforce the one in the least-represented plane, decoupling learned features from tiny parameter deviations and random initial synapses. (3) Coverage-driven adaptive plane allocation and pruning: each epoch compute residual coverage error per pattern using existing reinforced templates, add a plane only for persistent orphan features, and merge near-duplicate planes, so plane count grows to the minimum needed instead of a fixed 24. (4) Consensus seeding: run several short passes with different seeds/orders, keep planes recurring across passes, then continue training the consensus set for reproducible feature dictionaries. Evaluate on the neocognitron's own shift-tolerant recognition task (digits/letters with position shift, distortion, noise), measuring reliability: variance of accuracy across random parameters, shuffled orders, and seeds, plus planes and epochs to reach target accuracy. Hypothesis: consistent recognition with lower variance, fewer planes, and no manual tuning, quantifying reduced human, compute, and memory burden while staying faithful to the Hubel–Wiesel S/C hierarchy."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is found through a documented failure: sensitivity to parameters, presentation order, and random seeds making self-organization non-reproducible (failure_risk_gap), framed also as a resource bottleneck (compute/memory/expert labor). The central move is to reduce brittleness and unreliability of winner-take-all seeding via order-invariant batching, soft competition, and adaptive allocation (robustification). Precise bottleneck (greedy WTA seed selection) is identified. Not mere A+B stitching since components target the same identified failure mechanism."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: resource bottleneck in coupling physiology and self-organizing models.","method":"Test method: unify neocognitron self-organization with Hubel-Wiesel receptive-field data by seeding weights and using the model to plan recordings."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The stated motivation frames coupling physiology and self-organizing models as a bridge between disconnected evidence streams (neurophysiology and neural network models), and the method explicitly unifies the neocognitron with Hubel-Wiesel data. This is a synthesis/unification move connecting separate literatures. The 'resource bottleneck' framing in the test motivation is superficial; the real gap is bridging. Combining an existing model with existing data by seeding weights reads as an A+B stitching, hence moderate surface-stitching. Bottleneck specificity is low."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.35,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal fields are placeholder text ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), so labels are inferred from title/prior work: a self-organizing neural network for position-invariant pattern recognition suggests overcoming brittleness to positional shift (scope/failure gap) via a concrete model artifact bridging visual-cortex findings. Content is essentially boilerplate/empty."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation for scope mismatch in neocognitron invariance learning.","method":"test method building a temporal neocognitron with plastic pooling learned from motion."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The stated motivation explicitly flags a scope mismatch in neocognitron invariance learning, and the method extends the architecture to a temporal regime with plastic pooling learned from motion, i.e., relaxing/extending prior scope. Secondary artifact_system reflects the model-building component. The proposal is terse and reads like a generic A+temporal extension, hence moderate stitching and boilerplate; bottleneck is only loosely specified (learned invariance from motion)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works form a lineage of biologically-inspired self-organizing recognizers: Rosenblatt's four-layer series-coupled perceptron (1962), Fukushima's cognitron (1975/1981) and neocognitron (1980), justified by visual-cortex physiology (Hubel and Wiesel 1962/1965/1977) and category-selective inferotemporal responses (Gross et al. 1972; the 1980 IT discrimination study). Each claims unsupervised learning without a teacher yields position-invariant, distortion-tolerant, brain-like recognition. The Scope Mismatch: these claims were established only under narrow, idealized conditions. The neocognitron's evidence is a handful of hand-drawn patterns (five digits, then X/Y/T/Z, then ten numerals) on a small clean array, tested against essentially one axis (translation plus small distortion), with limited and often stationary presentation statistics; scale, rotation, noise, occlusion, class count, and class confusability go untested. The cognitron is admittedly position-dependent. The biological grounding is itself narrow: the neocognitron paper concedes the strict Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy does not hold in its original form (e.g., monosynaptic LGB-to-complex connections), and the physiological benchmarks came from reduced, small-stimulus preparations. So the operating envelope where these mechanisms deliver invariant recognition, and how well emergent units match cortical tuning, is unknown, limiting honest comparison and biological-fidelity claims for inherited mechanisms such as S/C alternation, lateral inhibition, and C-cell pooling.","method":"Build an empirical invariance and self-organization atlas mapping the operating envelopes of these classical models. First, reimplement the four-layer perceptron, cognitron, and neocognitron in one framework using the sources' stated parameters, with identical inputs and scoring. Second, construct a parameterized stimulus battery varying one factor at a time: translation, scale, rotation, elastic deformation, noise, occlusion, contrast, plus class-set properties (number of classes, inter-class similarity, intra-class variability), seeded with the original stimuli (digits, X/Y/T/Z) then expanded beyond them. Third, manipulate the unsupervised training regime: presentation order, class-frequency imbalance, number of patterns, stationary vs randomly shifted presentation. Fourth, compute diagnostics per model and axis: invariance breadth (accuracy vs transformation magnitude with breakdown thresholds), selectivity/grandmother-cell purity, capacity (max distinct patterns before representations merge), convergence stability and order-sensitivity, and tuning-curve/representational-similarity analysis of emergent S/C units. Fifth, cross-map to physiology by comparing emergent tuning to documented cortical properties: orientation/position tuning and growth of position invariance from simple to complex cells (Hubel and Wiesel) and selectivity-with-invariance of IT neurons (Gross et al.; 1980 study), yielding a per-layer biological-fidelity score. Sixth, ablate S/C alternation, lateral inhibition, C-cell pooling/blurring, and unsupervised reinforcement to attribute each invariance or failure to a specific ingredient. Deliverables: operating-envelope heatmaps locating where each model succeeds or fails, a capacity-vs-confusability frontier, and a mechanism-to-property attribution table, replacing anecdotal small-scale validation with a reproducible map of when these foundational self-organizing mechanisms transfer."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.95,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as scope mismatch: classical models validated only under narrow idealized conditions (few hand-drawn patterns, translation only), with untested envelopes; secondary evidence_gap since the field lacks systematic benchmarks. Method is empirical_mapping: reimplement models, build a parameterized stimulus battery, compute diagnostics, produce operating-envelope atlases and mechanism-attribution tables. Ablations and cross-mapping to physiology are all in service of the empirical map, not a synthesis contribution. Bottleneck is precisely identified (which mechanisms transfer under which transformations)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The foundational hierarchical recognition models here (Rosenblatt's series-coupled perceptron, Fukushima's cognitron, and the neocognitron) inherit the Hubel and Wiesel simple-complex-hypercomplex hierarchy with an inferotemporal grandmother-cell endpoint, and claim recognition unaffected by shift in position and by small distortion in shape. These guarantees hold only in a narrow regime the papers themselves expose. Invariance is genuinely built in only for translation, and only for small shifts; scale and rotation invariance are asserted merely qualitatively. Distortion tolerance emerges from C-cell local pooling whose window sizes, receptive-field growth, subsampling, and depth are tuned empirically for a tiny hand-crafted character set; the neocognitron paper notes recognition is critically influenced by these choices and that 24 cell-planes per layer were not sufficient. The structurally near-identical cognitron has no position invariance, showing invariance depends delicately on the pooling construction rather than any characterized principle. This is a scope mismatch: the models are presented as general solutions to shift and distortion, yet there is no formal statement of which transformation classes a simple-complex cascade can be invariant to, how much transformation magnitude a given pooling geometry and depth tolerate before selectivity collapses, or the invariance-versus-discriminability trade-off. Consequently the results do not transfer to scale, rotation, or large deformation, and there is no principled way to size an architecture for a target transformation range.","method":"Develop a group/semigroup-theoretic formal model of the S-cell/C-cell cascade these papers instantiate, and derive the exact class and magnitude of invariance it can realize. Formalize a stimulus as a function on the plane, an S-cell as thresholded shunting-inhibited template correlation, and a C-cell as a monotone local pooling operator over a window with given overlap and subsampling, weight-shared across a cell-plane; take the transformation set as the Euclidean group of translations, rotations, and scalings, plus a monoid of bounded local deformations. Prove Theorem 1 (translation): exact invariance under the discrete translation subgroup generated by successive pooling windows, with a closed-form tolerance radius equal to the sum over layers of half the pooling width times the product of preceding subsampling factors, predicting maximal tolerated shift from architecture parameters and explaining the pooling-free cognitron's near-zero radius. Prove Theorem 2 (scope/impossibility): spatial pooling alone cannot yield scale or rotation invariance beyond an order pooling-width-over-feature-size limit because these transformations do not commute with local spatial pooling; formalize a cell-plane-orbit condition, that invariance to a subgroup requires feature planes tiling each feature's orbit, giving the number of cell-planes per stage as the orbit covering number for a chosen tolerance. Derive an invariance-selectivity bound: larger pooling raises the invariance radius but shrinks the minimum separable inter-pattern distance, yielding an explicit Pareto frontier that formalizes the neocognitron's informal compromise between differentiating similar patterns and tolerating distortion. Produce a taxonomy classifying invariance mechanisms as pooling-based translation, orbit-tiling scale/rotation, and learning-based deformation tolerance via competitive learning over the deformation monoid, mapping each to requirements on receptive-field size, pooling geometry, subsampling, depth, and cell-plane count. Validate by re-simulating a minimal S/C cascade and the reported neocognitron configuration on stimuli with parametrically controlled shift, scale, rotation, and deformation, checking recognition degrades at the predicted thresholds and that adding orbit-tiling planes restores invariance as the covering-number formula predicts. This replaces hand-tuned, stimulus-specific invariance claims with transferable architecture-parameterized theorems and a taxonomy for sizing a cascade to a target transformation range."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.92,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a scope mismatch: models claimed as general shift/distortion solutions only work in a narrow tuned regime, with no characterization of which transformation classes the cascade can be invariant to. Secondary explanation_gap since it asks why invariance emerges. The method centrally introduces a group-theoretic formal model with theorems, bounds, a Pareto frontier, and a taxonomy — clearly formal_derivation. Validation via re-simulation is supporting, not central. Bottleneck is precisely identified (pooling geometry, orbit tiling, invariance-selectivity trade-off)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about neocognitron scope mismatch.","method":"Test method about adaptive cell-plane allocation and threshold search."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"artifact_system","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.5,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation explicitly frames a scope mismatch in neocognitron (position-shift invariance limits/assumptions); method proposes an adaptive cell-plane allocation and threshold search, indicating a neural network model artifact with search/tuning as the construction move. Proposal text is minimal placeholder, lowering specificity and raising boilerplate; optimization_search secondary reflects threshold search."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The founding self-organizing recognition models share a scope mismatch. The cognitron, the neocognitron, and Rosenblatt's four-layer series-coupled perceptron validate unsupervised self-organization and recognition only in a narrow regime: a single isolated near-noise-free pattern filling the retina, presented one at a time, with the experimenter choosing presentation order and tuning parameters. The neocognitron paper concedes this fragility: recognizing even ten digits requires patterns to be skillfully presented and is critically influenced by small parameter changes, with only small distortion tolerance. Rosenblatt lists figure-ground discrimination, relations of figures in complex visual fields, and selective attention as problems his single-letter-at-a-time training could not solve. Yet the biological targets these models invoke, size-invariant inferotemporal responses in behaving monkeys and the Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy, arise from cluttered, multi-object, variable-scale, noisy scenes. The shared winner-take-all reinforcement of the most-active representative cell assumes one pattern is present, so it cannot decide which of several co-present objects to learn and cannot bootstrap in clutter.","method":"Relax the single-clean-isolated-pattern assumption so self-organization and recognition work in cluttered, noisy, multi-object, variable-scale scenes, using only mechanisms licensed by the sources. Add attentional figure-ground gating via top-down feedback: descending connections from higher C-layers to lower S and C layers (Rosenblatt's cross-coupled feedback, consistent with the Hubel-Wiesel hierarchy), where the strongest-responding high-layer C-cell projects a spatial spotlight that facilitates S-cells of one candidate figure and suppresses those from other objects and background, segmenting one attended pattern. Use attention-scoped learning: restrict winner-take-all representative selection to the attended region so reinforcement targets a single segmented pattern even when many are present. Add noise-robust selection: replace fixed-threshold selection with local contrast normalization via lateral inhibitory cells (extending the cognitron's inhibitory cells and Hubel-Wiesel lateral interactions). Add scale invariance: parallel S-planes tuned to a range of feature sizes with C-cells pooling across scale and position. Add sequential multi-object readout with inhibition-of-return so attention shifts among figures. Evaluate by self-organizing unsupervised on scenes of two or three overlapping, noisy, differently scaled characters and comparing recognition accuracy, segmentation quality, and self-organization stability against the vanilla neocognitron."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames the gap as a scope mismatch: founding models validate only in a narrow single-isolated-clean-pattern regime while biological targets arise from cluttered multi-object scenes. Secondary failure_risk_gap reflects the noted fragility/brittleness. The core move is relax_extend_scope—making self-organization work under weaker, more realistic conditions (clutter, noise, scale variation), with robustification (noise-robust normalization, stability) as secondary. It identifies a precise limiting mechanism (winner-take-all assuming one present pattern), so bottleneck_specificity is high. Multiple added components are integrated toward extending scope, not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The neocognitron (Fukushima 1980) and cognitron (1975/1981) are presented as general learning-without-a-teacher mechanisms for shift- and distortion-invariant recognition, with the neocognitron advertised as a drastic solution to coping with position shift and shape distortion. But the demonstrated competence lives in a narrow, unrealistic regime: only a handful of clean, well-separated patterns presented in isolation, with hand-set parameters (inhibitory efficacy r_l, reinforcement speed q_l, saturation) and a fixed 24 cell-planes per layer. The author concedes the scope mismatch: scaling to ten patterns works only provided parameters are properly adjusted and the stimulus patterns are skillfully presented, and a small deviation of parameter values or a small change in presentation critically influences the ability of the self-organized network. The failure is structural: reinforcement goes to a single winner-take-all representative S-cell per plane, so an early or spurious winner can permanently claim a plane, features get duplicated or left uncovered, and there is no recovery, deduplication, or capacity reallocation. The learned feature dictionary thus depends on luck, ordering, and tuning, and the promised transfer to larger, noisy, cluttered pattern sets is unsupported. Prior work shows what the hierarchy can represent under idealized boundary conditions, not how to self-organize it reliably outside them.","method":"Develop a robustified self-organization procedure for Fukushima-style S-cell/C-cell hierarchies, in the same digital-simulation setting, aimed at stable low-variance feature learning under adverse conditions. Four mechanisms replace the fragile assumptions. (1) Consensus-consolidated reinforcement: within each S-column, reinforcement is graded by relative activation (soft competition), and a candidate feature is consolidated only after winning consistently across several recent presentations held in a short template-memory buffer, damping noisy single-presentation winners and making final templates approximately order-invariant. (2) Adaptive capacity: grow a new cell-plane when an input's local features are poorly covered (a novelty/residual test) and merge or prune planes that converged to near-identical templates, self-sizing the network and curing the admitted 24-planes-not-sufficient failure. (3) Homeostatic selectivity control: replace the hand-tuned inhibitory efficacy r_l with a per-plane controller that adjusts inhibition to hold each plane near a target selectivity/tolerance operating point, removing manual tuning of the selectivity-invariance tradeoff. (4) Adversarial training regime: self-organize under injected noise, position/size jitter, partial occlusion, and occasional simultaneous multi-pattern presentation, forcing robust features. Evaluation is stability-oriented and targets the original's admitted failures: comparing original versus robustified self-organization, measure mean and variance of recognition accuracy across randomized hyperparameters, randomized presentation orders, increasing noise/occlusion, and growing class counts (10, 20, 50). Primary metric is accuracy variance across seeds/settings; secondary is planes-used-versus-accuracy. Success is collapsing the sensitivity the original attributes to parameters and skillful presentation while preserving shift- and distortion-invariance."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly diagnoses the neocognitron's competence as living in a narrow, unrealistic regime dependent on tuning and skillful presentation (scope_mismatch), with structural failure modes of winner-take-all reinforcement (failure_risk_gap). The core move is a robustified self-organization procedure targeting brittleness, variance, and manual tuning (robustification), while extending to noisy/cluttered/larger regimes (relax_extend_scope). Not surface stitching: mechanisms are motivated by specific admitted failures. Bottleneck is precisely named (single-winner reinforcement, fixed capacity, hand-tuned inhibition)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"neocognitron-a-self-organizing-neural-network-model-for-a-me","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap. The cognitron and neocognitron established self-organizing, shift-invariant hierarchical recognition, but only under narrow, unrealistic conditions: single isolated, near-noise-free patterns shown one at a time; a strictly feedforward cascade; and a fully hand-designed static architecture (number of stages, S/C cell-planes, receptive-field sizes, and connection ranges all set by the designer). Learning is defined as without a teacher, excluding reinforcement or top-down signals, with no mechanism for clutter, figure-ground segmentation, or for the architecture itself to arise. Yet the literatures these models build on describe richer conditions left unused: Hubel and Wiesel document structured functional architecture (orientation and ocular-dominance columns, binocular interaction); inferotemporal recordings show position- and size-invariant grandmother-like units measured while an animal actively performs discrimination, not passively viewing; Rosenblatt's four-layer series-coupled perceptron work explicitly studies cross-coupled feedback from response to association units, selective attention, reinforcement rules, and geometric constraints on organization; and retinotectal neuroplasticity models describe how connectivity itself forms through activity-dependent and chemoaffinity processes. The feedforward, teacher-free, hand-wired, one-clean-pattern regime thus mismatches both the biology and the surrounding theory, limiting transfer to realistic cluttered vision.","method":"Synthesis and unification. Build one self-organizing recurrent visual hierarchy integrating four mechanisms currently siloed across the sources. (1) Bottom-up: retain cognitron and neocognitron competitive unsupervised S-cell plasticity with C-cell pooling for local shift tolerance. (2) Top-down back-coupling: add reciprocal higher-to-lower connections, importing Rosenblatt's cross-coupled feedback and selective attention, so a partial recognition hypothesis at deep stages re-weights and gates lower-stage activity, implementing figure-ground segmentation and attentional routing to parse cluttered scenes of multiple, overlapping, noisy patterns and relaxing the one-clean-pattern assumption. The same descending pathway carries an optional graded reinforcement signal, unifying learning with a teacher (perceptron reinforcement) and learning without a teacher (Fukushima competition) into one rule that degrades gracefully from supervised to unsupervised. (3) Developmental self-wiring: replace the hand-set architecture with a retinotectal-style plasticity process governing not only weights but growth and pruning of inter-stage connections and receptive-field extents, so the number of cell-planes, pooling radii, and depth emerge from input statistics plus a chemoaffinity-like topographic bias. (4) Structural prior and read-out: use Hubel and Wiesel functional-architecture regularities (columnar and topographic ordering, binocular combination) as a regularizer on emergent maps, and adopt inferotemporal-style position- and size-invariant category units as the top-layer objective, trained and evaluated during an active discrimination task. Validation: test on cluttered multi-object scenes with systematic position, size, and noise variation; measure invariant recognition and segmentation accuracy versus the feedforward neocognitron baseline; and check whether the emergent architecture reproduces columnar organization and the invariance-gradient-with-depth predicted by the hierarchy."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.86,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a scope-mismatch: prior neocognitron works under narrow, unrealistic conditions (single clean pattern, feedforward, hand-wired) that mismatch surrounding biology and theory, with a bridge-opportunity flavor of unused disconnected literatures. The method is overtly synthesis/unification, integrating four siloed mechanisms into one recurrent hierarchy, with a strong relax/extend-scope component (removing one-clean-pattern assumption). The plan reads somewhat as an A+B+C+D combination of the source literatures, hence moderate surface-stitching, though it specifies concrete integration mechanisms."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation for gap in active learning theory to system.","method":"Test method building a system."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.35,"confidence_paradigm":0.3,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is nearly empty boilerplate ('Test motivation', 'Test method building a system'), giving no substantive content. Inferring from prior-work context on active learning / example selection, the likely gap is sample efficiency (resource_bottleneck) and the method is query/selection optimization. Low confidence due to placeholder text; high boilerplate score."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Active query learning for perceptrons (Kinzel-Rujan; Watkin-Rau) selects the next input orthogonal to a single estimate J, giving only constant-factor gains with a power-law learning curve. Opper-Haussler show generalization is governed by the version-space posterior and that the ideal example halves the version-space volume; Fedorov formalizes querying the point of maximal predictive variance. Gap: no work chooses queries from the posterior version space rather than one point estimate, nor quantifies the gap to optimum; a point orthogonal to one J does not bisect the version space, and analyses are limited to the noise-free case.","method":"Build a statistical-mechanics theory and committee algorithm for posterior version-space active queries. Rule: pick the input where the posterior predictive is maximally uncertain (posterior label probability one half), bisecting the solution volume, one bit per query. Implement by sampling a committee from the Gibbs version-space ensemble (Opper-Haussler majority net, Langevin sampling, or repeated MinOver solutions) and querying where votes split fifty-fifty. Extend the Watkin-Rau replica calculation to committee-bisection, tracking overlap and version-space entropy versus alpha, predicting near-exponential error decay and a computable gap over single-estimate selection. Extend to the Ising perceptron freezing transition and to noisy cases via a finite-temperature posterior, validated by simulation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior active learning relying on a single point estimate (orthogonal to one J) giving only constant-factor gains, plus limitation to noise-free cases — a scope/assumption mismatch, with an explanatory component about quantifying the gap to optimum. The core move is building a statistical-mechanics theory (replica calculation, version-space entropy tracking, exponential decay bounds), i.e. formal derivation, with extension to noisy finite-temperature settings (relax_extend_scope). Precise bottleneck identified: point orthogonal to one J fails to bisect version space. Not surface stitching; the committee/version-space idea is a principled construction."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation for perceptron active learning empirical map.","method":"Test method: benchmark query strategies across learners and noise regimes."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"optimization_search"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.66,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder/test content: 'benchmark query strategies across learners and noise regimes' points to systematic comparison (empirical_mapping) driven by sample-efficiency/active learning concerns (resource_bottleneck). Highly generic phrasing yields high boilerplate and low specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Three traditions in the provided sources address the same question (which examples should a learner see) but none unifies them. (1) Statistical-mechanics learning theory (the Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby review; Tishby-Levin-Solla's Gibbs ensemble; Opper-Haussler's Bayes-optimal analysis) gives a version-space posterior, an ensemble entropy, a one-step information-gain notion, the halving relation V_{m+1} <= (1/2)V_m, and mostly power-law learning curves eps_g ~ 1/alpha, but only for RANDOM examples. (2) Query/active selection (Watkin-Rau \"Selecting examples for perceptrons\"; Baum's examples-and-queries) shows large speedups (a predicted 42% fewer wasted examples; midpoint binary search) but uses ad hoc single-hypothesis heuristics with no optimality principle and no bound on achievable speedup. (3) Fedorov's Theory of Optimal Experiments gives a mature design theory (D-/G-optimality, information matrix, Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence) built for regression, never connected to version-space generalization. The gap: no formal principle defining the optimal query in the stat-mech setting, no proof relating the perceptron heuristics to it, no bridge to optimal-design theory, and no bound on the best possible speedup (an active-learning analogue of the VC/sample-complexity bounds noted in the Bayesian-learning source). Closing it would put active learning on principled footing and connect literatures that reinvented the same idea in isolation.","method":"A formal-derivation contribution: one objective, three theorems, one bound, unifying version-space learning, perceptron query heuristics, and optimal design. Setup: following Tishby-Levin-Solla and Opper-Haussler, define the Gibbs posterior p_m(J) on the version space of m labeled examples, with volume V_m and entropy S_m. Define the query objective as expected one-step information gain of an unlabeled query x with unknown label s: DeltaI(x)=S_m - E_s[S_{m+1}(x,s)] = H2(pi_+(x)), where pi_+(x) is the posterior-predictive probability of label +1. Theorem 1 (optimal query = Bayes-point bisection): DeltaI(x) is maximized when pi_+(x)=1/2, splitting the version space into equal halves through the Bayes point and achieving V_{m+1}=(1/2)V_m with equality in expectation, the maximal reduction. Corollary: Watkin-Rau's rule (pick xi orthogonal to the current estimate J) and Baum's midpoint query are the MAP single-hypothesis approximations of this Bayes-point bisection; derive their suboptimality gap via the order parameter R(alpha). Theorem 2 (equivalence to D-optimality): in the large-alpha regime where p_m(J) is asymptotically Gaussian with covariance proportional to the inverse Fisher matrix M_m, expand DeltaI(x) ~ (1/2)[log det(M_m + beta x x^T) - log det M_m], exactly Fedorov's D-optimality criterion; thus greedy info-gain query learning equals sequential D-optimal design, and by Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence the optimal query measure is G-optimal, minimizing worst-case predictive variance and hence worst-case generalization. Theorem 3 (learning-curve bound and speedup): from S_m <= S_0 - sum DeltaI_k derive (a) query-complexity bound m >= (S_0 - S_target)/max_x DeltaI(x), an active-learning analogue of VC/Bayesian sample-complexity bounds; (b) optimal bisecting queries force exponential decay eps_g ~ exp(-c alpha) versus power-law 1/alpha for random examples; (c) explicit c for spherical and Ising perceptrons from the replica free energy (reusing Watkin-Rau's entropy S(alpha,kappa)), recovering the 42% reduction as the random-vs-optimal prefactor ratio. Noisy extension: replace the sharp version space with a temperature-T Gibbs weight; DeltaI reduces to a noise-scaled Fisher log-det (D-optimality weighted by label reliability), and the residual Bayes-vs-Gibbs gap reproduces Opper-Haussler's sqrt(2) factor, giving optimal query rates under noise. Feasibility: all ingredients exist in the sources (Gibbs/version-space formalism, replica entropies for spherical/Ising perceptrons, the halving relation, Fedorov's information-matrix theory); the contribution is analytic and validated against Watkin-Rau and Baum as limiting cases."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames three isolated traditions (stat-mech learning, perceptron query heuristics, optimal experiment design) that reinvented the same idea and were never unified, a clear bridge_opportunity; secondary explanation_gap since it also seeks a principled account of why heuristics work. The method constructs one objective plus theorems proving equivalences across these literatures (synthesis_unification), delivered via formal derivation (theorems, bounds), hence formal_derivation secondary. The unification is deep and derives non-trivial equivalences rather than superficially concatenating, so low stitching; the bottleneck (missing optimality principle / bound linking version-space to D-optimality) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Statistical mechanics yields exact learning curves G(alpha) for perceptrons (Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby review; Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal perceptron; Tishby/Levin/Solla information-gain/entropy). Active example selection helps: Watkin-Rau (analyzing the Kinzel/Ruajn scheme) show querying near the current single student's decision boundary cuts wasted examples (~42% for Ising perceptrons). Fedorov's optimal-experiment theory supplies adaptive-design machinery (D-/G-optimality, equivalence theorem, iterative mix-in), and Baum shows queries speed learning. Gaps: (1) existing perceptron query rules are greedy and one-step, placing the next example on a single point estimate's boundary, not optimizing the whole trajectory under a budget; Watkin-Rau even note that WHEN one starts selecting matters (selecting only for alpha>0.7 keeps most of the gain) but never optimize this scheduling. (2) The criterion is never tied to the Bayes posterior, though Opper-Haussler show the Bayes predictor beats the single-student one by up to sqrt(2) and flag that error vs. one-step information gain is unresolved -- maximizing information gain need not minimize error. (3) All analyses assume a realizable, noise-free teacher, with no principled way to reallocate a query budget once boundary queries stop shrinking the relevant version space. This leaves open a unified optimal-experimental-design theory of query allocation for perceptrons that is non-greedy, posterior-based, and noise-robust.","method":"Frame perceptron active learning as an optimal experimental-design and budget-allocation problem solved with statistical-mechanics objectives. (1) Represent the learning state by the Bayes posterior (version space) through order parameters: teacher overlap R, self-overlap q, and posterior anisotropy; use the replica/annealed free energy to predict, for a candidate query with projection profile rho, the one-step change in both ensemble entropy (information gain) and true error G=(1/pi)arccos R. (2) Define a Fedorov-style criterion adapted to this setting: maximize shrinkage of the version space along the generalization-relevant teacher-aligned direction, i.e. maximize dR/dalpha per query, and derive the error-optimal profile rho* versus entropy-optimal and single-student-boundary profiles. (3) Since order parameters obey ODEs in alpha given rho, treat the whole run as optimal control: choose a schedule rho(alpha) over a fixed budget to minimize terminal G(alpha*) by calculus of variations / dynamic programming, yielding a non-greedy allocation. (4) Implement with a Fedorov iterative update mixing the current design with a query matching rho*, sampled by rejection over a posterior committee's disagreement band -- a Bayes generalization of boundary sampling. (5) Extend the free energy to noisy/unrealizable teachers; use the annealed approximation to detect when boundary queries saturate and automatically reallocate budget to bulk queries, predicting the altered phase transition. (6) Validate by deriving predicted learning curves for random, greedy-boundary, entropy-optimal, and error-scheduled sampling, each paired with single-student and Bayes predictors, and test with finite-N simulations on spherical and Ising perceptrons; success is reaching target G with fewer queries than greedy boundary sampling and staying efficient under noise."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed around a contradiction/tradeoff: maximizing information gain need not minimize error, greedy one-step queries vs. non-greedy trajectory optimization, and Bayes-vs-single-student discrepancy. Secondary is scope_mismatch (realizable, noise-free assumption). The method centers on deriving statistical-mechanics free-energy objectives, error-optimal profiles, and optimal-control schedules (formal_derivation), while unifying Fedorov optimal-experiment theory with statistical-mechanics learning curves (synthesis_unification). Though optimization/scheduling appears, the core deliverable is a derived theory, not a search procedure. Bottleneck is precisely identified (greedy one-step boundary queries not tied to Bayes posterior or budget). Not superficial stitching given the deep integration of ODE order-parameter dynamics with optimal design."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"The prior work establishes two powerful but disconnected threads. (1) Query / self-selecting example learning: Watkin & Rau (\"Selecting examples for perceptrons,\" 1992) and the earlier Kinzel–Rujan example-selection idea show, via replica statistical mechanics, that a perceptron which chooses its next question ξ^{p+1} orthogonal to its current estimate J^(p) — i.e., right on its own decision boundary — dramatically accelerates learning (a 42% reduction in \"wasted\" examples, and faster-than-power-law approach to perfect generalization). Baum's polynomial-time algorithm similarly drives queries toward the separating hyperplane. (2) Bayesian/information-theoretic analysis of generalization: Opper & Haussler compute the Bayes-optimal perceptron learning curve and relate generalization to the one-step information gain, and Tishby–Levin–Solla formalize learning as reduction of ensemble entropy (information gain).\n\nThe critical, unaddressed limitation is that every one of these query/selection results assumes a NOISE-FREE, REALIZABLE oracle: labels are exact and the teacher is a single perceptron the student can match. This is exactly the regime where aggressive boundary-seeking queries are most dangerous. Querying points on the current decision boundary means querying inputs whose true labels have the smallest margin and are therefore the most likely to be corrupted by output noise or by teacher/student model mismatch. Intuitively, the greedy strategy that is optimal in the clean case should collect maximally unreliable, low-margin examples under noise, potentially destroying its advantage or even producing a residual error floor. Yet the noisy/unrealizable case has only been analyzed for PASSIVE, randomly drawn examples (Seung–Sompolinsky–Tishby), and classical optimal experimental design (Fedorov) treats noise but only for linear-regression-style designs, not the nonlinear threshold classifier or the statistical-mechanics order-parameter regime. This matters because real oracles (human labelers, physical experiments, noisy measurements) are noisy and imperfectly realizable, so the whole promise of \"learn faster by choosing your own examples\" is untested precisely where it would be used. There is thus room for a theory of when, and how, self-selecting perceptrons should query under noise.","method":"Relax the noise-free, realizable assumptions underlying the query-learning results and build a statistical-mechanics theory of self-selecting perceptron learning in noisy and unrealizable regimes, together with a noise-robust query rule.\n\n1) Extend the order-parameter/replica calculation. Take the Watkin–Rau framework (order parameters R = J·B and the query distribution induced by choosing ξ near the student's boundary) and add a teacher noise model: output label flips with probability η (and, as variants, Gaussian output noise, and a \"complex teacher\" the spherical/Ising student cannot represent — the unrealizable case). Recompute the generalization curve G(α; η) for the greedy boundary-seeking strategy. This yields a concrete, testable prediction: the point where greedy active learning stops beating passive random sampling, and the noise-dependent residual error floor / plateau it incurs, quantified as a function of α and η.\n\n2) Derive the optimal query margin. Instead of always querying at zero margin (on the boundary), parametrize queries by their projected margin m = ξ·J^(p) and ask which m maximizes the EXPECTED one-step information gain about the teacher B given the noise model — directly generalizing the information-gain quantity that Opper–Haussler and Tishby–Levin–Solla relate to generalization. Under noise, informativeness (highest near the boundary) trades off against label reliability (highest far from the boundary), so the argmax is a finite optimal margin m*(η, R) > 0 rather than the boundary itself. Deriving m*(η,R(α)) as an explicit function of the current overlap and noise level is the core theoretical deliverable and the mechanism by which the method \"works under weaker assumptions.\"\n\n3) Move from a point estimate to the noisy Bayes/posterior ensemble. Replace the single weight vector J with the Gibbs/Bayes posterior over weights (the object Opper–Haussler analyze), and define the query as the input maximizing posterior label disagreement weighted by reliability — a noise-aware, version-space / query-by-committee reading. Carry the posterior into the replica average so the analysis is self-consistent: examples selected from the posterior change the posterior. This gives an \"active Bayes-optimal\" learning curve to compare against the passive Bayes-optimal baseline and the greedy active baseline.\n\n4) Validate and delimit. Simulate spherical and Ising perceptrons at several η and under a mismatched teacher, comparing (a) greedy boundary queries, (b) the optimal-margin rule m*, (c) posterior-disagreement queries, and (d) passive random sampling. Map out the phase diagram in (α, η) showing regions where active learning helps, is neutral, or hurts, and confirm the predicted optimal margin and error floors.\n\nThis addresses the gap by taking results proven only for clean, realizable oracles and making them function — and prescribing what to actually query — under label noise and model mismatch, i.e., under the realistic conditions in which self-selecting learners are deployed."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as prior query-learning results relying on unrealistic noise-free, realizable oracle assumptions (scope_mismatch), with a clear secondary concern that aggressive greedy queries become dangerous/brittle under noise (failure_risk_gap). The core move is to relax those assumptions and make the theory function under noise and model mismatch (relax_extend_scope), executed via a statistical-mechanics/replica derivation of an optimal query margin m*(eta,R) (formal_derivation). The optimal-margin tradeoff is a precisely identified mechanism/bottleneck (specificity 3). Not surface stitching: it reworks the order-parameter calculation with a noise model rather than bolting two methods together."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Across these works, a learner generalizes far faster if it queries its own inputs rather than accepting random ones. Baum's polynomial-time algorithm locates a point on the target hyperplane by binary search between a + and a - example; Watkin & Rau (extending Kinzel/Rujan example selection) show a perceptron that queries inputs on its own current decision boundary wastes ~42% fewer examples and beats every random-sampling rule. The shared principle: query where the model is most uncertain (nearest the boundary), where a label is most informative. But all these efficiency results assume a noise-free, perfectly realizable teacher. Opper & Haussler compute the Bayes-optimal learning curve explicitly for noise-free examples, and the statistical-mechanics literature (Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby; Tishby-Levin-Solla's Gibbs/version-space formulation) treats output noise and unrealizable rules only for random example streams, never for actively selected inputs. This is the gap: the inputs that maximize information (on the boundary, teacher margin |B·S|->0) are exactly the ones whose labels are least reliable under noise and where a mismatched student is most systematically wrong. So query-learning speed-ups rest on the most brittle possible sampling strategy — under label noise or model mismatch, boundary-seeking queries amplify errors, induce sampling bias, and can drive the weight estimate away from the teacher (Baum's binary search fails on a single mislabeled query). No source characterizes or repairs this failure mode, yet active selection is precisely where the most labels are saved, making a silently unreliable query scheme a trustworthiness problem worth solving.","method":"We propose a robustified Bayesian query-selection scheme for perceptron learning plus a statistical-mechanics analysis quantifying its reliability gains over standard boundary-seeking active learning. Setup: a student perceptron learns teacher B in the thermodynamic limit (N->inf, p=alpha*N) with two corruptions absent from prior work: output label noise (flip probability lambda or Gaussian teacher-field noise) and model mismatch/unrealizability (finite-margin or extra-structure teacher). The learner maintains the Bayes posterior / Gibbs ensemble over weights (Opper-Haussler and Tishby-Levin-Solla version-space formulation), summarized by order parameters R (teacher-student overlap) and q (student-student overlap). Robust query criterion: instead of selecting the input maximizing raw expected information (which drives queries to the student boundary J·S=0), select inputs by a risk-adjusted objective that integrates over the noise model, maximizing expected posterior-error reduction rather than raw information. Since a boundary label is near a coin flip under noise, this prefers queries at a strictly positive stability margin kappa*>0, where labels are both informative and reliable. Three concrete levers: (1) tunable query-margin kappa (query inputs with predicted field J·S ~ kappa rather than 0), whose optimum we derive; (2) query redundancy, averaging r nearby/repeated queries per point to suppress label noise, trading query count for reliability; (3) an online unrealizability detector monitoring posterior entropy / training-error growth (available in the Gibbs formulation) that adaptively raises kappa and r to prevent catastrophic drift. Analysis: using Watkin & Rau's replica recursion (which already contains a Gaussian noise-like term whose width narrows with R) and the Gibbs free-energy machinery of the statistical-mechanics-of-learning framework, derive learning curves e_g(alpha) for random sampling, standard boundary query learning, and robust margin-plus-redundancy query learning, under noise lambda and a finite-margin unrealizable teacher. Predictions to establish: standard query learning plateaus or worsens past a critical alpha under noise (error amplification/sampling bias), while the robust scheme keeps an efficiency edge over random sampling and degrades gracefully; and there is an optimal kappa*(lambda,alpha) and r minimizing e_g. Validate with simulations on Ising and spherical perceptrons (the two Watkin-Rau regimes) with MinOver/Bayes-optimal students, comparing final generalization, run-to-run variance (a direct brittleness metric), and label budget. How it closes the gap: prior works either exploit boundary queries assuming no noise, or analyze noise only for random sampling. This is the first query strategy and analysis that makes active example selection robust, turning the most brittle sampling regime into a controlled, reliable one and providing a principled knob (query margin plus redundancy) for the efficiency-versus-reliability trade-off."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.83,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a brittleness/reliability failure: boundary-seeking queries maximize information exactly where labels are least reliable under noise/mismatch, amplifying errors — a failure_risk_gap, with a scope_mismatch element (prior efficiency results assume noise-free realizable teachers). The core move is robustification (risk-adjusted query criterion, margin, redundancy, drift detector to prevent brittleness), supported by formal_derivation via replica/Gibbs statistical-mechanics learning curves. Precise bottleneck identified (boundary labels near coin-flip under noise). Not surface stitching — the tension between informativeness and reliability is a genuine integrated insight."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":null,"paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"These sources contain four disconnected notions of an informative example: Fedorov D-optimality, Watkin-Rau near-boundary selection, Baum bisection queries, and Tishby version-space volume reduction, alongside Bayesian/VC information-gain bounds and Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal learning curves. They are never unified, and the truly optimal query strategy is never analyzed with exact average-case tools, so we lack a principled architecture-general selection rule and an exact theory of how much active learning can help.","method":"Unify the criteria under a single Maximum Expected Information Gain objective, defined as expected version-space log-volume shrinkage, equivalently the mutual information between the hypothesis and the unknown label under the Gibbs posterior of Tishby et al. and Opper-Haussler. Prove reductions showing this one objective specializes to Fedorov D-optimality in the linear-Gaussian limit, to version-space bisection for realizable binary classification (query where the Bayes predictive probability is nearest one half, recovering Baum midpoint queries and Watkin-Rau near-boundary selection), and to the average information-gain term bounded by VC dimension in the Bayesian sample-complexity result. Then use replica and Gibbs-ensemble analysis for spherical and Ising perceptrons to compute exact active-learning curves when queries follow this rule (implemented as maximal disagreement of hypotheses sampled from the posterior), determining whether error decays as a power law or exponentially and how much it beats the Watkin-Rau and D-optimal heuristics. Show Baum geometric decay is the worst-case shadow of the average-case result, and validate all reductions and curves by simulation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly identifies four disconnected notions of informative examples that are never unified, and asks for an exact theory of how much active learning helps — a bridge_opportunity with an explanation_gap component. The core move is unifying these criteria under a single Maximum Expected Information Gain objective and proving reductions to each special case (synthesis_unification), backed by replica/Gibbs formal derivation of exact learning curves. Not superficial stitching: the reductions are principled and derive one objective from which others emerge as limits. Bottleneck is precise (missing unifying objective and exact average-case analysis)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Three communities have independently answered the same question — \"which input is most worth querying?\" — without connecting their theories. (1) Statistics produced rigorous optimal experimental design (Fedorov 1972): D-optimality (maximize the determinant of the Fisher information matrix), G-optimality (minimize worst-case predictive variance), and the Kiefer–Wolfowitz D-equals-G equivalence. (2) The statistical-mechanics-of-learning community (Gardner; Opper–Haussler Bayes-optimal perceptron; Watkin–Rau \"Selecting examples for perceptrons\"; Baum's examples-and-queries algorithm) describes learning via order parameters (teacher–student overlap R, version-space volume) and replica learning curves, but its query rules are heuristic: Watkin–Rau pick examples orthogonal to the current estimate J (42% fewer \"wasted\" examples), Baum does binary search, neither derived from any optimality criterion. (3) The Bayesian/information-theoretic community (Tishby–Levin–Solla's Gibbs-ensemble \"information gain = KL reduction of accessible configuration volume\"; Haussler et al.'s sample-complexity bounds via information theory and VC dimension) measures example value as posterior-entropy reduction. These are three views of one object: Fedorov's log-determinant D-criterion equals Tishby's log version-space-volume reduction, which drives the order-parameter dynamics the physics learning curves describe. No work fuses them, so physics query heuristics ignore provably optimal design criteria, optimal-design theory ignores the exact Bayes-optimal ensemble and replica learning curves, and the information bounds never become a constructive query rule. Bridging them yields principled, near-optimal active learning with closed-form learning-curve guarantees, and lets us test whether the classical equivalence holds in the learning setting.","method":"Build an open Active Learning Workbench for perceptrons and layered nets whose central contribution is a system that operationalizes optimal experimental design inside the statistical-mechanics/Bayesian ensemble. Five components. (1) Posterior tracker: represent the learner as the Gibbs ensemble over weights consistent with labels (Tishby–Levin–Solla), summarized for perceptrons by order parameters (overlap R, self-overlap q) and, in general, by Monte-Carlo/Langevin samples; provide the Bayes-optimal predictor (center of mass of version space, per Opper–Haussler) plus baselines (Hebb, MinOver, Boltzmann/Gibbs). (2) Unified query scorer: score each candidate input x by design criteria re-expressed on the ensemble — Bayes-D equals expected reduction in log version-space volume (information gain), averaged over candidate labels weighted by the Bayes predictive probability p(y|x); Bayes-G minimizes the resulting worst-case predictive variance/generalization error; the greedy one-step rule maximizes Bayes-D and recovers Watkin–Rau's orthogonal-to-J heuristic as its leading-order approximation. (3) Analytic learning-curve module: extend Watkin–Rau's replica operator that inserts the (p+1)-th pattern to the case where the pattern is chosen by each criterion, yielding coupled ODEs for R(alpha) and generalization error G(alpha) under Bayes-D, Bayes-G, boundary-heuristic, and random sampling, for spherical and Ising perceptrons. (4) Simulation/benchmark harness: finite-N experiments for spherical/Ising perceptrons and a small two-layer net (matching Opper–Haussler hidden-unit approximations), comparing empirical curves to analytic predictions and across strategies; metrics include generalization error vs. alpha, examples wasted, information gain per query, and sample complexity implied by Haussler-style information/VC bounds. (5) Equivalence test: check analytically and empirically whether the Kiefer–Wolfowitz equivalence carries into the learning-curve regime (does Bayes-D also minimize worst-case generalization error?). This addresses the gap because the artifact is the bridge: Fedorov's design criteria, the Bayes-optimal ensemble, and Tishby's information gain become one scoring function evaluated three ways, validated by replica curves and simulation, replacing heuristic query rules with a principled criterion and quantifying how far heuristics such as the 42% figure sit from optimality. All required ingredients appear in the cited sources, and the perceptron setting keeps both analytics and simulation tractable."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as three disconnected communities (optimal experimental design, statistical mechanics of learning, Bayesian/information theory) answering the same query-selection question without connecting their theories — classic bridge_opportunity, with an explanation_gap element (why heuristics work, how far from optimal). The core move is fusing these into one scoring function with proven equivalences, i.e. synthesis_unification, backed by formal derivation (replica ODEs, Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence test). Though framed as a 'workbench,' the real contribution is the theoretical unification and derived criteria, not the artifact itself. The bottleneck (heuristic query rules lacking optimality criteria, three views of one object) is precisely identified. Not superficial stitching because it claims a genuine mathematical identity (Fedorov D = Tishby version-space reduction)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Three streams in these sources circle the same question—which training example is most informative—yet never connect, a bridge opportunity. (1) Statistical mechanics of learning (Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby 1992; Tishby-Levin-Solla 1989; Opper-Haussler 1991) gives a Gibbs posterior over a network's version space, an explicit information gain as entropy reduction from the prior, and replica learning curves; Opper-Haussler flag generalization-error versus one-step information gain as open but never use it to pick examples. (2) Physics example selection (Watkin-Rau 1992; Baum 1991 queries) shows big gains (about 42% fewer wasted examples) via an ad hoc rule—query orthogonal to the current estimate J (maximally ambiguous input)—with no optimality criterion or guarantee. (3) Classical optimal experimental design (Fedorov 1972) is a mature theory for this: D-optimality on the information matrix, the Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence theorem, and convergent sequential algorithms; Haussler 1991 adds information-theoretic/VC sample-complexity bounds. None of this has met the network Gibbs posterior or replica analysis. Gap: the physics heuristic lacks Fedorov's optimality criteria, equivalence theorems and convergence guarantees, while design theory has never been posed on the network posterior or given average-case learning curves. Bridging them explains why the maximally-ambiguous query works, makes it principled and guaranteed, and predicts how fast generalization falls under optimal querying.","method":"Recast active example selection for perceptrons as sequential Bayesian optimal experimental design on the statistical-mechanics Gibbs posterior, analyzed via replica theory. (1) From the Gibbs posterior over weights after m examples, define a candidate input x's expected one-step information gain as the mutual information between its label and W (expected entropy drop); for a binary perceptron this equals the binary entropy of the posterior vote split, maximal at 50/50. Show analytically that maximum information gain implies x orthogonal to the posterior-mean J, deriving the Watkin-Rau heuristic as the information-optimal query. (2) Define a posterior information matrix as the Hessian of the log error-partition-function, cast greedy querying as sequential D-optimal design, and prove a network analog of the Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence theorem: the information-maximizing query equals the query minimizing the maximum posterior predictive variance equals the maximally ambiguous point—giving a monotone-improvement convergence guarantee, with Baum's binary search as the 1-bit-per-query limit. (3) Via replica theory compute order parameters under the D-optimal query stream versus random sampling for spherical and Ising perceptrons, and for both Gibbs and Bayes-optimal (Opper-Haussler) predictors; predict asymptotic decay and test whether optimal design beats the 42% saving and turns power-law into exponential decay. (4) Chain per-query information gain against Haussler's VC/information bounds to bound queries needed for target error, and validate by simulating the sequential design algorithm (optimal-stability plus posterior sampling), probing label noise and replica symmetry."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.92,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames three disconnected streams (statistical mechanics of learning, physics example-selection heuristics, classical optimal experimental design) that circle the same question but never connect—a clear bridge_opportunity, with a secondary explanation_gap since it seeks to explain why the maximally-ambiguous query works. The method's central move is synthesizing these literatures into a unified framework, and it does deep formal work (deriving equivalence theorems, proving the heuristic as information-optimal, replica learning curves), so formal_derivation is secondary. Not surface stitching because the unification produces genuine analytic results (Kiefer-Wolfowitz analog, convergence guarantees, replica predictions) rather than a superficial A+B combination. Bottleneck is precisely identified: the heuristic lacks optimality/guarantees while design theory has never met the network posterior."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Bridge opportunity across optimal experimental design, statistical mechanics of learning, and PAC/VC learning theory for example selection.","method":"Empirically map and compare example-selection strategies on a perceptron teacher-student benchmark."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Opportunity framed as bridging optimal experimental design, statistical mechanics of learning, and PAC/VC theory for example selection (bridge_opportunity), with underlying concern about sample efficiency (resource_bottleneck). Method centers on unifying these separate literatures (synthesis_unification) via empirical comparison on a perceptron benchmark (empirical_mapping). The framing reads as combining three known frameworks, giving moderate surface-stitching signal, and the bottleneck (example selection cost) is only loosely specified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Two disconnected literatures answer the same question: which example should a learner query next to learn fastest? Classical optimal experimental design (Fedorov; Kiefer-Wolfowitz) offers rigorous objectives (D-optimality on the information matrix, G-optimality on max predictive variance), an equivalence theorem that D- and G-optimal designs coincide, and convergent sequential algorithms, but only for linear Gaussian regression, never for zero-one-loss classifier learning curves. Statistical mechanics of learning (Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby; Tishby-Levin-Solla Gibbs version-space posterior; Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal perceptron) gives exact learning curves via the student-teacher overlap R, and active-query heuristics (Watkin-Rau; Kinzel-Rujan) that pick examples on the decision boundary with a claimed 42 percent saving, but purely heuristically. A third stream (Haussler-Kearns-Schapire; Opper-Haussler one-step information gain) links information gain to generalization but gives no query rule. Bridge opportunity: no framework casts statistical-mechanics active learning as optimal experimental design, derives the physics heuristics as provable optima, and predicts learning curves. Connecting these would yield a principled query law with convergence guarantees, sample-complexity bounds, and predicted exponents.","method":"A formal-derivation, thermodynamic-limit optimal-experiment-design theory for classifier learning curves. (1) Use the Gibbs version-space posterior over perceptron weights and a query design measure rho over inputs, the analogue of Fedorov design measure, with order parameter R and error eps equal to (1/pi) arccos R. (2) Define Bayesian D-optimality (maximize expected posterior-entropy reduction, i.e. one-step information gain) and Bayesian G-optimality (minimize the max over inputs of posterior predictive disagreement). (3) Prove an equivalence theorem, the thermodynamic-limit analogue of Kiefer-Wolfowitz: via the replica-symmetric saddle point for spherical and Ising perceptrons, the D- and G-optimal query measures coincide and concentrate on the posterior-mean decision boundary, deriving the Watkin-Rau and Kinzel-Rujan heuristic as provably optimal and identifying wasted examples as the uniform design sub-optimality gap (recovering 42 percent). (4) Turn expected information gain into an ODE for d eps over d alpha, integrate to get the optimal-query learning curve, and compare its exponent to random sampling and the Opper-Haussler Bayes bound. (5) Give the Fedorov iterative update at the maximal-disagreement point, prove monotone convergence, and combine with Haussler-Kearns-Schapire information and VC bounds to bound queries needed for target eps. All ingredients exist in the sources and are analytically tractable in the perceptron model."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two/three disconnected literatures answering the same query question, so the gap is found via bridge_opportunity, with an explanation_gap secondary (deriving heuristics as provable optima, explaining why they work). The method reconciles optimal experimental design and statistical mechanics of learning (synthesis_unification), executed through theorem-proving, saddle-point derivations, and equivalence theorems (formal_derivation secondary). Bottleneck is precise: no framework casts SM active learning as optimal design; not superficial since it derives new equivalence theorems and exponents rather than merely concatenating methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Statistical-mechanics learning (Watkin and Rau; Seung and Sompolinsky) selects examples using only a single point-estimate weight vector, ignoring the full posterior. Bayesian work (Opper and Haussler; Tishby) shows version-space volume and information gain govern generalization but only analyzes them passively. Fedorov optimal experimental design gives principled sequential criteria but only for linear regression. Baum shows queries are cheap. These are disconnected; bridging them enables a principled posterior-based query rule for perceptrons.","method":"Maintain the Gibbs posterior over perceptron weights consistent with labels, sampled as an ensemble. At each step choose the query maximizing expected information gain, the classification analog of Fedorov D-optimality, biased toward the largest posterior-covariance eigendirection. Select queries by optimizing this objective over input space via gradient ascent or pool screening as costly resources. Derive the learning curve by replica theory and compare to random selection, the Watkin-Rau heuristic, and the Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal bound; validate on spherical and Ising perceptrons and extend to Baum depth-2 query nets."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames disconnected literatures (statistical-mechanics example selection, Bayesian version-space theory, Fedorov optimal design, query cheapness) that could be connected into a principled posterior-based query rule, so the gap is found via bridge_opportunity, with query cost/resource framing secondary. The core move integrates these strands into a unified information-gain query criterion (synthesis_unification), supported by replica-theory derivation of learning curves (formal_derivation). It precisely identifies the bottleneck: prior methods use only a point estimate, ignoring the full posterior. Not superficial stitching since it derives a genuinely new criterion and analysis."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Three research communities represented in these sources have independently developed the idea of *choosing which examples a learner sees*, yet they have never been connected, and each was worked out only under idealized assumptions.\n\n(1) The classical statistics of optimal experimental design (Fedorov, \"Theory of Optimal Experiments\") gives a rigorous, general machinery for sequentially selecting experiments to minimize the variance/entropy of estimated parameters: D-/G-optimality, the Kiefer–Wolfowitz equivalence theorem, and Fedorov's iterative rule \"add the point where the prediction-variance function d(x,ξ) is maximal.\" But this theory is built for linear regression with additive Gaussian noise.\n\n(2) The statistical mechanics of learning community independently invented active query learning for perceptrons. Watkin & Rau (\"Selecting examples for perceptrons\") show a 42% reduction in wasted examples by querying inputs that minimize the aligning field |J·ξ| (i.e. querying near the current decision boundary); Baum constructs queries geometrically by bisecting between + and − examples; Opper & Haussler compute the Bayes-optimal predictor and note a link to \"one-step information gain\"; Tishby, Levin & Solla frame learning as a Gibbs ensemble whose \"information gain\" is entropy reduction. But every one of these active-selection results assumes a *noise-free, realizable* teacher and the ability to place a query *anywhere* in input space.\n\nThe bridge that is missing: the perceptron \"minimize the field\" heuristic is nothing but Fedorov's \"query where prediction variance is maximal,\" specialized to a noiseless classifier — yet no one has stated this equivalence, nor used the mature experimental-design theory to justify, generalize, or correct the physics heuristics. Meanwhile the same review that studies active selection (Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby) shows that once rules are *unrealizable*, quenched disorder and spin-glass phases make generalization behave qualitatively differently and non-monotonically — exactly the regime in which greedy uncertainty sampling is most likely to be misled, and precisely the regime the active-learning papers never touch. This matters because real learners face label noise, model mismatch, and a fixed pool of inputs they cannot freely design, so we do not know whether the celebrated efficiency gains of query learning survive, vanish, or reverse.","method":"Build a single framework — \"statistical-mechanical optimal experimental design for learning\" — that identifies active example selection with sequential Bayesian optimal design on the Gibbs/version-space posterior, and then *relaxes the idealizing assumptions* under which all prior active-learning results were derived.\n\nStep 1 — Unify. Represent the learner not by a single weight vector but by the Gibbs posterior over networks at temperature T (following Tishby–Levin–Solla and the Seung–Sompolinsky–Tishby ensemble; Opper–Haussler's Bayes-optimal predictor is the T-averaged output). Define a design criterion = expected reduction in posterior entropy (information gain) from labeling a candidate input. Show analytically that this criterion (i) reduces to Fedorov's D-optimality and the equivalence-theorem \"maximum prediction-variance\" rule in the linear-Gaussian limit, and (ii) reduces to the Watkin–Rau \"minimize |J·ξ|\" rule and Baum's boundary-bisection in the noise-free realizable perceptron limit. This makes the two literatures special cases of one design functional.\n\nStep 2 — Relax the assumptions, one regime at a time, and compute typical-case learning curves with the replica/annealed methods already used in these sources:\n  (a) Label noise / stochastic teacher: introduce a teacher temperature and re-derive the optimal design. Prediction: greedy boundary-querying (which places all mass on the noisiest, most ambiguous inputs) becomes suboptimal exactly as Fedorov's theory warns; there is an optimal \"query softness\" that spreads queries away from the boundary, and an optimal matching between query temperature and inference temperature T.\n  (b) Unrealizable rules (model mismatch): here entropy reduction in *parameter* space (D-optimality) diverges from reduction in *generalization error*, because the posterior concentrates on a wrong minimum. Replace the parameter-space criterion by a predictive-error criterion (integrate Tishby–Levin–Solla's prediction error into the design objective) and compute whether active selection still helps; predict a phase where uncertainty sampling is actively harmful because it chases unrealizable structure, connected to the spin-glass phases reported for unrealizable rules.\n  (c) Pool-based / fixed input distribution: forbid free query construction (the unrealistic power Baum and Watkin–Rau assume) and instead select from inputs drawn from p(S). Introduce this as a constrained design measure (Kiefer–Wolfowitz designs are exactly measures over a compact input space), and quantify how much of the 42% saving survives when queries cannot be placed arbitrarily.\n  (d) Finite-N corrections to the thermodynamic-limit predictions.\n\nStep 3 — Validate against the known anchors: the framework must reproduce Watkin–Rau's 42% and Opper–Haussler's Bayes-optimal √2 factor in the noiseless realizable limit, and Fedorov's D-optimal designs in the linear limit, then extend beyond all of them. Deliverables: (i) a design–inference duality theorem linking experimental-design optimality to Bayes-optimal generalization; (ii) closed-form or numerically-solved learning curves showing when active selection helps, saturates, or reverses as functions of noise level, degree of unrealizability, and pool constraint; (iii) a corrected, noise-robust query criterion that interpolates between \"minimize the field\" and D-optimal spreading. This directly addresses the gap: it makes the physics active-learning results function under weaker assumptions (noise, model mismatch, restricted queries, finite size) by importing and generalizing the classical optimal-design theory they were unknowingly re-deriving."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.88,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as three disconnected communities (optimal experimental design, statistical mechanics of learning, Bayesian query learning) that independently developed active example selection but never linked — a bridge_opportunity, with a strong scope_mismatch secondary since prior work assumed noise-free realizable teachers and free query placement. The central move is synthesis_unification: a single design functional showing physics heuristics as special cases of Fedorov's theory, with a design-inference duality theorem. Secondary is relax_extend_scope, systematically relaxing idealized assumptions (noise, unrealizability, pool constraints, finite N). Though it combines literatures, the equivalence is a genuine mechanistic identification (minimize-field = maximum prediction-variance), not superficial stitching, and it identifies precise limiting regimes."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Four streams in these sources all address which examples a learner should acquire and how well it will then generalize, yet were developed in isolation: statistical-mechanics of learning and example selection (Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby 1992; Opper and Haussler 1991; Watkin and Rau 1992, showing orthogonal example selection cuts wasted examples about 42 percent); query learning in computational learning theory (Baum 1991, boundary membership queries with polynomial-time guarantees); classical optimal experimental design (Fedorov 1972, D and G optimality and information-matrix maximization) framed for linear regression and never connected to neural nets; and Bayesian and information-theoretic generalization theory (Opper and Haussler Bayes-optimal classifier, noted as hard to implement; Tishby, Levin and Solla posterior Gibbs measure; Haussler, Kearns and Schapire sample-complexity bounds). No work links Fedorov design theory and the Bayesian posterior view to statistical-mechanics query strategies. Critically, all concrete active and query strategies assume a noise-free realizable teacher and greedily pick the single most-uncertain boundary point, yet Seung et al. show that for unrealizable or noisy rules learning curves become non-monotone, approximations fail, and spin-glass phases appear. Greedy maximum-uncertainty querying concentrates on the boundary where label noise dominates, so under noise or mismatch the most efficient known algorithm wastes queries or degrades generalization, a brittleness none of the streams analyze because they never connect.","method":"Build a robust Bayesian active example-selection framework for perceptron learning that unifies Fedorov-style optimal design, the posterior Gibbs measure, and statistical-mechanics learning-curve analysis. First, represent knowledge as the Gibbs posterior over weights at temperature T rather than a single estimate, tracking the order parameter R equal to J dot B and the posterior spread analytically. Second, the bridging design criterion: replace greedy boundary querying with a Fedorov D and G optimality analogue on the posterior predictive, picking the query maximizing expected reduction in Bayes generalization risk rather than raw boundary information, importing optimal-experiment-design theory into neural query learning. Third, robustification: introduce an explicit noise and mismatch parameter (a label-flip rate eta, or a mismatched-architecture teacher as in Seung et al.), and make selection a minimax or Bayesian-averaged design maximizing worst-case expected risk reduction over an uncertainty set of eta, weighting candidates by predicted label reliability; this penalizes noise-dominated boundary queries, prevents boundary-collapse, and reduces to the Watkin and Rau orthogonal-query rule in the noise-free limit. Fourth, use replica and annealed machinery to derive generalization error versus alpha for random sampling, greedy margin query, plain Fedorov design, and robust minimax design, for Ising and spherical perceptrons, as functions of alpha and eta, predicting where greedy querying becomes non-monotone or diverges. Fifth, connect achieved query complexity to information-theoretic and VC bounds for worst-case reliability, and validate with finite-N simulations measuring query efficiency and, crucially, variance and worst-case error across increasing noise and teacher-student mismatch."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly identifies four isolated streams (statistical mechanics of learning, query learning, optimal experimental design, Bayesian/information-theoretic theory) that were never connected, making bridge_opportunity primary; the secondary gap is the brittleness of greedy querying under noise/mismatch (failure_risk_gap). The core research move unifies Fedorov design, Gibbs posterior, and stat-mech analysis (synthesis_unification), with an explicit robustification component via minimax noise-aware design. Combination is substantive with a concrete mechanism (greedy querying concentrating on noise-dominated boundaries), not surface stitching, and the bottleneck is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"bridge_opportunity","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Classical optimal experimental design and statistical-mechanics active learning are disconnected literatures.","method":"Unify them into one Bayesian information-theoretic design framework for perceptron learning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames two disconnected literatures (optimal experimental design and statistical-mechanics active learning) as the gap, which is a bridge_opportunity; the active-learning/example-selection angle touches resource bottlenecks in sample use. The method unifies them into one Bayesian information-theoretic framework, so synthesis_unification is primary with formal_derivation secondary. The terse A-plus-B framing raises surface-stitching concern, though the underlying committee/disagreement idea is more principled than mere concatenation. Bottleneck specificity is modest given the brief description."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"The works give sharp learning-theory predictions under incompatible idealized assumptions, with no shared instrumented testbed to observe, compare, audit, or accumulate evidence on whether they hold at finite N and across regimes.","method":"Build an open benchmark platform implementing each paper's selection strategy behind one interface over a common teacher-student perceptron generator, logging empirical learning curves against closed-form predictions, sweeping N and noise, and publishing a reproducible evidence repository."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"The motivation is that sharp theoretical predictions rest on incompatible idealized assumptions with no shared testbed to observe/compare/audit them (evidence_gap), with a secondary flavor of reconciling conflicting predictions (puzzle_contradiction). The method builds a benchmark platform logging empirical learning curves against closed-form predictions and sweeping regimes, which is systematic measurement/diagnostics (empirical_mapping) delivered as a benchmark platform (artifact_system secondary). The proposal is somewhat of a wrapper that puts many prior strategies behind one interface, giving moderate surface-stitching, but the identified bottleneck (finite-N validity across regimes) is reasonably specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"A cluster of results shows that a learner can do far better than passively absorbing random examples: Baum's query algorithm bisects near the decision boundary, Watkin & Rau's \"selecting examples for perceptrons\" predicts a 42% reduction in wasted examples by querying points orthogonal to the current weight vector, Opper & Haussler compute the Bayes-optimal generalization curve and relate it to an \"average one-step information gain,\" Fedorov's optimal experimental design offers D-/G-optimality criteria, and Tishby et al.'s consistent-inference framework identifies the natural currency of learning as the reduction of ensemble entropy (the accessible configuration / version-space volume). The statistical-mechanics-of-learning review and the storage-capacity and statistical-theory-of-a-rule works supply exactly solvable learning curves for the perceptron teacher–student setting.\n\nThe evidence gap: each of these selection principles (query-near-boundary, Bayesian information-maximization, D-optimal experimental design) is proposed and analyzed in its own idiom (replica computations, Bayesian posteriors, variance/information matrices, worst-case VC bounds), and each reports its gains against a different baseline. The field therefore has no common instrument to *measure* how efficiently any given query strategy actually extracts information, no way to *benchmark* competing strategies against the true achievable optimum in the same units, and no diagnostic to *audit* when and why a heuristic (e.g., always querying at the boundary) becomes wasteful (correlated, redundant, or noise-amplifying queries). Claims like the \"42% reduction\" cannot be placed on an absolute scale, and evidence about different regimes (spherical vs. discrete Ising weights, noise-free vs. noisy teachers) cannot be accumulated or compared. This matters because it is impossible to know how much room for improvement remains, or which principle to trust, without such a measuring stick.\n\nThe listed works leave this open: they provide the solvable model and each piece of the machinery (entropy currency, Bayes-optimal bound, exact learning curves) but never combine them into a shared measurement and benchmarking framework for query/example-selection strategies.","method":"Build a solvable \"information-efficiency measurement instrument\" for example-selection strategies, using the perceptron teacher–student problem in the thermodynamic limit as the testbed where a ground-truth optimum exists.\n\n(1) Common currency. Adopt Tishby et al.'s ensemble entropy — the reduction of the log accessible version-space (Gardner) volume, equivalently posterior entropy — as the single measurable quantity. For any strategy, express its behavior through the standard order parameters (student–teacher overlap R(alpha) and volume/entropy S(alpha)) obtained from the replica calculation, exactly as in Watkin & Rau. From these define the marginal per-query information gain g(alpha) = -dS/dalpha.\n\n(2) Absolute reference. Compute the Bayes-optimal one-step information gain g*(alpha) from the Opper–Haussler optimal generalization curve, which is the maximal achievable entropy reduction per example. Define the measurable \"information efficiency\" eta(alpha) = g(alpha)/g*(alpha) in [0,1], and an aggregate efficiency (area under the eta curve). This turns every strategy into a number on the same scale and lets the \"42% reduction\" and similar claims be re-expressed as efficiency relative to the true optimum.\n\n(3) Unified strategy family. Instantiate the same instrument on a menu of selection rules cast as different scoring functions on candidate inputs: (a) query-near-boundary / minimal-margin (Watkin & Rau, Baum), (b) Bayesian maximum expected information gain / query-by-committee style disagreement (Opper–Haussler), (c) Fedorov D-optimal / maximum-variance design mapped into the perceptron's information matrix, and (d) random sampling as the passive baseline. Each rule is fed into the same order-parameter equations (or Monte-Carlo version-space sampling in finite N) so that all are measured identically.\n\n(4) Benchmark and audit. Produce learning-curve benchmarks plotting generalization error and eta(alpha) for every strategy together with the optimal bound, across controlled conditions: spherical vs. discrete Ising weights (where entropy can go negative and a first-order transition to perfect generalization occurs), output noise, and input-distribution mismatch. Use eta and its breakdown to diagnose failure modes — e.g., quantify query redundancy/correlation by measuring the shortfall g(alpha) << g*(alpha) that arises when boundary queries become mutually informative-poor, and identify regimes where a heuristic actually underperforms random sampling.\n\n(5) Validation and accumulation. Cross-check the analytic replica predictions against finite-size simulations (perceptron learning with MinOver/optimal-stability constructions and posterior sampling), and package the whole thing as a reproducible benchmark suite with the version-space-entropy efficiency eta as the standard reported metric, so that future selection strategies can be dropped in and compared on the same absolute, information-theoretic scale.\n\nThis addresses the gap by supplying the missing shared instrument: it observes and measures information extraction in interpretable bits, benchmarks heterogeneous strategies against the exact optimum, audits when heuristics waste queries, and lets evidence accumulate across noise levels and network types — all within an exactly solvable model where the answers can be trusted."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as the field lacking a common instrument to measure, benchmark, and audit query-selection strategies against a true optimum in shared units (evidence_gap), with a strong bridging dimension across disconnected idioms (replica, Bayesian, Fedorov). The method builds a shared measurement/benchmarking framework with a common efficiency metric and diagnostics (empirical_mapping), reconciling separate selection principles into one scale (synthesis_unification secondary). Bottleneck is precisely named: heterogeneous baselines and no absolute reference. Not superficial stitching because it defines a genuine common currency (version-space entropy efficiency) grounded in a solvable model."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The sources predict perceptron learning curves under many separate assumptions but never compare them on one empirical platform, leaving an evidence gap about finite-size corrections, query gains, and assumption validity.","method":"Build a benchmark that simulates perceptron learning across model classes, learning rules, example-selection strategies, and system sizes, measures generalization curves, and compares them against the closed-form predictions of the sources to map finite-size corrections, query gains, and where replica assumptions break down."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames a lack of common empirical platform to compare separate theoretical predictions (evidence_gap), with a bridging flavor across disconnected theoretical accounts. The method builds a benchmark to measure and compare generalization curves against closed-form predictions and map where assumptions break down, which is empirical_mapping with a synthesis component. Note this reframes the actual query-by-committee contribution as a benchmarking exercise, showing some stitching of prior threads, but the bottleneck (finite-size corrections, replica breakdown) is reasonably specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the evidence gap in comparing query selection strategies for perceptron learning.","method":"Test method proposing a formal query value functional and an equivalence theorem."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"explanation_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation cites an evidence gap in comparing query selection strategies; method proposes a formal query value functional and equivalence theorem, indicating formal_derivation. Placeholder 'Test' text limits specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"The corpus contains two mature but disconnected bodies of work. First, statistical mechanics yields exact generalization curves and information-theoretic bounds for learning from randomly sampled examples: inverse-power-law and exponential learning-curve tails (Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby review), the Bayes-optimal error and its sqrt(2) advantage over Gibbs learning (Opper-Haussler), Bayesian sample-complexity bounds tied to VC dimension, and consistent-inference predictions for layered nets. Second, several works propose active example/query selection to beat random sampling: Watkin-Rau predict a 42 percent reduction in wasted examples by selecting questions orthogonal to the current estimate, Baum's polynomial-time algorithm uses membership-query bisection, and the classical theory of optimal experiments frames this as experimental design. The evidence gap: each selection strategy is analyzed in isolation for a single idealized model (usually a noise-free, realizable perceptron) and measured on its own terms. The field has no common yardstick to measure how much of the information-theoretically available error reduction a strategy actually harvests, to compare heterogeneous strategies on equal footing, or to audit when active selection's advantage survives label noise, model mismatch (unrealizable rules, where the review shows approximations fail and error can be non-monotonic), and over/under-parameterization. This matters because active learning's promise is efficiency, yet we cannot say how close any strategy comes to the achievable optimum nor where the savings evaporate. The exact SM learning curves are the missing measuring stick, but no work uses them to benchmark selection strategies.","method":"Build an optimization-driven benchmarking framework that uses exact statistical-mechanics learning curves as a ground-truth yardstick and casts next-example selection as adaptive optimization. First, metrics: for each model use the SM/Bayes-optimal curve e_g*(alpha) as reference; define information yield as realized error reduction per query divided by the maximum reduction implied by e_g* at the same alpha, and sample-complexity gap as extra examples needed to reach a target error relative to the Bayes-optimal curve. Second, a benchmark suite spanning axes the corpus isolates but never crosses: Ising vs spherical perceptrons, realizable vs unrealizable teachers, noise-free vs label-noise, and learner type (Hebb, optimal-stability/MinOver, Gibbs, Bayes committee), with large-N simulations compared to analytic predictions. Third, selection-as-optimization: at each step choose the next example by searching input space to maximize a tractable surrogate of expected information gain, unifying prior heuristics as instances: minimal-margin selection placing the query on the current boundary, query-by-committee/version-space bisection using weights sampled from the Gibbs posterior, and Baum membership-query bisection; use candidate-pool screening plus geometric or gradient search to place queries efficiently and scale to large N. Fourth, resource allocation: when cheap random labels and expensive designed queries coexist, treat the mixed budget as scheduling optimization, adaptively allocating queries versus random draws to minimize error per unit cost and comparing the realized cost-error frontier to the theoretical optimum. Fifth, audit: run all strategies across the suite, overlay realized curves on SM benchmark curves, and report information-yield and sample-complexity-gap heatmaps over noise, realizability, and parameterization, testing falsifiable hypotheses such as that minimal-margin selection is fragile under label noise while committee bisection degrades gracefully, and that under model mismatch active selection can underperform random sampling in the non-monotonic regimes the review flags. The output is a reproducible protocol and metric set letting future selection algorithms be benchmarked against the achievable optimum rather than evaluated in isolation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as the absence of a common yardstick to compare and audit active-selection strategies against the information-theoretic optimum (evidence_gap), with a strong bridging motivation between disconnected SM learning-curve and active-selection literatures. The central move is building a benchmark/metric suite that measures information yield and sample-complexity gaps across regimes (empirical_mapping), while explicitly unifying prior heuristics as instances of one selection-as-optimization framework (synthesis_unification secondary). There is some surface-stitching risk since it packages several existing methods together, though the shared benchmark yardstick gives genuine integrative value. Optimization language is present but subordinate to the measurement/benchmarking contribution."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Evidence gap: the field cannot measure or benchmark whether active query learning actually helps or silently hurts generalization once idealizing assumptions are dropped. Watkin and Rau show analytically a 42 percent reduction in wasted examples for a perceptron that greedily queries inputs on its current decision boundary; Baum's examples-and-queries algorithm and the maximum-information heuristic assume a clean realizable oracle; Opper and Haussler and Tishby-Levin-Solla provide Bayes-optimal and version-space prediction measures. But every result on the value of active selection assumes noise-free labels, a target realizable by the student, and the large-N limit. The review Statistical mechanics of learning treats noise and unrealizable rules only for passive random sampling. This matters because greedy querying concentrates queries exactly on the boundary, where labels are noisiest and an unrealizable target most misleading, so the mechanism that makes it efficient may make it self-defeating. No theory, metric, or benchmark exists to observe when this happens, nor evidence comparing greedy versus Bayes-optimal querying under realistic conditions.","method":"Relax the noise-free, realizable, and large-N assumptions of existing statistical-mechanics analyses of query learning and convert the relaxed theory into a diagnostic benchmark. First, take Watkin and Rau's replica order-parameter machinery and the Opper-Haussler version-space formulation and re-derive the generalization curve for query learning under three graduated relaxations: label noise where the oracle flips the teacher label with probability lambda so boundary queries get the least reliable answers; architecture mismatch with an unrealizable target such as a reversed-wedge perceptron or committee machine giving an error floor; and finite N with leading corrections. Second, compare three selection rules under each condition: passive random sampling as baseline, greedy boundary querying, and Bayes-optimal querying that maximizes expected version-space information gain using the full posterior. Third, define benchmark metrics as functions of lambda, mismatch, and N: the asymptotic error floor, the break-even sample size where active first beats then may lose to random, a query-safety margin measuring drift onto the noisy boundary, and a robustness ratio of active advantage under noise over active advantage when clean. These pinpoint the regime where greedy querying flips from beneficial to harmful and test whether posterior-aware Bayes-optimal querying stays robust where greedy fails. Fourth, validate against finite-N Monte Carlo simulations of Ising and spherical perceptrons scanning noise, mismatch, and N. The deliverable is a phase-diagram benchmark annotated with which strategy is safe plus closed-form metric expressions, giving the first auditable account of when active example selection helps versus hurts."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.75,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The core gap is that prior query-learning theory relies on idealizing assumptions (noise-free, realizable, large-N), a scope_mismatch, with a secondary evidence_gap since no metric/benchmark exists to observe when active querying hurts. The central move is relaxing those assumptions in the statistical-mechanics analysis (relax_extend_scope), executed via replica-based re-derivation of generalization curves and closed-form metrics (formal_derivation). The proposal identifies a precise mechanism—greedy querying concentrates on the noisiest boundary—giving high bottleneck specificity. Though it also builds a benchmark, the driving contribution is extending the theory to realistic regimes rather than superficial combination."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Active example-selection for perceptrons (Watkin-Rau) gives large efficiency gains but is derived only in noise-free, realizable teacher-student settings. Querying near the boundary is exactly where label noise and teacher-student mismatch cause most harm. The field lacks any way to measure, benchmark, or diagnose when active selection helps versus hurts generalization under noise, and lacks a reliability audit. The SM review flags noisy rules but not active selection; Bayes-optimal and active-learning results are noise-free. The provided works supply the machinery to both measure and fix this but never combine it.","method":"First, build a robustness benchmark: extend the replica learning-curve calculation for boundary-querying to label noise and teacher-student mismatch, measuring the gap between idealized and noisy curves and the point where selection underperforms random sampling. Second, robustify the query rule: sample at a tunable margin offset from the boundary rather than exactly on it, score candidates by Bayes posterior variance to reduce single-point leverage, and down-weight noise-dominated queries. Third, add an online diagnostic using the prediction-probability criterion and committee disagreement to detect harmful regimes and revert to random sampling. Validate analytically and via finite-N simulation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is found by noting prior active-selection results assume noise-free realizable settings (scope_mismatch), with a secondary framing that boundary querying is brittle under noise (failure_risk_gap). The central move extends the replica learning-curve analysis to noisy/mismatched regimes (relax_extend_scope) and then robustifies the query rule (robustification). Though it combines measurement and fixing, these are integrated around a precise bottleneck (querying near the boundary maximizes noise harm), not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"evidence_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: the field lacks a common way to benchmark and compare active-learning and learning-curve predictions across statistical mechanics, Bayes-optimal analysis, VC bounds, and optimal experimental design.","method":"Test method: unify these under version-space posterior entropy and benchmark per-query information gain on perceptron learning."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames a lack of common ground across separate literatures (statistical mechanics, Bayes-optimal, VC, optimal experimental design), a bridge_opportunity, with a secondary evidence_gap around benchmarking/comparison. The method unifies these under version-space posterior entropy and information gain, a synthesis_unification move with a formal_derivation component (query-by-committee's information-theoretic framing). Not superficial stitching since a genuine unifying quantity is proposed."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the explanation gap in why example selection speeds up perceptron learning.","method":"Test method building a version space measurement platform."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Placeholder 'test' motivation and method give little signal. Motivation explicitly names an explanation gap about why example selection speeds learning; method mentions a version space measurement platform, leaning empirical but the underlying query-by-committee context suggests formal derivation. Low confidence due to boilerplate content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"TEST motivation about explanation gap in query learning under unrealizable rules.","method":"TEST method extending replica analysis with query concentration and misspecification knobs."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation frames an explanation gap in query learning, with a scope mismatch under unrealizable/misspecified rules. Method extends replica analysis (formal derivation) into broader regimes (relax_extend_scope). Test proposal so specificity is moderate."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about the explanation gap in active example selection for perceptrons.","method":"Test method describing an empirical simulation map across selection strategies."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.55,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is a placeholder ('Test motivation'/'Test method') describing an explanation gap in active example selection and an empirical simulation map across strategies. Opportunity is framed as an explanation gap; method is a systematic comparative empirical map. Highly generic/boilerplate due to placeholder content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"Across these works, active/query-based example selection for perceptrons produces puzzlingly heterogeneous outcomes that lack a unified explanation. Watkin & Rau (\"Selecting examples for perceptrons\") show that choosing questions orthogonal to the current weight estimate (queries lying on the decision boundary) gives only a CONSTANT-FACTOR benefit for the spherical perceptron — a 42% reduction in \"wasted\" examples — while leaving the asymptotic power-law generalization curve unchanged; yet for the Ising perceptron the same style of selection interacts with the discontinuous jump to perfect generalization. Meanwhile, for PASSIVE (random) learning, Seung–Sompolinsky–Tishby provide a clean taxonomy: the asymptotic form of the learning curve (inverse power law, nontrivial power law, exponential tail, or discontinuous transition) is dictated by the exponent z in the version-space entropy s(ε)∝ε^z near ε=0, distinguishing smooth (continuous-weight) from nonsmooth (discrete-weight) networks. Opper & Haussler hint at a governing \"one-step information gain\" and quantify a √2 gap between Bayes-optimal and Gibbs/Boltzmann learning; Tishby–Levin–Solla cast generalization as a free-energy/entropy contraction of the posterior ensemble; and classical optimal experiment design (Fedorov, via Kiefer–Wolfowitz D-/G-optimality) offers a variational language for \"most informative\" probes. Despite these ingredients, there is NO causal/mechanistic account of WHY and WHEN actively selecting examples changes the ASYMPTOTIC FORM (exponent) of the learning curve versus merely rescaling its prefactor. Why does boundary-querying buy only a constant factor for the spherical perceptron but qualitatively reshape learning for discrete-weight networks? What is the optimal query and the best achievable rate? This explanatory gap matters because it decides whether active learning is fundamentally more powerful or only marginally cheaper — and the listed works compute isolated cases without deriving the underlying principle.","method":"Construct a formal theory of active perceptron learning as sequential Bayesian optimal experiment design over the version-space Gibbs ensemble, and derive from it a predictive dichotomy for learning-curve forms. (1) Model: define the posterior/Gibbs measure on weight space and its relative entropy S(α) (following Tishby–Levin–Solla), together with the exact map e_g=(1/π)arccos R between generalization error and target-overlap order parameter R used throughout the SM literature. (2) Variational characterization theorem: derive the expected one-step entropy reduction ΔS(x) for a candidate query x and prove it is maximized by the maximally ambiguous query — the input on the current posterior's decision boundary (margin→0), i.e., Watkin–Rau's orthogonality prescription — thereby unifying their heuristic with Opper–Haussler's \"one-step information gain\" and with Fedorov D-optimality (a perceptron analogue of the D/G-optimality equivalence). (3) Flow equations: using replica/annealed averaging, derive the deterministic ODE for S(α) and R(α) under greedy optimal querying, a query-driven counterpart of the SSNT saddle-point equations. (4) Central dichotomy theorem: introduce a \"query-informativeness exponent\" q that measures how the best attainable per-query information gain scales as the version space contracts (e_g→0), controlled by the density of achievable maximally-ambiguous inputs — which depends on whether inputs are drawn from a fixed distribution or can be synthesized, and on weight-space smoothness. Prove: (a) when informative queries are limited by a fixed input measure with bounded boundary density (continuous weights), optimal querying preserves the SSNT power-law exponent and only improves the prefactor — quantitatively recovering the constant-factor (≈42%) speedup for the spherical perceptron; (b) when the version space can be split by a constant fraction per query (freely synthesizable inputs, or discrete/Ising weights where entropy has a finite floor, SSNT z≥1), S decreases linearly in the number of queries, yielding an exponential curve e_g∝e^{-cα} and/or an earlier discontinuous jump to perfect generalization. (5) Matching lower bounds: combine the entropy-contraction rate with the information-theoretic/VC-dimension Bayesian sample-complexity bounds (Haussler et al.) and the storage-capacity constraints (Gardner's capacity works) to certify that no query strategy beats these rates, establishing that the achievable rate equals min(information supplied per query, version-space geometric contractibility). (6) Validation: check the derived curves reduce, in the appropriate limits, to Watkin–Rau's 42% spherical result and Ising behavior, Opper–Haussler's √2 Bayes factor, and the SSNT passive taxonomy — turning three disparate empirical observations into consequences of a single derivation. The theory explains the \"why\" (informativeness supply vs. entropy geometry) and provides a constructive optimal-query rule with provable rate."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal is explicitly framed around a missing causal/mechanistic account of WHY active querying changes learning-curve exponent for some networks but only rescales prefactor for others, driven by conflicting/heterogeneous empirical outcomes (explanation_gap primary, puzzle_contradiction secondary). The method constructs a formal theory: variational characterization theorem, flow equations, a central dichotomy theorem with a new exponent, and matching lower bounds (formal_derivation primary). It also unifies Watkin-Rau, Opper-Haussler, SSNT, and Fedorov optimal design into one framework (synthesis_unification secondary). Bottleneck is precisely identified (informativeness supply vs entropy geometry), and the unification is derivation-driven rather than superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Query-based example selection greatly speeds perceptron learning (Watkin-Rau 1992 zero-margin selection; Baum 1991 queries), yet no theory explains why the zero-margin heuristic works, whether it is optimal, or how active selection reshapes the learning-curve exponent that Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby (1992) derived only for random examples. Optimal experimental design (Fedorov 1972) and information objectives (Tishby-Levin-Solla 1989; Opper-Haussler 1991) are never linked to the version-space picture, so the optimal query strategy and achievable acceleration are unknown.","method":"Formulate adaptive query selection as sequential optimal design. Track order parameters R and version-space entropy S, and choose each query by its margin m. Optimize m analytically under several objectives (version-space-volume reduction, error decrement, information gain, committee disagreement) using replica averages, deriving the optimal margin schedule and testing whether zero-margin is optimal. Feed the optimal query into the saddle-point equations to derive the learning curve, explaining when a power law becomes exponential and quantifying acceleration. Compare Gibbs and Bayes learners, and validate with simulations and Watkin-Rau numerics."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly an explanation gap: no theory explains why the zero-margin heuristic works or whether it's optimal, and how active selection reshapes the learning-curve exponent. Secondary is bridge opportunity since optimal experimental design and information objectives are never linked to the version-space picture. Method is formal derivation (replica averages, saddle-point equations, deriving optimal margin schedule and learning curves), with synthesis_unification secondary from connecting the disconnected frameworks. Precise bottleneck identified (the margin schedule); not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
