{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Query-based active example selection is the headline sample-complexity result in statistical-mechanics learning theory: Watkin & Rau (1992) predict ~42% fewer wasted examples for the Ising perceptron via continual selection, Baum (1991) shows queries evade NP-hardness limits, and the idea descends from optimal experiment design (Fedorov 1972). But every such analysis assumes a realizable, noise-free target, so querying near the current decision boundary maximizes information per example. This leaves an explanation gap: there is no mechanistic account of why the active-learning advantage appears and, crucially, why, when, and how much it should erode or reverse under unrealizability or label noise. This matters because Seung, Sompolinsky & Tishby (1992) show unrealizable rules produce qualitatively new physics: non-monotonic generalization, spin-glass phases, and failure of annealed/high-temperature approximations. The mechanism that makes greedy querying fast (concentrating examples at the boundary) concentrates them exactly where noise and model mismatch are most corrupting; Watkin & Rau even note an effective per-example noise term whose width shrinks with teacher-student overlap, yet never analyze the noisy case. No source combines active selection with the spin-glass/unrealizable regime, so it is unknown whether the celebrated speedup is robust or a brittle artifact of the noise-free idealization.","method":"Part 1, mechanistic explanation: extend Watkin & Rau's continual-selection replica calculation to controlled unrealizability by adding teacher label noise and capacity mismatch (overlap R cannot reach 1), using the unrealizable-rule setup of Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby, finite-temperature Gibbs learning of Tishby-Levin-Solla, and Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal learning as baseline. Track order parameters R, q, stability kappa, and the effective per-example noise width, and derive the generalization curve for greedy query-at-zero-margin selection. Output a phase diagram over noise, mismatch, and temperature marking where greedy active learning accelerates, turns non-monotonic, or enters a spin-glass phase where selection hurts, explaining how boundary-concentrated querying amplifies noise. Part 2, robustified rule: replace maximize-information-per-example with a risk-adjusted criterion selecting examples at an optimal offset from the boundary, maximizing expected information minus a noise-amplification penalty computed online from current order parameters; add two stabilizers flagged by the theory, enforcing positive optimal stability and finite-temperature Gibbs averaging to stay out of the spin-glass regime. Offset and kappa adapt from R, q, and estimated noise width, reducing to standard greedy querying in the clean limit. Validation: compare random sampling, greedy querying, and the robust rule in spherical and Ising perceptron simulations across noise and mismatch levels, measuring mean generalization error, run-to-run variance as brittleness, and agreement with predicted phase boundaries. Success means the theory predicts the crossover where greedy querying loses to random sampling, and the robust rule keeps most of the speedup in the clean limit while removing degradation and variance under noise and mismatch."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames an explanation gap: no mechanistic account of why the active-learning advantage appears and when it erodes under noise/unrealizability, with a strong secondary failure_risk_gap concern about brittleness of the celebrated speedup. Part 1 is a replica-calculation formal derivation producing a phase diagram; Part 2 is a robustified risk-adjusted selection rule, hence robustification secondary. The bottleneck is precisely identified (boundary-concentrated querying amplifies noise where the effective noise width matters). Not surface stitching since it derives new physics rather than gluing methods."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"explanation_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Active example selection accelerates generalization dramatically but unevenly, and no one explains why the speedup varies. Watkin and Rau predict a 42 percent reduction in wasted examples for the Ising perceptron and find optimally selected examples for spherical perceptrons generalize far faster than random ones. Opper and Haussler show the Bayes-optimal predictor beats the Gibbs learner by a factor approaching sqrt(2) and flag the unexplored link between generalization error and one-step information gain. Tishby, Levin and Solla recast learning as entropy reduction, shrinking accessible version-space volume. Fedorov's classical Theory of Optimal Experiments gives a mature calculus of query design: D-optimality, G-optimality, Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence. These literatures developed in isolation, leaving an explanation gap: no unified causal account of why active selection helps, why it sometimes yields only a constant-factor gain, sometimes changes the learning-curve exponent, and sometimes yields near-exponential generalization, and how this depends on hypothesis-space geometry and learner type.","method":"Build a unifying framework identifying the statistical-mechanics version-space entropy with the information matrix of classical optimal experimental design. Map the Gibbs-ensemble version-space log-volume onto Fedorov's information matrix, so reducing accessible volume becomes a determinant or variance functional; show maximizing Opper-Haussler one-step information gain is a D-optimality step and Watkin-Rau boundary selection is a G-optimality step, using Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence to explain why they coincide. Using replica order parameters already computed in these papers, derive per-query entropy reduction as a functional of the chosen criterion, predicting when it yields a constant factor, changes the exponent, or drives an Ising first-order transition to perfect generalization. Reconcile the sqrt(2) Bayes-vs-Gibbs gap as the difference between prediction-optimality and design-optimality. Validate by recovering known cases and issuing new falsifiable predictions, such as the criterion converting the spherical Bayes power law to exponential decay, testable with existing replica calculations and simulations."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"explanation_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.9,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly states an explanation gap: no unified causal account of why active selection helps and why speedups vary. It also frames disconnected literatures (statistical mechanics, Bayesian learning, classical optimal experimental design) as the bridge, hence secondary bridge_opportunity. The core move is unifying these frameworks (identifying version-space entropy with Fedorov's information matrix, mapping D/G-optimality onto known criteria), so synthesis_unification is primary; the derivation of per-query entropy functionals and reconciliation of sqrt(2) gap via formal derivation is secondary. Not surface stitching: it identifies a precise structural correspondence (Kiefer-Wolfowitz equivalence, determinant functionals) with concrete falsifiable predictions."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation about brittleness of active query learning under noisy oracles.","method":"test method building a platform to stress test and harden query selection."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"artifact_system"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Motivation frames the gap as brittleness of active query learning under noisy oracles (failure_risk_gap). Method aims to harden query selection (robustification) via a stress-testing platform (artifact_system secondary). Content is a placeholder 'test' proposal, hence generic/boilerplate and low specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Active example-selection methods for perceptrons (Watkin and Rau; Baum) gain efficiency by querying points near the current decision boundary, and the information-gain and Bayes-optimal analyses reward the most ambiguous queries. All assume a noise-free oracle. But near-boundary points are exactly where labels are least reliable, so greedy selection harvests the most corruptible labels and can turn information gain into misinformation. The statistical-mechanics review shows noise and unrealizability cause non-monotone curves and spin-glass phases for passive sampling, but this is never combined with active selection. The gap is an uncharacterized reliability hazard: active learning may be brittle and worse than random sampling under label noise, with no theory of when it is safe.","method":"Extend the statistical-mechanics theory of example selection to a noisy oracle. Model a perceptron learning a teacher where each queried label flips with probability eta. The learner queries points at an adjustable margin kappa from its current boundary estimate; kappa near zero is greedy boundary-hugging, large kappa is random sampling. Using replica and annealed methods, compute the generalization curve versus load alpha, noise eta, and margin kappa, capturing that low-margin points are flipped more by noise. Derive the eta-alpha phase diagram and the critical curve beyond which greedy selection makes generalization worsen and passive sampling wins. Derive the information-optimal margin kappa-star trading information against noise reliability, and add replicated queries with majority voting plus a Bayes-posterior acceptance step to reject inconsistent labels. Validate with Monte Carlo simulations comparing greedy, kappa-star, and passive sampling, quantifying when active learning is safe."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is a reliability hazard: active learning may be brittle under label noise, worse than random sampling, with no theory of when safe (failure_risk_gap). This arises from prior work assuming noise-free oracles (scope_mismatch). The method extends statistical-mechanics theory to a noisy oracle regime (relax_extend_scope) via replica/annealed derivations of phase diagrams and optimal margin (formal_derivation). Precise bottleneck identified: near-boundary queries harvest most corruptible labels."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Active example-selection for perceptrons accelerates learning but assumes clean data, leaving a reliability gap under noise.","method":"Empirically map when active boundary-querying helps or hurts perceptron learning across noise, mismatch, and selection aggressiveness."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.7,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a reliability concern: active example-selection assumes clean data, leaving vulnerability under noise (failure_risk_gap), with a scope_mismatch element (clean-data assumption is unrealistic). The method systematically maps when querying helps or hurts across noise/mismatch/aggressiveness conditions, which is empirical_mapping. Bottleneck (noise sensitivity of aggressive boundary-querying) is reasonably specific."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"The most efficient learners in these works choose their own inputs: Baum's examples-and-queries algorithm drives a binary search toward the separating hyperplane, and Watkin and Rau's statistical-mechanics analysis of selecting examples gains about 41 percent efficiency by querying inputs with near-zero margin to the current decision boundary. Fedorov's optimal-experiment theory (D- and G-optimality via the information matrix) justifies such greedy information-maximizing designs, and Opper and Haussler give the Bayes-optimal decoder such designs feed. Crucially, all these query and selection results assume a noise-free oracle: Opper and Haussler explicitly study noise-free examples, and Watkin and Rau assume a deterministic teacher. This is a Failure/Risk gap. Boundary-greedy querying concentrates samples exactly where labels are least reliable, because near the true boundary the correct label is inherently ambiguous, so a flip there is maximally misleading. The statistical-mechanics review already warns that noise yields unrealizable rules and nontrivial phase behavior, yet no source combines active example selection with noise. Practitioners thus inherit a silent hazard: active learners are assumed to always beat random sampling, but under label noise their defining property of proximity to the boundary can bias the version-space posterior and make them worse than passive learning. No provided work characterizes when active query learning breaks down under noise, nor gives a robust query objective. This matters for the reliability and reproducibility of any system trusting an active learner or a costly, noisy oracle.","method":"Develop a derivation-first theory of noisy query learning for the perceptron, fusing Fedorov-style optimal experimental design with the version-space Gibbs-ensemble statistical mechanics of Tishby-Levin-Solla, Watkin-Rau, and Opper-Haussler. Step 1, Model: a teacher B and a learner that selects the next input to maximize information about B, but with margin-dependent output noise p_flip(m), where m is the query distance to the true boundary and p_flip decreases from one half at the boundary to zero far away, formalizing that near-boundary queries are least reliable; setting p_flip to zero recovers existing noise-free results. Step 2, Formal object: compute the Fisher information, equivalently the expected version-space volume reduction, of one query at margin m under noise, and derive that noisy information is non-monotonic in m, vanishing both far away and at the boundary and maximized at an interior optimal margin m-star that depends on noise, obtained in closed form as a noise-corrected D-optimality condition maximizing (1 minus 2 p_flip(m)) squared times the marginal information at m. Step 3, Phase-transition theorem: extend the Watkin-Rau replica order-parameter calculation for the teacher-student overlap R to include p_flip, derive learning curves for boundary-greedy versus random sampling as functions of load alpha and noise, and prove a threshold theorem giving a critical noise eta_c(alpha) above which boundary-greedy querying yields asymptotically larger generalization error than passive random sampling, a negative-value-of-active-learning result, also determining whether the noise-free first-order freezing transition to perfect generalization survives, is delayed, or is destroyed. Step 4, Robust optimal design: derive the query distribution maximizing noise-discounted expected information gain, querying at posterior margin m-star rather than at the boundary, as an explicit corrected D-optimal objective, couple it to the Opper-Haussler Bayes decoder to define a robust Bayes-active learner, and prove it recovers the fast alpha-inverse rate in the noise-free limit yet never underperforms random sampling above eta_c. Step 5, Validation: verify m-star, the eta_c crossover, and the robust learner curves against finite-N perceptron simulations with label noise, as Watkin-Rau validated their noise-free predictions, confirming the theory predicts both the failure regime of naive active learning and the safe operating region of the robust design."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.86,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as a Failure/Risk gap: boundary-greedy active learning concentrates queries where labels are least reliable, silently breaking under noise. Secondary is scope_mismatch since prior work assumes noise-free oracles. The method is derivation-first (Fisher information, D-optimality condition, phase-transition threshold theorem, provable rates), so formal_derivation is primary; it fuses optimal-experiment theory with statistical-mechanics learning theory, hence synthesis_unification secondary. The bottleneck (non-monotonic noisy information, interior optimal margin m-star, critical eta_c) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation about robust active learning gap","method":"test method using optimization and search"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.35,"confidence_paradigm":0.4,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('test motivation', 'test method'), offering no substantive content. Motivation gestures at an active learning gap (sample efficiency = resource bottleneck) and 'robust' (failure/risk), method mentions optimization and search. Confidence low given empty content; boilerplate maximal."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Query-based active example selection for perceptrons is celebrated as the most efficient known training scheme: Watkin and Rau's replica analysis shows that continually selecting the next example on the current estimate's decision boundary pushes generalization about 40 percent closer to the theoretical bound than random sampling. Yet every such analysis assumes a perfectly realizable, noise-free teacher, hiding a reliability gap. The queried examples lie essentially on the boundary, which are exactly the examples whose labels are most easily corrupted by output noise, input noise, or teacher-student mismatch. The most informative query is thus the least trustworthy label, so aggressive query learning risks amplifying noise, destabilizing the estimate, and generalizing worse than random sampling. No source characterizes when this happens or how to prevent it: Opper and Haussler's Bayes-optimal perceptron analysis is explicitly noise-free; the statistical-mechanics theory of noisy and unrealizable learning (Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby; Gyorgyi-Tishby) treats only random passive examples; and Fedorov's optimal-experiment theory assumes homoscedastic Gaussian noise, not the heteroscedastic boundary-concentrated label-flip noise that active selection provokes. This matters for the safety and reproducibility of active learning in realistic deployment regimes.","method":"Relax the noise-free, realizable assumptions of active perceptron learning and derive a noise-robust query rule by extending the replica machinery. First, model a teacher B and student J with heteroscedastic label noise whose flip probability grows as an example's teacher-stability shrinks toward the boundary, plus variants for input noise and teacher-more-complex-than-student mismatch. Second, generalize Watkin and Rau's operator that averages the log-volume over the next selected pattern: rather than constraining the query to lie on the boundary, constrain it to a tunable margin m and carry the label-noise distribution through the replica average, yielding the overlap R(alpha) and generalization G(alpha) as explicit functions of noise level and margin m for Ising and spherical perceptrons. Third, optimize m to trade off information gain against label reliability, deriving the information-per-reliable-example-maximizing margin and its generalization curve, and embed this in a Bayes-optimal posterior/version-space framework rather than a single estimate, linking sample complexity to the information-theoretic and VC bounds of Haussler-Kearns-Schapire under noise. Fourth, predict analytically the noise threshold beyond which greedy boundary queries fall below random sampling, and show the robust-margin rule (optionally with repeated boundary querying to average out flips) restores an advantage. Fifth, validate with simulations of MinOver/optimal-stability and Bayes-Gibbs learners across output-noise rates and student/teacher capacity ratios, comparing random, greedy-active, and robust-margin-active selection. This makes prior active-learning theory operate under weaker, noisier, unrealizable conditions and converts the identified brittleness into a tunable robustness knob."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as a reliability/brittleness risk: aggressive boundary queries select the least trustworthy labels, potentially generalizing worse than random. This is a failure_risk_gap, with a secondary scope_mismatch since prior analyses assume noise-free realizable teachers. The core move is to relax those assumptions and extend the replica machinery to noisy/unrealizable regimes (relax_extend_scope), with substantial formal derivation of overlap/generalization functions and thresholds. Precisely identifies the bottleneck (boundary examples = most corruptible labels), so high specificity. Not superficial stitching—it genuinely extends one theory under new noise conditions."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior works show perceptrons generalize faster by querying examples near the decision boundary, but only under noise-free labels.","method":"Develop a noise-robust example-selection rule using the Gibbs posterior and a noise-hedged information-gain criterion, analyzed via replica theory."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that prior active example-selection results for perceptrons only hold under noise-free labels; the proposal extends them to noisy conditions (scope_mismatch, with a failure/risk dimension). The central move relaxes the noise-free assumption via a Gibbs-posterior, noise-hedged criterion analyzed with replica theory, i.e. extending prior work to a more realistic regime, supported by formal derivation. Precise bottleneck (noise robustness of boundary querying) is clearly identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"failure_risk_gap","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation about active learning brittleness under noise.","method":"Test method unifying experimental design and Bayes generalization."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"failure_risk_gap","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation cites active learning brittleness under noise (failure/risk gap), with a bridging angle between experimental design and Bayes generalization. Method explicitly unifies two literatures, indicating synthesis. Text is thin and placeholder-like ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), suggesting stitching and low specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"A puzzle runs through these works. Actively choosing the most informative question looks like a clear win: Watkin and Rau call boundary example-selection the most efficient training algorithm yet devised (42% fewer wasted examples for the Ising perceptron; near-exponential speedups for spherical ones), echoing Fedorov's D-optimal design of querying the max-variance point, and Baum shows membership queries let nets escape NP-hardness limits. The shared prescription: query the maximally uncertain, near-boundary point. Yet the same statistical-mechanics literature undermines this. First, these strategies choose queries relative to a single point-estimate hypothesis J, but Opper and Haussler prove a single perceptron (Gibbs/Boltzmann) is generalization-suboptimal by about sqrt(2) versus the Bayes posterior average, which no single perceptron realizes, so we ask the most informative question about a biased boundary. Second, Seung, Sompolinsky and Tishby show metastable low-overlap phases and first-order transitions (the discontinuous jump at alpha_c=1.245 for discrete weights); greedy querying can entrench poor-learning states. Third, Watkin and Rau's own reinterpretation shows boundary points are exactly those most corrupted by label noise, so maximally informative is also maximally noise-amplifying, and Baum-style synthesized queries can be off-distribution. This contradiction has never been reconciled, no tool exists to map when aggressive querying helps or hurts, and no strategy queries with respect to the Bayes posterior rather than one hypothesis. It matters because active learning is deployed precisely in noisy, imperfectly realizable settings where clean-case guarantees may silently fail.","method":"Build an open, reproducible active-learning simulation platform for perceptron learning that instantiates every query strategy in these papers, introduces a posterior-based strategy, and serves as an experimental instrument to resolve the puzzle. Component one, a posterior-ensemble engine: maintain a committee of K weight vectors sampled by Monte Carlo/Langevin dynamics from the Gibbs posterior at inverse temperature beta over weights consistent with observed labels, on the sphere or hypercube. Prediction is the committee majority vote, a tunable realization of Opper and Haussler's n-hidden-unit majority approximation to Bayes (beta to infinity gives the realizable limit, finite beta the noisy regime, K=1 recovers Gibbs/Boltzmann). Component two, a pluggable query module with four strategies: random examples; single-hypothesis boundary querying (Watkin-Rau/Kinzel-Rujan, inputs orthogonal to current J); Baum-style synthesized boundary queries allowed off-distribution; and a new posterior/committee-disagreement query that, from a candidate pool, picks the input maximizing committee vote entropy, a computational realization of Fedorov's max-variance D-optimal point and Tishby-Levin-Solla one-step information gain taken over the full posterior instead of one hypothesis. Component three, a noise-and-mismatch module: controllable label-noise rate, target/hypothesis geometry mismatch (spherical vs Ising), varied alpha=P/N. Component four, on-line instrumentation: generalization error G(alpha), overlap R=J.B, committee entropy, wasted-example counts, and detectors for metastable trapping and first-order jumps. Validation and use: first certify the platform by reproducing the sources' analytic predictions (42% Ising reduction, sqrt(2) Bayes-vs-Gibbs gap, alpha_c=1.245 transition). Then sweep noise rate, alpha, beta, geometry, and K to produce a query-strategy phase diagram identifying where each strategy wins. Central hypothesis: posterior/committee querying dominates single-hypothesis boundary and random sampling under noise and near first-order transitions, because it queries the unbiased Bayes boundary rather than the biased Gibbs boundary, hedges across competing metastable basins, and implicitly down-weights noise-fragile isolated boundary points while staying on-distribution. This unifies disparate analytic results into a deployable tool and explains the paradox: greedy boundary querying is optimal only in the clean, realizable, single-basin regime, and posterior-referenced querying is its robust generalization. It is feasible with standard perceptron simulations (N up to thousands, committees of tens, cheap MC sampling) using the sources' closed-form benchmarks for correctness checks."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.6,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly a contradiction: active boundary querying looks optimal yet the same statistical-mechanics literature (Gibbs sub-optimality, metastable transitions, noise amplification) undermines it, an unreconciled paradox—clearly puzzle_contradiction, with a strong failure_risk_gap flavor (noisy/mismatched deployment). The method reconciles disparate analytic results (Fedorov, Opper-Haussler, Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby, Watkin-Rau, Baum) into a unified posterior/committee framework and resolves the paradox, so synthesis_unification is primary; the phase-diagram sweep and platform-as-instrument give strong empirical_mapping secondary. Though a simulation platform is built, its purpose is measurement/explanation rather than being the central artifact deliverable. Bottleneck is precisely identified (biased Gibbs boundary vs unbiased Bayes boundary under noise/metastability)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation about active learning tradeoff","method":"test method extend replica analysis with noisy oracle"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Test placeholder text; sparse content. Motivation mentions active learning tradeoff (resource/scope) and method extends replica analysis to noisy oracle, suggesting relaxing idealized assumptions plus formal derivation. Low confidence due to boilerplate stub."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"A paradox runs through this body of work. The active/query-learning literature declares that letting a learner pick its own examples is the most efficient training algorithm yet devised: Watkin & Rau (Selecting examples for perceptrons) predict a 42% cut in wasted examples for the Ising perceptron and more for optimal-stability spherical perceptrons; the earlier Improving a network's generalization ability by selecting examples, Baum's examples-and-queries algorithm, and the D-optimal experimental-design tradition (Fedorov) all agree: choose the most uncertain, near-boundary points and learning accelerates. Every one of these results assumes a realizable rule (teacher matches student) and noise-free labels. The statistical-mechanics results warn that these are exactly the dangerous assumptions. Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby show that for unrealizable rules and quenched disorder the clean approximations fail: learning curves turn non-monotonic and spin-glass phases with degenerate, barrier-separated minima appear. Opper & Haussler and Tishby-Levin-Solla recast learning as Bayes-optimal inference and one-step information gain, and Gardner's version-space analysis shows how each example shrinks the solution volume. The contradiction: query strategies deliberately select points of maximal label uncertainty (minimal stability, nearest the boundary) - precisely the points most likely to be mislabeled or unrealizable, and thus most able to inject misleading, disorder-amplifying constraints. So the always-beneficial premise may invert and querying may hurt, yet nobody has located the crossover. The evidence is also non-comparable across papers (Ising vs. spherical; Hebb, optimal stability, Gibbs, Bayes), giving conflicting speedups, so we cannot yet say when or why selecting examples helps versus harms.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map - an active-learning phase diagram - of when self-selected examples help, do nothing, or hurt, in the analytically solvable perceptron-in-the-thermodynamic-limit setting shared by these papers. The map is spanned by four axes drawn from the sources. (1) Selection strategy: random baseline; minimal-stability/maximal-uncertainty query (Watkin & Rau and the earlier selection paper); one-step maximal-information-gain/Bayes query, operationalizing Opper & Haussler's average one-step information gain, Tishby-Levin-Solla's entropy-based gain, and the perceptron analogue of Fedorov D-optimal design; and version-space bisection (Gardner volume halving). (2) Realizability: from a matched teacher through increasing architectural mismatch using the unrealizable-rule constructions of Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby. (3) Label noise: output-flip probability from 0 upward, exploiting the boundary-variable-behaves-like-Gaussian-noise observation in Selecting examples and Opper & Haussler's note that their methodology extends to noise. (4) Inference rule: Hebb, optimal stability (MinOver), Gibbs/Boltzmann at temperature T, and Bayes-optimal. For each grid cell compute the learning curve of generalization error as a function of alpha two ways for cross-validation: replica/order-parameter calculations where tractable (tracking teacher-student overlap R and the stability distribution of accepted examples) and large-N Monte Carlo elsewhere. Extract diagnostics: (i) query advantage A = e_g_random minus e_g_query, whose sign partitions the noise-by-mismatch plane into helps/neutral/harms regions with mapped transition lines per strategy and rule; (ii) stability/margin distribution and mislabeling fraction of the points each strategy actually queries, testing the hypothesis that harm arises when queries concentrate on corrupted near-boundary points; (iii) spin-glass/replica-symmetry-breaking and non-monotonicity signatures, testing whether querying itself induces the disorder-driven pathologies flagged by SST; and (iv) a myopia gap comparing greedy one-step information-gain querying against its realized long-run generalization, locating where the single-step Bayes/Fedorov-optimal choice is globally suboptimal. The deliverable is a comparative atlas plus a practical decision map: given noise level, degree of mismatch, example budget, and inference rule, it states which selection strategy (including plain random sampling) minimizes generalization error and explains the mechanism, converting fragmented, assumption-specific speedup claims into one calibrated picture of when selecting examples is a boon versus a trap."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.88,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation is explicitly framed as a paradox/contradiction: query strategies claim always-beneficial speedups but statistical-mechanics results suggest querying near-boundary points may inject disorder and harm under noise/unrealizability, and nobody has located the crossover. Secondary evidence_gap reflects the non-comparable, conflicting speedup claims across papers. The method is a systematic empirical map (phase diagram) across four axes with diagnostics quantifying helps/neutral/harms regions - clearly empirical_mapping. Because it reconciles fragmented, assumption-specific claims into one calibrated picture, synthesis_unification is secondary. The bottleneck (harm from querying corrupted near-boundary points inducing spin-glass pathologies) is precisely specified. Not surface stitching since it targets a genuine unresolved contradiction with mechanistic hypotheses."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"TEST_MOTIVATION","method":"TEST_METHOD"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.5,"confidence_paradigm":0.55,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal fields are placeholders (TEST_MOTIVATION/TEST_METHOD), so labels rely on context. Prior work centers on selecting informative examples/queries to reduce sample burden (resource_bottleneck) with information-theoretic bounds. The query-by-committee lineage suggests active selection/query strategies (optimization_search) grounded in formal analysis. Low confidence due to placeholder content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: active example selection for perceptrons gives only constant-factor speedups (Watkin-Rau, 41%) while membership queries (Baum) give exponential speedups; this contradiction is unexplained and unresolved.","method":"Test method: use Fedorov optimal-design search plus Opper-Haussler Bayes committee to choose queries maximizing version-space shrinkage under a budget, optimizing an allocation fraction between informative and representative queries."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as an unexplained contradiction: passive example selection yields only constant-factor speedups while membership queries give exponential speedups (puzzle_contradiction); the sample/query efficiency framing brings in resource_bottleneck. The method combines Fedorov optimal-design search with a Bayes committee to select queries maximizing version-space shrinkage under a budget, optimizing an allocation fraction — the central move is query selection/optimization (optimization_search), with a secondary integration of two prior frameworks. Precise bottleneck identified (version-space shrinkage rate / query informativeness)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Query/active-learning theory for perceptrons (Watkin-Rau 1992; Baum's examples-and-queries; Kinzel-Rujan selection) achieves large speedups by querying minimal-margin points on the current decision boundary. But Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby (1992) show unrealizable/noisy learning behaves qualitatively differently, and Opper-Haussler show Bayes-optimal uncertainty is largest at the boundary. Thus the strategy that is optimal in the noise-free realizable case targets exactly the least-reliable points under noise. It is unknown whether active selection still helps or backfires under noise, because query-learning results assume a perfect oracle while noisy/unrealizable analyses assume passive random sampling. The two never meet.","method":"Extend the replica statistical-mechanics framework of query selection to noisy, unrealizable, pool-based settings. Introduce a query-aggressiveness parameter kappa_q controlling the margin of queried points (kappa_q=0 = boundary-seeking Watkin-Rau/Baum; large kappa_q = passive random). Add margin-dependent label noise (flips concentrated near the boundary) and an unrealizable teacher. Use the Bayes-optimal posterior predictor (Opper-Haussler; Tishby-Levin-Solla) as student and query scorer. Compute generalization error versus alpha, kappa_q, and noise via replica theory for Ising and spherical perceptrons, predicting an information-vs-reliability tradeoff with an optimal margin kappa_q*(noise) and a crossover where aggressive boundary-seeking becomes worse than passive learning. Derive an adaptive online rule choosing the query margin that maximizes expected posterior-variance reduction under estimated noise, reducing to Watkin-Rau in the clean limit. Validate with simulations comparing passive, aggressive, fixed-margin, and adaptive strategies across noise levels and realizable/unrealizable teachers."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is a genuine contradiction: boundary-seeking queries are optimal in clean realizable settings but target the least-reliable points under noise, and the two literatures (query-learning with perfect oracle vs noisy passive analyses) never meet. This is puzzle_contradiction with a bridge_opportunity secondary. The method extends the replica statistical-mechanics framework, introduces a query-aggressiveness parameter, derives generalization error and an optimal margin, and predicts a tradeoff/crossover analytically — formal_derivation, with synthesis_unification as the two frameworks are reconciled. Precise bottleneck identified (information-vs-reliability tradeoff, kappa_q parameter). Not superficial stitching since the reconciliation is the analytic core."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"A striking contradiction runs through the active-learning results in these works. When a perceptron is allowed to choose its own training inputs, it learns dramatically faster than from random examples: Watkin & Rau show a 42% reduction in \"wasted\" examples for the Ising perceptron and large gains for spherical perceptrons; Kinzel/Rujan's example-selection scheme and Baum's example+query algorithm show similar or exponential speed-ups. The mechanism is always the same: the most informative query lies exactly on (or orthogonal to) the learner's current decision boundary — the point of maximum ambiguity, minimum margin |J·S|≈0 — because its label maximally constrains the target direction B (Watkin & Rau's Figure-1 geometry; Fedorov's D-optimality intuition).\n\nHere is the puzzle. Every one of these optimality claims assumes a noise-free oracle. But the statistical-mechanics literature on the same models tells us that low-margin inputs are precisely where labels are least trustworthy: in the realistic \"output noise\"/unrealizable regime (Seung–Sompolinsky–Tishby; the noise extension noted by Opper & Haussler), the probability that a teacher label is flipped grows as the true margin |B·S| shrinks toward zero. So the very examples active learning prioritizes as \"most informative\" are simultaneously the \"least reliable.\" This suggests a surprising failure that none of the provided works analyzes: the selection rule that is provably optimal at zero noise may be maximally brittle under noise — concentrating the query budget where the label signal-to-noise is worst, corrupting the estimate J, and potentially yielding generalization worse than passive random sampling. Watkin & Rau, Kinzel/Rujan and Baum all assume a perfect oracle; Opper & Haussler compute the Bayes-optimal learner but only for noise-free random examples; the review treats noise only with passive sampling. Whether, and how, informative-example selection can be made trustworthy under label noise is therefore an open and important question, since real oracles (human experts, physical experiments) are noisiest exactly at the ambiguous boundary points active learning seeks out.","method":"We propose a noise-robust active example-selection theory for perceptron learning, analyzed with the replica method of Watkin & Rau and validated by simulation, that turns the brittle boundary-querying strategy into a reliable one and characterizes when active selection helps versus hurts.\n\n(1) Noise model tied to margin. Teacher B produces label sign(B·S), flipped with probability f(|B·S|) that increases as the true margin shrinks toward the boundary (plus a uniform baseline rate). This encodes the source of the paradox — boundary queries are the noisiest — and connects to the unrealizable-rule setup of the review.\n\n(2) Robustified selection rule with a tunable stability offset. Instead of querying at the current estimate's boundary (J·S=0), query at a controlled distance |J·S| = κ_q from it. κ_q interpolates between the existing \"maximally informative\" scheme (κ_q=0) and conservative, high-reliability queries (large κ_q, borrowing Gardner's optimal-stability geometry). We solve for the offset κ_q*(f, α) that maximizes expected information per reliable label.\n\n(3) Noise-aware posterior and information criterion. Following Opper & Haussler's Bayes-optimal posterior and Tishby–Levin–Solla's consistent inference, we fold the flip model f into the version-space/Gibbs posterior so near-boundary evidence is automatically down-weighted. The query is then chosen to maximize expected posterior information gain under the noise model — a noise-discounted, Fedorov-style D-optimal criterion — rather than raw ambiguity. We also study a redundancy variant: spend queries repeating nearby ambiguous points and majority-vote to average out noise, quantifying the breadth-versus-redundancy trade-off.\n\n(4) Analytic predictions and validation. Using replicas we compute the order parameters R(α) (overlap J·B) and the generalization error G(α) as functions of noise level f, offset κ_q, and query budget. We predict a crossover/phase transition: below a critical noise level naive boundary-querying still beats random sampling, but above it naive selection becomes worse than random, whereas the offset/noise-aware scheme stays monotonically better and degrades gracefully. Predictions are checked against Ising and spherical perceptron simulations, as in Watkin & Rau.\n\nThis directly resolves the gap: it identifies the regime where the \"optimal\" noise-free strategy fails, and supplies a concrete, feasible selection rule (margin offset + noise-aware posterior + optional redundancy) that restores robustness and trustworthiness of active learning under label noise, with quantitative guarantees on generalization."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as a contradiction: active learning prioritizes exactly the low-margin points that are least reliable under noise, so the provably-optimal noise-free strategy may be maximally brittle. This is a puzzle_contradiction with a strong failure_risk_gap secondary (brittleness under noise). The method constructs a formal replica-based noise-robust theory (order parameters, phase transition, D-optimal criterion) making formal_derivation primary, with robustification as the explicit goal (tunable offset restoring reliability). Precisely identifies the limiting mechanism (margin-dependent label noise), so high bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"puzzle_contradiction","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"The provided works prescribe the most informative next example in contradictory ways. Watkin and Rau (Selecting examples for perceptrons, 1992) prove that querying at the current decision boundary (margin near zero, maximum uncertainty) is the most efficient scheme yet devised, cutting wasted examples by 42 percent. Fedorov (Theory of Optimal Experiments; D and G optimality) prescribes the opposite: high-leverage points maximizing Fisher information about the weights, not low-signal boundary points. Opper and Haussler show Bayes-optimal passive learning beats Gibbs by a factor approaching sqrt(2) and tie generalization to one-step information gain; Tishby, Levin and Solla formalize information gain as ensemble-entropy reduction; Baum and the VC sample-complexity bounds show queries give exponential PAC speedups. Yet none states which query maximizes the expected drop in Bayes generalization error, nor whether uncertainty sampling is Bayes-optimal or a heuristic. The puzzle: two rigorous optimal-query theories point in opposite directions (boundary versus high-leverage), and the Bayes/information stream that should adjudicate has never been connected to either. This matters because active-learning gains hinge on the query criterion, so the wrong choice wastes the theoretical advantage, and evidence conflicts on whether uncertainty sampling is optimal.","method":"Build one statistical-mechanics theory of optimal query selection unifying uncertainty sampling (Watkin-Rau), Fedorov D-optimal design, and Bayes/information-theoretic learning (Opper-Haussler; Tishby-Levin-Solla). Use the realizable teacher-student perceptron of Opper-Haussler; represent the learner as the Gibbs posterior and Gardner version-space measure, summarized by order parameters R and q via the replica method of Watkin-Rau. Following Tishby-Levin-Solla, define a query-value functional equal to expected ensemble-entropy reduction, the mutual information between the candidate label and the weights under the current posterior, expressed as a function of only the query projected-margin distribution, from which both the boundary criterion and the Fisher-information D-optimal criterion can be read off. Maximize it to get the Bayes-optimal query and show it reduces to Fedorov D-optimality in the diffuse low-alpha regime and to Watkin-Rau margin-zero uncertainty sampling in the concentrated high-alpha regime, predicting a crossover in alpha and locating where uncertainty sampling is suboptimal, thus dissolving the contradiction as two limits of one criterion. Compute the resulting generalization-decay exponent and place the Opper-Haussler sqrt(2) factor, the Watkin-Rau gain, and the Baum PAC speedup on one phase diagram, and combine Bayes-optimal estimation with Bayes-optimal querying to test whether gains multiply. Validate by simulating online query learning on spherical and Ising perceptrons, comparing D-optimal, uncertainty, and unified-optimal rules against random sampling, and probe robustness under label noise."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"puzzle_contradiction","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as a contradiction: two rigorous optimal-query theories (boundary vs high-leverage) point in opposite directions, with a third stream never connected to adjudicate. That is puzzle_contradiction, with bridge_opportunity secondary since disconnected literatures are involved. The method builds one statistical-mechanics theory unifying uncertainty sampling, Fedorov D-optimality, and Bayes/info-theoretic learning, showing they are limits of one criterion — synthesis_unification. The derivation of a query-value functional and generalization-decay exponent supports formal_derivation secondary. The unification is principled (limits of a single functional), not surface stitching. Bottleneck (which query maximizes expected Bayes error drop) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"AAAA","method":"BBBB"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.4,"confidence_paradigm":0.45,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":1,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Proposal body is placeholder (AAAA/BBBB), so inference relies on prior-work context about active learning / query selection to reduce sample complexity (query-by-committee), suggesting a resource bottleneck in labeled-example burden addressed via adaptive query selection with theoretical grounding. Low confidence due to missing content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Across these works the binding constraint on learning is a resource bottleneck: labeled examples (equivalently, oracle/expert queries or physical experiments) are expensive, so the central question is how to reach a target generalization error with the fewest labels. The statistical-mechanics learning curves (Seung/Sompolinsky/Tishby review; Opper & Haussler's exact Bayes-optimal G(α); Gardner-style version-space volumes; Tishby/Levin/Solla predictive inference) all describe how error falls with the ratio α = examples/weights, and show that even the *optimal* passive learner needs α of order 1 — i.e., O(N) labels — with a slow tail. Two lines attack the bottleneck by choosing examples: Watkin & Rau (\"Selecting examples for perceptrons\") and the Kinzel–Rujan-type rule select the next example on the decision boundary of the *single current best estimate* J(p), predicting a ~42% saving; Baum's query algorithm constructs synthetic membership queries by bisection. But each leaves a resource gap. (i) Boundary selection uses only a point estimate, discarding the posterior uncertainty that Opper & Haussler show is what the Bayes-optimal learner actually exploits, so it under-uses each costly label. (ii) Both methods are strictly sequential: one query, then full retraining, then the next — so the number of oracle-interaction rounds and retraining cycles equals the number of labels, which is the true cost when the oracle is a slow expert, a wet-lab assay, or an expensive simulation. (iii) Baum's constructed queries can be unnatural/unanswerable inputs (the membership-query pathology), and no work connects the classical optimal-experimental-design machinery (Fedorov: iterative D-/G-optimal designs that add the point of maximum predictive variance and provably converge) to version-space classification learning. There is therefore room for a query-selection theory that squeezes maximum information from every label *and* collapses the number of interaction/retraining rounds, using only realistically available inputs.","method":"Develop and analyze \"Bayes-optimal batch experimental design\" for perceptron learning, unifying Opper–Haussler's posterior-over-version-space view with Fedorov's optimal-design algorithm, and evaluate it with the replica/statistical-mechanics tools of Watkin–Rau and the SSC review. Steps: (1) Maintain the Bayes posterior (Gibbs ensemble on the version space consistent with the labels so far), represented cheaply by a small committee of weight vectors — reusing Opper & Haussler's result that an n-hidden-unit majority committee approaches Bayes-optimal as n grows — so no exact posterior computation is needed. (2) Define a per-candidate information utility for inputs drawn from a *finite realistic pool* (not synthetic points): the posterior label ambiguity, i.e., the committee-vote disagreement / posterior label variance for x. This is the classification analogue of Fedorov's maximum-predictive-variance point and strictly generalizes Watkin–Rau's boundary rule (which is the degenerate one-member-committee case), thereby using each expensive label to bisect the whole version-space volume rather than only the neighborhood of one estimate. (3) Turn single-point selection into *batch* selection to cut interaction/retraining rounds: adapt Fedorov's iterative design update, greedily adding to the batch the pool point of highest residual ambiguity while penalizing redundancy between points whose version-space cuts are nearly parallel (a diversity/D-optimality term on the induced information geometry), so a batch of k points jointly slices the posterior into near-equal informative pieces. Label the whole batch, retrain once, repeat. (4) Derive predicted learning curves G(α) and, crucially, the number of batch rounds to reach target error, using replica theory as in Watkin–Rau for both spherical and Ising perceptrons, and compare against three baselines: random (passive Bayes-optimal), single-estimate boundary selection, and Baum-style membership queries. (5) Validate with simulations, measuring the two resource axes explicitly — total labels and total oracle-interaction/retraining rounds — and characterize how batch size k trades a small label overhead for a large reduction in rounds. The approach addresses the bottleneck by (a) extracting more information per costly label via the full posterior, (b) using only answerable pooled inputs, and (c) amortizing the sequential interaction and retraining cost through principled batching, yielding a feasible, analyzable active-learning scheme grounded entirely in the provided works."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.8,"confidence_paradigm":0.7,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames labeled examples/queries as the binding resource bottleneck (label cost, interaction rounds, retraining cycles), so resource_bottleneck is primary; the gap is also found by noting disconnected literatures (Opper-Haussler posterior view, Fedorov optimal design, Watkin-Rau boundary selection) are not connected, giving bridge_opportunity secondary. The core method move is unifying the Bayes-posterior-over-version-space view with classical optimal experimental design and evaluating via replica theory, so synthesis_unification is primary with formal_derivation (deriving learning curves G(alpha), generalizing the boundary rule as a degenerate case) secondary. It goes beyond superficial A+B by identifying a precise mechanism (using full posterior ambiguity and batching to reduce rounds), yielding high bottleneck specificity."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"The practical bottleneck across these works is the cost of labeled examples and oracle queries: labeling requires expensive experts or physical experiments, and most new random questions give no new information, so examples are wasted (Selecting examples for perceptrons; Neural net algorithms that learn from examples and queries). Three separate traditions each promise to cut this cost: statistical-mechanics active example selection (a predicted 42% reduction in wasted examples for the Ising perceptron), classical optimal experimental design (D-/G-optimal iterative designs in Theory of Optimal Experiments), and query/halving strategies for multilayer nets. The sample-complexity literature (VC/information-theory bounds; Bayes-optimal generalization; Statistical mechanics of learning from examples) supplies the learning-curve yardsticks. The gap: every savings claim is derived inside one idealized model under convenient assumptions — the thermodynamic limit (N to infinity), replica-symmetric ansatze, a realizable teacher-student match, and a noise-free oracle. The stat-mech review itself warns these approximations fail in general for unrealizable rules and finite systems, and the Bayes-optimal result is explicitly noise-free. No one has measured how much predicted query savings survive at finite N, under noisy labels, under teacher-student mismatch, or across learning rules, nor how much extra compute the selection oracle itself costs. A practitioner with a fixed labeling budget therefore cannot tell whether active selection's operational and computational overhead buys real savings in their finite, noisy, misspecified setting, or backfires by over-querying ambiguous points. The listed works leave this comparative, condition-resolved measurement open.","method":"Build a systematic empirical map answering when active example selection actually pays, via a controlled factorial simulation study on a common learning-curve yardstick that unifies the three selection traditions. Factorial axes: (1) Model: spherical perceptron, Ising perceptron, and a small committee/two-layer net. (2) Learner: Hebb, optimal-stability (MinOver), stochastic Gibbs/Boltzmann, and Bayes-optimal. (3) Selection strategy: random baseline, maximum-uncertainty selection near the decision hyperplane (Selecting examples), D-/G-optimal iterative design (Fedorov), and query-by-halving (poly-time query paper). (4) Stressors, the core novelty: finite size N with finite-size scaling toward the N-to-infinity theory, oracle label noise, teacher-student mismatch/unrealizability, and input-distribution shift. Measurements: per cell, estimate the empirical learning curve G(alpha) and a sample-savings ratio (examples needed by random selection divided by examples needed by the strategy to reach a target generalization), averaged over many teachers and training sets. Overlay the analytic asymptotics (the 42%/41% Ising savings, spherical exponents, Bayes-optimal sqrt(2) factor, VC/information bounds) to quantify a prediction gap equal to theoretical minus measured savings as a function of N and each stressor. Add a cost-adjusted savings metric that debits the compute of running the selection oracle, reporting savings per unit of total (query plus compute) budget. Deliverables: (a) an empirical phase map over the stressor axes marking regimes where selection helps, is neutral, or hurts, for example predicting that noise makes uncertainty sampling over-concentrate on ambiguous inputs and collapse savings; (b) finite-size scaling curves showing how fast measured savings approach the thermodynamic-limit theory; (c) a compact budget-aware decision rule telling practitioners which strategy is worth its overhead given their N, noise level, and suspected misspecification. The study is fully feasible from simulation alone, uses only models and estimators already defined in the sources, and turns three isolated savings claims into one validated, actionable cost map."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"evidence_gap","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"empirical_mapping","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.82,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is that savings claims are never measured under finite N, noise, mismatch, or across rules — a lack of comparative validation (evidence_gap), driven by narrow idealized assumptions (scope_mismatch). The method builds a controlled factorial simulation phase map with a unifying learning-curve yardstick, quantifying prediction gaps and a cost-adjusted decision rule — empirical_mapping, with synthesis of three selection traditions on a common metric as secondary. Precise bottleneck (compute cost of oracle, over-querying ambiguous points under noise) is well identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"In perceptron / feed-forward network learning, the binding resource is not compute but *labeled examples*: each label can require a costly oracle — a human expert producing an answer for a synthesized input (Baum 1991, \"queries by appeal to a human expert\"). Random sampling squanders this budget, because once a rule is partly learned \"most new questions give no new information,\" and near-perfect generalization needs many redundant examples (Watkin & Rau report a large fraction of examples \"wasted\"). Active example selection promises far fewer oracle calls, but the theory that would let us minimize this cost is incomplete in three ways. (1) The statistical-mechanics active-learning result (Watkin & Rau 1992) analyzes only a specific *greedy* heuristic — place the next query on the current decision boundary, orthogonal to the estimate J — implicitly assuming an isotropic version space, and it proves no optimality nor any budget guarantee. (2) It assumes free synthesis of arbitrary boundary inputs (membership queries), which is exactly the expensive/infeasible operation in practice, and says nothing about the realistic pool-restricted or noisy-label regimes. (3) The classical, mature theory of optimal experimental design (Fedorov 1972: D-/G-optimality through the information matrix), which was built precisely to spend experiments frugally, is never connected to the Bayesian version-space / information-gain machinery available here (Opper–Haussler 1991 version-space subvolume relations; Tishby–Levin–Solla 1989 ensemble entropy and \"information gain\"). As a result there is no formal, resource-aware answer to the practically central question: what is the minimum number of oracle queries needed to reach a target generalization error, which query achieves it, and how much is lost when inputs cannot be freely synthesized?","method":"We develop a formal, resource-aware theory of query-efficient perceptron learning that unifies optimal experimental design with the statistical-mechanics/version-space picture, and derive the queries and bounds it implies.\n\n1. Objective. Cast learning as Bayesian inference with posterior equal to the normalized measure on version space (Opper–Haussler), with ensemble entropy S(m)=log V(m) (Tishby et al.). Define the query-selection objective as the *expected reduction in ensemble entropy* (expected one-step information gain) of labeling input x. Using Opper–Haussler's subvolume relation V(σ^{m+1}) = min-subvolume of V(σ^m), prove that the optimal single query bisects the version space (V(σ^{m+1})=½V(σ^m)), extracting exactly 1 bit — the maximum possible per label.\n\n2. Equivalence theorem. Under a saddle-point/replica Gaussian approximation of the posterior on weight space, derive that maximizing expected entropy reduction is equivalent to Fedorov's D-optimality: maximizing the determinant of the posterior precision (Fisher-information) matrix. This is the core formal contribution — a bridge showing statistical-mechanics active learning IS optimal experimental design in the appropriate limit.\n\n3. Anisotropy correction (new prediction). From the equivalence, derive that the truly information-optimal query is NOT Watkin–Rau's boundary-orthogonal input but one *tilted toward the principal eigenvector of maximal posterior variance*. Give a closed form in terms of the order parameters (overlap R and the within-version-space covariance of J); recover Watkin–Rau as the isotropic special case.\n\n4. Query-complexity bound. Because each optimal query yields ≤1 bit and target error ε maps to version-space volume through the known generalization relation G(R) (Gardner/Watkin), derive a lower bound m*(ε) on required queries and the fastest achievable ε(m) decay, contrasting it with random-sampling scaling.\n\n5. Resource-aware extensions and taxonomy. Extend the derivation to (a) the pool-based setting where inputs are drawn from a distribution and cannot be synthesized on the bisecting hyperplane — derive achievable per-query information as a function of pool density near that hyperplane, giving an explicit degraded bound; and (b) noisy labels, via a modified subvolume-splitting factor. This yields a conceptual taxonomy of three regimes — membership-query-optimal, pool-optimal, noisy-optimal — each with its own query-complexity bound.\n\n6. Validation. Compute replica learning curves and run simulations on Ising and spherical perceptrons comparing random sampling, greedy Watkin–Rau selection, and the anisotropy-corrected optimal design, checking that the corrected design saturates the derived bounds and outperforms greedy selection.\n\nThis directly targets the labeled-query bottleneck by prescribing provably information-maximal queries and quantifying, for the first time in this setting, the minimum oracle budget and the penalty imposed by realistic (pool/noisy) constraints."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"formal_derivation","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.6,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as disconnected literatures — statistical-mechanics active learning and classical optimal experimental design — that could be connected, and also as a labeled-example resource bottleneck. The core move is a formal equivalence theorem, bounds, and derivations (formal_derivation), with the unification of two theories central (synthesis_unification secondary). The equivalence and anisotropy correction are genuine derivations, not superficial stitching. The oracle-query bottleneck is identified precisely."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Labeled queries are the scarce resource in perceptron learning; existing statistical-mechanics learning curves assume unlimited random examples and greedy boundary-query heuristics are not budget-optimal, noise-aware, or pool-constrained.","method":"Optimize the active-learning query distribution as an experimental-design measure using replica learning-curve predictions to allocate a fixed labeling budget minimizing generalization error."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"scope_mismatch"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.74,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The motivation centers on labeled queries as the scarce resource, with prior work assuming unlimited examples and non-budget-optimal heuristics — a resource_bottleneck with scope_mismatch undertone (unrealistic unlimited-example assumptions). The method optimizes a query distribution to allocate a fixed labeling budget minimizing error, which is fundamentally optimization_search / active experimental design; the use of replica learning-curve predictions adds a formal_derivation secondary. The bottleneck (budget-optimal, noise-aware, pool-constrained querying) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Labeled examples are the scarce, expensive resource in learning a rule. The active-selection results here promise large label savings: Watkin and Rau (1992) predict up to 42% fewer wasted examples by requesting the label of an input on the current decision boundary (perpendicular to estimate J), and Baum (1991) learns in polynomial time by querying constructed points such as midpoints and points on separating hyperplanes. But these gains rest on two idealizations that break in real deployment. First, free synthesis or unlimited filtering of inputs: the boundary-aligned-example rule assumes one can construct arbitrary inputs or reject an infinite stream until a boundary example appears, whereas in practice one has only a finite pool of naturally distributed unlabeled inputs and cannot synthesize arbitrary vectors. Second, noise-free labels. The complementary statistical-mechanics work that handles noise, Opper and Haussler's Bayes-optimal perceptron and Seung, Sompolinsky and Tishby's review, treats only passive random sampling. No listed work characterizes how much of the active-learning label savings survives under a finite pool and noisy labels. This matters because of a hidden tension: near-boundary inputs are the most informative but, under output noise, the least reliable, so naive boundary-selection may amplify noise and waste the very labels it aims to save.","method":"Relax the two idealizations of the active-selection theory and re-derive both the learning curve and the optimal selection rule for a finite pool with noisy labels, unifying Watkin-Rau selection analysis with Opper-Haussler Bayes-optimal and noise framework. Setting: a teacher perceptron B; a finite pool of p_pool = beta*N unlabeled inputs from the input distribution; a label oracle returning sign(B dot S) flipped with probability lambda; the learner may pay for only m = alpha*N labels with alpha at most beta, the scarce resource, and estimates J via the Gibbs or Bayes-optimal posterior. Selection rule: replace pick the input perpendicular to J (which needs infinite supply and is noise-blind) with, from the current pool, request the label maximizing expected posterior information gain about B under the noise model. For a perceptron this reduces to a noise-aware margin band: prefer small absolute J dot S but discount points so close to the boundary that their noisy label is near a coin flip, giving an optimal nonzero target margin that grows with lambda. It is deployable without knowing B: estimate margins from J and estimate lambda from label disagreement on repeated queries. Analysis: extend the Watkin-Rau replica calculation along two axes, first finite pool size beta, adding an order parameter tracking depletion of near-boundary inputs as they are consumed, and second noise lambda, giving an effective margin threshold. Compute the generalization curve G(alpha; beta, lambda) and its asymptotics and produce a phase diagram of regimes where pool-based selection still beats random, where finite beta erases the gain, and where noise inverts the optimum so that selecting at a nonzero margin is best and naive boundary-selection is worse than random. Derive the optimal label budget alpha given beta and lambda. Validation: mirror Watkin-Rau by checking replica predictions against simulations of pool-based spherical and Ising perceptron learning with controlled label-flip noise and finite pools, benchmarked against the Bayes-optimal passive baseline. This maximizes generalization gained per expensive label under realistic finite-pool, noisy conditions that prior active-learning results assumed away."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"synthesis_unification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior active-learning results resting on idealizations (free synthesis, noise-free labels) that break in realistic finite-pool noisy deployment — a clear scope_mismatch, with a puzzle-like tension that near-boundary inputs are most informative but least reliable under noise. The core move is relaxing those two assumptions and re-deriving the learning curve and selection rule under weaker conditions (relax_extend_scope), while also unifying Watkin-Rau selection analysis with Opper-Haussler noise/Bayes framework (synthesis secondary). The bottleneck is precisely identified: noise-aware margin band with nonzero optimal target margin plus pool depletion order parameter."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation: labels are the scarce resource; active learning queries the boundary where oracles are unreliable.","method":"Test method: select queries at an optimal nonzero margin weighted by oracle reliability, with posterior consistency filtering."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":"robustification"},"confidence_opportunity":0.72,"confidence_paradigm":0.68,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":2},"rationale":"Motivation frames labels as scarce (resource_bottleneck) with unreliable oracles near the boundary (failure_risk_gap). Method selects queries at optimal margin weighted by reliability with consistency filtering, which is a query-selection/optimization move (optimization_search) plus reliability weighting for robustification. The margin+reliability+consistency combination has some stitched feel and identifies a moderately specific bottleneck (oracle reliability at boundary)."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"resource_bottleneck","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Acquiring labeled examples is the real cost of learning in these works. Baum's query paradigm shows each label may need an oracle or expert, and statistical-mechanics results show random sampling wastes many examples since most carry no new information. Cutting labels is the bottleneck, but knowledge is split across four disconnected literatures: optimal experimental design (Fedorov D-/G-optimality, iterative maximum-variance-point updates) for linear regression only; SM learning-curve theory predicting exact payoffs (Watkin-Rau 42 percent; Bayes-optimal sqrt2) but via hand-crafted perceptron heuristics; the Bayesian ensemble entropy/information-gain framework (Tishby-Levin-Solla) lacking a concrete rule or savings prediction; and query learning (Baum) with worst-case bounds detached from generalization curves. No single cheap, analyzable rule tells which example to label next, generalizes beyond linear models, and predicts savings.","method":"Unify the four streams into one information-optimal example-selection framework. Represent the learner as the Gibbs posterior ensemble of Tishby-Levin-Solla. Define the criterion: select the query maximizing expected ensemble-entropy reduction (information gain), and prove this generalizes Fedorov D-optimal design (in the linear-Gaussian limit it maximizes the Fisher-information determinant, recovering the maximum-variance-point rule) while for classification it becomes maximum committee disagreement, recovering Watkin-Rau near-boundary selection and Baum boundary queries. Derive learning curves via replica calculations with the example distribution set to this self-consistent query distribution, quantifying labels saved and the gap to the Bayes-optimal sqrt2 bound. Implement a practical algorithm: sample a committee from the Gibbs ensemble by MCMC, score candidates by disagreement (Monte-Carlo info-gain), label the most informative, iterate, needing no NP-hard search and applicable to layered nets. Validate against replica theory and simulations on Ising and spherical perceptrons, and on a small multilayer net show reduced oracle queries for target accuracy."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"bridge_opportunity","secondary":"resource_bottleneck"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.86,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The proposal explicitly frames the gap as four disconnected literatures (optimal experimental design, SM learning curves, Bayesian ensemble entropy, query learning) that could be connected, with the labeling cost as the driving bottleneck. That is a bridge_opportunity with resource_bottleneck secondary. The core move is unifying these streams into one information-optimal criterion, proving it subsumes each special case (synthesis_unification), supported by formal replica derivations and generalization bounds (formal_derivation). This is genuine theoretical unification with proofs recovering prior rules as limits, not a superficial A+B combination, so surface stitching is low and bottleneck specificity high."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"artifact_system"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior active-learning theory (Watkin-Rau 42 percent gain, Baum queries, Fedorov D-optimal, Opper-Haussler Bayes optimal, stat-mech learning curves) assumes N to infinity, noise-free realizable single-layer perceptrons, and arbitrary oracle queries; real settings are finite-N, noisy, unrealizable, and pool-based, so the promised gains are unverified and the theory is not a usable tool. This scope mismatch matters because active/query learning is exactly where sample efficiency is decisive.","method":"Build a modular active-example-selection platform implementing theory-derived acquisition criteria (Watkin-Rau margin, committee-disagreement Bayes-optimal voting, Fedorov D-optimal), a finite-temperature Gibbs soft version space for noise robustness, a pool-based query mode with manifold-projected synthesized queries, and a finite-N calibration and benchmark harness comparing empirical learning curves to asymptotic theory across perceptrons and small multilayer nets."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"evidence_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"empirical_mapping"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.72,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":true,"surface_stitching_score":2,"bottleneck_specificity":2,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is explicitly framed as prior theory assuming N->infinity, noise-free, realizable single-layer, arbitrary-oracle conditions while real settings are finite-N, noisy, unrealizable, pool-based — a clear scope_mismatch, with a secondary evidence_gap since gains are 'unverified' and need benchmarking. The central move relaxes those assumptions into realistic regimes (relax_extend_scope), supported by a benchmark/calibration harness comparing empirical curves to theory (empirical_mapping). The platform assembles several existing acquisition criteria plus a Gibbs soft version space, leaning somewhat toward A+B assembly, hence a moderate stitching score, but the finite-N/noise extension gives it a specific limiting-factor focus."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":null},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope-mismatch gap. Prior active and query-learning theory for perceptrons derives its efficiency from unrealistic boundary conditions. Watkin and Rau (Selecting examples for perceptrons) obtain a 42 percent example reduction and a shifted discontinuous transition to perfect generalization by constructing each next example to lie exactly on the current student decision hyperplane, and Baum uses membership queries that fabricate input points and receive noise-free oracle labels. Both assume a realizable, noise-free, matched teacher in the large-N limit with inputs synthesizable anywhere in feature space. These assumptions are narrow: real inputs come from a fixed natural distribution and can only be selected, not manufactured; synthetic boundary queries fall off the data manifold and cannot be labeled by real oracles; labels are noisy; teachers are often unrealizable. Seung, Sompolinsky and Tishby show unrealizable rules under passive random sampling behave very differently, with non-monotonic curves and spin-glass phases, yet no one has analyzed selective example choice once the idealized query model is dropped. So it is unknown whether the promised savings survive, or reverse due to selection bias toward ambiguous noisy points, in the regime that actually occurs: pool or stream selection from a natural distribution with noise and mismatch.","method":"Build a statistical-mechanics replica and order-parameter-flow theory of stream-based selective sampling for perceptrons under the natural-distribution constraint. Examples arrive i.i.d. from the true input distribution; a Gibbs student at temperature T, or a Bayes posterior over version space following Opper-Haussler and Tishby-Levin-Solla, decides from the input alone whether to spend a label, accepting when the margin is below a threshold for uncertainty sampling, or when two Gibbs students disagree for a pool-compatible query-by-committee. Unlike Watkin-Rau, inputs cannot be forced onto the boundary; we only filter the isotropic stream. Extend the Watkin-Rau and Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby replica machinery by treating accepted examples as a selection-biased effective distribution concentrated near the current boundary, deriving coupled equations for student-teacher overlap and stability along two axes, examples seen and labels spent, giving learning curves in labels-per-generalization plus an acceptance rate. Solve three regimes: a realizable noise-free baseline to reproduce then relax the 42 percent result, label noise, and an unrealizable teacher, testing whether the freezing and discontinuous transition and the savings persist, degrade, or invert. Optimize the acceptance-threshold schedule via the information-gain and D-optimality logic of Fedorov optimal-experiment theory adapted to a filterable rather than constructible design space, and compare achievable label scaling to passive sampling and the idealized membership-query bound. Validate with finite-N MinOver and Gibbs simulations on natural streams."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.9,"confidence_paradigm":0.85,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames prior query-learning theory as relying on unrealistic boundary conditions (synthesizable inputs, noise-free realizable teacher), a clear scope_mismatch; there's also a puzzle element about whether savings survive or invert. The method extends the Watkin-Rau/SST replica machinery to the natural-distribution filterable regime with noise and mismatch (relax_extend_scope), delivering coupled order-parameter-flow equations and learning curves (formal_derivation). Precise bottleneck identified: selection-biased effective distribution near the boundary. Not superficial stitching."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"empirical_mapping"},"idea":{"motivation":"Test motivation.","method":"Test method."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.3,"confidence_paradigm":0.3,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal text is placeholder ('Test motivation'/'Test method'), so labels are inferred from prior-work context on active/query learning and sample selection, which centers on reducing sample complexity via query selection. Confidence is low given absent content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"formal_derivation"},"idea":{"motivation":"test motivation","method":"test method content here"},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"resource_bottleneck","secondary":null},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"optimization_search","secondary":null},"confidence_opportunity":0.2,"confidence_paradigm":0.2,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":0,"bottleneck_specificity":0,"boilerplate_score":3},"rationale":"Proposal content is placeholder text ('test motivation', 'test method content here'), providing no substantive information. Labels are weak inferences from prior-work context on active learning / example selection, which suggests sample-efficiency bottlenecks addressed via query/selection strategies. Confidence is low given absent content."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"optimization_search"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior optimal query work relies on unrealistic assumptions. Watkin and Rau query exactly on the decision boundary, Baum synthesizes arbitrary inputs with perfect oracle labels, and Opper and Haussler and Fedorov assume noise free data and free choice of design points. But real tasks offer only a finite pool of sampled inputs, and boundary points, which are the most informative, have the noisiest labels. This trade off is uncharacterized, so reported gains may vanish in noisy pool limited settings where active learning is actually needed.","method":"Cast query selection as optimization over a query margin and a query budget under boundary dependent label noise and pool based inputs. Keep the Gardner and Watkin Rau perceptron setup with overlap R and generalization G, but add a noise channel where an example of stability t is mislabeled with probability peaking at the boundary, and require candidates to be drawn from the input distribution so the learner may only label points whose projection onto its current estimate lies in a chosen margin band. Extend the Watkin Rau replica analysis so the new example sits at a tunable margin rather than at zero, deriving the learning rate as a function of margin and noise. Solve for the margin that maximizes expected version space entropy reduction net of noise corruption, which predicts a nonzero optimal margin reducing to zero only in the noise free limit. Treat oracle calls as a scarce budget and derive an adaptive margin schedule maximizing final generalization for fixed budget. Implement a pool based committee algorithm that maintains a version space sample, screens candidates by expected entropy reduction discounted by a boundary distance reliability factor and an online noise estimate, greedily selects the best within budget, and re tunes the margin. Validate analytically and by simulation by comparing generalization for random sampling, boundary querying, and margin optimized pool selection across noise levels and pool sizes, testing the predicted crossover where boundary querying underperforms random sampling under noise."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.8,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":1},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior query work relying on unrealistic assumptions (noise-free, free choice of design points, boundary querying) that fail in noisy pool-limited settings — scope_mismatch, with a puzzle/tradeoff element (most informative points are noisiest). The method extends the Watkin-Rau replica analysis to weaker/realistic conditions (noise channel, finite pool, tunable margin), which is relax_extend_scope; the derivation of optimal margin and learning rate is formal_derivation. Bottleneck is precisely identified: boundary-dependent label noise vs informativeness tradeoff."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"relax_extend_scope"},"idea":{"motivation":"Prior active example-selection theory for perceptrons (Watkin and Rau 1992; the Kinzel-Rujan boundary-query scheme; Baum's query bisection) assumes a noise-free realizable teacher and unrestricted membership queries, and prescribes querying points on the decision boundary; Opper and Haussler's Bayes-optimal analysis is likewise noise-free. Yet the boundary region is exactly where labels are least reliable under margin-dependent noise and where an unrealizable student cannot track the teacher. The Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby review shows noisy and unrealizable rules give spin-glass phases and non-monotonic learning curves, but only for random examples. Thus the boundary heuristic may underperform random sampling once noise and unrealizability are admitted, and no theory says when active learning helps. Fedorov's optimal experimental design handles noise via the information matrix but is never linked to perceptron query learning. The scope mismatch is that selection theory holds only under noiseless realizable free-query assumptions that fail where sample efficiency matters most.","method":"Build a noise-aware active-selection theory that relaxes the noiseless realizable free-query assumptions. Model teacher and student weight vectors at large N with load alpha, adding margin-dependent output noise whose flip probability rises as the teacher field shrinks, plus unrealizable teachers. Replace boundary querying with an information-gain D-optimal criterion maximizing expected version-space-volume reduction under a noise-corrected likelihood, using the Bayesian ensemble of Tishby-Levin-Solla and Bayes-optimal prediction of Opper-Haussler. This yields an optimal nonzero query margin that trades informativeness against label reliability and reduces to the boundary rule only at zero noise. Use replica and annealed theory to compute the teacher-student overlap and generalization error versus load for random, boundary, and optimal-margin protocols, predicting a harmful-active-learning phase removed by optimal-margin querying. Extend from membership queries to finite-pool selection to quantify how the optimal margin and the gain degrade with pool size. Validate with finite-N MinOver and posterior-sampling simulations."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"puzzle_contradiction"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"relax_extend_scope","secondary":"formal_derivation"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The motivation explicitly frames a scope mismatch: active-selection theory holds only under noiseless realizable free-query assumptions that fail where sample efficiency matters, with a contradiction that the boundary heuristic may underperform random sampling under noise. The method's central move is relaxing those assumptions (noise-aware, unrealizable, finite-pool) to make the theory function in realistic regimes, with heavy formal/replica derivation as secondary. Not surface stitching since it derives an optimal-margin criterion with a predicted phase transition rather than gluing components. Bottleneck (boundary=least reliable labels under margin noise) is precisely identified."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"robustification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Scope mismatch in query-based example-selection for perceptrons. The efficient training rules here (Watkin and Rau's self-selecting perceptrons with about 42 percent fewer wasted examples, the Kinzel/Rujan and Gardner-Derrida constructions, and Opper and Haussler's Bayes-optimal generalization analysis) all obtain their gains under narrow, unrealistic assumptions. First, noise-free labels: Watkin and Rau select each query so that J dot xi is near zero, the point of minimal stability and maximal ambiguity where the student is least confident; this maximizes information per example only if labels are trustworthy. Opper and Haussler explicitly assume noise-free examples and only remark that noise can be extended without significant change, with no analysis. Yet realistic output noise flips labels with probability rising sharply as stability z goes to zero, so the maximally informative queries are exactly the maximally corrupting ones, and the speedup is bought in the regime where the strategy is most brittle. Second, exact realizability: the analysis leans on a sharp freezing transition to perfect generalization that loses meaning under noise or mismatch. Third, synthesizable boundary-hugging queries drawn from an assumed uniform input distribution, a membership-query assumption unrealistic for real data. No source characterizes how much query speedup survives noise or offers a rule that degrades gracefully, which matters because active learning is advocated for expensive-label settings where labels are noisy and boundary-hugging is dangerous.","method":"Develop a noise-robust, uncertainty-aware query-selection theory for perceptron learning that robustifies the boundary-hugging rule against label noise and model mismatch, using the same replica statistical-mechanics framework as Watkin-Rau and Opper-Haussler for direct comparability. Step 1, noise model: introduce output noise with flip probability eta(z) increasing as query stability z equals J dot xi approaches zero. Recompute expected information gain per query as a function of z discounted by label reliability, so the noiseless optimum at z equal zero is replaced by a strictly positive safety margin z-star depending on noise level and current overlap R. Step 2, replica derivation: extend Watkin-Rau's order-parameter recursion, which already reads the selection variable as a Gaussian noise narrowing as R grows, to include eta(z), solving self-consistently for the query-stability distribution that maximizes robust information gain at each alpha; this yields learning curves and an optimal margin that starts far from the boundary at high noise and tightens as confidence rises. Step 3, committee robustification: replace the single-estimate margin criterion with disagreement among weights sampled from Opper-Haussler's Bayes-optimal posterior version space, querying where a Bayesian committee disagrees but the label is still likely reliable, removing dependence on a single freezing point and staying meaningful under mismatch. Step 4, realism and fallback: a pool-based variant selects, from finite real data-distributed inputs, the point whose stability is closest to z-star rather than a synthesized ideal boundary point; a mixture policy blends selected and random examples in a proportion tied to posterior uncertainty, guaranteeing performance never worse than random sampling and bounding the downside of pure boundary-hugging under noise. Step 5, validation: compare generalization curves, the freezing transition, and asymptotic error against random sampling and the original noiseless rule for Ising and spherical perceptrons across noise levels, with replica predictions checked by Monte-Carlo simulation. The target is retaining most query speedup at low noise while avoiding noise-induced collapse at moderate noise, matching random-sampling robustness while preserving active-learning efficiency. This relaxes the noiseless, realizable, and synthesizable-query assumptions and converts select where confidence is lowest into select where robust information gain is highest, reducing brittleness and downside risk."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"failure_risk_gap"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"robustification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.85,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed explicitly as scope mismatch: prior query-selection rules assume noise-free, realizable, synthesizable queries, and the proposal notes these break precisely where advocated (secondary failure_risk_gap on brittleness). The central move is robustifying the boundary-hugging rule against label noise and model mismatch, with relax_extend_scope as it extends the replica framework to weaker assumptions. It identifies a precise mechanism (maximally informative queries at z=0 are maximally corrupted), so bottleneck specificity is high. Not superficial stitching despite reusing Watkin-Rau and Opper-Haussler frameworks."},"archetype":null}
{"paper_id":"query-by-committee-1992","source":"claude-opus-4-8","condition":{"pattern":"scope_mismatch","paradigm":"synthesis_unification"},"idea":{"motivation":"Active/query learning theory for neural nets (Watkin-Rau 1992; Baum 1991; Opper-Haussler 1991) assumes a noise-free oracle, a realizable target, and the thermodynamic limit, yielding results like a 42% reduction in wasted examples. But Seung-Sompolinsky-Tishby (1992) show these idealizations break under noise and unrealizable rules, where annealed approximations fail and spin-glass phases appear. Separately, Fedorov's Theory of Optimal Experiments (1972) offers a mature, noise-aware theory of informative-measurement selection, but only for linear/nonlinear regression, disconnected from the version-space/Gibbs picture, SM learning curves, and info/VC sample-complexity bounds (Haussler 1991; Tishby-Levin-Solla 1989). No framework predicts active example selection in the realistic noisy, unrealizable regime.","method":"Build a Bayesian information-gain framework unifying Fedorov optimal design, SM Gibbs learning curves, version-space Bayes optimality, and query heuristics. Central object: the finite-temperature Gibbs posterior P_beta(W|D), with 1/beta encoding noise/unrealizability (a soft version space). A query's value is the expected ensemble-entropy reduction, i.e. mutual information I(label(x);W|D). Reconciling limits: (a) beta to infinity collapses to Opper-Haussler's hard version space, recovering Watkin-Rau's orthogonal-query rule and Baum's queries; (b) a Laplace approximation yields a Fisher matrix, making entropy reduction equal Fedorov's D-optimal design with computable iterative algorithms; (c) cumulative information gain lower-bounds query count via Haussler's info/VC bounds. Program: redo the replica/SM learning-curve calculation with the query-generating measure set by information gain, extended to finite beta, teacher-student mismatch, and Ising/spherical perceptrons with Gardner capacity constraints. Test whether the 42% active gain survives under noise, whether optimal queries shift from boundary to interior under unrealizability, and agreement with Bayes-optimal error; validate on the perceptron analytically and Baum's depth-2 nets by simulation."},"annotation":{"opportunity_pattern":{"primary":"scope_mismatch","secondary":"bridge_opportunity"},"method_paradigm":{"primary":"synthesis_unification","secondary":"relax_extend_scope"},"confidence_opportunity":0.78,"confidence_paradigm":0.82,"diagnostics":{"surface_stitching":false,"surface_stitching_score":1,"bottleneck_specificity":3,"boilerplate_score":0},"rationale":"The gap is framed as prior active-learning theory relying on unrealistic assumptions (noise-free oracle, realizable target, thermodynamic limit) that break under noise/unrealizability — scope_mismatch — while also noting disconnected literatures (Fedorov optimal design vs SM version-space picture), giving a bridge_opportunity secondary. The central move unifies Fedorov design, SM Gibbs learning curves, Bayes optimality, and info/VC bounds under a single information-gain framework (synthesis_unification), with the concrete goal of making these work under finite beta/noise/mismatch (relax_extend_scope). The unification is principled via limit-recovery arguments rather than superficial stitching, and identifies precise limiting mechanisms (finite-temperature Gibbs posterior, Fisher/D-optimality equivalence)."},"archetype":null}
